<HEADLINE>
PETTITTE YANKS BLOW OUT TWINS  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Andy Pettitte hardly gazed at the scoreboard in
left-center field while pitching against the Minnesota Twins Friday
night, even though the numbers were incredibly positive for the
Yankees. Pettitte kept his eyes mostly on the grass and rarely
moved an inch away from the pitcher's rubber at Yankee Stadium. He
had to keep working, no matter how lopsided the score. And it was
very lopsided.
</P>
<P>
   By the third inning, the Yankees were ahead by six runs. By the
fourth, the lead had grown to 10. By the fifth, the only drama
remaining was whether Pettitte could throw a complete game, whether
Joe Girardi could join the other starters with a hit and whether
the Twins would volunteer to impose the 10-run mercy rule. By
game's end, the Yankees had a 14-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch slugged a grand slam against his former team,
Bernie Williams and Luis Sojo stroked two-run homers and Derek
Jeter socked three hits in the softball-type atmosphere. But the
most important development for the Yankees was Pettitte's revival.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre knows the Yankees can score and, against the
dismal Twins, a trouncing like this was not surprising. But the
Yankees are monitoring Pettitte closely, hoping that his prolonged
drought is a memory and that he can be a stellar contributor in the
postseason. It seemed very likely Friday night as Pettitte stifled
the Twins on one run and five hits while striking out 11 in eight
strong innings.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Pettitte halted the team with the fourth-worst batting
average in the American League, but he looked precise and powerful
enough to tame the Indians or the Rangers. Since the nonwaiver
trade deadline passed on July 31 and Pettitte learned that he would
be staying with the Yankees, he is 3-0 and has allowed two earned
runs in 23 innings for a tiny 0.78 earned run average. ``I really
think a turning point was the 31st,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who did not have outdoor batting practice because
of the afternoon rain, treated LaTroy Hawkins and Benj Sampson like
batting practice pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins was battered for nine runs and 12 hits in 3 1/3 innings
while Sampson allowed five runs and 10 hits in 2 2/3 innings
</P>
<P>
   Williams was 3 for 4 with three runs batted in and is batting
.512 (21 for 41) with six 6 homers and 25 RBIs this month.
Knoblauch had three hits, scored three runs, drove in five runs and
was in the middle of all three rallies.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch hit a bloop single off shortstop Cristian Guzman's
glove in the third to begin a six-run burst that included Paul
O'Neill's two-run double, Williams' two-run homer and Sojo's
two-run homer. Sojo, who started at third because Scott Brosius is
handling personal matters with his ailing father, had two hits.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, Knoblauch started another rally with an infield
single that traveled about 60 feet. Williams, Tino Martinez, Chili
Davis and Sojo all ripped run-scoring singles in the inning as the
Yankees grabbed a 10-0 lead. Hawkins had won five straight
decisions, but he is now 0-4 with a 7.83 ERA in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch's grand slam, off Sampson in the sixth, switched the
theme from softball to football by making the score 14-0.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
