<SLUG> BC-LA-SHOOTING-GUN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACING TWISTED PATH OF PISTOL USED IN CALIFORNIA KILLING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to modify language in lede; changes eastern to western in 2nd
graf; expands 5th graf.)   (See also LA-SHOOTING-MENTAL) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Glock semiautomatic pistol that police say Buford O. Furrow
Jr. used to kill a mail carrier after shooting five people at a
Jewish community center in Los Angeles was sold last year by an
unlicensed vendor at a gun show near the north Idaho compound of
the Aryan Nations, the neo-Nazi group to which Furrow belonged,
according to interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The path of the Glock model 26, which was sold new by Glock in
1996 to a small police department in western Washington state, ran
from the department to a gun dealership owned by an officer in that
department to a paint dealer to a friend of that businessman.
</P>
<P>
   That friend, according to law-enforcement authorities in
Washington, is the person who sold the Glock in early 1998 at a gun
show in Spokane, Wash. That city is near Hayden Lake, Idaho, the
town that serves as the home enclave for the Aryan Nations and
other white supremacist groups.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, gun collectors and others who do not have
federal firearms licenses can legally sell guns at gun shows _ and
they are not required to do background checks on buyers, as gun
stores must. The disclosure that the gun used by Furrow to kill the
letter carrier, Joseph Ileto, was bought from such a vendor may
restart a stalled debate in Congress over whether buyers at gun
shows should first undergo background checks.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the Senate passed a bill requiring that all
dealers at gun shows, including the 40 percent who do not have
federal licenses, conduct background checks on customers, allowing
three days for completing those checks. The House also approved
mandatory background checks though allowing only one day for them,
but the bill containing that amendment was defeated. The issue of
how much time to devote to background checks remains a political
flashpoint between lawmakers because it will come up when a
juvenile-justice bill is considered in conference.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear whether Furrow was the person who bought the
Glock 9-mm pistol early last year at the Spokane show.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Chester, a spokesman with the Seattle office of the Bureau
of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, said the agency still had not
determined how Furrow had acquired the Glock pistol or six other
weapons, including an Uzi assault-style submachine gun, that were
recovered from a car he had hijacked.
</P>
<P>
   However, Chester said Furrow may have recently traded for some
of those guns using others he had acquired while he was a federally
licensed firearms dealer between 1992 and 1995. Chester said there
were ``indications'' that some of those trades had occurred after
this May when Furrow was released from jail and was prohibited from
owning firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Michael Haymon of the Aberdeen, Wash., police department
said that when ATF agents came to that town on Thursday to
interview the man said to have sold the Glock at the gun show, they
found that the man and his wife were on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Furrow had to acquire the weapon between January and October
1998 or after this May, because he spent the intervening time in
jail for threatening to stab a nurse at a psychiatric hospital. He
had gone to the hospital for help, saying he was having fantasies
of committing a mass killing.
</P>
<P>
   In a criminal complaint filed on Wednesday in Los Angeles,
federal officials said Furrow had confessed to killing Ileto, who
was of Filipino descent. Furrow described Ileto as a good ``target
of opportunity'' because he was ``non-white'' and worked for the
federal government, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The killing of Ileto on Tuesday came soon after Furrow had
sprayed a Jewish day center in Los Angeles with gunfire from an Uzi
assault-style machine gun. Five people were wounded in that attack,
including three children.
</P>
<P>
   More evidence emerged Friday that Furrow had spent considerable
time planning the Los Angeles attacks in a city that he apparently
knew little about, prompting some to wonder if he had help from
other conspirators, one of the major unanswered questions this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Marvin Hier of the Simon Wiesenthal Center here said that
police told him they had found maps in Furrow's possession on which
he had circled the Wiesenthal center, as well as other Jewish
sites, as potential targets for his attack. The Los Angeles Times
said that one of the other sites was the Skirball Cultural Center,
a complex next to the Getty Museum that is dedicated to Jewish
culture. Police would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   The gun used to kill Ileto, which bore the serial number BSM901,
was one of two Glock model 26 guns that were purchased in January
1996 by the police department in Cosmopolis, Wash., from Glock
Inc., the Atlanta-area distributor for the Austrian gun producer.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Eisenhower, chief of police in Cosmopolis, a town of 1,600
near the port city of Aberdeen, said in an interview Friday that
the weapons were bought by his predecessor, Donald Lapacek, to
determine whether they were suitable for police work.
</P>
<P>
   After it was determined that the guns were too small, the
department swapped them for larger Glock models at Don's Guns, a
federally licensed gun store in Cosmopolis then owned by Donald
Dineen, a reserve officer in the town's police department.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Dineen said he was with Eisenhower when police
in Cosmopolis were reached Wednesday by ATF agents tracing the
Glock 26. Dineen said he recognized the gun's serial number and
recalled that he had sold it to an area resident in February 1996
soon after getting it from police.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gun went to a local resident,'' said Dineen. ``Someone
I've known for 14 or 15 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Dineen declined to disclose that person. But both Eisenhower and
Haymon said that person was Dave Wright, who works at the House of
Colors, a family-run paint store in Aberdeen.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief telephone interview, Wright would only say that he
had given all his ``information'' when interviewed by an ATF agent.
</P>
<P>
   Those Seattle-based agents had arrived Thursday in Aberdeen to
interview Wright and a friend, Andy Palmer, said Haymon. He said
that Wright had told the ATF agents that he had given Palmer
several guns including the Glock to sell at a Spokane gun show in
early 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Haymon said that when authorities tried to contact Palmer's wife
on Thursday they were told that she and her husband had just left
on a week's vacation. Palmer's telephone number is unlisted.
</P>
<P>
   Dineen, the former firearms dealer, also said that the person
who had bought the gun from him, Wright, had said that he had given
it to a friend, Palmer, to sell at a Spokane gun show. He said
Palmer worked as a food broker and was a gun enthusiast, adding
that he did not believe he had a federal firearms license.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not a gun dealer, he is a collector,'' Dineen said.
</P>
<P>
   John D'Angelo, an ATF spokesman, said the only record that the
agency has for a licensed dealer named Andrew Palmer is for the
operator of a pawn shop in Bainbridge, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Senate and House lawmakers on a conference committee that is
expected to hammer out new gun control legislation are scheduled to
start that work when they return on Sept. 7 from a monthlong
congressional recess. In early August, when the conference
committee met, the lawmakers postponed any decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's latest round of debate over gun control started in
April after two teen-age gunmen at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo., killed 12 students, a teacher and themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
