<SLUG> BC-NJ-OLD-MURDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
41 YEARS LATER, MAN IS CHARGED IN KILLING OF NEW JERSEY OFFICER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Penn.) (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Putting an end to an investigation that has spanned four
decades, a Pennsylvania man was arrested Thursday night in the 1958
killing of a police officer in Rahway, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Theodore Schiffer, 61, was taken into custody by
Pennsylvania and New Jersey law enforcement officers without
incident at his room in an apartment complex for the elderly in
Peckville, Pa., the authorities in both states said.
</P>
<P>
   In Superior Court in Scranton, Pa., Friday morning, Schiffer was
charged with murdering Officer Charles Bernoskie. He is being held
in Pennsylvania without bail until a hearing next week to determine
when he will be returned to New Jersey, where the case will be
presented to a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 28, 1958, Bernoskie, who was 30 and had been a policeman
for four years, was gunned down by an unknown assailant while
responding to a burglary call at a Pontiac dealership in Rahway,
said Richard Rodbart, a spokesman for the Union County prosecutor's
office. Though the officer was shot several times, he managed to
stagger to a nearby home, where he collapsed and ultimately died,
Rodbart said.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Kevin White of the Rahway Police Department said that
witnesses reported seeing two men flee the dealership on the night
of the shooting and that investigators are looking for a second
suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Since the day of the shooting, local detectives and
investigators in the Union County prosecutor's office have been
working to solve the murder, White said.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, Schiffer's cousin came forward and told
investigators that he may have committed the crime, said Kathleen
Granahan, an assistant district attorney in Lackawanna County, Pa.,
who helped capture Schiffer. Both Rodbart and White declined to
release the cousin's name and refused to offer any reason why the
woman had chosen to turn Schiffer in.
</P>
<P>
   The Scranton Times reported Friday that, according to a police
affidavit, a woman named Judith Sapsa told police that Schiffer and
her brother, Robert Zarinsky, came to her home with gunshot wounds
on the night Bernoskie was shot.
</P>
<P>
   According to the account of the affidavit, Ms. Sapsa watched as
her mother removed bullets from Schiffer's chest and Zarinsky's
buttocks. Zarinsky told her that he had shot Bernoskie after the
officer shot Schiffer, the affidavit reportedly said.
</P>
<P>
   Police also found a scar on Schiffer's chest where Ms. Sapsa
said a bullet had been removed, the affidavit reportedly said.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported that Zarinsky, who has not been
charged in the killing of Bernoskie, has been serving a life prison
sentence since 1975 for the murder of a 17-year-old girl from
Atlantic Highlands, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Granahan said law enforcement officials had initially looked
for Schiffer in Florida before tracking him to Lackawanna County
through motor vehicle records. His fingerprints matched those
collected at the crime scene 41 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Though most of Bernoskie's peers have long since retired, White
said he had a reputation as being honest and hard-working.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Tilton, the chief of the Rahway police, said that the
officer's widow, Elizabeth Bernoskie, was ``gratified'' by the
arrest. Mrs. Bernoskie lives in Rahway but has an unlisted phone
number.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Bernoskie, who was 5 years old when his father was
killed, said he was stunned and happy when he learned Friday
morning of Schiffer's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first thought was: Boom, it's over,'' said Bernoskie, 45,
who lives in Holmdel, N.J., and works as a mechanical engineer.
``It brought some closure to all of this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
