<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: ADOLF EICHMANN'S DIARY, AND HIS FADING ECHO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany, Israel)  (mk) 
 By TINA ROSENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial observer for Saturday,
Aug. 14:
</P>
<P>
   Adolf Eichmann, hanged by Israel in 1962 for organizing the Nazi
deportation of millions of Jews eastward to the gas chambers, was
by his own description the epitome of the bureaucratic mass
murderer. This week the German daily Die Welt began publishing
excerpts from a recently discovered diary Eichmann wrote during his
imprisonment. Eichmann details a life of obedience _ to his father,
to the military and to his Nazi superiors, a life in which
apparently even the prospect of freedom to choose his own path left
him panicked and bereft.
</P>
<P>
   Eichmann's memoir echoes what he told his examiners at the time
of his trial. Hannah Arendt, who chronicled the trial, aptly
described the ``banality of evil'' that Eichmann seemed to
represent. He was not a psychopathic killer, nor a personal enemy
of Jews, he said, and some psychiatrists who evaluated him
concurred. He was normal _ ``more normal, at any rate, than I after
having examined him,'' Ms. Arendt quotes one of them. The Eichmann
trial was chilling in part because he showed that an ordinary
person, whose most fervent desire was to fulfill the role his
society assigned him, could be made to participate in the murder of
millions of people.
</P>
<P>
   Today his memoirs chill Germany for a different reason. Perhaps,
he speculated in the diary, his need to obey orders was also ``the
attitude of many Germans.'' Certainly the rigid organization of
Communist East Germany proved that Germans can still be
indoctrinated to ignore the voice in their heads in favor of the
one coming through the loudspeaker. East Germany's largest
employers were the army and the Stasi, or secret police. Perhaps a
million people acted as occasional Stasi informants. Border guards
were persuaded to shoot fellow citizens who committed no other
crime than possession of a thirst for freedom.
</P>
<P>
   But Eichmann was wrong about the German nature. Overwhelming
propaganda can persuade normal people to kill their neighbors in
many places _ Serbia and Rwanda are two examples. East Germany's
petty conformists would not likely have sunk to the level of mass
murder, and West Germany shows that under a different system,
Germans can be as self-critical and questioning as anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   East Germany created a birth-to-death cocoon for its citizens.
The state took care of all aspects of what was a fairly comfortable
existence. Many, especially those in small towns far from the
contamination of West German television, had little exposure to
people or ideas that countered the official story.
</P>
<P>
   The least curious among them were drafted as border guards, and
then saturated with propaganda about the aggressive West and told
that only dangerous criminals tried to flee. (Even so, thousands of
border guards themselves made successful escapes to the West.)
Stasi collaborators had more diverse backgrounds. Some were victims
of extortion. Others informed for money, or were expertly
manipulated to feel that their relationship with the Stasi or their
handlers filled some psychological need in their lives. Many
informed because they were told it was their duty as citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were not adults,'' a dissident, Wolfgang Templin, once
told me of his fellow East Germans. ``What fascinated me about the
West when I was kicked out (of East Germany) was not the technology
or standard of living, it was that people were strong within
themselves ... they took their lives into their own hands.''
</P>
<P>
   When Germany decided to open the Stasi files to its victims, it
inadvertently hit on a productive way to stir the conscience of
those who followed orders and informed for the Stasi. Conscious
that they will be caught, they have come forward to confess to
those _ often close friends _ they spied on. This has produced a
torrent of soul-searching, as spies and victims met in smoky bars
and in televised confrontations. The national conversation has not
always been satisfying, but it has caused many Stasi informants to
face their acts for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   West Germany, whose habits dominate Germany today, still has a
culture that loves bureaucracy and order. No one eats on the
subway, and jaywalkers are scolded. It is unlikely that Germany
would ever produce a Solidarity movement like that of Poland, where
a history of rebellion is a source of national pride.
</P>
<P>
   But Germany would be unrecognizable to Eichmann today, and his
trial helped to change it. In 1961, after years of silence about
Nazi crimes, Germany was just beginning trials of war criminals.
The embarrassment of the Eichmann prosecution abroad gave them
momentum. The trial of Auschwitz camp guards in 1964 provided many
Germans with their first exposure to Nazi crimes _ in part because
it took place at a time when German youth, like youth around the
world, were in rebellion. Their parents never talked about the
crimes of the Nazis. The children, it seemed, spoke of little else.
In total, Germany has convicted more than 7,000 of its own citizens
for war crimes, many of them committed against foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Although the sentences have been extremely lenient, this is a
record of self-criticism no other country has approached. If
democracy has not exactly created a land of free spirits, it has
transformed the nation's political culture into one that Germans
cling to, in large part because they remember the crimes of
Eichmann and those Germans like him who followed orders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
