<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-VIKINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS IMPRESSIVE IN 36-21 WIN OVER VIKINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ With a rookie's blazing burst up the middle, with
a looping pass fired precisely over a defender into the arms of a
leaping receiver and with a defense that swarmed and befuddled a
record-setting offense, the Giants Friday night fashioned an
impressive and startlingly explosive beginning to their 1999
preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Such a start may prove meaningless in four months, but in about
one hour of football against the Minnesota Vikings, the Giants
displayed new confidence on offense and renewed resolve on defense.
</P>
<P>
   By the game's end, both teams had their third-stringers in
action in the Giants' 36-21 victory. But the Giants dominated both
lines of scrimmage in a little more than a quarter of play when
each team's first unit was on the field.
</P>
<P>
   No play epitomized these rejuvenated Giants more than running
back Sean Bennett's 53-yard, first-quarter sprint through the heart
of the Vikings' defense.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, a little-known, fourth-round draft pick this spring
from Northwestern who started the game only because of injuries to
several other running backs, caught a middle screen pass and then
sliced through a half-dozen Minnesota defenders. Benefiting from
superb blocks by guard Lance Scott and wide receiver Amani Toomer,
Bennett showed outstanding acceleration, running right past
Minnesota safeties Robert Griffith and Orlando Thomas for the
game's first touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   But the injury jinx dogging Giants running backs in training
camp continued into the exhibition season when Bennett left the
game early in the third quarter with a concussion. Bennett carried
up the middle for nine yards on his first carry of the second half,
but as he slid on the artificial turf at the end of the play he was
hit in the head by Minnesota safety Don Morgan, whose blow snapped
Bennett's head backward.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett got up slowly but did not return to the game, finishing
with 35 yards rushing on 10 carries and two receptions for 65
yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants played the game without coach Jim Fassel, who was in
Arizona with his critically ill mother, Dorothy. Jim Skipper, the
offensive coordinator, and John Fox, the defensive coordinator, ran
the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Giants' offense didn't let Bennett have the
spotlight all to himself. On the team's next possession,
quarterback Kent Graham, who completed five of six passes for 145
yards and two touchdowns, led the Giants on a five-play, 67-yard
drive. Graham connected with Toomer for nine yards, Ike Hilliard
for 18 yards on a perfectly executed underneath post pattern, and
then found Joe Jurevicius where the goal line meets the sideline
for his second touchdown, a 37-yard completion.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' defense, in turn, was harassing the Vikings' offense
into two turnovers. With frequent pressure on Minnesota quarterback
Randall Cunningham, the Vikings _ the most productive offense in
National Football League history a year ago _ generated only 51
yards in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Phillippi Sparks had a sack of Cunningham on a blitz
and also broke up a pass intended for Minnesota's Randy Moss. The
Giants' left defensive end Michael Strahan also repeatedly caused
trouble for the Vikings' front line, disrupting a handful of
running plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out and played well,'' Strahan said of the game's
beginning. ``We were fast and kept them in check. You don't want to
get too excited about the preseason but the first team really
played well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all knew coach Fassel was watching. We want to make him
proud and our hearts go out to him and his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham also said he was thinking of Fassel.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our leader and he's not here so it hurts,'' Graham said.
``We worked efficiently and effectively as a first unit. I felt
comfortable out there.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Giants' starting defense left the field, Jeff George
and the rest of the Vikings' second-string offense moved the ball
successfully, scoring 14 second-quarter points. The Giants, with
cornerbacks Jason Sehorn and Conrad Hamilton out with injuries, had
trouble defending some pass routes and were victimized by a 40-yard
pass interference penalty on the rookie defensive back Reggie
Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   But the Giants also added two Brad Daluiso field goals of 48 and
24 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Tiki Barber gave the Giants a 29-14 lead in the third quarter
with a shifty, darting run on a draw for a 6-yard touchdown run.
The backup quarterback Kerry Collins led that drive and another in
the fourth quarter that ended with a 5-yard touchdown pass to David
Patten. Earlier, Patten had dropped what would have been a
touchdown pass from Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, working exclusively with the second string, completed 5
of 17 passes for 127 yards with one touchdown and no interceptions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
