<HEADER>
A7062 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-SHOOTING-RAMPAGE-2TAK     08-14 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-RAMPAGE-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETAILS EMERGE OF FURROW'S BLOODY RAMPAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDS, runs with SHOOTING-SERGEANT, SHOOTING-HOPE, SHOOTING-KIDS,
SHOOTING-HATE) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A woman heard the ``pop, pop, pop'' of gunfire
outside her home about noon Tuesday and looked out her bedroom
window as postal carrier Joseph Santos Ileto ran for his life, she
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran at an angle. I thought, Oh, my God, this is real. I
grabbed the boys and made them go under the bed.''
</P>
<P>
   She immediately called 911 and said, ``Somebody shot my
mailman!''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until later that she learned she had witnessed the end
of Buford O'Neal Furrow Jr.'s rampage through Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The woman was home with her son and a nephew when a ``target of
opportunity'' emerged for Furrow: a nonwhite federal employee,
according to his confession to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   She said she couldn't get a clear view of the gunman because he
was behind thick bushes. She hurried outside to help but realized
it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became hysterical,'' she said, adding that she and her son
are getting help to deal with the emotional trauma and did not want
their names used.
</P>
<P>
   More details have emerged of the rampage that began with the
shooting of three small boys and two staff members at the North
Valley Jewish Community Center at 10:49 a.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after the shooting, Furrow is accused of hijacking a
Korean waitress' car and then threatening her four Korean
co-workers at gunpoint before fleeing, they said in interviews
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until later Tuesday night that the waitress and
sandwich shop workers realized they had come face to face with the
white supremacist who is accused of rampaging through the San
Fernando Valley, shooting five people at the North Valley Jewish
Community Center and killing a Filipino mail carrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so lucky,'' said the owner of Captain's Sub Sandwiches,
still visibly shaken from the encounter and unwilling to have his
name published. ``He's got the gun pointed at us. I don't want to
think about it now.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the shop, Furrow shot Ileto.
</P>
<P>
   Why Furrow didn't shoot the waitress and workers remains a
mystery to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would speculate that he was intent on getting away from the
location, and he probably didn't want to create any more
attention,'' said Los Angeles police Detective Brian Carr of the
Robbery-Homicide Division. ``But who knows, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Furrow dumped his van in back of the sandwich shop on Roscoe
Boulevard about 11:05 a.m., 16 minutes after the shooting at the
North Valley Jewish Community Center. He walked up behind the
waitress as she got out of her car to go to work and at gunpoint
demanded her car keys.
</P>
<P>
   She complied and somehow managed to get into the restaurant as
Furrow moved her car and began transferring his belongings,
including several firearms and ammunition, from his van to the
victim's car.
</P>
<P>
   She ran into the shop and hollered, ``Please help me, somebody
just took my car!'' the shop owner said.
</P>
<P>
   They ran outside and peeked around the corner of the building,
only to see Furrow loading bags of weapons into the 23-year-old
woman's green Toyota.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Get back in!''' the shop owner said.
</P>
<P>
   They ran into the store and locked the doors, while a customer
called 911 and then fled, fearing the gunman would somehow get in
and kill him.
</P>
<P>
   The sandwich shop encounter was among the details that began to
emerge about Furrow's shooting rampage, as police trace his bloody
trail through the San Fernando Valley and then to Hollywood and Las
Vegas, where he surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   After gunning down the postal worker, Furrow abandoned the
carjacked car at the 7-Star Suites hotel, walked to a Latino-owned
shop where he bought a new shirt and went to a Supercuts for a
haircut.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he needed a haircut,'' according to a police source.
</P>
<P>
   He then took a cab to Hollywood, where he had a few beers before
finding another cab that ultimately took him to Vegas. The source
also said that Furrow spent time in Chatsworth on the Sunday
evening before the shootings, drinking at a bar.
</P>
<P>
   Sandwich shop customers and the workers reflected on their good
fortune but expressed grief for the other victims of Furrow's
hatred.
</P>
<P>
   ``The postman did nothing. These people are working very hard
for a good life here in the United States. Why do these kind of
people hate them?'' asked one Korean customer.
</P>
<P>
   According to the sandwich shop owner, the waitress plans to
return to Korea and return to school for a degree in landscape
architecture. Although she recently wanted to return to her
homeland, Tuesday's rampage made up her mind, friends said.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUES ON NEW TAKE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
