<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MORTIMER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANLEY MORTIMER, 86, SPORTSMAN AND AD EXECUTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Pa.)  (mk) 
 By ENID NEMY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stanley Grafton Mortimer Jr., a sportsman, advertising executive
and member of one of the founding families of the exclusive enclave
of Tuxedo Park, N.Y., died on Wednesday after a long illness at his
home in Harriman, N.Y. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   Mortimer was a member of an illustrious American family. Through
his father, a Wall Street broker, he was a descendant of John Jay,
the first chief justice of the United States and a signer of the
Declaration of Independence. His mother, the former Kathleen
Tilford, was the daughter of Henry Morgan Tilford, a founder of
Standard Oil Co. of California.
</P>
<P>
   Mortimer grew up in Tuxedo Park in Keewaydin, a Stanford White
house that once belonged to Pierre Lorillard. The Mortimers and
Lorillards were the founding families of Tuxedo Park. Sally Bedell
Smith, in her book ``In All His Glory: The Life of William S.
Paley,'' noted that Mortimer's grandmother, the widow of Henry
Morgan Tilford, was for four decades one of the reigning dowagers
of Tuxedo Park, and that her annual debutante dinners before the
Autumn Ball determined which young women were approved for New York
society.
</P>
<P>
   Mortimer was educated at St. Mark's School and graduated from
Harvard in 1936. He served in the Pacific in World War II, rising
to lieutenant commander in the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   A vigorous sportsman, he was a member of the Jockey Club, and
his Keewaydin racing stable was successful for many years in
France. He was also a tennis player and low-handicap golfer, and he
took part in hunting-dog field trials.
</P>
<P>
   In his career, he was director of advertising for both Trans
World Airlines and Pan American World Airways.
</P>
<P>
   Mortimer was a member of the Racquet and Tennis Club in New
York; the National Golf Links and the Southampton Club on Long
Island, and the Tuxedo Park Club, where he served on the board of
governors.
</P>
<P>
   His first marriage, in 1940 to Barbara Cushing, ended in divorce
in 1946, and she later married Paley, the longtime leader of CBS.
The following year, Mortimer married Kathleen Harriman, daughter of
W. Averell Harriman and the granddaughter of E.H. Harriman, the
railroad tycoon.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife; five children, all of Manhattan _
Stanley Mortimer III and Amanda Mortimer Burden from his first
marriage, and David Mortimer, Jay Mortimer and Averell Mortimer
from his second marriage; two sisters, Eve Mortimer Ledyard of
Unionville, Pa., and Katherine Mortimer Blaine of Manhattan; two
brothers, Richard Mortimer of Southampton, N.Y., and John Jay
Mortimer of Manhattan, 10 grandchildren and one great-grandchild.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 0043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990814.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7066 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-SHOOTING-RAMPAGE-2ndT     08-14 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-RAMPAGE-2ndTAKE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
LOS ANGELES: ``mind, friends said.'' The possibility that Furrow may have cased high-profile Jewish
institutions also has been raised.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rabbi Marvin Hier, founder and dean of the Simon Wiesenthal
Center and its Museum of Tolerance, said police told him that a map
found in one of the vehicles Furrow used had the center, the
University of Judaism and another well-known Jewish institution
identified by sources as the Skirball Cultural Center.
</P>
<P>
   Hier said that museum staff believe Furrow visited there about
six weeks ago. The man showed no interest in the exhibits but was
constantly looking at the ceiling and left after security guards
moved close to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is quite possible we would have been the target,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The museum and the University of Judaism have increased security
since the attack. ``People ask whether security pays,'' Hier said.
``I think it does.''
</P>
<P>
   While Furrow was held in the federal detention center, Los
Angeles County District Attorney Gil Garcetti said Friday he was
continuing to meet with U.S. Attorney Alejandro Mayorkas to
determine who would get to try the case first.
</P>
<P>
   Furrow faces federal charges of murder of a federal employee and
weapons possession while a felon. State charges include murder with
the special circumstances that the slaying was motivated by hate
and while fleeing a crime. If convicted of either state or federal
charges, he could receive the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Furrow also is charged with five counts of attempted murder for
wounding the three children and two staff workers at the Jewish
Community Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure that justice is served in the best
manner,'' Garcetti said. ``We will continue to meet to resolve
jurisdictional issues and legal issues and hope to resolve that
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcetti said he is also concerned that Furrow will attempt to
use the trial as a forum to espouse his views _ and that not much
could be done to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he intends to use it as a forum, there isn't much we can do
to prevent him from taking the stand and explain why he did what he
did,'' Garcetti said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 100 people _ children in the center during the shooting
and their parents _ have applied for victims assistance through a
state program that offers up to $10,000 for private psychotherapy
and counseling, officials announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Other people, including those wounded in the shooting, the young
woman who was carjacked and family members of slain U.S. Post
Office worker Joseph Ileto, are also eligible for this assistance. &QL; 
The wounded can also qualify for up to $46,000 for out-of-pocket
medical costs, said Los Angeles City Attorney spokesman Mike
Qualls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is to provide whatever assistance that the victims
need to get through this tragedy,'' Qualls said. &QL; 
Anyone traumatized by coming to the aid of victims can apply for up
to $10,000 in ``Good Samaritan'' grants, although no one has done
that yet, he said. &QL; 
Staff with the City Attorney's Victim Assistance Unit met Friday
with the injured and their families, who are expected to sign up
for the assistance next week, Qualls said.
</P>
<P>
   The money is made available through the state Victim of Crimes
Fund, which is raised from fines imposed in criminal cases. &QL; 
Appearing before the Los Angeles City Council, Chief Bernard C.
Parks and other top police and fire officials detailed the
deployment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so proud of the men and women of the Los Angeles Police
Department and Los Angeles Fire Department for their
professionalism and their courage,'' said Mayor Richard Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   Parks vowed to continue working closely with federal agents to
seal the case against suspect Buford O'Neal Furrow Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very cowardly act to take advantage of some very
young people,'' said Parks. ``We will do all in our power to bring
him to justice to the fullest extent possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Police responded in four minutes, and 16 firefighters, including
seven paramedics, were at the site within eight minutes, Los
Angeles fire and police officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Every major agency involved in the event had officers on scene
within an hour _ an unusual feat of cooperation that resulted from
two years of intensive planning and training among local and
federal agencies, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my 15 years of law enforcement, the professionalism
displayed by the L.A. Fire Department, L.A. Police Department and
U.S. (law-enforcement agents) was of the highest caliber I have
ever witnessed,'' said Virginia O'Brian, assistant special agent
with the bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Council members praised officers and proposed solutions,
including a call by Councilman Mike Feuer to tighten gun control
laws and a demand by Councilman Alex Padilla to hire more police
officers and build new police facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan released a statement urging residents to reflect on the
events of this past week.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we begin to heal from the tragic events of this week, I
hope Angelenos take a few moments to reflect on the precious nature
of life,'' Riordan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I urge Angelenos to attend services at their places of worship
and pray for the victims, their families and for our city. Let us
also renew our commitment to work together, to respect each other
and to celebrate our diversity through knowledge and understanding.
By reaching out to one another, we will move beyond this dark
moment and emerge a better, stronger community.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
