<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARRY SHOULD FIT RIGHT IN WITH NEW, NASTIER SONICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Not even a game played yet, and already Brent Barry
has a Sonics record: Quickest cringe from management after hearing
a player's opening press conference remarks.
</P>
<P>
   At his first media chat Friday at the Sonics practice facility,
the newcomer guard, acquired for the venerable Hersey Hawkins, was
explaining how delighted he was to be leaving the Chicago Bulls,
the NBA's third-worst team last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to sound abrasive,'' said Barry, ``but you can't
make chicken salad out of chicken (poop).''
</P>
<P>
   After Wally Walker, Paul Westphal and Billy McKinney
collectively blanched, Barry apologized to the TV cameras for his
barnyard bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the cringe record, Barry also raised the bar for next
season on what will constitute abrasiveness, proved he inherited
more from his dad than merely a passion for offense, and provided
more color in one sentence than Hawkins did in his four years as a
Sonic.
</P>
<P>
   Say this about the 1999-2000 Sonics: They may not be able to
play a lick, but in a heckle contest against Chris Rock, Dennis
Miller and David Letterman, take the Seattles and spot the
entertainers a Sam Kinison CD.
</P>
<P>
   With Barry, Gary Payton, Vernon Maxwell, Ruben (``The Kobe
Stopper'') Patterson, Jelani McCoy and even little rookie guard
Shammond Williams, Seattle may become the world capital of smack.
Move over, Starbucks: Here comes Swearbucks.
</P>
<P>
   What all this means for wins and losses is dubious. Sonics coach
Paul Westphal, good Christian man that he is, nevertheless will own
up to an abstract appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot easier to rein people back,'' he said, ``than to
light a fire.''
</P>
<P>
   That observation summarizes as well as anything what the Sonics
have tried to do this offseason. If anything can summarize it.
</P>
<P>
   The curious, almost desperate moves made by the Sonics after
missing the playoffs as well as Mitch Richmond are at first hard to
comprehend, particularly with perspective still fresh from the
free-agent debacles of eight months earlier in preparation for the
lockout-degraded 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics have so far failed to land an impact player, or a
name that will sell tickets, or a guy that will make the rest of
the NBA take Seattle seriously again as a contender.
</P>
<P>
   What they have acquired are provocateurs who are, to use
Walker's words, ``mean, ornery and tough.''
</P>
<P>
   If Westphal finds he can't handle it, here's a suggestion for a
replacement: Jack Palance.
</P>
<P>
   But if Westphal maintains control of this milling snarl, the
possibility exists that the group will at least be entertaining, in
a pro wrestling sort of way.
</P>
<P>
   This new mix of personalities and talents is so abrupt and
volatile that no one, including Walker and Westphal, can say with
much authority how it will turn out.
</P>
<P>
   Walker is on record as guaranteeing the playoffs, and Friday
Westphal said, ``I'll back him on that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fact is, the Sonics last season would have been a
playoff team with one more win. So forecasting a one-game
improvement is not exactly leaping to the distant end of the limb.
</P>
<P>
   What is more significant is whether the Sonics can make the
final four in the West, which requires winning a first-round
series. That reasonable goal is what the Sonics not only missed
last year, but nearly blew the two previous years under George
Karl.
</P>
<P>
   After making the Finals in 1996, the Sonics had to go to five
excruciating games in 1997's first round to get past undermanned
Phoenix. Same thing happened in 1998 against even more undermanned
Minnesota. After those narrow escapes against more youthful,
energetic teams, the conclusion was that the Sonics looked old and
slow, which the second-round defeats bore out.
</P>
<P>
   So the departures of Detlef Schrempf, 36, Dale Ellis, 39, Hersey
Hawkins, 33 next month, along with the previous season's departures
of Sam Perkins and Nate McMillan, were as necessary from a
strategic standpoint as they were regrettable from a personality
standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Things change faster in the NBA than they do in any other sport,
and the Sonics stayed pat longer than most, thanks mostly to Karl's
reluctance to use younger players. The league changed even more in
'99 with the new labor agreement as well as the impending rules
changes emphasizing quickness over strength, and offense over
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in Walker's free-agent blunders with Jim McIlvaine, Craig
Ehlo and Billy Owens, and the Sonics' rigidity and mistakes made
the fall from eminence swift and brutal.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Payton now finds himself the only player remaining
from the '96 team. But it's hardly unique. The only remaining
member of the Bulls team that beat them will be Toni Kukoc.
</P>
<P>
   Given that the Sonics needed help on so many fronts, the failure
to acquire Richmond might turn out to be a help simply because the
Sonics will spread out more salary to more players on the rise,
such as Barry and Patterson, instead of a star in decline.
</P>
<P>
   Next season likely won't be pretty, but it will be much like
your average grunge or hip-hop show: Noisy and wild.
</P>
<P>
   Check your sensitivities at the KeyArena door.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
