<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS KICK OFF HOLMGREN ERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. _ Mike Holmgren's face is everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   In newspaper ads and on TV spots promoting season-ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   On the cover of the Seahawks media guide.
</P>
<P>
   On a 10-by-20-foot banner that hangs from the side of the field
house at Eastern Washington University, overlooking the practice
fields and giving a ``Big Brother is Watching'' feel to the team's
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   And, even more noticeably, in the faces of his new players as he
prepares them for the most anticipated season in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night's game against the Buffalo Bills is only the
preseason opener. But like everything else that has transpired
since Holmgren was named executive vice president of football
operations/general manager and head coach, his first game looms
with the allure of Mount Rainier on a sunny afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   With all eyes on Holmgren, what does he need to see from his
team?
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to win, first,'' Holmgren said Friday after the team's
light 45-minute workout. ``But almost more importantly is to be
able to come away from the preseason making fair, honest, good
decisions on who we keep. So I have to get answers out of the
preseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Mistakes kill that evaluation process, so Holmgren wants during
this game the same things he demands in practice _ efficiency and
crispness, not mistakes and sloppiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we're going to be working hard on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren admits he always feels pressure before a game. If he is
experiencing it more because of the heightened expectations that
are rooted in his presence, he isn't showing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I've ever walked out of a tunnel and on the field
for a game, preseason or regular season, I realize how fortunate I
am,'' Holmgren said. ``I love what I do, and I get to do that
because it's fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first game as a Seahawks coach, there will be a lot of
stuff running through my mind, but I'll be very excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren was somewhat bewildered by his last visit to the
Kingdome. It was in 1996 and he was on the opposite sideline as
coach of the Green Bay Packers. The Packers undressed the Seahawks,
31-10. But an even bigger embarrassment to the team and the
franchise were the green-and-gold clad Packers fans who nearly
outnumbered and definitely out-yelled the ``hometown'' fans,
turning the Kingdome into Lambeau West.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a very unusual day,'' Holmgren said. ``I trust that
won't be the case (Saturday).''
</P>
<P>
   But just how many fans will turn out for Holmgren's debut? Will
the buzz generated by his arrival, when 904 orders for season
tickets were taken on the day he was hired, translate into bodies
in the stands for a preseason game?
</P>
<P>
   More than 55,000 season tickets have been sold _ a far cry from
the 62,000 that was the norm in the mid-1980s but also far better
than the 34,000 total when billionaire Paul Allen bought the
franchise in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren has become the pitch man. Or at least his face has.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never had to be the focus point in selling tickets
before,'' said Holmgren, a slight smile spreading across that
ever-present face. ``I think if we put a really good product on the
field, the people will want to come and watch us.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Clare Farnsworth can be reached at 206-448-8016
</P>
<P>
   or clarefarnsworth &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
