<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-WHITE-SOX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-BAYLOR PITCHER HELPS WHITE SOX SWEEP RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
Ex-Baylor pitcher helps White Sox sweep Rangers
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Rangers and the Chicago White Sox had to dip into
their minor leagues last night for a starting pitcher to get them
through a doubleheader.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox chose their No. 1 draft pick from last year, a
former All-American out of Baylor. The Rangers had to settle for
Ryan Glynn, whose first trip to the majors earlier this summer
wasn't exactly stellar.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage worked both ways for the White Sox in a
doubleheader sweep over the Rangers last night at Comiskey Park.
</P>
<P>
   Kip Wells, making just his second major-league start, held the
Rangers to one run on three hits through five innings, and the
White Sox went on to a 4-2 victory in the first game.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 2, the White Sox pounded Glynn for seven runs in
five-plus innings and completed the sweep with a 7-4 victory. White
Sox starter James Baldwin held the Rangers scoreless for six
innings while his teammates were working over Glynn.
</P>
<P>
   The two losses and the Oakland Athletics' 9-8 victory over the
Toronto Blue Jays cut the Rangers lead to 5 1/2 games in the
American League West. That's their smallest lead since July 21,
when they were five ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating all the way through,'' first baseman Rafael
Palmeiro said. ``We just didn't execute tonight. We've got a good
hitting team, but overall we were flat tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers played both games without right fielder Juan
Gonzalez, who was sidelined for a third consecutive day with
tightness in his left hamstring muscle. They also rested catcher
Ivan Rodriguez and third baseman Todd Zeile in the second game and
had to make do in both games with left fielder Rusty Greer and
center fielder Tom Goodwin, both of whom are obviously not 100
percent healed from their leg injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fine,'' manager Johnny Oates said. ``Short-handed? No.
Banged up? Yeah. But I don't think that had anything to do with the
way we played.''
</P>
<P>
   Glynn, who allowed nine hits, three walks and a balk, is 2-4
with an 7.24 earned-run average in 13 major-league games, and he'll
likely be sent back to Triple-A Oklahoma. Danny Kolb is expected to
rejoin the team as a long reliever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glynn threw more strikes,'' Oates said. ``I know he gave up
seven runs _ he missed location, got some balls up and it hurt him
_ but he wasn't ball two, ball three every time. He was around the
plate, I was glad to see that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells was optioned back to the minors last night, but there's
little doubt he'll be back for an extended stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very impressive,'' Oates said. ``He moved the ball
around, it looked like the ball went where he wanted it to go. We
had some ugly swings against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells was taken 16th overall in last year's draft, six spots
after the Rangers used their first-round pick to take Northeastern
University first baseman Carlos Pena. He won his only other
major-league start Aug. 2, beating the Detroit Tigers, and the only
reason he doesn't have a permanent job in the majors is that the
White Sox have been unable to trade veteran starter Jamie Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew coming in there would be a good chance I'd be going
back,'' said Wells, who is 6-1 with a 2.18 ERA at Birmingham. ``I
just wanted to give them a good performance out there. I'm not
down. It's part of the game. This is my first year, I didn't expect
to walk in and take over.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had Wells in trouble a couple of times but failed to
deliver a punishing blow. Instead they let him slip through five
innings, allowing just one run before turning it over to the White
Sox bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Wells started the third by giving up a double to Roberto Kelly
and walking Royce Clayton. But Goodwin fouled off two bunt
attempts, then _ after the rain delay _ struck out. Wells then got
Mark McLemore on a fly to short left and Ivan Rodriguez on a
grounder to short to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers got a run off Wells in the fourth but, with runners
at first and third, he escaped a bigger mess by striking out Kelly
and Clayton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kip came in with a big outing at a time we sorely needed a
lift,'' White Sox manager Jerry Manuel said. ``It's impressive he
knows how to pitch when he gets in trouble. He has a very good
presence on the mound.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
