<SLUG> BC-TEN-GRAF-REACTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOES RECALL GRAF'S TALENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ It is apropos that the WTA Tour played
down the road from Hollywood. Studios, celebrities and limelight
were just a brief drive from women's tennis and its stars.
</P>
<P>
   It also is apropos that Steffi Graf wasn't there.
</P>
<P>
   As Graf announced her retirement Friday in her hometown of
Heidelberg, Germany, WTA players at Manhattan Country Club in the
Acura Classic reacted mostly with surprise and sadness to Graf's
announcement, using the words ``professional,'' ``hard-working''
and ``quiet'' to describe her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steffi was remarkable in that she played tennis, but she
didn't want anything to do with the politics of it,'' Lindsay
Davenport said. ``She just wanted to get out there and play tennis,
and that was admirable. She just loved to play tennis and that was
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, in all, it's a sad day for tennis,'' said Aranxta
Sanchez-Vicario, one of Graf's top rivals from 1989 to 1996. ``I am
kind of sad because I have great memories playing against Steffi.
It's hard to think she's not going to be there any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Austin, who beat Graf in her professional debut in
Filderstadt, Germany, in 1982, recounted the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was this 14-year-old kid who hit the ball so hard I
couldn't believe it,'' Austin said, at the tournament working for
TV. ``I said to myself, `Who is this kid? I've never heard of her.'
She was painting the lines, but I ended up winning 6-4, 6-0.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Graf won her first professional tournament,
beating Chris Evert in Hilton Head. That victory was the beginning
of a storied career in which she held the No. 1 ranking from Aug.
17, 1987 to March 10, 1991 and won a Grand Slam, all four major
tournaments, in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Martina Hingis, who staked her claim as the top player in the
world during Graf's recent absence, could never control Graf on the
court, losing seven of nine matches against her. But after her
return, while Graf was playing well, she was no longer dominant.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was like an icon when I played her,'' Hingis said. ``You
always want to beat the No. 1 player, but I barely had a chance in
the beginning. She always killed me. ... She was a great legend and
still is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 0050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
