<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FENWAY FOLLIES CONTINUE FOR MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Built 87 years ago, the dull green ballpark is on its
last legs. People come for the history. Unless you are the Seattle
Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, Fenway memories are getting tiresome as well.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to a long list of unpleasant visits, the Mariners twice
battled back to take the lead and a third time to tie, then settled
into old habits Friday night and lost 11-6 to the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Gone was a three-game win streak. Gone were any whispers of wild
card. Still there is the Green Monster and its fondness for
anything wearing blue with Seattle stitched across the front of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, you can't walk people,'' manager Lou Piniella said. ``In
this ballpark, you can't put people on _ they score.''
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Brian Daubach was a large part of the Boston
welcoming committee, doubling twice, homering once and driving in a
career-best five runs. Teammates Troy O'Leary had a bases-clearing
triple and Darren Lewis a career-high five runs.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was the Mariners' 10th in their past 12 appearances in
the tea party city, their 85th in 138 games here. The Mariners have
won only two season series at Fenway in franchise history, 1984 and
1989, and unless they sweep the next two games, that dry spell is
going to stretch to 10 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``They play well at home; they're a tough team to beat at
home,'' catcher Dan Wilson said. ``But I can't see any reason for
their consistency against us. Tonight, we just didn't do the things
we needed to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Ken Griffey Jr. of franchise-long Fenway failures, ``That's
too much stuff to pay attention to.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's a little more tangled than all that.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' woes extend well beyond the 420-mark in deep
center at Fenway. Simply put, this Seattle club can't play with the
big boys this year, no matter where the ballpark is located, even
if it's on Royal Brougham Way (see recent Yankee series, an 0-for-4
effort).
</P>
<P>
   Entering this matchup, the Mariners had won just four of 15
series against teams now with winning records, splitting three.
Their overall record against teams in the plus-column was 18-26.
Since late June, the Mariners had won just two series against clubs
over .500, sweeping Texas and taking two of three against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, Piniella used the first of three rookie pitchers
he intends to start against the Red Sox. Freddy Garcia lasted just
four innings. Which doesn't bode well, considering he's the most
established of the first-year mound trio.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia left with a 5-4 lead and two runners on in the fifth. His
replacement? The once-hearty, since-smarting Jeff Fassero, now
working on his second bullpen banishment. Fassero's third pitch was
ripped to right by Daubach for a double to put the Red Sox up 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   David Bell's grounder tied the game at 6-6 in the sixth, but
Fassero gave it right back with a four-spot in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The lefty walked the leadoff hitter, watched a sacrifice bunt
get thrown into center field by replacement first baseman Raul
Ibanez and, with one out, walked Nomar Garciaparra intentionally.
O'Leary socked an 0-1 Fassero pitch into the right-field corner to
clear the bases and leave no questions, then O'Leary scored on
Jason Varitek's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Ibanez, subbing for an injured John Mabry, made no excuses for
his miscue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blew it,'' he said quietly. ``I just threw it away.''
</P>
<P>
   It all added up to more Fenway misery, as well as Fassero's 14th
loss in 18 decisions, the setback tying his high in the majors. He
was 13-14 for Montreal in 1995. He is just five from the Mariners
record for losses by a pitcher in a season, shared by Matt Young
(1985) and Mike Moore (1987).
</P>
<P>
   Besides the game, the Mariners lost Mabry to a bruised knee,
leaving them in a manpower predicament. The club already was one
player short on the bench, choosing to keep a full bullpen while
reliever Jose Paniagua first serves a fight-related suspension,
then fellow reliever Frankie Rodriguez follows suit.
</P>
<P>
   Mabry fouled a ball hard off his right knee in the second
inning, tried to keep playing, but had to leave two innings later
after reaching base with a single. His status will be evaluated
daily, but his immediate availability appears shaky at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how he feels, but I doubt if he'll be able to play
(today),'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   As the manager relayed that bit of news, outfielder Charles
Gipson was headed out the door with a bag over his once-injured
shoulder. He was headed up the road, to Class AA New Haven, for a
rehab assignment. Guess it was too late to call him back.
</P>
<P>
   But Gipson might have been the smart one, making an early exit
from Fenway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 0050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
