r s BC-BKC-UCLA-REED-LADN     08-14 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-REED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVIS REED TRANSFERS TO LONG BEACH STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Former UCLA basketball player Travis Reed said
Friday he has decided to attend Long Beach State rather than
Oklahoma, ending a summer of speculation where he'd wind up.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-8 forward will become eligible to play for the 49ers
in the 2000-2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long Beach State is closer to home,'' Reed said, explaining
the decision he's been mulling most of the summer. ``I also have a
family situation to take care of, and I couldn't do that back there
(in Oklahoma).''
</P>
<P>
   Reed previously signed financial-aid agreements with Long Beach
State and Oklahoma, though neither was binding. Reed said he will
be on the Long Beach State campus for the beginning of school
Aug.30.
</P>
<P>
   Reed had committed to the 49ers while he was at Fontana High,
then changed his mind and ended up at UCLA, where he played for two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``UCLA had always been a dream of mine,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   So, why transfer now from UCLA to Long Beach State?
</P>
<P>
   ``In order for me to get to the next level I have to play my
total game,'' Reed said. ``I wasn't playing my total game at UCLA.
At Long Beach State, I believe I'll be able to show my skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed said he sees no problem switching from the fast-paced
Pac-10 Conference to the Big West.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pac-10 is a fast conference, probably the fastest
conference in the country,'' Reed said. ``The Big West will be a
change. But there are good teams and good players in the Big West.
Players do get drafted out of the Big West.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the idea of playing for Coach Wayne Morgan and
assistant Tom Lewis, who has been recruiting Reed since his high
school days, is appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be interesting,'' Reed said. ``They're two great coaches
on the way up.''
</P>
<P>
   At UCLA, Reed played in 27 games his freshman year, 31 games
last season, altogether starting just seven. He averaged 4.0 points
per game as a freshman, 5.4 points as a sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   Since he's transferring, Reed must redshirt the coming season.
</P>
<P>
   Not a problem, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be that tough,'' Reed said. ``In the Olympics, they
train four years for one event, right? The year will go by fast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
