<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALKS, ERA ASIDE, MECHE MESHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He is the youngest player in the Mariners clubhouse,
often alone in his thoughts and pregame workouts. But after seven
outings on the mound, 20-year-old Gil Meche feels like he belongs
in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Meche, who will pitch again Sunday at Fenway Park, has won three
of five decisions and demonstrated rare poise for someone so young.
The downside is a 6.61 earned run average and 23 walks in 322/3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm just being too fine,'' he said of his frequent
free passes. ``I'm not trusting my stuff like I should be. It seems
like if I get through the first few innings, I'm OK. I know I have
good stuff, I just have to use it. That's why I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   Meche pitched just once for the Mariners during spring training,
but it was enough to make a lasting impression. Manager Lou
Piniella liked his composure, then and now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really a good looking young pitcher; he's a
blue-chipper,'' Piniella said. ``Remember, he's a young man, just
20 years old. He's still got to find himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Meche says he's not making adjustments quickly enough when he
runs into trouble. Against the Chicago White Sox for instance, he
walked a batter on four pitches. Rather than regroup, he walked the
next batter on four pitches. Then he straightened himself out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the kind of pitcher I am,'' Meche said. ``But if
that's the worst it can get, and I keep winning games, that's all I
can hope for.''
</P>
<P>
   The youngster has been to Fenway once before; in 1995, he was a
member of the U.S. Junior Olympic Team. He didn't get a chance to
pitch on that trip.
</P>
<P>
   That will change Sunday, when he opposes Boston's Mark Portugal,
a veteran pitcher 16 years older.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am definitely looking forward to pitching here,'' Meche
said. ``I think about all the legends who have pitched here, and
I'll be on the same mound. Babe Ruth pitched here.''
</P>
<P>
   HUSKEY REVISITED: A former Mariner for three weeks now, Butch
Huskey got effusive hugs from Piniella and Ken Griffey Jr. during
pregame workouts. He chatted up several other Seattle players
behind the batting cage. A big bear of a man with a wide smile, he
was the same old Huskey, except for one thing.
</P>
<P>
   Huskey wore No. 44, rather than his trademark 42.
</P>
<P>
   The outfielder is one of the few players allowed to wear the
latter digits, receiving grandfathered rights after the number was
retired league-wide two years ago to honor Jackie Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Huskey wore the number in deference to Robinson. He passed this
time because he saw potential conflict; former Red Sox standout Mo
Vaughn, who was immensely popular at Fenway, wore 42. Boston
catcher Lenny Webster did the same when acquired earlier in the
year; he wears 38 instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to come in and make a name for Butch Huskey instead
of being compared to Mo Vaughn,'' Huskey said. ``I knew it would
happen if I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Huskey initially inquired about No. 36, his high school jersey,
but it belongs to injured reliever Tom Gordon. Huskey can reclaim
42 at any time, in Boston or elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   HURT FEELINGS ONLY: This time Red Sox catcher Scott Hatteberg is
the one shaking off the signs. The Tacoma resident and one-time
Washington State University player has been told to go back on the
60-day disabled list after missing all but six games this season
with a shoulder injury,
</P>
<P>
   His answer: He's healthy, ready to play and going to fight this.
</P>
<P>
   Hatteberg, the Red Sox's starting catcher the past two seasons,
says he has done all that's been asked. He has rehabilitated
himself, tested his shoulder in the minors and received medical
clearance from team physicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel they're saying I can't help the team this year,'' he
said. ``But there are rules to protect the players and keep them
from getting passed down. I'm not going.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatteberg, Boston's alternate players' representative, says he
has contacted the Major League Baseball Players Association
regarding the matter and won't sign anything indicating he's not
healthy.
</P>
<P>
   By taking this somewhat radical action, the catcher says he
expects to be activated or waived this weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
