<SLUG> BC-NY-SLASHED-BOY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO 12-YEAR-OLDS CHARGED WITH SLASHING NECK OF 8-YEAR-OLD BOY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two 12-year-old Queens boys have been arrested and
charged with slashing the neck of an 8-year-old boy as he played in
the front yard of his family's home in Long Island City, the police
said.
</P>
<P>
   The victim, Adis Lucevic, was playing with a younger cousin
about 7 p.m. Thursday at his home on 35th Street when the two boys,
wearing bandannas over their faces, entered the fenced-in yard and
drew a single-edge razor blade across his throat, the investigators
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we know, they didn't have any motive,'' said
Detective Joseph Pentangelo, a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Adis' father, Amer Lucevic, heard the commotion from inside the
house and ran after the two boys. A passing police car joined the
chase, and the two boys were caught a few blocks away, at 36th
Street and 34th Avenue, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Adis was taken to Elmhurst Hospital Center, where the doctors
used 75 stitches to close the wound, which was on the left side of
his neck, a hospital spokeswoman said. He was released Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Lucevic said his son did not provoke the incident. ``He told me,
`Daddy, I never saw these boys before in my life,''' Lucevic said.
``They just passed by and did what they did.''
</P>
<P>
   The youths, whose names were not released because of their ages,
have been charged with assault and attempted murder, Pentangelo
said. The youths will be prosecuted in Family Court, the Queens
District Attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the boys may have had a previous brush with crime. As the
boys were being arrested by the police, a passer-by identified him
as one of five youths who mugged him on July 29 outside a health
club on 38th Street in Astoria. The youth has been charged with
robbery for his role in that incident, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Lucevic, speaking from his home, said his son has made a
remarkable recovery. ``He's happy to be back,'' he said. ``The only
thing is that he doesn't want to play outside anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
