<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ERICKSON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OREGON STATE JOB NO STEP DOWN TO ERICKSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORVALLIS, Ore. _ Did he lose his job and then his mind?
Questions were as persistent as the reporters asking them, and
Dennis Erickson stood there Friday like Alex Rodriguez, fielding
and firing, flawlessly handling all of the curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   Although many believe otherwise, Erickson said he has not made
an error in becoming the head coach at Oregon State, that it is not
a step down, just a proper move at this time in his 52-year-old
life.
</P>
<P>
   Were it not for a dubious touchdown awarded to the New York Jets
that prevented the Seahawks from advancing to the playoffs,
Erickson could be standing in the Kingdome tonight, wearing the
customary headset and quizzical look, coaching against the Buffalo
Bills.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he will be on the sidelines at Reser Stadium, formerly
Parker Stadium, conducting his first fall workout with the Beavers.
Erickson is delighted with the opportunity, spurred by the
challenge, and it doesn't matter if the cynics think he's gone mad.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I took the job, the least of my worries was what other
people thought in the, quote, public,'' he said. ``When I talked to
other coaches, they said it was a chance to put your signature on
something and leave a legacy. Nobody said: `Hey, you're a dummy.'''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, given the chance, brain surgeons and rocket
scientists would fail here, too, but Erickson is a coach known for
resurrecting sluggish programs.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson appeared relaxed as he gave his Beavers briefing to the
media Friday. He assessed his team's few strengths and many
weaknesses from the Valley Football Center, which looks down upon
the new artificial turf and bright orange Oregon State end zones.
</P>
<P>
   Reser still resembles an overgrown high school stadium, but
there will be plenty of people in the seats this year. Erickson's
hiring and a 5-6 record last year have ignited a season-ticket
sales record; more than 10,000 fans want to see every home game.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson has gone from Jon Kitna as his starting quarterback to
Jonathan Smith, who threw for 469 yards against the Huskies last
year.
</P>
<P>
   This is how much things have changed: Rather than discussing the
Seahawks' first three opponents _ Detroit, Chicago and Pittsburgh _
Erickson talked about the importance of getting off to a good start
against Nevada, Fresno State and Georgia Southern.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the ease with which Oregon State defeated Nevada last
year, Erickson was asked if the Beavers might be caught looking
past the Wolfpack. At that moment Erickson showed he knew where he
was, in Corvallis, where losing has reigned for 27 straight
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason to be complacent at Oregon State,'' he said.
``You've got to be kidding me.''
</P>
<P>
   As coach of the Seahawks, Erickson seemed uptight at times,
recognizing the uncertainty of his status.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hard year,'' said Gregg Smith, former Seahawks
assistant head coach who has joined Erickson here. ``There is
always that thing in the back of your mind. You wonder: `Can you
really coach?' You second-guess yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Erickson was decisive and even humorous, poking fun at himself,
acknowledging that he had seen a picture of himself at his last
Pac-10 stop at Washington State in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had black hair, a little buffed up, it wasn't bad,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his first return to the Palouse to face the Cougars
on Oct. 30, Erickson said: ``Martin Stadium? It will be
interesting. From what I understand, they've got long memories in
Pullman. They threw stuff at me when I was coaching there, so
what's the difference?''
</P>
<P>
   His best line was this one: ``This team can win more games than
it loses and go to a bowl game.''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone laughed, it was inaudible, because Erickson was
serious this time. If you want to buy into this laughingstock, your
shares are about to soar, or so Erickson believes.
</P>
<P>
   There were many reasons why he came to Corvallis, and Erickson
rehashed them all: his ties to the Northwest, his desire to return
to college football, to call the plays, to help shape the lives of
his players, to experience the campus excitement on game days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to prove I can do it,'' he said. ``That's as big a part
of me as there is, to turn around something that hasn't been turned
around for 28 years.''
</P>
<P>
   He will follow the Seahawks, read about them on the Internet and
watch their games on Sunday. But it will not be his focus. If that
was the mountaintop, this is the Willamette Valley, and Erickson
plans to rise again.
</P>
<P>
   Why can't it happen here, just like it did in Moscow and Laramie
and Pullman, where he revived Idaho, Wyoming and Washington State
before maintaining the high standards at Miami?
</P>
<P>
   Erickson reluctantly talks about the situation in Seattle, not
wanting to discuss leftovers when he's got a new main course in
front of him. He says he is proud of his four years with the
Seahawks, inheriting a 2-14 team and making it respectable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think I did a very good job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson could have sat out a season and considered other
options while earning more than a million dollars from the
Seahawks. Because he is a coach who relishes improbable tasks,
Erickson chose to tackle the ultimate renovation project.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted this opportunity, it wasn't like he needed to do
this,'' said Ron Davis, Oregon State's director of football
operations, who also came with Erickson from Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   If he can succeed here, they just might name a street after him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a unique challenge,'' Smith said. ``The first coach that
takes this team to a bowl game, his next job might be governor. I
know one thing: If it can be done, Dennis will do everything in his
power to make sure it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe no one in Seattle can believe the Everett native's
apparent downward mobility, but the move is intriguing, turning
Corvallis into a fascination station where Erickson hopes to avoid
train wrecks past.
</P>
<P>
   In a mutually beneficial way, even if neither is deserved,
Erickson and Oregon State will search for respect together in what
is generally viewed as a strange convergence of coach and team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes things are applicable at certain times of your
life,'' he said. ``This is a fun place for me to be. I could be
perfectly happy here a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Moore can be reached at 206-448-8013
</P>
<P>
   or jimmoore &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
