<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TAIWAN-CRISIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A WORSENING CRISIS OVER TAIWAN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Aug. 14:
</P>
<P>
   With tensions mounting dangerously across the Taiwan Strait,
both sides need to step back and consider the risks they are
courting _ Taipei by its reckless declarations and Beijing by its
unacceptable military threats.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan and the mainland have escalated the crisis by repeatedly
flying warplanes in the direction of each other's territory.
Chinese publications now regularly report on Beijing's preparedness
to assault Taiwanese-held territory, and Taiwan's president, Lee
Teng-hui, holds to his provocative demand that China deal with his
island as a separate sovereign state.
</P>
<P>
   Any military clash between China and Taiwan would imperil
Taiwan's prosperity and democracy, threaten China's economic
development and gravely damage relations between Washington and
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, like most countries, recognizes Beijing's as
the only lawful government of China. Washington considers Taiwan
geographically part of China, but not currently subject to mainland
political rule. That widely accepted formula leaves the question of
China's eventual reunification to be resolved peacefully, at a
later date, by people on both sides of the Taiwan Strait.
Meanwhile, America is committed to providing Taiwan with adequate
means to defend itself against attack.
</P>
<P>
   That sensible arrangement was deliberately challenged last month
by Lee with his new formula of two separate sovereign states.
Beijing predictably and unjustifiably responded with threats of
military force. Concern has centered on the possible blockade,
shelling or occupation of several small islands controlled by
Taiwan just off the Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Four decades ago, Chinese shelling of the two offshore islands
Quemoy (now called Kinmen) and Matsu brought American warships to
the Taiwan Strait and Washington and Beijing close to military
confrontation. Relations between the United States and China have
come a long way since that unhappy era. Beijing should not risk
reversing that progress with a new episode of aggression.
</P>
<P>
   In the event of Chinese military action against Taiwan,
President Clinton would have little choice but to chill relations
with Beijing, freeze economic talks and consider whether American
military intervention was warranted. The administration must be
sure that Beijing understands these likely consequences before
China resorts to force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 0104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990814.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7083 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-OMAK-RACE-SPI &LR;      08-14 1349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OMAK-RACE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OMAK STAMPEDE JUST NOT THE SAME WITHOUT FAMED SUICIDE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REBEKAH DENN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAK, Wash. _ As daylight began to fade at the Omak Stampede,
Christopher Newman pointed toward Suicide Hill and explained how it
should look.
</P>
<P>
   Right about now, he told Maxime Vroman, his friend, people would
be lining the riverbed to watch the Suicide Race.
</P>
<P>
   There would be a nervousness in the air, he said, as spectators
waited for the horses to come flying over the top of the
near-vertical hill.
</P>
<P>
   But the description was the best he could do for Vroman, who
came all the way from France to watch the race, only to learn it
had been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you explain that experience?'' Newman asked, unhappily.
``It's one you have to see for yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, he turned to Vroman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you come again next year?''
</P>
<P>
   The Stampede, which began Thursday and runs through Sunday,
still features a rollicking rodeo and a lively carnival.
</P>
<P>
   But attendees and organizers agree: It just isn't the same this
year without the Suicide Race and Native American encampment that
have been highlights for more than a half-century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm left-handed, and it feels like I don't have my left arm,''
said Jack Miller, the Stampede's vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Stampede officials canceled the race after the Colville
Confederated Tribes boycotted the Stampede in an 11th-hour dispute
over parking and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal members normally make up most of the riders in the race _
the Stampede's most popular and controversial event. During the
races, which take place each night of the Stampede, horses barrel
over the hill and swim across the Okanogan River.
</P>
<P>
   The event draws tens of thousands of visitors to Omak, and they
spend $3.5 million on motels, restaurants, gasoline, Stampede belt
buckles and other knicknacks.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Miller estimates ticket sales are down 20 percent to 30
percent from the 30,000 people who normally attend the Stampede.
</P>
<P>
   It will take some time to gauge whether lower attendance this
year would significantly affect the sales-tax revenues that help
bolster Okanogan County's $42 million budget, said John Rayburn,
director of the county's Economic Development Council.
</P>
<P>
   His initial impression _ judging from the patches of empty grass
he saw on the camping grounds normally packed bumper-to-bumper _
was that the county would notice the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know,'' said Cheryl Lampe, president of the Omak
Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The Stampede, she said, is never a sure bet, with bad weather
sometimes discouraging visitors from shopping downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The daily Suicide Races have been crossed out by hand on the
thousands of printed Stampede schedules, but there's nothing to be
done about the emblem featured on everything from the Stampede
banners strung along Main Street to the menus at a downtown pub.
</P>
<P>
   On the grassy field at the Stampede grounds downtown, normally
crowded with Native American singers and dancers and games, one
empty tepee stands alone, pitched as a symbol by a tribal member.
</P>
<P>
   It was the field that caused the tension between Stampede
organizers and the tribe.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal members said they objected to plans to restrict tribal
parking on the field. They were concerned, too, because they felt
the encampment was being moved around too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks just bare here,'' said Pearl Charley, a member of the
Yakama tribe, as she cooked golden fry bread in bubbling oil at a
picnic table on the field's edge.
</P>
<P>
   Charley drove to the Stampede with her daughters to sell the
bread, and she was amazed to see the encampment grounds vacant.
</P>
<P>
   She had heard talk of a boycott, she said, but she didn't
realize it was that serious.
</P>
<P>
   More than the field was emptier than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Stampede President Fred Winningham attributed some of the
decline in attendance to the area's soft economy.
</P>
<P>
   Orchard owners who normally bought blocks of tickets for
employees couldn't afford it this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the tribe's boycott clearly caused others to stay away.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Cook, who was manning the Omak Food Bank table at the
Stampede, said her son normally attends each year, but he balked
this time because he has friends among the tribal racers. ``He said
no, I'm going to stay away,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The race's loss was a psychological blow for many in town, who
said the race put Omak _ population 4,400 _ on the map and made the
Stampede different from other rodeos.
</P>
<P>
   The race is an attraction for visitors from as far as Holland
and Japan. Vroman heard about the race in France, where he met
Newman, an exchange student who was studying abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's horrible without the Suicide Race ... it kind of makes
the town what it is,'' said Amanda Shafer, the desk clerk at the
Omak Lodge, the town's largest hotel.
</P>
<P>
   But it won't be clear until Saturday, traditionally the
Stampede's biggest day, whether the impact will be a serious
financial blow as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big shot in the arm for a lot of the businesses in
this town ... they're pretty nervous,'' said Max Frazier, who set
up a table downtown to sell inspirational ornaments as a church
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   At the Omak Lodge, the effect was already dramatic, said manager
Russ Huppert.
</P>
<P>
   The 61-room hotel, which can normally name its price on Stampede
weekend, cut rates by 25 percent after fielding 15 or 20
cancellations when the race was called off.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel was booked solid again by Friday, but the cut rates
translated to a $1,200 loss _ the equivalent of two or three days'
receipts on a normal weekend, Huppert said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the time of year when it gives us a major boost to
live out the rest of the year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was crushed to see the race gone.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Jones of the Progressive Animal Welfare Society, which has
campaigned against the Suicide Race for years, strolled quietly
around the Stampede grounds Friday with PAWS communications
director Richard Huffman.
</P>
<P>
   Jones had told race officials he would encourage tourists to
come to Omak if the race were canceled, he said, and wanted to show
his support for the Stampede's decision.
</P>
<P>
   And then there were visitors such as Lisa and Ernest Lenz of
Marysville, who bought Stampede tickets in November after years of
anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, they were looking forward to the race, but they never
considered canceling their plans after hearing the race had been
called off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have come anyway just to see the rodeo,'' Lisa Lenz
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets ranged from $5 to $12, and organizers were not issuing
refunds.
</P>
<P>
   And there was plenty of excitement in the rodeo stands Thursday
night as the first horses pounded into the ring. Cheers and
whistles erupted as riders held fast to animals bucking so wildly
all four feet seemed to dance in midair.
</P>
<P>
   Supportive cheers came even when a rider fell after one wild
ride, his cowboy hat rolling off his head and into the dusty ring.
</P>
<P>
   Teenage rodeo queens waved gracefully to their clapping fans as
they raced in a tight circle, with the stampede's queen the
evening's clear star.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might have a Miss Rodeo America in front of you!'' the
announcer gushed.
</P>
<P>
   Already, as the Stampede box office sells tickets for next
year's event, there's talk and hope that the race and encampment
will return next year.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Thile, an Okanogan County commissioner and Stampede board
member, said he's working on brokering a meeting among the city,
tribe and rodeo committees.
</P>
<P>
   They will likely bring in a mediator to help work through their
misunderstandings and miscommunications, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's enough blame to go around on everyone's
part....''
</P>
<P>
   For Stampede Vice President Miller, whose wife and children are
tribal members, he's not sure he would want to stay involved if the
race and encampment don't return.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of healing that needs to be done,'' he said. ``I
think when it's all over, we'll all say `How did we let this
happen?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
