A7084 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-SHOOTING-HOPE-LADN &LR;      08-14 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-HOPE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DOMINIC BERBEO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Prayer and song at the North Valley Jewish
Community Center Friday replaced the overshadowing tragedy left
behind by a racist shooting rampage at the center just three days
before.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 family members of the 36 children and staff who
were there during Tuesday's shooting gathered to celebrate the
Sabbath, pray for peace and tighten community bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of coming together to heal and bringing us back
to normal when the kids come back to camp on Monday,'' said Mike
Doner, whose 10-year-old daughter Samantha was at the center the
day of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Doner's 13-year-old son Mike summed it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just nice to know that everyone is here for the same
reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's shooting gripped the nation for nearly 24 hours as
police searched for suspect Buford Furrow. Furrow turned himself in
the next day in Las Vegas and allegedly confessed to the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Police later linked Furrow to white supremacist hate groups,
including the Aryan Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those present at the gathering in Granada Hills were
connected in some way to the center or the adjacent Episcopal St.
Andrew and St. Charles churches.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Lebowski, a local resident and member of the center, said
the tragedy should serve as a reminder that dangers exist
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as Americans need to be more aware, because it can happen
to any of us.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the lesson is that residents need to ``elect the right
politicians'' who ``aren't afraid to push for strong gun control
legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Dreyfuss has three children in the camp, including one
who was present at the time of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   He said one of his children had 16-year-old Mindy Finkelstein,
who was wounded in the shooting, as a counselor. All three of his
children were shaken up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're keeping a close watch on our kids,'' he said. But
Friday's gathering served to give them a sense of security
``knowing that there's a lot of us out here supporting each
other,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Gregory Frost, from the Episcopal church next door,
spoke at the gathering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christians are not called to kill Jews or hate Jews,'' he
said. ``When people target Jews, they target us.''
</P>
<P>
   Prayers were offered for the families of the five wounded,
including three children, and for Filipino-American mail carrier
Joseph Ileto, who was shot dead the same day, allegedly by the same
gunman.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky and members of the
Los Angeles police and fire departments also came out to show
support for the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're grateful for the lives that were spared and regretful of
the life that was lost,'' Yaroslavsky said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was glad that ``L.A.'s diverse population has come
together to heal and demonstrate what we as human beings have in
common with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   All of those wounded were in fair condition, except for
5-year-old Benjamin Kadish, who was wounded in the abdomen and leg
and remained in serious condition. &UR;  &QL; 
!dlim!!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
