A7090 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-FURROW-SPI &LR;      08-14 1394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FURROW-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SAY WEAPON USED BY FURROW WAS SOLD AT SPOKANE GUN SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KIMBERLY A.C. WILSON AND JUDD SLIVKA  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The pistol that police say was used to kill a U.S.
postal worker in Los Angeles on Tuesday traded hands several times
before it was sold last year at a gun show in Spokane, near the
north Idaho compound of the Aryan Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The gun is a key piece of evidence in the ongoing investigation
of Buford O. ``Neal'' Furrow Jr., an avowed separatist and white
supremacist who confessed to police that he attacked the North
Valley Jewish Community Center, and then shot and killed the postal
worker with a 9mm Glock model 26 semiautomatic pistol.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents investigating the slaying of Joseph Santos Ileto
on Friday were retracing the ownership of the 9mm pistol, trying to
pinpoint when and how Furrow obtained it.
</P>
<P>
   The gun, which bore the serial number BSM901US, was first bought
in 1996 by the Cosmopolis Police Department in Grays Harbor County,
Wash. The police traded it to a gun dealer, who also was a reserve
officer in the department, who then sold it to a local businessman
who passed it on to a friend to sell.
</P>
<P>
   That friend, according to local law-enforcement authorities, is
the person who sold the weapon in early 1998 at a gun show in
Spokane.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the gun was bought from an unlicensed vendor at a
gun show may restart the stalled debate in Congress over whether
background checks should be mandatory on all purchases at gun
shows, as they are now required at gun shops. It may also renew
debate in Washington state over how police departments dispose of
unwanted weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is set to debate a series of modest gun control
measures as part of a juvenile crime bill when it returns after the
Labor Day holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the Senate passed a bill requiring that all
dealers at gun shows, including the 40 percent who do not have
federal licenses, conduct background checks on customers, allowing
three days for completing those checks. The House defeated such
legislation, which was also opposed by the National Rifle
Association as too restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   Furrow, a 37-year-old felon convicted of a knife assault last
year at a Kirkland, Wash., mental health facility, was not legally
permitted to own a gun. Authorities say it is not clear whether he
was the person who bought the Glock 9mm pistol early last year at
the Spokane show.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Chester, a spokesman with the Seattle office of the
federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, said the agency
still had not determined how Furrow acquired the pistol or six
other weapons, including an Uzi assault-style submachine gun, that
were recovered from a car he had hijacked Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The ATF also was searching Friday for a gun dealer who was the
registered owner of the semiautomatic rifle that Los Angeles police
found in a van that belonged to Furrow.
</P>
<P>
   Chester said Furrow may have recently traded for some of those
guns using others he had acquired while he was a federally licensed
firearms dealer between 1992 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Chester said there were ``indications'' that some of those
trades had occurred after this May when Furrow was released from
jail and was prohibited from owning firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Furrow had to have acquired the weapons between January and
October 1998 or after this May, because he spent the intervening
time in jail for the assault at the Kirkland psychiatric hospital.
He had gone there for help, saying he was fantasizing about
committing a mass killing.
</P>
<P>
   Furrow could face the death penalty for federal murder and
attempted-murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   The gun used to kill the postal worker was one of two Glock
model 26 guns that were bought by the Cosmopolis police, from Glock
Inc., the Atlanta-area distributor for the Austrian gun producer.
</P>
<P>
   The department purchased the stubby handgun to evaluate it, said
Police Chief Gary Eisenhower. ``It just wasn't to our liking,'' he
said Friday after ATF agents called him to say the weapon was
involved in a ``high-profile case.''
</P>
<P>
   After a month of testing, the department traded it to Don
Dineen, a reserve police officer and the owner of Don's Guns Store
in Cosmopolis, a town of 1,600 near the port city of Aberdeen. In
return, the department received a Glock model 17, a larger sidearm,
and the department's standard issue to its officers.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, Dineen sold the pistol to David Wright,
owner of a paint and home-decorating supply store in nearby
Aberdeen. Wright kept it for two years, until January 1998, when he
transferred the gun to Andy Palmer, a local friend who collected
antique guns.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents tried to reach Palmer Friday but he was
unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   Aberdeen Police Capt. Michael Haymon said Wright had told ATF
agents who interviewed him that he had given Palmer several guns,
including the Glock, to sell at a Spokane gun show in early 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Cosmopolis Police Department's decision to trade the Glock
model 26 troubled gun control advocates Friday, although state law
allows police chiefs to determine how they dispose of unwanted,
unclaimed or forfeited weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that law enforcement agencies should be in the
business of selling guns. Whether they're new or old, guns just end
up back at crime scenes,'' said Bruce Gryniewski, executive
director of Washington Cease-fire Foundation, a gun-control
advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   The department should have destroyed the gun rather than trade
it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Police have the option, under state law, of destroying, selling,
using or trading guns in for new ones.
</P>
<P>
   When most departments upgrade their standard weapons _ many in
recent years have changed from revolvers to automatic pistols _
they trade them in to manufacturers or dealers to reduce costs,
according to Larry Erickson, executive director of the Washington
Association of Sheriffs and Police Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   An exception is Seattle, where local laws prohibit police from
returning guns back to the market. A Seattle police spokeswoman
said a property room has been filled with nearly new .38-caliber
revolvers since the department adopted another Glock automatic as
standard issue a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over what police should do with seized weapons is a
long one. In 1989, the Legislature passed a law that prohibited
police from destroying confiscated weapons, while requiring them to
auction them to licensed gun dealers and use the proceeds for gun
safety programs.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, the Legislature changed the law to give local
authorities more options, including destroying the weapons. Some
guns, including antiques, cannot be destroyed, however.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was sponsored by then-Rep. Gary Locke, now Washington's
governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor believes that police departments should not act
as a revolving door for guns confiscated from criminals,'' said
David Chai, a Locke spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's departments in at least three counties _ King, Pierce
and most recently Snohomish _ destroy at least some of the guns
they seize. The Washington State Patrol destroys about half the
estimated 450 guns it seizes each year, and trades in the rest to
acquire new weapons, a spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   In King County, Sheriff David Reichert recently sought the
authority to destroy more guns, including rifles, shotguns and
assault weapons. But the County Council balked because members
believed that would violate state law, which they interpret as
requiring such weapons to be sold or traded.
</P>
<P>
   The Snohomish County Council recently ordered the sheriff's
department to stop selling confiscated weapons, restricting options
to destruction or use by the department.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Rick Bart opposed the restrictions, arguing the sales
provided income for the cash-strapped department.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Waldron, a lobbyist for two Washington gun owners groups,
said Friday that it doesn't make sense to stop the sales of
confiscated guns, since they are sold only to licensed dealers,
subject to all state and local firearms laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think its stupid to turn off a source of revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Post-Intelligencer reporter Rob Gavin contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times and the Sacramento Bee contributed to this
report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
