r a BC-SHOOTING-HATE-LADN     08-14 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-HATE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COALITION URGES TASK FORCE TO FIGHT HATE GROUPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDS, runs with SHOOTING-SERGEANT, SHOOTING-RAMPAGE, SHOOTING-HOPE,
SHOOTING-KIDS) 
BY TERRI HARDY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Reacting to the hate-driven shooting
rampage in Los Angeles, a coalition of politicians, activists,
religious leaders and entertainers urged Gov. Gray Davis to create
a task force to combat hate groups and violent paramilitary
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   While battling street gangs has gotten attention, white
supremacists haven't received enough scrutiny, said Sen. Tom
Hayden, D-Los Angeles, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must ask ourselves why we have failed to recognize and
confront the pattern of violence that has arisen from white male
Christian hate groups and militias in America,'' Hayden said. ``We
don't seem to acknowledge there's a mass movement of Aryan natives
in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Davis received a letter from the coalition requesting the task
force Friday and is ``reviewing the possibility,'' said Davis
spokeswoman Hilary McLean.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor is appalled, shocked and saddened by the hate
crimes we've seen unfortunately too often thus far in his
administration and earlier this century,'' McLean said.
</P>
<P>
   The letter calls on Davis to combat paramilitary extremists ``by
every means, ranging from law enforcement to public education to
addressing the underlying causes of this organized hatred and
bigotry.''
</P>
<P>
   Coalition members include Cecil ``Chip'' Murray of the First
African Methodist Episcopal Church of Los Angeles, actor and
environmentalist Ed Begley, Los Angeles County Supervisor Yvonne
Brathwaite Burke and labor leader Miguel Contreras.
</P>
<P>
   David A. Lehrer, regional director of the Anti-Defamation
League, was not among those who signed the letter but said he
supports the call for action, saying it is ``ripe for
examination.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It will help focus public attention on this issue,'' Lehrer
said. ``The task force needs to explore hate groups in California,
focus the spotlight on their activities and recommend additional
laws, if necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   While attention to hate groups has been episodic throughout the
country, Lehrer said white supremacist groups are growing more
organized and gathering increasing numbers of recruits. The
Internet has been instrumental in the change, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a cheap and easy way to communicate and get the message
out like they've never been able to do before,'' Lehrer said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 0122EDT &QL; 
