<DOCNO> NYT19990814.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7107 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-RODEO-LEGENDARY-BULL-     08-14 1849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RODEO-LEGENDARY-BULL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGENDARY TALE OF BODACIOUS: A HALL OF FAME BULL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bull bucked legendary cowboy Tuff Hedeman to the prime-rib
ride of his career.
</P>
<P>
   And the bull made the former world champion wear titanium plates
in his face after knocking him out quicker than Muhammad Ali
dropped Sonny Liston.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the barnyard brute had become so ferocious that
Hedeman, the world's toughest bull rider, refused to lock his spurs
into Bodacious at the most lucrative rodeo in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Athletically speaking, Bodacious was the 275-pound lineman who
also could star at cornerback,'' said Hedeman, a four-time world
champion who lives in Morgan Mill. ``But if Bodacious would have
kept on bucking, he would have killed someone.''
</P>
<P>
   After clubbing many a cowboy and sending only a handful to the
pay window from 1992 though 1995, the lore of the light
coffee-colored Charolais-Brahman crossbreed bull, all 1,800 pounds
of him, transcended his sport.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, Bodacious will be among six inductees into the
ProRodeo Hall of Fame in Colorado Springs, Colo. He is the lone
livestock inductee this year. He is arguably the most dangerous
world champion-caliber bucking bull of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Bodacious could vault a rider into the elite 90s in points after
staying on for an eternal eight seconds. But near the end of his
career, he habitually hit riders in the face with his massive front
end as the cowboy leaned forward to stay in sync as the bull
reared.
</P>
<P>
   After staying on the bull twice in four tries, Terry Don West
said he's thankful that he didn't have to face Bodacious over the
past four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to keep my teeth, and he's the type of bull that will
take them away,'' said West, who suffered rib injuries during the
two failed attempts. ``He's like playing with a rattlesnake: If you
keep on he'll bite you.'' Next to impossible Bodacious was
discovered by Phil Sumner who raises bucking bulls at his Goldtree,
Okla., ranch. Sumner, in turn, sold the 1,500-pound whippersnapper
to East Texan Sammy Andrews, one of the most renowned rodeo
livestock contractors in the sport, at the beginning of the 1992
season.
</P>
<P>
   Like a coach starting a feisty freshman on the varsity squad,
Andrews immediately put Bodacious on the card at the Houston
Livestock Show Rodeo, the Professional Rodeo Cowboys Association's
largest regular-season show.
</P>
<P>
   In the Astrodome, Bodacious burst out with Cody Lambert aboard
and put the seven-time National Finals Rodeo qualifier on the ropes
early during the eight-second attempt. After six seconds, Bodacious
jerked Lambert down on his then-wiry front end and hit him in the
face, a mere prelude of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, I've got a scar on my face as a result of that
accident,'' Lambert said. ``When I shave every morning, I think of
that bull.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodacious continued to accelerate that rookie season, and at the
NFR he bucked off champions Ty Murray and Jim Sharp. The bull was
selected as the top bull of the 10-day rodeo, the first stamp on
his Hall of Fame passport.
</P>
<P>
   All the hype over Bodacious whetted Hedeman's appetite. Hedeman
faced the bull in Memphis, Tenn., and Tampa, Fla., in 1993. He was
bucked off in both attempts after having his hand jerked out of the
rope.
</P>
<P>
   When Hedeman faced Bodacious at the 1993 championships for a now
defunct organization dubbed as Bull Riders Only in Long Beach,
Calif., he threaded the tail of his tightly braided bull riding
rope through his fingers. Then, he wrapped the tail around his hand
tighter than a hangman's noose, a bull rider's equivalent of
playing double or nothing.
</P>
<P>
   With a deerskin glove, Hedeman also had rubbed an overabundance
of heated rosin into the rigging handle, equivalent to a football
receiver spraying stickum on his hands.
</P>
<P>
   In the chute, Hedeman eased down on the bull, nodded, and
Bodacious began a rapid fire of explosive rears and sledgehammer
drops. Hedeman countered the bull's every move and received 95 out
of 100, a score as rare as a perfect game in baseball, but a tally
that Andrews said was not high enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's really amazing was Bodacious just got stronger and
stronger at the end of the ride,'' Andrews said.
</P>
<P>
   After 135 attempts, only six riders completed a total of eight
rides on Bodacious in the professional ranks.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Hedeman, West is the most noted rider to conquer
the bull. The first was at a show in Ponca City, Okla., when
Bodacious was several hundred pounds smaller and was yet to embark
on a pro career. West's second qualified ride was in the San
Antonio Livestock Show Rodeo final round when West claimed the
title and $10,000 in February 1995, the last time a cowboy made the
eight-second count on the bull.
</P>
<P>
   West discovered a method of enduring Bodacious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to bending my knees and I wouldn't let go,'' he said.
``He was wanting to pull me down on his head, and so I pushed my
knees in him to alleviate the pressure. It was like I floated on
top of him. But he was no fun to ride. He was real strong and had a
lot of jerks and skips. I just had to bounce on my knees jump for
jump to stay on him.'' A lethal legend Unlike some of his pasture
mates who flaunted ``Flintstone'' clubs for horns, Bodacious' ivory
stubs sprouted only a few inches from his head. The bull's high
jumps, in unpredictable and impromptu patterns, however, were his
greatest asset to intimidate the roughest of bull riders.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you watch Bodacious highlights on tape, it's apparent
that a lot of the riders are not really trying to stay on him,''
Hedeman said. ``You can see it in their eyes. They're just looking
for a place to get off.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bodacious seemed to have a sixth sense of just who was
cinching a rope and cowbell around his oil drum of a midsection.
When Hedeman climbed on for a final ride of a clinched '95 PBR
world championship in Las Vegas, Bodacious seemed to hear
eight-time champion Don Gay's commentary for TNN:
</P>
<P>
   ``This is matchup of the season and maybe even the century.''
</P>
<P>
   Hedeman exuded confidence. He had conquered Bodacious in Long
Beach and was excited to culminate a banner season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I could be at least 95,'' Hedeman said. ``But I
didn't realize how bad of a habit he had developed of hitting
riders since I had last been on him.''
</P>
<P>
   When the gate opened, Bodacious reared and leaped several feet
from the arena floor, sucked back and skipped unevenly in between
two soaring jumps. Each jump climaxed with a toward-the-moon kick.
</P>
<P>
   Hedeman countered the first two jumps with a perfect seat, the
same precision moves that had enabled him to snare a gold buckle in
Long Beach. But as the bull reared and Hedeman leaned forward to
stay in rhythm and alleviate the pressure of the jumps, Bodacious
threw his head back and struck Hedeman in the face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was where I was supposed to be, but all of a sudden:
crash,'' Hedeman said. ``He proved that his head was harder than
mine.''
</P>
<P>
   As Hedeman tumbled, his face collided with bull's massive
shoulders. Then, as Hedeman rolled on the dirt floor, Bodacious
came face to face with the fallen star.
</P>
<P>
   Hedeman clutched his bleeding face, and paramedics rushed in
with bandages to plug the gap. Hedeman refused a stretcher and
walked out of the arena with blood drenching a top portion of his
starched white shirt, making a spot almost the size of the
garment's stylish red-plaid elbow patch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember being in that much pain, I guess because I
had so much adrenaline going through me,'' Hedeman said. ``But
people gave me the most horrified looks, as if they had encountered
Frankenstein.'' The divorce Hedeman underwent reconstructive facial
surgery in a Las Vegas hospital. When he returned to his Morgan
Mill ranch home, his 4-year-old son, Robert Lane, didn't recognize
his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Dad, the next time that you draw Bodacious, you'd
better chicken out,' '' Hedeman said. ``And I said, `Deal.' ''
</P>
<P>
   After being battered at the 1995 PBR championships in October,
Hedeman was sidelined for two months and entered the 1995 NFR, also
in Las Vegas, weighing in 20 pounds lighter.
</P>
<P>
   During the middle of the NFR, a neon night in which organizers
feature the ``rank pen'' of bulls, the odds of Hedeman drawing
Bodacious was 15 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even before the National Finals, somehow we just knew that
Tuff was going to draw Bodacious,'' Carolyn Andrews said. ``It was
like Bodacious was a magnet that Tuff couldn't break away from.''
</P>
<P>
   Hedeman drew Bodacious and faced a dilemma. When he was called
to ride, Hedeman mounted Bodacious in the chute, put his hand in
the rope handle and called for the gate to be opened.
</P>
<P>
   As the panel swung and Bodacious began exiting, a stalwart stock
contractor yanked Hedeman off Bodacious and planted Hedeman on the
walkway behind the chute. As a riderless Bodacious loped across the
arena, Hedeman stood among a sea of Stetson-capped competitors and
reverently tipped his hat toward the bull.
</P>
<P>
   Hedeman received affirmation from the 17,000 Las Vegas fans in
the Thomas and Mack Center. Andrews retired Bodacious at the
conclusion of the 1995 National Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was denied the world title at the end of the 10-day
championships, Hedeman said that he wisely threw in the towel.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had become impossible to ride,'' Hedeman said. ``There just
wasn't any use in getting on him anymore.'' A smash hit Though it
has been four years since the bull bucked off his last cowboy, the
Andrews family receives an abundance of inquiries about Bodacious.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous glossy spreads on Bodacious have graced publications,
including ``Sports Illustrated'' and ``GQ''.
</P>
<P>
   After pairing and parting with legends like Hedeman, Bodacious
requires a $2,500 appearance fee at rodeos and fairs. There's an
abundance of Bodacious memorabilia, including posters, T-shirts,
caps and belt buckles. For Internet addicts, there's even a
Bodacious mouse pad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've even had one person write and say that they would like a
jar of his snot,'' Carolyn Andrews said. ``When we have him in a
pen for viewing, people want him to `autograph' their T-shirt by
throwing it down in the pen and letting him stomp on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodacious, selected as the bull of the year by the PRCA (1994,
1995) and PBR (1995), also became a prominent breeder and has sired
an abundance of offspring. The breeding is managed by Buckers Inc.,
which is based in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Bodacious calves are beginning to surface at junior
competitions. Seven of his sons were pitted against junior cowboys
at a 1998 benefit rodeo in Fort Worth, and some of them bucked in
hoof prints similar to their sire.
</P>
<P>
   Though his offspring are expected to flood rodeos during the
next decade, Hedeman said he doubts that Bodacious' charismatic
appeal will be duplicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one Secretariat in horse racing, and there's only
one Muhammad Ali in boxing,'' Hedeman said. ``And I think rodeo
will have only one Bodacious.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
