A7114 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-CA-HOMES-LADN     08-14 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CA-HOMES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY AREA POSTS PRICIEST HOME SALES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Beverly Hills 90210 is down and out, at least when
it comes to sales of palatial homes, and the new address that
glitters these days in the Golden State is Hillsborough 94010.
</P>
<P>
   That trend emerged Friday in a survey of sales of million-dollar
homes in California, which reached a record level 2,130 properties
during the year's second quarter for a whopping 34.4 percent
increase on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
   The tony San Francisco suburb of Hillsborough, a magnet for
nouveau high-tech money, supplanted Beverly Hills as the zip code
attracting the most cash-flush buyers, Acxiom Corp.'s DataQuick
Products Division said. During the April-June period, Hillsborough
recorded 79 sales of residential properties selling for $1million
or more compared with 46 such sales in the 1998 second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Hills finished sixth on the list with 40 sales, down
from 51 in the 1998 period, marking the second consecutive quarter
in which the legendary haven for movie stars has been down and out.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Hillsborough has always been the kind of place money
found.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillsborough has been a tony address since the '20s or '30s,''
said DataQuick market analyst John Karevoll. ``It's just been
cooking lately because of all the windfall high-tech money coming
into the area and the new millionaires are buying homes like
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the state's better neighborhoods should all feel like a
million bucks compared to the rest of the nation. Karevoll
estimates that 90 percent of the nation's million-dollar
transactions take place in California.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, towns like Greenwich, Conn., and Vail, Colo., have
seven-figure addresses. But they don't have the kind of dollar mass
California does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are million-dollar markets, but they just don't have the
numbers. If Vail has three sales in a month, it's high. The sales
volume is here,'' Karevoll points out.
</P>
<P>
   The market up north is tighter in terms both housing stock and
available land, which pushes prices up, Karevoll noted.
</P>
<P>
   The most expensive home sold during the second quarter was a $10
million house in Pebble Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, size lives in the Golden State, too. The
largest home sold during the period was a 16,599 square-foot,
10-bedroom, 6-bathroom house in Pasadena. It sold for $4.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the surge in sales of high-priced properties is
the appreciation of California real estate. Karevoll notes that the
price spike has simply pushed more homes past the $1 million
barrier, especially in the more prestigious neighborhoods in
Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   Karevoll does not believe the sales pace will slow, either, and
he expects this quarter to set a new record for the pricey homes.
</P>
<P>
   The only surprising development was the rate of appreciation _
just under 10 percent _ which means buyers are not getting carried
away and trying to outbid one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``The values in that (prestige) market are going up at about the
same rate as that little home in Palmdale. It's uniform across the
board,'' Karevoll said of appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   The San Fernando Valley did not get left out of this home hit
parade, either. Calabasas finished 22nd on the list of the 25
hottest markets with 24 sales of homes priced at $1 million or
more, up from 23 in the 1998 second quarter. The most expensive
home sold for $2.73 million.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kyser, chief economist for the Economic Development Corp.
of Los Angeles County, said that Beverly Hills residents should not
feel slighted by their slip on the prestige scale. After all, this
is a city where million-dollar homes are torn down to make way for
new digs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they have million-dollar tear-downs up there, too,''
Kyser said of Hillsborough. ``But Beverly Hills is somewhat unique.
If you went to London and stopped a person on the street and said,
`Hillsborough' they would look at you and probably say it's in the
north (of England.) But Beverly Hills is an international brand.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
