critic of consumption, Robert Frank. By Peter Applebome. (1800
words)
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-VACATION (Undated) _ Once upon a time the rich played
when the mood struck, and almost everyone else worked their farms
and confined relaxation to the Sabbath. Although August is now
established as prime vacation time, few Americans realize that
their treasured paid vacation is a fairly recent phenomenon. The
very concept reflects ever changing American ideas about work,
leisure and the markers of middle-class status. By Felicia R. Lee.
(1275 words)
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-DISPUTE (Unated) _ If the sum total of human knowledge
becomes instantly and universally accessible on the Web, will every
fact become private property, to be leased or sold? Or will
information become so cheap as to lose any value, eliminating
incentives for using it or adding to it? Doomsday scenarios, to be
sure. But with the Web growing at a rate that defies human and
institutional experience, it is not surprising that such fears have
spread, and that both consumers and purveyors of facts _ which
includes most everyone, really _ have squared off over how and how
much to regulate the proliferation of raw and packaged knowledge.
By Serge Schmemann. (1050 words)
</P>
