<HEADER>
A7117 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-GIANTS-NYT &LR;      08-14 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME RUNS POWER GIANTS; SEND METS RIGHT BACK TO SECOND PLACE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For much of Friday evening, Masato Yoshii did
his part. But he also allowed two solo home runs, which was one too
many, and the New York Mets are back in second place.
</P>
<P>
   In his first start in two weeks, Yoshii allowed just four hits
and three runs (two earned) in six innings. But San Francisco
starter Russ Ortiz (two runs in seven innings) fared a little
better, and the Giants held on for a chilly 3-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with Atlanta's 7-3 victory in Los Angeles, Friday
night's defeat dropped the Mets (71-46) a game behind the Braves in
the National League East. The Mets now lead Houston by a game in
the NL wild card race. Houston dropped percentage points behind
Cincinnati in the NL Central.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were 0 for 5 with runners in scoring position. They had
the bases loaded when they were down by 3-1 in the seventh against
a faltering Ortiz (13-8), but Rickey Henderson was robbed of a
single in the hole at short by Rich Aurilia, who turned the play
into a run-scoring force at third. Roger Cedeno grounded to second
to leave runners on first and second and the Mets down by 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii had not started since he allowed seven runs in 1 1/3
innings in Chicago on July 30. With the July 23 acquisition of
Kenny Rogers, the Mets had six starters, and Yoshii became the odd
man out.
</P>
<P>
   In two relief appearances after his demotion, Yoshii allowed
five runs in four innings. But Rick Reed injured his finger on
Sunday and Yoshii got the starting assignment Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Mets manager Bobby Valentine was asked if
Yoshii's start could be viewed as a second chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, this is his job,'' Valentine said. We told him we
wanted him to be in the bullpen, ready to start when we needed him
in case of injury or other misfortune. He's just doing what he's
been preparing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But Yoshii could not have been prepared for what happened in the
first inning. The right-hander surrendered a one-out double to
Ramon Martinez, who is filling in at second base for the injured
Jeff Kent. An out later, Yoshii walked two batters to load the
bases.
</P>
<P>
   But when Bill Mueller rolled a slow grounder toward second, it
looked as though Yoshii would escape the inning unscathed because
the Mets have the most reliable infield defense in the major
leagues. But Edgardo Alfonzo, who has not made an error since May
20, was in Venezuela for a funeral, not at second base. Luis Lopez,
who had not started at second since July 2, tried to barehand the
ball. He muffed it for an error and an unearned run. Yoshii came
back to strike out Aurilia and strand three Giants' baserunners,
but the Mets were down, 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team scored until the fourth, when Ortiz, who had
allowed just two singles to that point, tried to sneak a 1-2
fastball past Piazza. Piazza, who was booed loudly here before each
of his at-bats, blasted the ball into right-center field for his
24th home run of the season, which tied the score at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants recaptured the lead, 2-1, in the bottom of the inning
when Yoshii surrendered a two-out homer to Aurilia (his 17th). And
when Marvin Benard hit a one-out home run in the fifth, the Giants
had a 3-1 lead. Yoshii had allowed his 21st homer in 21 starts this
season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
