<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 02:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7136 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTSGAME-BOS &LR;      08-14 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTSGAME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDSKINS BEAT PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ It wasn't until seventh-round pick Michael Bishop,
the third-string quarterback, threw a pair of touchdown passes in
the fourth quarter and nearly pulled out a comeback victory with a
third score as time ran out that there was any semblance of
excitement Friday night at Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But by then the stadium was half empty, as New England lost its
exhibition opener, 20-14, to the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' first- and second-stringers failed badly and
quarterback Drew Bledsoe injured his right ankle, though it doesn't
seem to be serious and Bledsoe is expected to be able to play in
next week's game against the Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   It took the third-string offense and defense to show any signs
of life, and it was Bishop, with his scrambling and energized play,
that added some zip to a flat night.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was fun to watch,'' said Bledsoe, who was 7 of 10 for 87
yards with one interception _ by rookie Champ Bailey, who raced 46
yards for a touchdown in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a fiery competitor who can run fast, and he has a
powerful arm,'' said Bledsoe, who may not have to worry about a
quarterback controversy now but may see the day when Bishop is
inserted as a change of pace.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said his ankle was ``not an issue.'' He iced it for a
while during the first half but said he would have played only one
more series anyway and sat out just to be on the safe side.
</P>
<P>
   The sellout crowd at Foxboro Stadium wasn't too pleased with a
first-half effort that saw the Patriots trailing, 20-0. Coach Pete
Carroll was beside himself on the sideline, upset with the defense
that let the Redskins run up the middle with ease. That's where
rookie linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer roamed, but the Big Cat played
more like a kitten. He also was beaten on a 7-yard pass play from
Brad Johnson to Larry Centers for the second Redskins score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really disappointed in the first three quarters,'' said
Carroll. ``On defense we missed a lot of fundamental things. In the
first half they had six yards a carry, and that's not good
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe was injured in the first quarter as he dropped back to
throw a pass to Vincent Brisby on the right side only to have a
defender roll on his ankle as Bailey stepped in front of Brisby to
pick off the errant pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vincent did what he was supposed to do,'' said Bledsoe. ``The
kid (Bailey) made a good play. I thought the first drive was a good
drive, and I thought Kevin Faulk looked very good. There's things
we can build off of.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots also lost fullback Chris Floyd, who started but
suffered a sprained right ankle, while defensive end Willie
McGinest didn't start as a precaution, nursing his oft-injured
groin.
</P>
<P>
   Faulk ran 11 times for 44 yards and caught an 8-yard touchdown
pass from Bishop in the fourth quarter. Faulk showed power,
elusiveness, and what Bledsoe called ``the ability to hit the
middle of the line and then start making his cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots took the opening kickoff and moved from their 21 to
the Washington 12. Bledsoe hit Lamont Warren for 17 yards and Terry
Glenn for 15 along the way. But once the Patriots got into the red
zone, they couldn't push it across, and Adam Vinatieri's 29-yard
field goal try was wide right.
</P>
<P>
   John Friesz took over for Bledsoe late in the first quarter and
was erratic at best. He was 10 of 20 for 102 yards and one
interception in the first half. His interception came in the second
quarter when tight end Rod Rutledge had a perfectly thrown pass
bounce off his hands into the arms of Darryl Pounds, who ran 16
yards to the Patriots 25. Brett Conway would hit the second of two
field goals to make it 20-0.
</P>
<P>
   One of Friesz's best moments was a 26-yard pass play to Tony
Simmons over Bailey that got the Patriots to the 49 midway through
the second quarter, but the drive stalled.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins broke a big play on a slant pattern from backup
quarterback Rodney Peete to Albert Connell. Tebucky Jones held
Connell as he was making the catch and Vernon Crawford missed the
tackle before Connell finally was brought down at the Patriots 21.
This led to a 39-yard field goal by Conway.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop, who was 9 of 17 for 148 yards, hit a 43-yard pass to
Sean Morey, who made a diving catch. Harold Shaw finished the drive
with a 4-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   With the score 20-7, Bishop went to work again, hitting a
45-yard pass to Mike Sheridan followed by an 8-yard touchdown to
Faulk with 1:56 left.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots still had time, and the fans were ready for
heroics. With Vinatieri and punter Lee Johnson on the field at the
same time, the Patriots tried an onside kick, and it worked.
Bernard Russ, who had nine tackles, recovered the ball, giving
Bishop 1:48 with which to work.
</P>
<P>
   He moved the team downfield, scrambled for 13 yards, converted a
fourth down, and got to the Redskins 20 with two seconds left, but
he couldn't make the connection with Troy Brown at the end.
</P>
<P>
   And even if he had, it was the third unit. And the third unit
won't be playing against the Jets Sept. 12.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
