<HEADER>
A7137 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     08-14 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTERY: WHY IS MONDY MOODY?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What's eating Raul? To think you know Raul Mondesi
is to wonder if you can stomach the answer.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers right fielder, despite all he recently
has said and done, can count many stalwart supporters inside the
organization. Supporters who to a man are at a loss to reconcile
the player's sudden fits of temper with his inherently sweet soul.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the lurch-right-out-of-his-cleats cuts he sometimes
takes at the plate, it's Mondesi's mood swings that are most
disquieting to those in his corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what all is bothering Mondy,'' manager Davey
Johnson said Friday before the Dodgers' game against Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was worried about the player who is being paid
beaucoup bucks to hustle the Dodgers into the next millenium,
Johnson rubbed his forehead and wearily, warily replied, ``Yes. I
want to help him. I don't have the answers. I wish I did.''
</P>
<P>
   You can't blame Johnson for worrying. He was managing the New
York Mets in the late 1980s when another tremendously talented
outfielder under his sway, Darryl Strawberry, started behaving
erratically.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson tried coddling, cajoling, cautioning and chastising
Strawberry. Always, Strawberry's standard reply was a contrite,
``Yes, Skip.'' His actions, though, screamed, ``No, No, Never,
Never, Naah ahh ahh.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he was in the dark about the demons competing with
him for Strawberry's soul right up until the day the player was
admitted to a drug-and-alcohol rehabilitation center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope Mondy doesn't have issues like Darryl,'' said
Johnson, who was quick to add the outfielder has given him no
reason to suspect that is the case.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, missing a practice during the All-Star break,
turning up late for batting practice, lashing out in frustration,
even drinking too much on at least one occasion, doesn't exactly
constitute a preponderance of evidence of guilt on any charge.
Except immaturity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question in my mind he's an immature person,''
Johnson said of Mondesi.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson would just as soon leave it at that. But will Mondesi's
malevolent storm, which tore through the visiting clubhouse in
Montreal the other day, let him?
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is, I want Mondy to be happy,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   It would appear to be a tall order at the moment. Mondesi
clearly wasn't enjoying himself when the Dodgers were winning five
of six on the road and his mood didn't improve when he returned
home to vociferous boos every time he batted in the Dodgers' 7-3
loss.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like Mondesi to wear such a monotone expression. His
normal game face is a grin. That's why the anger that spewed out of
him like lava from a volcano the other day in Montreal shocked his
supporters within the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody is entitled to a bad day. But Mondesi, until recently,
exuded the attitude that a bad day at the ballpark was better than
a good day most anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   No mystery, that. To grow up dirt poor, as Mondesi did in the
Dominican Republic, is to appreciate early on that there are a lot
worse ways to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi's joie de vivre is central to his success. And now,
inexplicably, it has left him.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone would gladly
lead a search party, if only either had a clue where to start
looking.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi has provided few clues. He was mum before the game. He
issued a standard written apology on Thursday but has yet to offer
a satisfactory explanation for his expletive-laced condemnation of
Johnson and Malone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always going to be there to help and support our
players,'' Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, sounding more like a parent than a GM, he added,
``Sometimes they have misguided anger.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers can't diffuse Mondesi's fury until they get to the
root of it. At this point, all Johnson knows is, ``You can't play
this game and not be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough. Baseball players are not like painters who can
express their anger with violent brushstrokes on a canvas and
create something for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are obliged to help Mondesi get his inspiration
back. But first they have to figure out where it has gone and why.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
