<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOXMARINERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX BEAT MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is the forgotten man of the MVP race. But it's no wonder Troy
O'Leary has a legion of supporters among the Fenway Faithful.
</P>
<P>
   Overshadowed by rookie Brian Daubach (a career-high five RBIs)
for most of the evening, O'Leary came through with the biggest hit
of an 11-6 Red Sox victory over the Seattle Mariners Friday night
at Fenway. O'Leary brought a sellout crowd of 33,653 to its feet
with a bases-loaded triple in the seventh inning to break a 6-6
tie.
</P>
<P>
   The blow sent Boston not only to a wild victory but to the
wild-card lead. With Toronto losing to Oakland, the Sox took over
the top spot on the also-ran playoff race, a half-game in front of
the Blue Jays and two games ahead of the A's.
</P>
<P>
   In three previous trips, O'Leary had struck out twice and popped
up with men on base. In the seventh, he made up for it in a big
way.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Offerman led off with a walk, and Darren Lewis, who scored
a career-high five runs, reached on a sacrifice bunt, with the
runners moving up on first baseman Raul Ibanez's throwing error.
</P>
<P>
   After Daubach grounded to second, the Mariners elected to walk
Nomar Garciaparra and test O'Leary, who made them pay with his
triple down the right-field line. O'Leary scored the fourth run of
the inning on a double by Jason Varitek. Boston picked up an
insurance run in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to make contact,'' said O'Leary. ``He
(reliever Jeff Fassero) throws the ball hard, but he just happened
to leave the forkball up where I could do something with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need this. We know the A's and Toronto have been playing
well. We're playing well also. If we can continue, we'll be all
right. This was an interesting game.''
</P>
<P>
   It was indeed interesting if you didn't mind several periods of
sloppy play. The ball was sailing around Fenway thanks to a strong
breeze. Each side made two errors, and neither starter, Freddy
Garcia for Seattle or Pat Rapp of Boston, made it through five
innings.
</P>
<P>
   After taking a 1-0 lead on a Daubach double in the first, Boston
overcame deficits of 3-1 and 5-4, with Daubach showing the way. The
rookie's two-run homer in the third gave the Sox a 4-3 lead, and
his two-run double in the fifth made it 6-5, Boston, though he was
thrown out trying to stretch the hit into a triple.
</P>
<P>
   But, as is usually the case with the Red Sox, nothing came easy.
Closer Tim Wakefield started the ninth and loaded the bases with a
two-out walk to Jay Buhner. It was Lewis who should be credited
with the save, as he ended the game with a leaping catch on an
Ibanez shot to the wall in left center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a lot of big catches,'' said Lewis. ``But to end the
game on a play like that is something. I know when the ball is hit
I have to basically give myself up. I know if it's anywhere near
the wall, I've got to jump up and do whatever I can to catch it. In
that situation, you're going to get banged up a little bit. But
you've got to go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   While he doesn't draw the attention of Garciaparra, O'Leary is
popular with the fans and solid as a rock on offense and defense.
The triple, his only hit in five at-bats, extended his hitting
streak to 14 games, tying a career best. O'Leary is batting .293
with 24 home runs and 82 RBIs. He has at least one hit in 38 of his
last 42 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems relaxed and confident,'' said manager Jimy Williams.
``He's a very durable kid. He doesn't like days off. Righthanders,
lefthanders, it doesn't matter. He's a very good RBI guy, and he
plays an outstanding outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having the opportunity to bat against lefthanders started in
1997. All last year and then coming into spring training, his
mindset was pretty good. It seemed to me he was going to have a
good year, just by the way he came to the park. This kid has a
chance to have a very good year just based on the way he is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
