<SLUG> BC-TEN-ACURANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIERCE UPSET BY HALARD-DECUGIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ The Acura Classic semifinals are set.
Three names No.1 Lindsay Davenport, No.2 Martina Hingis and No.6
Serena Williams may have been expected to be there. But one name
Julie Halard-Decugis probably was not.
</P>
<P>
   Halard-Decugis, ranked 16th in the world, beat No.3 Mary Pierce
7-5, 6-1 Friday in the quarterfinals of the Acura Classic at
Manhattan Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce was unsatisfied with her unforced errors and termed her
performance ``terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just kept making the same mistakes over and over,'' Pierce
said.
</P>
<P>
   Halard-Decugis won by serving well, never allowing Pierce to
break her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little bit easy,'' Halard-Decugis said. ``She made
many unforced errors.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierce, 0-3 against Halard-Decugis, led 5-4 in the first set,
but Halard-Decugis won eight of the next nine games to demoralize
the fellow Frenchwoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Julie has a very erratic game,'' Pierce said. ``You can never
get any rhythm on the court. Either there's a quick winner or
mistake from either one of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport survives marathon: Davenport won a 2-hour, 12-minute
night match against Conchita Martinez 6-7 (7-4), 6-3, 6-2. Martinez
dropped to 7-3 against Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty happy with how I hung in there,'' Davenport said.
``I could have easily folded. I don't have a good record against
her, and that's the one player I haven't beaten in a couple of
years.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second set, Davenport broke Martinez to take a 5-3 lead.
To get the break point, Davenport had a winner that the linesman
called out, then changed the call to good. The umpire upheld the
change, even though Martinez may have been thrown off when the
linesman yelled out.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez threw down her racket and yelled at the umpire. From
that point, the match turned drastically to Davenport's favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was bizarre,'' Davenport said. ``The guy called it out and
changed it, and when that happens it's a judgment call for the
umpire. It was a big turning point. She got really upset then.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Martina Hingis recovered to beat No.7 Barbara Schett 6-7
(7-5), 6-3, 6-3. After the first set, Hingis controlled the match.
In the first set, Schett broke Hingis to take a 5-3 lead. But
Hingis battled to force a tiebreaker. There Schett took a 5-0 lead,
but again Hingis rallied, pulling to 6-5 before the Austrian won.
... Hingis will face a different style tonight against powerful
Serena Williams. Hingis beat Williams' older sister, Venus, in the
TIG Classic in San Diego. ``I beat Venus last week and consider her
toughest of the two,'' Hingis said. ``You have to take Serena very
serious, but she's not as consistent as Venus yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's matches:At noon, Davenport vs. Halard-Decugis,
Halard-Decugis/Mirjana Lucic vs. Larisa Neiland/Arantxa
Sanchez-Vicario. ... At 7 p.m. Williams vs. Hingis, Lisa
Raymond/Rennae Stubbs vs. Winner of Ines Gorrochategui/Elena
Tatarkova Kimberly Po/Anne-Gaelle Sidot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
