<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BORGESCOLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS HAVE HOLES IN MIDDLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ To rework a phrase from the old Brooklyn Dodgers,
``Wait till next week!''
</P>
<P>
   That's all you can really say about the Patriots' performance
Friday night against the Washington Redskins. The score is
unimportant (although for the record it was 20-14 Washington, 20-0
at halftime). The game itself was unimportant as well because the
starters came out in relatively the same state of health that they
went into it, which is always a victory at this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   So the only thing that bears watching is that the run defense
that had been an anchor of New England's system last year was
dreadful, allowing the Redskins to rush for 5.8 yards a carry in
the first half and for 127 yards (6.4 a carry) by the end of the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Too often New England's young defensive tackles failed to
protect the linebackers behind them, allowing the Redskins line to
fire out and bury Andy Katzenmoyer and Tedy Bruschi. At times they
were all but defenseless to do much about it when the ballcarrier
passed by them because they were attached to an offensive lineman
the way a bumper is to the grill of an Oldsmobile.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer in particular often seemed lost, but how else was he
supposed to look? After spending two minicamps and the first two
weeks of training camp working to master the ``plugger'' position,
Todd Collins's old spot, he was suddenly thrust into Ted Johnson's
middle linebacker position this week and asked to compensate for
the loss of the team's best tackler. He did not do well. No one
should have been surprised by that.
</P>
<P>
   So what is important is not this steamy night or the performance
of the Patriots' defense. What will be important is next weekend's
steamy night and the defense's performance in the season's second
meaningless game because one thing about that game will have
meaning regardless of what else happens _ the progress, or lack
thereof, of the run defense.
</P>
<P>
   For that to improve, other things must happen as well. Will the
mistakes be decreased? Will people line up in the right place more
often than they did Friday night when, quite frankly, they too
often did not? Will the defensive tackles do a better job
protecting the linebackers, and will those linebackers all get into
position to make plays as a coordinated unit, which they did not do
often enough against the Redskins?
</P>
<P>
   If they do these things better next Saturday than they did on
Friday the 13th, what happened Friday night can be forgotten by
Patriot fans. But if the Cowboys come in and average six yards a
carry after a week spent working on how to prevent that, then it's
time to worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to do better against the run,'' said Bruschi, who
has replaced Collins at outside linebacker. ``If we don't, it'll be
a long day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to point to Ted Johnson not being there as the
problem, I'll point to that, too, but he's not going to be back
there for a while so we've got to buck up regardless. But before we
throw a panic fit, let's see if we can improve against Dallas. I
think we'll improve. If we don't, then you can say we've got a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it was not a good start Friday night because the
defense that was the strength of the Patriots the past few years
had a hole in the heart of it. It was a hole that made the Grand
Canyon look like a pothole.
</P>
<P>
   In baseball, it is a given that you have to be strong up the
middle to win. Catcher, pitcher, shortstop, center field. That's a
key to victory in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   So what if you try to play football with rookies at running
back, center, middle linebacker, and, for all intents and purposes,
safety?
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, it wasn't strong enough. Not strong enough to
survive for long in the most competitive division in the AFC, the
East, where four teams made the playoffs a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots didn't run well enough when they had the ball. And
the Redskins didn't just run through the middle of New England's
defense _they floated through it, often without being touched until
their backs were well past the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   But there were acceptable reasons for the defensive problems, at
least on this night.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Chad Eaton played sparingly, and Brandon
Mitchell played with a broken hand wrapped in a huge cast that made
it near impossible for him to defend himself let alone protect
Katzenmoyer behind him. An assortment of other linemen were rolled
in and out so often that mistakes were almost guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, head coach Pete Carroll made clear his disappointment
when he said, ``I know some of you are waiting for me to find
something positive in this game tonight, but we're not talking
about that right now,'' Carroll said. ``The first half was a
classic screw-up. I was really disappointed with the first three
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first three quarters we couldn't get them down (tackle
them). A lot of it was fundamental defense. We play run defense
around here.''
</P>
<P>
   What Carroll didn't say _ because he didn't have to _ was that
they didn't play run defense Friday night. Not when you give up 149
yards on 30 carries, a 5-yard average, to a team that was 19th in
the NFL in rushing a year ago at a time when your own running game
was sadly already in midseason form _ rushing for only 3.4 yards a
carry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the run defense) felt soft,'' Carroll said. ``We were not
close enough to the inside gaps. It was poor run defense.''
</P>
<P>
   It was. No one can argue otherwise. But as Bruschi correctly
pointed out, it was the first game, and the defense basically had
not really tackled anyone since last January, in a playoff loss to
Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   Since then they have gone through the motions of hitting but
done little of it. That is how it is in training camp, when
throwing your teammates on the ground is usually frowned upon
except during goal-line drills.
</P>
<P>
   So let us reserve judgment for seven more days, difficult as
that will be for the denizens of talk radio. There was a problem in
the heart of the Patriot defense Friday night. It was an obvious
problem born from the absence of Johnson, Collins, and Willie Clay
_ who are gone and won't be back _ and from the absence of Willie
McGinest and Henry Thomas _ who were held out for precautionary
reasons and soon will be back.
</P>
<P>
   When the missing are present and Katzenmoyer has a few more
weeks to figure out where to stand and where to go after the ball
is snapped and those defensive tackles remember how to protect the
linebackers behind them, the picture will be clearer.
</P>
<P>
   Until then it might be wise to shop for some worry beads before
there's a run on them. But don't start using them yet. Wait till
next week, and let's see what happens with the Cowboys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 0231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
