u s BC-BBA-HOLLEYCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-14 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOLLEYCOLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASTOFFS BUCK SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Michael Holley  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am taking a break from a protest to write this. And when I
resume my defiant stand, I think you should join me. I'll even give
you your own sign and let you have ample shouting time on my
official, boycott megaphone.
</P>
<P>
   My issue is that I no longer believe in baseball's system. I
think there are too many scouts who spend millions of dollars on
evaluating talent, even if they don't know what they're watching. I
do not believe that the best players will immediately be given a
fair chance to perform. I do believe that there are players who
have subtle skills that the current system cannot recognize.
</P>
<P>
   I could go on. Instead, let me introduce you to three Red Sox.
Their names are Brian Daubach, Troy O'Leary, and Darren Lewis. The
system doesn't understand them. If they hadn't been at Fenway Park
Friday night, the Sox wouldn't have beaten up on the sad Seattle
Mariners, 11-6. And they certainly wouldn't have their slim,
half-game lead over the Toronto Blue Jays for the American League
wild card.
</P>
<P>
   This is why I protest: If the system had its way, Daubach would
be in Japan right now; O'Leary would be somewhere in California
wondering why the Milwaukee Brewers released him; and Lewis still
might be thinking why the San Francisco Giants traded him to
Cincinnati for a football player named Deion Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Do you mind holding this ``Free Daubach!'' placard for me?
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, the 27-year-old rookie first baseman was 3 for 5
with 5 RBIs. He hit his 18th home run of the season and fifth in
his last six games. He will receive several votes for AL Rookie of
the Year. But after having the best season of his career last
season in Triple A, the Florida Marlins released him. Some guys are
released for hitting .216. Daubach was released for hitting .316
with 35 homers and 124 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I wasn't very good,'' Daubach said of his time in
Charlotte. He was still wearing his uniform when he spoke. The
front of it was covered with infield mud. That came when he tried
to turn a fifth-inning double into a triple, doing a belly slide
into third base.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was bad baserunning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He's right. But there is no doubt Daubach is an above-average
hitter. I didn't spend a dime on scouting last season and I can see
that. You mean to tell me that neither the Mets nor Marlins could
figure that out? Daubach said he was close to going to Japan when
Sox general manager Dan Duquette invited him to spring training.
Now he is close to receiving a plaque for first-year excellence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy to be here,'' he said. ``I'm probably too old
to win Rookie of the Year.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, anybody want to buy a ``Put Your Money on Yummy'' T-shirt?
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary sits across from Daubach. His teammates call him
``Yummy.'' The Brewers didn't think Yummy could hit for power. They
also doubted that he could have success against lefthanders. Friday
night, Yummy had a three-run triple in the seventh that broke a 6-6
tie. He hit it off a mysterious lefty named Jeff Fassero. A couple
of years ago, Fassero was a valued member of baseball's system. He
won 15 games and was a No. 2 starter, behind Randy Johnson. Now, he
has something in common with former Patriots cornerback Chris
Canty. That is, he gives up 6s and 7s. His earned run average is
7.11.
</P>
<P>
   In his first two at-bats, O'Leary appeared to be overmatched.
After Fassero intentionally walked Nomar Garciaparra to load the
bases, O'Leary connected with one of his pitches and sent it down
the right-field line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let Troy win the game tonight,'' Daubach said. ``That was a
big hit for us.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary now has a career-high 14-game hitting streak, which
shouldn't surprise the Brewers. If they look at their archives,
they will see that the left fielder hit .334 and .329 in the
minors. If he continues his current pace, he will finish with 100
RBIs for the first time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Excuse me, brother, would you like to wave this ``D-Lew'' Flag?
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Sox went into the ninth with an 11-6 lead, the
33,653 fans in the park were nervous. Tim Wakefield, a natural
starter, was on the mound trying to be a closer. He got two outs in
the inning, but he also loaded the bases. Raul Ibanez threatened to
make things interesting when he blasted a Wakefield pitch to deep
center field. If it had dropped, three runs would have scored and
Ibanez could have been on third.
</P>
<P>
   It dropped in the glove of Lewis. He stops several balls from
dropping. Friday night, he ended the play by crashing into the
center-field fence and falling on his backside, glove extended in
the air. That's what the man known as D-Lew does. But we live in a
baseball era where hitting home runs receives more attention than
preventing runs.
</P>
<P>
   Some Sox observers say Lewis is one of the smartest men on the
team. During the offseason, he takes classes at Cal-Berkley. He
loves to read. He also likes preparing for endings such as Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   And so I protest. I am now a baseball anarchist. The system has
failed us. But if the system failures continue for the Sox, they'll
be in the playoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 0233EDT &QL; 
