A7142 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-BRAVES-LA     08-14 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-BRAVES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONDESI BOOED IN DODGERS LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If Raul Mondesi thought fans would love him for
doing what they might want to do _ cuss out his employers and get
away with it _ he was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after unloading on manager Davey Johnson and general
manager Kevin Malone in a profanity-laced tirade, Mondesi returned
to Dodger Stadium for the first time Friday night and was loudly
booed each time he batted in a 7-3 loss to the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 40,353, most of which have been supportive during
Mondesi's turbulent season, sounded like they are hoping the Los
Angeles Dodgers right-fielder gets his wish to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Johnson said he considers the incident closed
and hopes Mondesi, who did not speak Friday, can rebound to finish
the season on a high note. Malone, however, said Mondesi's words
still sting and hopes to receive a personal apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a formal apology and that was important,'' Malone
said. ``In time, you will forget. We all love Mondy.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone, who fined but did not suspend Mondesi, said he has no
immediate plans for a trade, but did not rule anything out in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new situation,'' Malone said. ``I think we will do
what is in the best interest of the Dodgers.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone had nothing but praise for left fielder Gary Sheffield,
who said he wants out if the Dodgers don't make significant changes
during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he wants to do is win,'' Malone said. ``He always has put
the team first in everything he has done for us.''
</P>
<P>
   But Malone conceded that will be difficult with many of his
underachieving veterans locked up in multi-year contracts. Mondesi
still is owed $20.5 million for the next two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, who has said he will drop his no-trade clause, was
paid $7.5 million to waive the no-trade clause last May when he was
sent to the Dodgers in the Mike Piazza deal. Sheffield still has
four years left on his contract worth $39.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the game today, teams place a high value on young talent,''
he said. ``They are not likely to give up young talent for veterans
with long contracts.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the boos, Mondesi played little role in Friday's
loss, which was just the Dodgers second in the last seven games. He
struck out in the second, flied to deep center in the fourth and
grounded to third in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi's final at-bat came with one out in the ninth against
former Dodger teammate Rudy Seanez. He singled to center and
received a smattering of cheers along with the boos. He later
scored Dodger final run.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi initially was charged with an error in the Braves'
four-run fourth inning when his throw back to the infield on Bret
Boone's RBI double sailed past shortstop Mark Grudzielanek and
allowed Gerald Williams to score.
</P>
<P>
   But the call was changed when replays showed Mondesi actually
made an accurate throw to second, but Grudzielanek was grossly out
of position.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the attention in the game went to Dodgers starter Darren
Dreifort, who was coming off an impressive 10-4 victory over the
New York Mets. Dreifort (9-12), attempting to keep his spot in the
rotation for next year, did not have the control problems that
plagued him most of the season, but he was hit hard.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed five runs and nine hits in the first four innings,
including the first of two homers by Chipper Jones and two-run
double by Boone in the fourth. Dreifort opened the fourth by
allowing three consecutive hits.
</P>
<P>
   After a sacrifice bunt by Braves starter Kevin Millwood (13-7),
Williams lined a two-run single past Eric Young, who came off the
disabled list (left ankle) before Friday's game. Boone's double
made it 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   The knock on Dreifort had been his inability to pitch late into
games. In this one he settled down after the fourth and retired the
next eight batters until Boone walked to open the seventh and Jones
crushed a 2-0 fastball over the center-field fence. It was the
fifth multi-home run of Jones' career and fourth this season. He
now has 31 homers.
</P>
<P>
   When Brian Jordan, who stared down Dreifort after he was hit by
a pitch in the third, followed Jones with a single, Dreifort was
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is one of the things we will be watching the rest of the
way,'' manager Davey Johnson said. ``He needs to go deeper into
games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
