<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(th) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Aug. 15:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-CHILD-ABUSE (Tokyo) _ Authorities in Japan are beginning
to face up to the ugly challenges of family violence and child
abuse, problems that have been so clandestine that most Japanese
believed they existed only in the West. By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DAGESTAN (Moscow) _ Russia has carried out its threat to
bomb guerrilla bases inside Chechnya, widening its war against the
Islamic rebels in the North Caucuses, a spokesman for Russia's
Interior Ministry said Saturday. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLAMPDOWN (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ International
peacekeepers in Kosovo are clamping down hard on the Kosovo
Liberation Army, seizing arms caches almost daily and confiscating
documents and even cash from premises, in what some say is a
determined effort to break the movement. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NOTEBOOK (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ A reporter's notebook
on tales of revenge from Kosovo. By Steven Erlanger. (With a
photo.)
</P>
<P>
   BONN-BONVOYAGE (Bonn, Germany) _ After half a century when this
modest city on the Rhine was a government center, years when
Germany was stabilized and the cold war ultimately won, the United
States is leaving town. Behind the trucks headed for Berlin lies
the sprawling evidence of a vast mission that symbolized America's
assumption of great-power commitments in the postwar years. By
Roger Cohen. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   RWANDA-DEPORT _ Elizaphan Ntakirutimana, a Rwandan under
indictment for genocide by an international war crimes tribunal in
Africa, made a final plea to the Supreme Court on Friday to avoid
deportation from the United States, American officials said
Saturday. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN-BASQUES (Bilbao, Spain) _ Like the peace talks in Ireland
that inspired them, negotiations between the Spanish government and
the guerrilla movement that has been fighting for independence for
the Basque country have stalled but not stifled hopes for peace in
a long and bloody conflict. By Craig R. Whitney. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-NKOREA (Tokyo) _ With no apparent diplomatic solution in
site and no military ability to defend themselves, the Japanese are
growing increasingly jittery over North Korea's threat to test-fire
a long-range ballistic missile. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-PROTESTS (Omagh, Northern Ireland) _ Police of the
Royal Ulster Constabulary clashed Saturday with Roman Catholic
demonstrators protesting the passage of Protestant parades through
Catholic neighborhoods. By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-ECUADOR (Lima, Peru) _ As recently as one year ago, Peru
and Ecuador were preparing to go to war _ something they have done
with unfortunate regularity ever since the Peruvian Navy blockaded
Ecuador's principal port in 1860. But in a sign that the squabbling
neighbors are inally learning to live together, President Jamil
Mahuad of Ecuador completed a three-day, whirlwind visit through
Peru on Friday. By Clifford Krauss. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CATHOLIC-RADIO _ A group of wealthy Roman Catholic
entrepreneurs, concerned that the nation's religious radio
programming is dominated by evangelical Protestants, has started a
radio network intended to broadcast a conservative Catholic spin on
politics, news, personal problems and spiritual questions. By
Laurie Goodstein. (With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-SPY (Miami) _ To Ana Margarita Martinez, an avowed
anti-Communist Cuban-American, the dashing young jet pilot seemed
to have dropped from heaven. Juan Pablo Roque, a disenchanted
officer in the Cuban air force, escaped the Communist-controlled
island by swimming to the U.S. Navy base at Guantanamo Bay in
February 1992. The two later married. Then in 1996, Roque, who was
really a Cuban spy, returned home. Now Ms. Martinez is suing the
Cuban government for sexual battery. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON-COLLEGE-FEMINIST (Boston) _ For nigh on 20 years, Mary
Daly, who is widely considered the world's foremost radical
feminist philosopher and theologian, has barred men from her
classroom at Boston College, arguing that they marred the learning
experience of women. Now the university is retiring her. By Carey
Goldberg. (With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBINE-REOPEN (Littleton, Colo.) _ Inside Columbine High
School, where two teen-agers shot and killed a dozen other students
and a teacher last April 20, the library, where much of the mayhem
occurred, has disappeared. When students return to classes on
Monday for a new school year, not quite four months after the chaos
ended with the young gunmen turning their weapons on themselves,
Columbine faces the rather daunting challenge of seeking normalcy
in a place that could never be the same after what happened there.
By Michael Janofsky. (With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-STRAW-POLL (Ames, Iowa) _ Iowans go to the Republican
Party's straw poll on Saturday, an early test of the political
organizing power and, to some extent, popularity of presidential
candidates. An early story will move between 2 and 3 p.m. ET,
updating throughout the news cycle with significant developments.
(Sidebars as warranted.)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS _ Short items on politics from around the
nation. By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HMO-LAWSUITS (Washington) _ In a string of rulings over the last
20 months, judges across the country have begun allowing patients
to sue health maintenance organizations for medical malpractice,
after decades in which such claims were repeatedly rejected by the
courts. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   EPA-WATER-POLLUTION (Washington) _ The Environmental Protection
Agency will propose later this week that states regulate water
pollution by focusing on bodies of water, instead of individual
discharges. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   RENO-PARKINSONS (Washington) _ As an advocate for people with
Parkinson's disease, Joan Samuelson has pounded on many a Capitol
Hill door trying to increase financing for research into the
incurable disorder. In August 1996, she found herself with a rare
opportunity to make her pitch to a member of the Clinton Cabinet:
Attorney General Janet Reno, a fellow Parkinson's sufferer. But any
illusion the advocate may have had about enlisting the nation's
highest law-enforcement officer in her cause was quickly dispelled.
``She didn't feel she should make Parkinson's a part of her public
agenda,'' Samuelson said. Three years later, Reno has little
choice. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   PHONE-INTERNET-FEE (Washington) _ Two years ago, when the
government imposed a new fee on long-distance telephone companies
to raise money for Internet connections at schools and libraries,
the reaction from some quarters was ferocious. But the program,
officially called the e-rate, has proved to be so popular that even
the harshest critics now agree that further complaints are futile.
By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN _ Buford O. Furrow Jr. is the symptom. We can
deal with him. Lock him up. Convict him. Kill him. But how do you
deal with that sickness in the nation's soul that will still be
there even after a fiend like Buford Furrow is gone? By Bob
Herbert.
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ I can tell you in one word why Warren
Beatty won't run for president: lighting. The man is a master at
putting himself in the most flattering light, literally and
figuratively. By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move at 11:30 a.m. ET.
</P>
