ended with the young gunmen turning their weapons on themselves,
Columbine faces the rather daunting challenge of seeking normalcy
in a place that could never be the same after what happened there.
By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 12:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-LEMKE-COMEBACK (Little Falls, N.J.) _ The first pitch moved
through the night like a butterfly drunk on tequila, blithely
fluttering past the catcher. The sixth pitch tripped and fell
somewhere near home plate, then bounced off a batters shin. Six
pitches into a Jersey Jackals game against a lowly team from
Connecticut called the Waterbury Spirit, Mark Lemke found himself
with nobody out, runners on first and second base, and 3,000
spectators wondering what business he had being on the pitchers
mound. By Dan Barry.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 1 p.m. ET in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
