<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7179 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-EUROPE-ECLIPSE-REVIEW     08-14 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-ECLIPSE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PAUSE TO GAPE AT CELESTIAL FIREWORKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Out of gas, out of money and 200 miles from
home, Roland Pahland had good reasons to regret his passion for
seeing a solar eclipse.
</P>
<P>
   He had battled traffic jams for nine hours driving south from
Hannover to Stuttgart to get directly in the eclipse's path
Wednesday. When he got there, rain clouds blocked his view and that
of hundreds of thousands of others. Now, having failed to calculate
how much gas he would burn sitting in traffic, Pahland, an
unemployed truck driver, was drumming up donations by singing
country-and-western songs at a highway rest stop.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all that, he spoke with wide-eyed wonder about watching
the sky turn dark and then light again. ``This was a
once-in-a-lifetime experience,'' he said. ``We didn't get to see
the corona of the eclipse, but we did see the sky become totally
dark and then suddenly turn light two minutes later. I will never
forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   Eclipses do that to people. Millions of Europeans drove for
hours, just for the chance to put on paper glasses with blackened
lenses and gape at an event that lasted two-and-a-half minutes.
</P>
<P>
   There was something wondrous about the wonder itself. Between
horrible weather and ghastly traffic in much of Europe, it was as
if the Grinch had tried to steal the eclipse.
</P>
<P>
   German autobahns were clogged all day with more than 200 miles
of traffic jams. Yet there were few signs of bitterness or
frustration. Even though they woke up to warnings of both bad
weather and bad traffic, thousands of people decided they simply
had to take a chance to witness the event, which won't repeat
itself in the area until 2081.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, which was almost directly in the path of the eclipse,
traffic stopped almost entirely and office workers poured into the
streets. Trading came to a near halt at stock exchanges in
Frankfurt, Paris and other cities. In Rome, Pope John Paul II
shortened his weekly general audience in order to watch the
eclipse.
</P>
<P>
   Many Germans drove as close as they could to the eclipse's path,
then parked along shoulders of the autobahn or at gas stations and
rest areas. Parking areas became picnic spots. Astronomy buffs
compared notes on their solar-shielded cameras and telescopes.
Strangers shared their spectacles, which had become all but
impossible to buy by Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And as the moon slowly crept in front of the sun, novices and
experts alike grew quieter and more reverent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had the feeling that people had put everything behind them
for the two minutes when it was happening,'' said Marcel Wenderoth,
23, a hotel receptionist who decided Tuesday night to drive with
his wife and 2-year-old son several hours from Dortmund. ``It was
euphoric.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 1119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990814.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6259 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-EUROPE-ECLIPSE-REVIEW     08-14 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-ECLIPSE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PAUSE TO GAPE AT CELESTIAL FIREWORKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Out of gas, out of money and 200 miles from
home, Roland Pahland had good reasons to regret his passion for
seeing a solar eclipse.
</P>
<P>
   He had battled traffic jams for nine hours driving south from
Hannover to Stuttgart to get directly in the eclipse's path
Wednesday. When he got there, rain clouds blocked his view and that
of hundreds of thousands of others. Now, having failed to calculate
how much gas he would burn sitting in traffic, Pahland, an
unemployed truck driver, was drumming up donations by singing
country-and-western songs at a highway rest stop.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all that, he spoke with wide-eyed wonder about watching
the sky turn dark and then light again. ``This was a
once-in-a-lifetime experience,'' he said. ``We didn't get to see
the corona of the eclipse, but we did see the sky become totally
dark and then suddenly turn light two minutes later. I will never
forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   Eclipses do that to people. Millions of Europeans drove for
hours, just for the chance to put on paper glasses with blackened
lenses and gape at an event that lasted two-and-a-half minutes.
</P>
<P>
   There was something wondrous about the wonder itself. Between
horrible weather and ghastly traffic in much of Europe, it was as
if the Grinch had tried to steal the eclipse.
</P>
<P>
   German autobahns were clogged all day with more than 200 miles
of traffic jams. Yet there were few signs of bitterness or
frustration. Even though they woke up to warnings of both bad
weather and bad traffic, thousands of people decided they simply
had to take a chance to witness the event, which won't repeat
itself in the area until 2081.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, which was almost directly in the path of the eclipse,
traffic stopped almost entirely and office workers poured into the
streets. Trading came to a near halt at stock exchanges in
Frankfurt, Paris and other cities. In Rome, Pope John Paul II
shortened his weekly general audience in order to watch the
eclipse.
</P>
<P>
   Many Germans drove as close as they could to the eclipse's path,
then parked along shoulders of the autobahn or at gas stations and
rest areas. Parking areas became picnic spots. Astronomy buffs
compared notes on their solar-shielded cameras and telescopes.
Strangers shared their spectacles, which had become all but
impossible to buy by Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And as the moon slowly crept in front of the sun, novices and
experts alike grew quieter and more reverent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had the feeling that people had put everything behind them
for the two minutes when it was happening,'' said Marcel Wenderoth,
23, a hotel receptionist who decided Tuesday night to drive with
his wife and 2-year-old son several hours from Dortmund. ``It was
euphoric.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
