<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7187 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-DROUGHT-BLAME-REVIEW-     08-14 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DROUGHT-BLAME-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAMING THE VICTIM IN THE DROUGHT WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By JOE SHARKEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As this summer's drought hangs on like an unwanted guest at the
cottage, the cherished American pastime of lawn watering has been
criminalized by states desperate to change people's behavior and
save water.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, Gov. Christine Todd Whitman declared a state of
emergency Aug. 5, invoking extraordinary powers that threaten
people with fines up to $5,000 for disobeying water-use rules.
State Environmental Protection Commissioner Robert Shinn even
called on citizens to snitch on one another. ``We depend on
neighbors to monitor their neighbors because there aren't enough
police to do what we have to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey officials also said more severe measures could be
imposed, including the monitoring of home water use.
</P>
<P>
   The restrictions may be helping. New Jersey's water supply has
improved slightly since the emergency decree and with the help of
recent scattered thunderstorms. But a basic question remains: How
did this rap get pinned on the average citizen?
</P>
<P>
   After all, when a power blackout hit a big chunk of Manhattan
during July's heat wave, no one blamed apartment-dwellers for
running air conditioners. Instead, politicians denounced
Consolidated Edison for not planning better and investing more to
anticipate surges in demand.
</P>
<P>
   But during the current drought, virtually the only official
response has been to point a finger at homeowners and issue
emergency measures. While cutting back sharply on nonessential
water use makes obvious sense, some experts say state and local
governments and the news media have failed to recognize drought as
a complex set of phenomena that demand long-range regional planning
and hard decisions after the inevitable rains come and the
emergency decrees fade away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government should have a greater role in planning for water
resources rather than just blaming people,'' said Wenonah Hauter,
the director of the Public Citizen's Critical Mass Energy Project,
a Washington organization founded by Ralph Nader that lobbies for
better technological and political approaches to the use of energy
and natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of what we're hearing is haphazard responses about
lawns,'' Hauter said, ``but there are longer-term issues such as
the effect of urban sprawl on water resources that government
should be paying attention to.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans are willing to make sacrifices in crises. There is
widespread support, for example, for providing emergency relief to
the farm industry, which is exempt from most emergency water
restrictions. But there is often little public discussion about
emergency powers exercised by governors on matters like home water
use and lawn watering.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, there should be a more robust public debate about
how about government functions in a liberal democracy in times of
emergency _ especially about the amount of power that moves to the
central authority, whether in Trenton, Albany or Washington,'' said
Andrew Grossman, a political science professor at Albion College in
Albion, Mich., citing the potential for civil rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has set up a commission to study the
drought. But so far the government's chief response has been to
declare disaster emergencies in New Jersey, Connecticut, West
Virginia and parts of New York, Pennsylvania, Maryland, Virginia,
Kentucky, Ohio and New Mexico. These decrees provide federal
emergency subsidies to the farming industry, which has lost
billions of dollars in withered summer crops.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just food crops at stake. In New Jersey, for
example, the leading cash crop category is nursery, greenhouse and
lawn-sod products _ mainly decorative plants, shrubs and bushes
sold at garden centers for home use _ which accounted for $255
million in sales last year. So while homeowners are restricted in
watering their shrubs and plants, farmers are able to continue
producing such plants for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Even with their beloved lawns, Americans have shown a
willingness to voluntarily reduce water use without the threat of
criminal prosecution, said Professor Gordon Geballe, an associate
dean of the Yale University School of Forestry and Environmental
Studies. ``In the New Haven area, there are a large number of lawns
that are brown, and we don't have a water shortage yet,'' he said,
noting that lawns account for about 30 percent of water use in
metropolitan regions.
</P>
<P>
   Geballe said some people are reappraising the real costs of
their emerald-green expanses of grass _ and are adjusting their
behavior to ``escape the lawn-must-always-be-green addiction'' in
favor of an ``ecological approach'' that takes into account both a
lawn's use of water and the contribution that lawn mowers make to
carbon dioxide emissions, which may contribute to climatic
phenomena like drought.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, plant experts say there is a practical way to
mitigate future droughts without the threat of criminal
prosecution. Karen Snetselaar, a professor of biology at St.
Joseph's University in Philadelphia, said the overwatering of grass
and plants encourages them to keep their roots close to the soil
surface, where they are most vulnerable during droughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend to water every day,'' she said, ``and most of the
time that's the wrong thing to do, unless you are trying to get
seeds to germinate or when you have very young plants.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, by watering grass, shrubs and plants no more than once
a week the plants will modify their behavior and ``send their roots
farther down in the soil,'' she said. ``That way, when it doesn't
rain for a while, the plants have extensive root systems and
they're OK for a longer period the next time there's a drought.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 1131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
