<DOCNO> NYT19990814.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 12:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7196 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-SCENT-SENSITIVITY-REV     08-14 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCENT-SENSITIVITY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST, NO SMOKING. NOW, NO COLOGNE OR HAIR SPRAY. 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By JAMES BARRON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A madeleine dipped in lime-blossom tea sent Marcel Proust off on
an eight-volume reminiscence. A visit from a highly perfumed
Parisian prompted a one-sentence rant. ``My dear friend,'' Proust
wrote, ``the last time you were so good as to come and see me _ for
nobody comes any more to see the wretched invalid that I am _ I was
obliged to take the chair you sat in and keep it out in the
courtyard for three days: it was impregnated with the scent.''
</P>
<P>
   One can only imagine the blast Proust would have sent the friend
who gave him a subscription to a glossy magazine packed with
``scent strips.'' But if Proust lived in Halifax, Nova Scotia, he
would have less to complain about, perhaps. Some buildings and
businesses there have declared themselves fragrance-free zones. The
Halifax Herald newspaper has a no-scent policy: Employees may not
wear perfume, after-shave lotion or scented hairspray at work.
Schoolchildren may be sent to the principal's office if the teacher
can smell them. A telephone customer-service center enacted a
similar policy; it sends employees home to bathe.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some people who are sensitive to smells _ so sensitive that
they can be paralyzed by perfume, but not in the provocative way
Madison Avenue promises _ say Halifax has not gone far enough.
``It's very, very minor compared to what I see as absolutely
required for people with chemical sensitivities,'' said Susan
Molloy, who has been on disability for multiple chemical
sensitivity more than 10 years, ``and yet it's the best thing
that's happened so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Nelson of the National Foundation for the Chemically
Hypersensitive in Rhodes, Mich., who estimates that he has advised
25,000 people on fragrance problems, concurred. ``In California,
they made it a courtesy, not a law, not to wear over-heavy
fragrances that cause these problems,'' he said. That's not going
far enough for Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   In this country, efforts to provide fragrance-free zones _ which
gained steam in the early 1990s, before the passage of the federal
Americans with Disabilities Act _ appear to have slacked off. The
2,500-member First United Methodist Church in Boise, Idaho, dropped
its fragrance-free service after the minister who organized it (and
whose wife was fragrance-sensitive) moved to another church. The
75-seat chapel where the service was held is made of untreated
materials _ the walls are Arizona sandstone, the floors are made of
marble and flagstone, not covered with chemical-laden carpeting
like the main sanctuary. The pews are natural wood.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Ms. Molloy, 50, describes her life as a struggle
to avoid nearly everything _ including densely populated places.
Eight years ago, she left the San Francisco Bay Area for a remote
corner of Arizona. There, she and a handful of other people with
multiple chemical sensitivity have bought 400 acres in chunks of 20
or 40 acres. ``It's overgrazed ranchland,'' she said. ``The
ranchers can't make much use of it. We are letting the native
grasses grow back.'' Unlike allergy sufferers who worry that the
great outdoors aggravates their sneezes and sniffles, Ms. Molloy
said, ``Natural things are for the most part not too bad, at least
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   She works for a disability organization, advising others with
similar symptoms by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   And employment? Forget it, she said. ``It's impossible to get
hired if you have this,'' she said. ``If you develop MCS after you
have a good position and they can't get rid of you, there is the
possibility that effective accommodations can be approached, but
there's no way to apply for a job after you have this disease.
Imagine calling a prospective employer and saying, `Hi, will you
come outside to interview me?' The first time a truck goes by or
somebody lights a cigarette and you fall or lose the ability to
speak, the employer figures you probably can't do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Molloy avoids moviehouses and malls. And the zoo? Forget it
_ at least the Dallas Zoo. Reuters reported that researchers there
have found a scent that drives the endangered ocelot positively
wild _ Calvin Klein Obsession for Men cologne.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought about what would work with them and used things
like rat feces and ocelot scent,'' the zoo's research curator, Dr.
Cynthia Bennett, was quoted as saying. ``Then on a lark my research
technician brought in cologne because a lot of other animals like
it and we put Obsession out and our ocelots went wild over it.''
</P>
<P>
   The researchers have passed their findings along to Calvin Klein
Cosmetics Co., she said. ``They thought it was cute,'' she said.
``I think they were grateful we weren't trying it on vultures.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 1200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990814.0082 </DOCNO>
