<DOCNO> NYT19990814.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7200 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-ELVIS-ARCHIVES-REVIEW     08-14 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELVIS-ARCHIVES-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PRESLEY PAPERS: ARCHIVES OF THE KING'S RISE AND FALL 
</HEADLINE>
  The Week in Review 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(EDITORS: text that should be italicized is marked with (BEGIN
ITALICS HERE) and (END ITALICS HERE) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS, Tenn. _ These are high holy days for Elvis fans: the
end of a week of commemorations leading up to the anniversary
Monday of the pop icon's 1977 death here at Graceland amid
overindulgence and drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
   This year, attention is being drawn to long-mothballed artifacts
of the singer's odyssey from mere mortal to flawed deity. Lisa
Marie Presley, Elvis' only child and primary heir, has decided to
auction off thousands of her father's personal items and documents
_ most of which have never been publicly displayed. Her aim is to
raise millions to build a homeless shelter in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   The bidding, handled by the New York auction house Guernsey's,
will take place Columbus Day weekend at the MGM Grand casino in Las
Vegas. Bids on the items, organized in more than 1,000 lots, will
also be taken online at icollector.com.
</P>
<P>
   For sale are not only Elvis artifacts like guitars, costumes,
posters, credit cards, the 1956 Lincoln in which he squired around
Natalie Wood and even the King's blue velvet beanbag chair, but
also contracts he signed and hundreds of other unpublished
documents and letters illuminating the singer's rise and fall. Here
is a small sampling from the Elvis archives.
</P>
<P>
   _ By TOM KUNTZ
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Early on, the King had a hard time getting
bookings. In 1954, his manager and guitarist, Scotty Moore,
received this reply from an assistant to Col. Tom Parker (who was,
curiously enough, soon to take over as Elvis' manager):(END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Scotty Moore . . . Thank you so much for your letter
regarding your artist, and while we are a booking and promotion
agency, I don't have anything at present where I could place your
artist. There are few outlets for hillbilly entertainers in this
area around Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Kindest regards, Tom Diskin
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)By the next year, Elvis still wasn't a
household name, as this letter to Parker from a West Coast promoter
attests:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Dear Tom: There is a good possibility I may be able to use ALVIN
PRESLEY during April, (starting approximately April 10). Please let
me know if he is available and the price for one date, as well as
for a series of dates. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Sincerely, A.V. Bamford
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)1956: With his career gathering steam, Elvis
went to Hollywood. But the future bankable star couldn't land the
first part he auditioned for, that of Jim in ``The Rainmaker.'' (It
went to Earl Holliman in a film starring Burt Lancaster and
Katherine Hepburn.) Still, the screen-test script seems to have
Elvis-style gravitas. Here Jim (Elvis) is about to reveal his
engagement to Snookie:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   THE DINING-LIVING ROOM - (NIGHT) . . .
</P>
<P>
   JIM (Elvis): God e-ve-ning!
</P>
<P>
   NOAH: Where the heck have you been?
</P>
<P>
   JIM (with a lordly gesture): Out - out - out!
</P>
<P>
   NOAH: What's wrong with you? Are you drunk?
</P>
<P>
   JIM (with mighty superiority): No big brother, I ain't drunk.
But if I cared to be drunk, I'd be goggle-eyed! . . .
</P>
<P>
   H.C. (secretly amused): Where'd you get the stogie, Jim?
</P>
<P>
   JIM: It ain't a stogie. It's a Havana panatella. Eighty-five
cents. And it's a present.
</P>
<P>
   NOAH: Who the Sam Hill gave it to you?
</P>
<P>
   JIM: I-the-Sam-Hill gave it to me! . . . For bein' a big boy! .
. .
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)1956: A letter from Elvis endorsing a
restaurateur suggests the King's culinary leanings:(END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   HELLO FRIENDS . . . THIS IS ELVIS PRESLEY ADDING MY
CONGRATULATIONS TO THE THOUSANDS OF CUSTOMERS OF MY FRIEND BILL
WILLIAMS' MANY FINE RESTAURANTS . . . UPON THE OPENING OF HIS
LATEST AND NEWEST IN HIS FABULOUS CHAIN . . . AND THE NEXT TIME
YOU'RE EATING FRIED CHICKEN IN ANY BILL WILLIAMS RESTAURANT LOOK
CLOSELY AT EVERYBODY EATING THAT DELICIOUS CHICKEN BECAUSE . . . IT
MIGHT BE ME . . .
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)By 1957, with hits like ``Heartbreak Hotel''
and national TV successes behind them, Elvis and the Colonel felt
they could name their price. In a letter to Elvis, the manager
reveals himself as a tough bargainer. (He calls Elvis ``Wallaby,''
after the gift of a pet from Australian fans):(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Dear Wallaby; The First:
</P>
<P>
   I have been bombarded befuddled befogged bewildered and snowed
under the past few months to have you do a television show on a
spectacular for RCA.NBC in color. . . . They came up with a pretty
good offer several times but I turned them all down, with respect
to our motion picture work and for the reason (sic) I know are best
for us. So I told them that our next TV show for any sponsor we do
would be $50,000 fifty thousand dollars as I want to do only one or
two TV shows this year. . . . At least you will not be overexposed
like some of the top stars that are now working for nothing as they
are worn out on TV. . . . Please indicate by marking either Yess
(sic) if you think you should work cheaper or NUTS if you think I
should keep snowing for the $50,000. . . .
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Elvis' handwritten note (in italics):(END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)YESS IF YOU WANT TO CUT THE PRICE: NUTS.(END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)1957: Trouble in the band. Bill Black,
Elvis' bass player, presses complaints about being denied the
fruits of Elvis' success. Black and Moore, the guitarist, soon quit
over their pay of only $200 a week each: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Dear Tom: Haven't heard a word from you on the money situation
you were going to look into after we left. Knowing that you are a
man of your word and faithfully devoted to us, your complete
silence has me worried. What's the lowdown. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Yours truly, Bill Black
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Diskin, the Colonel's assistant,
replies:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Dear Bill:
</P>
<P>
   If I had information on the money matter you may be sure I would
have passed it on. However, I mentioned it to the people out there
and they said they would look into it and that they would advise if
anything was forthcoming. . . . It is not likely that they are
going to make any further payment.
</P>
<P>
   Hope you had a very pleasant vacation. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Sincerely, Tom Diskin
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
