replies:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Dear Bill:
</P>
<P>
   If I had information on the money matter you may be sure I would
have passed it on. However, I mentioned it to the people out there
and they said they would look into it and that they would advise if
anything was forthcoming. . . . It is not likely that they are
going to make any further payment.
</P>
<P>
   Hope you had a very pleasant vacation. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Sincerely, Tom Diskin
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)1960: Elvis is in the Army now, stationed in
Germany, and declines a royal invitation. The letter from a
representative of Buckingham Palace suggests that Princess Diana
wasn't the first member of royalty interested in rock 'n' roll:(END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Dear Mr. Presley:
</P>
<P>
   I am arranging a Royal Command Performance for her Majesty,
Queen Elizabeth of England, and His Royal Highness, Prince Philip,
Duke of Edinburgh, to be held Monday evening, May 16th, at the
Victoria Palace Theatre, in London.
</P>
<P>
   If it is at all possible for you to come to London on that date,
I should be very pleased if you will accept this invitation to
appear in the programme. . . . Yours sincerely, Jack Hylton
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)1961: Back in civvies, Elvis learns that the
producer Hal Wallis is worried that he won't be in shape for the
filming of ``Blue Hawaii'':(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Dear Elvis: Today, the Colonel received a letter from Mr. Wallis
in which he said that in the next picture it is very important that
you look lean and hard and well tanned to fit into the Hawaiian
background and situation properly. He said you should have a good
overall coat of tan on your body as well as your face and said also
that you should watch your weight and your physical condition and
that you should look very much like you did for ``GI Blues.'' He
enclosed a folder on an ultraviolet lamp . . . and suggested that
you get one of these and start using it a few weeks before you
leave for the West Coast, using it a few minutes a day over your
entire body. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Sincerely, Tom Diskin
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)1965: As rock 'n' roll moves beyond the
King, the Beatles visit his California mansion. But it goes badly
when Elvis largely ignores the Fab Four and Brian Epstein, their
manager. A thank you note belies the awkwardness:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Dear Colonel Parker: There are many things for which I must
thank you. Above all, for the trouble and consideration you took
towards making the meeting of the boys and myself with Mr. Presley
such a wonderfully relaxing and happy evening. I cannot say how
much we all enjoyed ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Very Sincerely, Brian Epstein
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)1970: Even Johnny Carson got the cold
shoulder:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Dear Elvis:
</P>
<P>
   I wonder whether my recent message to you regarding the 33rd
Anniversary of the Wiltwyck Schoool for Boys got lost as a result
of the recent postal tie-up or that your resonse was held up by it.
In any event the enclosed invitation will serve as a reminder. ....
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)1974: Elvis is in decline and flirting with
self-parody, as illustrated by this rambling monologue transcribed
during his concert tour that year:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Good evening, ladies and gentlemen, my name is Wayne Newton.
Hope you have a good time _ really, true, true. If you didn't get a
scarf or didn't get kissed, I'll get to you. Just, you know, I'll
make the rounds. Sure, you know, everybody in the whole place,
except the guys, and they get a handshake. This song is a song I
recorded about 15 years ago and my voice was much higher. I have to
be careful singing it 'cause I'll break something, you know.
(Evidently to an audience member) Honey, I couldn't come over
during that number. I can just see me trying to hug you. OK, want a
kiss? You might catch the crud or something. Hey, wait a minute.
Tough way to make a living, I'll tell you. I'd like to intro _
Well, it's like the day . . . and there it goes . . . the voice,
the brain, everything. . . .
</P>
</TEXT>
