<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETIMES ALL YOU CAN DO WITH A FLICKERING MONITOR IS GET RID OF
IT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My son recently gave me a hand-me-down Windows 95 computer so
we can communicate by e-mail. I like it a lot, but I am having a
hard time looking at the monitor for very long. It seems to be
flickering, but it's something I can really only see out of the
corner of my eye. How can I fix it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sounds like the computer hasn't properly identified the kind
of monitor you have, or it's a very old and/or cheap monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Using beams of electrons, monitors actually draw an image on the
screen line by line, but it happens so quickly that it appears to
be one big picture to you. The faster it draws the image _ known as
the refresh rate _ the better it looks. The refresh rate is
expressed in hertz.
</P>
<P>
   (Some older models draw the image by painting every other line
on the screen. The electron beams then go back and pick up the
remaining lines on a second pass. This is called interlacing, and
it can also lead to nasty flickering. Most modern monitors are
non-interlaced, in which all the lines are painted in a single
pass.)
</P>
<P>
   If it draws the image at a refresh rate of under 72 hertz,
you're apt to detect a flickering. This can cause eyestrain and
ultimately lead to a headache.
</P>
<P>
   You can change the refresh rate in the Windows display
properties control panel. Right-click on the open desktop, and
choose Properties. Click on the Settings tab, and then click the
Advanced button.
</P>
<P>
   What happens from here depends on how your video drivers are set
up, or what version of Windows you have. In most cases, you'll
click on the Adapter tab, where you'll see a drop-down titled
Refresh Rate. If your monitor is properly supported in Windows, and
if it's capable of higher refresh rates, you should have options in
this box that let you set the refresh rate at 72 hertz or higher.
</P>
<P>
   If you have only a couple of choices, none of them above 72
hertz, your monitor may not be properly recognized.
</P>
<P>
   You should see a Monitor tab at the top of this dialog box.
Choose it and see if the system has identified your monitor
correctly. If not, click the Change button and follow the
instructions to set up your monitor.
</P>
<P>
   If the monitor is correctly identified and you still don't have
access to higher refresh rates, it's likely that this is an older
model and you may want to consider replacing it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently bought a new computer that came with Windows 98. I
had been using Windows 3.1. Try as I might, I can't get used to
using My Computer to see what's on the hard drive. I want the old
File Manager back. Is there some way I can use File Manager on my
new machine? What files would I have to copy from Windows 3.1?
</P>
<P>
   A: None. The File Manager is still present in Windows 98 _ it's
just not obvious.
</P>
<P>
   When Microsoft introduced Windows 95, the company knew that
people had grown accustomed to the File Manager _ even though it's
a pretty klunky way to work with files. Microsoft decided to leave
the program in the operating system, but not point to it with a
shortcut.
</P>
<P>
   You can invoke the File Manager by going to Start, Run and enter
WINFILE, then hit Enter.
</P>
<P>
   The old Program Manager is there, too, but it likely won't have
any program groups in it. From Start/Run, enter PROGMAN.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been thinking about getting a new iMac to replace my
aging Apple Performa, but I really like my printer, and I
understand the iMacs don't have a traditional printer port. Is
there a way I can use my old printer with an iMac?
</P>
<P>
   A: Check with the maker of your printer. Many manufacturers have
come out with adapters and drivers that let you plug an older
printer into the Universal Serial Bus port on a newer Macintosh.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
