<HEADER>
A7206 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CATHOLIC-RADIO-ART-61     08-14 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLIC-RADIO-ART-615(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLICS CONTEST EVANGELICALS' RADIO DOMINANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Ill., Minn., Kan., Wis., Ohio, Colo., Calif., R.I.,
Mass., Maine, Ala.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By LAURIE GOODSTEIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A group of wealthy Roman Catholic entrepreneurs, concerned that
the nation's religious radio programming is dominated by
evangelical Protestants, has started a radio network intended to
broadcast a conservative Catholic spin on politics, news, personal
problems and spiritual questions.
</P>
<P>
   The network, Catholic Family Radio, began broadcasting in
January and has already bought stations in eight cities and expects
to take over stations in six more next month. The format is
all-talk, and the hosts include pundits, psychologists and
politicians like Dan Lungren, a Republican who was California state
attorney general and a gubernatorial candidate, and Raymond Flynn,
a Democrat, formerly mayor of Boston and U.S. ambassador to the
Vatican. Each has his own three-hour show.
</P>
<P>
   The talk often sounds like the fare served up on secular
conservative talk shows like Rush Limbaugh's: taxes, abortion and
traditional family values, the Clintons, the Kennedys and the
candidates for president. In fact, the network has hired as a
consultant Bruce Marr, the radio programmer who helped make
Limbaugh a household name.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to stealth evangelize,'' said John Lynch,
president and chief executive of Catholic Family Radio, ``as
opposed to the Christian evangelicals who do hitting-over-the-head
evangelizing. There are probably too many people who had
hit-over-the-head Catholicism imposed on them, and that's not the
approach we want.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of nominal, fallen-away Catholics and
non-Catholics,'' Lynch said. ``That group is who we want to
reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Evangelical Christian programs are heard regularly on 1,616
radio stations in the United States, said Karl Stoll, a spokesman
for National Religious Broadcasters. But before Catholic Family
Radio emerged, there were only six radio stations run by Catholic
dioceses, said Msgr. Francis Maniscalco, a spokesman for the
National Conference of Catholic Bishops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't have to do with the lack of Catholic interest in
media,'' Maniscalco said, ``but with the fact that the church has
run into this major problem that the opportunities for free air
time are closing, and that's why we see less and less of Catholic
media.''
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II, whose words are featured on compact discs and
in the Vatican Web site, has called on Catholics to expand the use
of media to spread the faith. But since the death in 1979 of
Archbishop Fulton Sheen, the voice of ``The Catholic Hour'' on
national radio and later on television, the Catholic Church has
lacked a ubiquitous nationwide presence in the American media.
</P>
<P>
   Mother Angelica, an abbess in Birmingham, Ala., runs the Eternal
Word Television Network, which reaches millions worldwide over
satellite television and radio. But she is not well known outside
her audience of committed Catholics attracted by her traditionalist
approach.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic Family Radio is not run by the Roman Catholic Church
itself, but by a board of investors who are among the nation's most
successful Catholic businessmen, some billionaires. They include
Thomas Monaghan, former chairman of Domino's Pizza; David Weyrich,
former owner of Martin Media LP, a billboard advertising company,
and John Saeman, founder of Medallion Enterprises. Peter Lynch, the
well-known former money manager of Fidelity Magellan Fund, is also
an investor, but not a board member.
</P>
<P>
   The investors' goal is to own stations in 40 of the 50 top radio
markets and to take the company public next year. The stations that
already broadcast Catholic Family Radio programs are in
Philadelphia, Chicago, Minneapolis, Milwaukee, Denver, Kansas City,
Kan., Los Angeles and San Francisco.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We came to peace, our group of investors, with the idea that
we could make a little money and do a little good,'' John Lynch
said. ``Hopefully, it's make a lot of money and do a lot of good.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishops have been asked to contribute two-minute commentaries,
and some have, including Cardinal John Cardinal O'Connor, the
archbishop of New York.
</P>
<P>
   But Archbishop Rembert Weakland of Milwaukee, a liberal-leaning
prelate, declined the invitation and said that the station was not
welcome in his archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   ``He finds the people involved have a track record of being more
combative than in the spirit of dialogue,'' said Jerry Topczewski,
spokesman for the Milwaukee archdiocese. ``Some of them have a
track record of criticizing bishops throughout the country and the
world on various doctrinal issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the Catholic network originated with the Rev.
Joseph Fessio, a Jesuit who heads Ignatius Press in San Francisco.
Fessio is an influential conservative who has criticized bishops
who proposed using sex-neutral language in the revised Catholic
catechism. He also voiced his disapproval of the Vatican's decision
to allow altar girls.
</P>
<P>
   Fessio said that he sought help from Nicholas Healey, then vice
president of Franciscan University of Steubenville, Ohio, a campus
also known for its conservative orientation; Archbishop Charles
Chaput of Denver, and Frank Hager, the managing director of Morgan
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   They proposed the idea for a Catholic radio network to John
Lynch, a former linebacker for the Pittsburgh Steelers who became
president of the Noble Broadcast Group, a network of 12 radio
stations that was sold in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lynch raised $50 million from investors for Catholic Family
Radio, and last year bought the first seven stations from
Children's Broadcasting Corporation for $37 million. The investors
recently added the station in San Francisco, and are awaiting
approval from the Federal Communications Commission next month to
take over stations in Boston, Providence, R.I., Springfield, Mass.,
Rumfords, Maine, and two in Portland, Maine The network's corporate
offices are in San Diego, and its programming headquarters is in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   All the hosts, commercials and programs produced by outside
sources must be approved by a contents committee composed of
Fessio, Chaput and Healey.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no topic that's not appropriate,'' Fessio said. He has
proposed inviting Dr. Jack Kevorkian on the air to debate assisted
suicide, he said. He said the festering intrachurch controversies,
like ordination of women or married men, could be discussed but are
not encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really did not want to emphasize very much inner-church
controversies, but they come up, so we don't exclude them,'' Fessio
said. ``We'd rather deal with ordinary people's ordinary
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Listeners who have questions about potty training or teen-age
dating call in to Dr. Ray Guarendi, a psychologist and author of
books on parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   The network has been vulnerable to criticism that it is too
conservative and too Republican. One host was Alan Keyes, a
Republican presidential candidate and staunch social conservative.
When Keyes missed dozens of his broadcasts because of campaigning,
Lynch said he made sure to find a Democrat as a replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to make sure that this didn't come off as a far
right-wing effort,'' Lynch said.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren's show veers from political talk about the Clintons'
marriage to theological discussion about the second coming of
Christ. In an interview, he said he always tried ``to express what
the Catholic Church's position is on a particular issue,'' and he
also shares his own. Lungren supports the death penalty, while the
pope says it is ``cruel and unnecessary'' and inconsistent with the
church's ``pro-life'' teachings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obvious that I am conservative and I am Republican,''
Lungren said, ``and I make that clear. But I also make clear that
the Republican conservative position is not necessarily the
Catholic position, if there is a the Catholic position.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for the Catholic Radio Network, said the Rev.
Thomas Reese, editor of America, a weekly Jesuit magazine, is
whether it can be consistently Catholic in its content.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's a cafeteria Catholic, whether they're liberal or
conservative,'' picking and choosing which teachings to embrace,
Reese said. ``There are lots of issues in terms of welfare reform
and peace and justice where the bishops and the pope are way to the
left even of liberal Democrats, let alone Republicans. Will this
radio network be Catholic in that sense?''
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``That's going to be very difficult to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 1214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
