him.
</P>
<P>
   But with historical revisionism and micro-medicine running amok,
scientists have now cast a fresh eye on that hair, and on an 1839
sample, and now proclaim _ in a study in The Journal of the
American Medical Association _ that it was in fact lead poisoning
that caused Jackson's chronic kidney problems. Neither hair sample
showed toxic levels of mercury.
</P>
<P>
   In an 1813 gunfight, a bullet landed in Jackson's shoulder _ and
stayed there for nearly 20 years. The 1815 sample showed enough
lead to cause problems, but by 1839, years after the bullet was
removed, the lead was down to a safe level. And one expert not
