   So how far will revisionism go? Now that mercury is off the hook
in this celebrated case, will innovative doctors propose that we
again dose ourselves with Jackson's old remedy, mercury-laden
calomel, which one scientist called ``the aspirin of the early 19th
century''?
</P>
<P>
   You never know.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Eichmann, in Memoirs, Tries to Explain His Psyche
</P>
<P>
   Adolf Eichmann, seeking to explain his central role in the
killing of 6 million European Jews by the Nazis, was moved to
organize the mass murders by a visceral sense of duty rather than
hatred, according to memoirs published by the German newspaper Die
Welt. ``Obeying an order was the most important thing to me,''
Eichmann wrote. ``It could be that is in the nature of the
German.''
</P>
<P>
   That statement was contained in 127 pages of handwritten
reflections that Die Welt said it found at the Center for Research
on Nazi Crimes in the southern German town of Ludwigsburg.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli Justice Ministry announced that 1,200 pages of notes
by Eichmann would be released to German researchers for scholarly
publication. Eichmann was captured in Argentina by Israeli agents
in 1960 and executed in Israel two years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I look back,'' Eichmann wrote, ``I realize that a
life predicated on being obedient and taking orders is a very
comfortable life indeed. Living in such a way reduces to a minimum
one's own need to think.''
</P>
<P>
   China-Taiwan Tensions
</P>
<P>
   China and Taiwan are sending military planes flying over the
100-mile-wide straits separating the two rival nations, and the
United States is urging both sides to calm down. The situation is
``dangerous'' and ``very delicate,'' said one official. Washington
fears an accident or a misunderstanding could set off acts of war.
China has considered Taiwan a renegade for 50 years, and refuses to
renounce violence as a means to bring it back under mainland
control.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Beatty Hints At a Presidential Run
</P>
<P>
   Eyes rolled when Ronald Reagan first ran for California governor
and when Sonny Bono said he wanted to be a congressman. So it was
probably inevitable that Warren Beatty's toying with running for
president would draw some laughs. But the movie star's hints that
he is weighing a bid either as a Democrat or a Reform Party
contender also drew some praise from liberals who think they are
not adequately represented by Vice President Al Gore or his rival,
former Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Beatty's involvement in politics is far deeper than his role as
a senator who could not help but speak the truth in the film
``Bulworth.'' He was an early supporter of Robert F. Kennedy, and
he was also a confidant of former Sen. Gary Hart, who has publicly
encouraged a Beatty candidacy. Beatty has said his central issue
would be campaign reform.
</P>
<P>
   But he has not explained why he showed up this summer at a
Hollywood fund-raiser for Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD L. BERKE
</P>
<P>
   Tax Court Hits U.P.S. With A Huge Bill
</P>
<P>
   A Tax Court judge ruled that United Parcel Service took inflated
tax deductions in 1984 and must pay taxes, penalties and interest.
The company said the total might be close to $300 million for 1984
alone, and it could owe hundreds of millions more for later years.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was a rare victory for the IRS in its efforts to
prevent companies from claiming deductions when they move money to
subsidiaries overseas for the sole purpose of avoiding taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In Iraq, Good and Bad News On Child Mortality
</P>
<P>
   The first large survey of the mortality rates of Iraqi children
living under international sanctions since Iraq invaded Kuwait in
1990 produced mixed findings from Unicef. In areas of the country
where President Saddam Hussein controls the distribution of relief
food and medicines, babies and children under 5 are dying at twice
the rate they were in the late 1980's.
</P>
<P>
   Where relief goods are distributed by the United Nations in the
autonomous northern Kurdish areas, child mortality rates are
falling. Unicef urged Iraq to spend more on child and maternal
nutrition and asked the United Nations Security Council to put a
higher priority on getting aid to the youngest Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARBARA CROSSETTE
</P>
<P>
   India Shoots Down A Pakistani Jet
</P>
<P>
   An Indian jet fighter shot down a propeller-driven Pakistani
naval surveillance plane, killing its 16 passengers and sending the
subcontinent into yet another moment of nail-biting.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians said the naval aircraft was on a spying mission
above their air space while the Pakistanis insisted that the plane
was on an entirely innocent training mission and had never crossed
the border. Both sides were able to salvage chunks of the scattered
wreckage, parts of which fell into each nation's territory.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARRY BEARAK &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty for Puerto Ricans
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said he would commute the sentences of 16
members of a Puerto Rican independence group if they agree to
renounce violence. Although their group, the FALN, has been linked
to more than 100 bombings of political targets and military
installations in the United States in the 1970s and '80s, none of
the 16 were involved in any deaths, the White House said. The
action followed pressure from human rights leaders, who argued that
the sentences, some as long as 90 years, were out of proportion to
the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   _ By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Customs Announces Changes In Its Search Policy
</P>
<P>
   After years of complaints and lawsuits, U.S. Customs Service
officials said the agency would change the way it conducts personal
searches of thousands of people who arrive in the United States
each year and are suspected of smuggling narcotics. Customs has
adopted tighter criteria to determine who will be subjected to body
searches in place of an unwieldy system that agency officials said
permitted searches of anyone who looked too nervous or too calm.
</P>
<P>
   Black women in Chicago have filed a class action lawsuit
complaining that they were singled out for what they said were
abusive searches, but the agency has denied that it intentionally
targeted any group.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   New Directive on Gays
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department's ``don't-ask, don't-tell'' policy was
supposed to make it easier for gay soldiers to remain in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   But recent criticism that the policy is having exactly the
opposite effect led the Pentagon to announce new guidelines for
enforcement of the five-year-old policy.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new directives, troops will receive anti-harassment
training throughout their careers, beginning with boot camp, and
commanders will have to get approval from senior Pentagon officials
before opening certain types of investigations of a soldier's
sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PHILIP SHENON
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
