<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7221 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-BBO-LEMKE-ART-2TAKES-     08-14 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LEMKE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEMKE KEEPING A LOOSE GRIP ON A BALL, A TIGHT GRIP ON A DREAM
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DAN BARRY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE FALLS, N.J. _ The first pitch moved through the night
like a butterfly drunk on tequila, floating blithely past the
catcher. The second pitch sailed about like a party balloon
sputtering helium. The sixth pitch tripped and fell somewhere near
home plate, bouncing off a batter's shin.
</P>
<P>
   Six pitches into a New Jersey Jackals game against a lowly team
from Connecticut called the Waterbury Spirit, Mark Lemke found
himself with nobody out, runners on first and second base, and
3,000 spectators wondering what business he had being on the
pitcher's mound.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, didn't this guy used to play second base for the
Atlanta Braves when it won four National League pennants and a
World Series? What was he doing at a bandbox called Yogi Berra
Stadium, where foul balls prompt the recorded sound of breaking
glass and the recommendation to visit ``Mulligan Motors in Nutley
for all your automotive needs?''
</P>
<P>
   Such questions are beyond the concerns of this baseball
knight-in-training. At 34, Lemke is attempting a comeback by
embarking on the most offbeat path known to the sport, a path that
requires years of practice and the ability to embrace the mystical,
to entrust to the air the cowhide sphere that you offer.
</P>
<P>
   Lemke wants to be a knuckleball pitcher. And in that quest, he
becomes an almost mythical character in not one but two of the
game's most seductive story lines. The fallen baseball veteran
seeking redemption on backwater ball fields far from the glittering
baseball diamonds where he once starred. And the baseball Everyman,
pinning his major-league hopes on an improbable pitch that, with
enough practice, an overweight plumber in his 40s conceivably could
master.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the tiny clubhouse after the game, his right arm
wrapped in ice and his left hand clutching a can of beer, Lemke
pondered the question of whether he hoped this might lead to a
return to the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say no,'' he said softly. ``But I don't think that
on the other hand it would crush me'' if no offer came. ``To be
honest with you, I enjoy playing the game of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The few knuckleball pitchers in the major leagues today are the
counterculture cousins to all other pitchers. Instead of
overpowering batters with spinning fastballs and curveballs, a
knuckleballer holds the baseball in an entirely different fashion _
essentially by the fingernails and fingertips _ and then lofts it
toward home plate with as little spin as possible.
</P>
<P>
   If it works, the leisurely pitch will veer this way, that way
and any way that catches its fancy, all while giving what seems to
be the Bronx cheer to physics. If it doesn't, the pitcher might as
well have thrown the ball underhand for the batter to hit over the
fence.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, many scientists wrote off confounded hitters _ ``a
butterfly with hiccups,'' the great hitter Willie Stargell once
called the knuckleball _ as victims of optical illusions. But in
recent years physicists have determined that the protruding
stitches on a barely spinning ball disrupt the air flow, cause
aerodynamic distress, and dramatically alter the ball's trajectory.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that can cause the baseball to act, in the vernacular of
baseball, as though it is fluttering,'' said Dr. Joel W. Hollenberg
of the Cooper Union School of Engineering. Hollenberg spent many
years addressing the aerodynamic questions posed by the
knuckleball, but has moved on to matters that he suggests are of
more value to humankind _ like trying to make hydrogen from water
by using sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   But the lure of the knuckleball is known to children and
scientists alike. Growing up in Utica, N.Y., Lemke joined the
legions of backyard ball tossers who spend waning summer days
trying to unlock the mystery of the knuckler. In addition to
wanting to make a ball jitterbug, they harbor the seductive fantasy
that learning to throw an effective knuckleball, a pitch that does
not tax the arm, might lead them to the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Some of its masters, including the Hall of Famers Phil Niekro
and Hoyt Wilhelm, pitched well into their 40s; others have
displayed physiques more reminiscent of groundskeepers than of
professional athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a giant killer,'' said Jim Bouton, the former New York
Yankees fastball pitcher whose use of the knuckleball allowed him
to extend his career by several years. ``It's like David with a
slingshot. It allows a small man to humble a big man and do it
humorously.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaching for that slingshot now is another small man, Mark
Lemke.
</P>
<P>
   In the 11 years he spent in the majors, Lemke never bathed in
the adulation that washes over the likes of Mark McGwire and Sammy
Sosa. Although his catlike quickness made him a premier second
baseman, he was not much of a hitter. Under the Ralph Kiner law
that home-run hitters drive Cadillacs, Mark Lemke drove a Yugo.
</P>
<P>
   But Lemke had certain traits that endeared him to students of
the game. He played so hard and with such boyish joy that he was
nicknamed ``Dirt.'' He was an integral member of the Atlanta
Braves, perhaps the dominant team of the 1990s. And in 62
post-season games, including appearances in four World Series, the
light-hitting Lemke seemed to will himself to greatness, hitting
well above his batting average and coming through at crucial
moments time and again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't a superstar on a team full of superstars, and he
didn't get much recognition,'' Tom Glavine, the Braves' star
pitcher, said in a telephone call to Yogi Berra Stadium the other
night. ``But he was a clutch player in the postseason, and
extremely underrated. And as a defensive player, he was as good as
it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   But professional baseball offers no promise of lifetime
membership. A slap-hitting second baseman who loses a half-step in
his 30s _ his hard style of play took its toll on his ankles and
his vision _ can suddenly find that hustle and attitude are not
enough. At the end of the 1997 season, the Braves brushed off their
beloved ``Dirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemke hooked on for another year with the Boston Red Sox. But as
last winter gave in to spring, the silence of the telephone helped
him to realize that his major-league career, however remarkable,
apparently had come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   There did come one telephone call, though, from Kash Beauchamp.
Beauchamp, a minor-league teammate of his in the 1980s, was now the
manager of the New Jersey Jackals of the independent Northern
League. Its players, from young prospects to aging veterans, hope
to attract the interest of a major-league franchise with the feats
they perform on ball fields in Allentown, Pa., Fargo, N.D. _ and
Little Falls.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The two friends struck a deal. Lemke, who lives outside Atlanta
with his wife and family, would spend the summer coaching
Beauchamp's young infielders if he got to pitch his knuckleball.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he told me he wanted to be a knuckleball pitcher, it hit
me,'' Beauchamp recalled. ``That's all he used to do. Everyone
messes around with it, but he would throw it every day. And when he
throws a good one, it's as good as I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine had the same recollection. ``If I was having a catch
with him and he started throwing it, I'd stop having a catch with
him,'' he said. ``It was that good. But I wasn't about to take one
off the kneecap.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the mechanics of throwing the knuckleball, however, Lemke
must learn what Bouton calls the ``Zen quality'' of letting the
ball go.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the fastball and other pitches, you're controlling
everything,'' he said. ``The knuckleball, on the other hand, is the
opposite of all that. You can't make a knuckleball happen. There is
nothing you do with your hands except release it and leave it up to
the wind and the air and the gods.''
</P>
<P>
   The student Lemke said that he understood the concept. When he
strode toward the pitcher's mound this night, he did not hear the
cajun music being played to promote ``Mardi Gras Night,'' or notice
the mascot, Jack the Jackal, cavorting in the stands, or see the
Little Leaguers clutching his Atlanta Braves baseball card.
</P>
<P>
   He was concentrating on his mantra _ trust your knuckleball _
but it was mentally taxing. ``You can throw the greatest one in the
world,'' he explained, not bothering to hide his awe. ``And then
the next hundred don't do anything. It's the challenge of saying to
yourself, `How did I throw that?'''
</P>
<P>
   Lemke got out of that first-inning jam with only one run scored
against him, and his teammates rallied to his cause by scoring 12
runs over the next two innings. By the fourth inning, he seemed to
have command of his knuckleball, consistently releasing it in the
general direction of the plate. The Spirits of Waterbury flailed
and whiffed and grunted.
</P>
<P>
   But when he started the sixth inning with his sixth walk of the
night _ the bane of knuckleball pitchers _ Beauchamp came out to
the mound to pull his friend from a game that the Waterbury Spirit
had all but conceded.
</P>
<P>
   According to the game's official scorer, Lemke had given up two
earned runs and only three hits in five innings, a success by any
measure. But there was also the unrecorded gift that he had
presented to those fans paying attention: knuckleball after
knuckleball, dancing summertime waltzes on a muggy night in New
Jersey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
