<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-595&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABBATH MOVE THREATENS COALITION IN ISRAEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ETHAN BRONNER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel permitted the
truck transport of a huge metal turbine part on the Jewish Sabbath
on Aug. 14, defying an Orthodox party that forms a crucial part of
his coalition government and raising concerns over a possible
government crisis.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Eliahu Suissa, the minister of national
infrastructure and a leader of the Orthodox Shas party, tried to
prevent the transport _ Jewish law prohibits vehicular travel on
the Sabbath. He threatened to take his party's 17 seats in
Parliament and leave the government.
</P>
<P>
   It was then announced that the turbine part would be moved on a
different day. But then the police said the 14-hour job would begin
on Friday night and be completed Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians were waiting until Saturday night, when the Sabbath
ends, to see whether Suissa would try to make good on his threat.
</P>
<P>
   Barak governs Israel with a 75-member coalition, providing more
than the majority he needs in the 120-member Parliament. But if
Shas were really to leave _ possibly followed by the five-member
United Torah Judaism party, which might not wish to seem less
concerned over violations of religious law than its colleagues _
Barak would no longer hold a majority.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear on Friday how seriously Suissa viewed the affair,
but there was analysis on Israel Radio suggesting that he had his
own internal party reasons for provoking a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   His words, when the original plan was announced to move the
turbine part to an electrical power station in the coastal city of
Ashkelon, were unambiguous. He said that if the move went ahead he
could not imagine ``that there will be anyone with a kippa'' _
yarmulke, or skullcap _ ``on his head who will be willing to sit at
the government's table.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barak responded that ``transporting oversized cargo on the
Sabbath has been the custom for 50 years and there is nothing new
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The 250-ton turbine part moved at a pace of 10 mph and took up
nearly three lanes for the journey from an Israel Military
Industries plant near Tel Aviv to the electric company station in
Ashkelon.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of making the move overnight on the Sabbath was to
avoid the traffic jams that would result at any other time. Some in
Israel do not drive on the Sabbath, and virtually nobody works
then.
</P>
<P>
   Some rabbis had called on their followers to protest if the
Sabbath transport went ahead, but perhaps because the move was
called off and suddenly revived, very few did so. About two dozen
strictly Orthodox followers shouted ``Shabbos!'' (Sabbath) at the
truck as it passed near the religious neighborhood of Bnei Brak.
</P>
<P>
   But secular Israelis who came to support the move far
outnumbered them. Perhaps 200 secular backers near Bnei Brak
cheered the flatbed, accompanied by 15 police cars and numerous
police motorcycles. Scores of others greeted it as it crawled down
the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Transport of the turbine part had been held up for days because
of religious Jews' opposition to moving it on the Sabbath. On
Friday, Suissa said, ``An evil spirit has entered the decision
makers, including those at the prime minister's office, and it is
causing them to desecrate the Sabbath.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, the nation's High Court of Justice gave the
go-ahead to a Sabbath move on the grounds of public safety after
various efforts to find alternatives were rejected as impractical.
The proposals included transporting the part between midnight and 4
a.m. over three nights, with special parking areas reserved for the
truck.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The political motives behind Suissa's move may have to do with
his loyalty to Aryeh Deri, the party's longtime chairman, who was
ousted after his conviction on charges of corruption. Other parties
had told Barak they would not sit in a coalition with a convicted
felon, so Shas dropped Deri, who is now in New York, and became
part of the government. Since Deri's departure, the party has been
rife with factionalism.
</P>
<P>
   Some political analysts say they believe that Suissa's
calculation is that if a crisis ensues, the party will call on Deri
to return and save it.
</P>
<P>
   Religious concerns have long plagued Israeli governments that
have needed the participation of religious parties to govern.
</P>
<P>
   But aides to Barak said Saturday that he did not believe this
issue should be permitted to cause a crisis, especially considering
that Shas had already participated in four governments that
permitted Sabbath transport of such objects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
