<SLUG> BC-BONN-BONVOYAGE-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT `LITTLE AMERICA' IN BONN, LIGHTS ARE GOING OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ROGER COHEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BONN, Germany _ ``It kind of reminds me of Saigon,'' said Tom
Jackson as he surveyed the dismal evidence of U.S. withdrawal here:
the closed American diner, the shuttered American bookstore, the
movie theater advertising its last movies, the emptying shelves of
the general store, where just two Butterball turkeys remained.
</P>
<P>
   After half a century when this modest city on the Rhine was a
government center, years when Germany was stabilized and the Cold
War was ultimately won, the United States is leaving town. Behind
the trucks headed for Berlin lies the sprawling evidence of a vast
mission that symbolized America's assumption of great-power
commitments in the postwar years.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson _ ``U.S. Embassy Bonn, Ret.'' was the only way he would
describe his role _ said he supposed he too would move at some
point. ``It's like losing a chunk of your life,'' he remarked,
evidently unbuoyed by the fact that Bonn's abandonment stems from a
victory over communism, whereas Saigon fell to its advancing tide.
</P>
<P>
   What a war it was, the one quietly orchestrated here and
immortalized in John le Carre's spy novel of Bonn, ``A Small Town
in Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   There was the struggle to anchor a democratic Germany in Europe,
the cloak-and-dagger fight with the Soviet bloc, the battle over
the Berlin blockade and the Berlin wall, the confrontations with
the millions of Germans who were opposed first to Vietnam and later
_ in the 1980s _ to the deployment of U.S. missiles in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the height of things in Bonn,'' said Michael Polt, the
embassy's deputy chief, who has just moved to the new German
capital in Berlin, ``the number of staff in the embassy rose as
high as 1,400, our largest single bilateral mission. It was one of
the most elaborate American diplomatic communities that we ever had
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   How elaborate is clear in the area referred to in Bonn as Little
America _ the riverside community in the Plittersdorf district
where a victorious America began building houses for its diplomats
and spies in the 1950s because war-ravaged Germany had none to
provide.
</P>
<P>
   The number of American houses mushroomed, to more than 400.
Later, there was the U.S. post office, the American Embassy Club
with its nine tennis courts, its bowling alley and its vast indoor
swimming pool, the movie theater, the thrift store, the Bonn
Booster Club, the American School, the ball fields and even an
American gas station.
</P>
<P>
   A whole world, in fact, on a scale with the Cold War mission _
but conspicuously out of scale with the placid Rhineland town that
was chosen as Germany's postwar capital precisely because it was so
unthreatening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We even had our own heating plant,'' said Truman Brown, who
served in the U.S. Embassy in the late 1970s as an administrator.
``We were totally self-sufficient.'' He has now returned to Bonn as
the official charged with the mission of turning out the lights.
</P>
<P>
   Despondently, Brown led a visitor through the long, empty
embassy corridors of countless vacated offices where desks,
shelves, telephones, calculators and other bits and pieces await
disposal or transportation.
 &UR;  &LR; The ambassador, John Kornblum, always an enthusiast for Berlin,
was one of the first out. The commercial section moved the week
before last. A large printing plant used for embassy publications
was moved earlier. The Internal Revenue Service office will be one
of the last to go.
 &UR;  &LR;  In all, Brown said, about 140 truckloads will be needed to clear
cargo from a building that began life almost 50 years ago as the
U.S. High Commission, charged with winding down the allied military
occupation of Germany and creating in its place a solid alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was in the conference room just opposite the
ambassador's now-abandoned office that on May 5, 1955, the
agreement ending Germany's status as an occupied state was signed,
the country's sovereignty formally restored and Germany's entry
into NATO ratified.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place was really the nerve center for Eastern Europe,''
said Brown, who expects to need about eight more months to complete
the last details of the move. ``It's unbelievable to see it like
this. I guess that without Mr. Gorbachev, we'd still be going
strong.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And Johnny Bevins would not be having such a strenuous time.
 &UR;  &LR; Bevins rides the trucks to Berlin to make sure nobody tampers with
America's secrets. He has already made the trip more than 15 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never leave the truck,'' he said.
 &UR;  &LR; The trip is long. By German law the drivers have to stop every two
hours for a short break, and every four hours for one hour. So a
trip that would take five or six hours of steady driving ends up
taking 10, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a few days, Bevins will undertake a high-security mission
when the political section of the embassy, complete with its Cold
War secrets, moves to Berlin. ``It's a big move,'' he said.
``Everything very tightly controlled.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, some of the Americans in Bonn are staying behind.
Because the German Defense Ministry is not moving to Berlin _ the
symbolism of a Berlin-based German military is still too charged _
a few dozen U.S. military and other officials will remain in the
top floors of the embassy, forming a liaison office.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, parts of the top four floors of the seven-story
building are to be kept by the State Department, at least for the
next several years. German Agricultural Ministry officials _ ``food
and beverage people,'' Brown said _ are moving into the rest of the
building.
</P>
<P>
   How long the United States will hold on to part of the embassy
depends to some extent on whether it is able to build one in
Berlin. A plan to begin construction next to the Brandenburg Gate
has been stalled by a drawn-out dispute with Berlin city
authorities over how large a buffer zone the building needs to be
secure.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the more than 500 State Department employees who have
moved from Bonn will be scattered in several Berlin buildings,
principally the former U.S. Embassy to the now defunct East German
state. Several hundred other Bonn-based American diplomats have
moved to Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   In Berlin, the situation will clearly be far less cozy than in
the Little America that has been left behind and is now rapidly
being dismantled. America's few survivors in Bonn will no longer be
pampered.
</P>
<P>
   The movie theater will close at the end of this month, the
general store a month later. Already the seats at the movie theater
have been sold to the U.S. military in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   The American Club, acquired by a German company, will close on
Oct. 31. The 400 American houses have all been sold or exchanged.
The American church has been given to the city of Bonn. Kornblum,
the ambassador, is expected to lower the flag at the embassy in
late September.
</P>
<P>
   The process will be dignified, unlike in Saigon, but a curtain
will be falling on a period of American history nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   On his card, Brown, the diplomat closing up shop, is identified
as ``coordinator of transitions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why `transitions' in the plural?'' he was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' he said. ``From Bonn to Berlin, from Bonn to Frankfurt,
from Cold War to post-Cold War, from one era to another. Plenty of
transitions. You name it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
