</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NOTEBOOK-ART-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO NOTEBOOK: ALBANIANS RECLAIM PRISTINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-CLAMPDOWN) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ At one end of one of Pristina's prime
shopping streets, known as Peyton Place, is a baby shop known as La
Poire. It was Serb-owned, and during the NATO war against
Yugoslavia, it was damaged by bomb blast, its windows shattered.
</P>
<P>
   In early May, during the war, its owners were replacing the
glass and preparing to reopen, an eerie sight then, because most of
the Albanian shops on the same street, at least those that had
survived the bombing, had been looted and burned by Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Today La Poire is a charred ruin, looted and burned in turn by
Pristina's Albanians. In what is now an almost exclusively Albanian
town, the Albanians are busy putting their own shops in order.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, two young brothers, Berkan and Edroan Mumini,
18 and 15, worked with a neighbor, Rian Sherifi, also 15 and
wearing an earring, to rebuild the family grill restaurant,
Topkapi, which the Serbs had burned.
</P>
<P>
   Or tried to work. Actually, with the electricity off again, they
were sitting around drinking warm Coca-Cola canned in Macedonia,
about an hour away, across what remains a mostly unregulated
border. When the Cokes were done, they used the cans as ashtrays.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant was a gutted shell, but there are the beginnings
of a roof, and frames already installed for plate-glass windows.
</P>
<P>
   The Mumini family remained in Pristina during the war, moving to
an aunt's apartment when Serbs took over their own, after doing
some looting. But they allowed his grandmother to remain, Berkan
said, and treated her decently. Still, it was too dangerous to keep
an eye on the restaurant, he said. ``We just stayed inside as much
as we could.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the restaurant burned on June 10, only two days before
NATO troops crossed into Kosovo, when the Serbs were withdrawing in
a last paroxysm of rage.
</P>
<P>
   What exercises Berkan now is the lack of any help to rebuild
Topkapi from the growing numbers of Westerners and aid workers who
fill the functioning restaurants of Peyton Place every night.
``Before we started the work, I took photos,'' Berkan said
hopefully. ``Will there be any kind of help at all?''
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing from friends, the family will spend about $6,000 to
put up a roof and put in kitchen equipment and tables.
</P>
<P>
   Seven people of the Mumini family will work in Topkapi, said
Berkan. ``Do you think they will help us if I send the photos to
the United Nations?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Peyton Place
</P>
<P>
   When asked how they feel now that the war is over, Albanians
speak in metaphors about breathing, about how they can breathe now,
or breathe more easily, or more freely.
</P>
<P>
   They walk more freely in Pristina, too, and speak more freely,
their Albanian unhindered by armed Serb police or army officers,
who had filled the streets during the war.
</P>
<P>
   At night, Peyton Place is packed with young Albanians, sitting
at tables sometimes in candlelight, when the electricity is gone,
nursing coffee or drinks.
</P>
<P>
   But for Mehmet Bashkim, a waiter at Bagram, a popular Albanian
restaurant that reopened in mid-June, the customers are doing more
sitting than spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here have a lot less money now, that's for sure,'' he
said. ``The only people that come here to eat dinner are the
foreigners.''
</P>
<P>
   As in Cambodia or anywhere the outside world flocks to rebuild,
remake and reshape, foreigners are distorting the economy, creating
needs for services that will disappear when they do and absorbing
many of the young educated class as interpreters and ``fixers'' _
people who will serve as guides and arrange interviews for
journalists, but who might ordinarily work in local businesses,
universities or newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, too, the foreigners are overwhelming those services
that do exist. The mobile phone network in Pristina is now so
jammed that it is essentially unusable from about 8:30 in the
morning until nearly midnight. But part of the problem, too, are
the Albanians who lived and worked abroad, but who have now
returned, with their own cell phones.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Politics of License Plates
</P>
<P>
   Pristina's roads now are packed with cars, but many of them have
German or Swiss license plates. Albanians returning from abroad
either own them or are trying to sell them, sometimes at such low
prices that NATO peacekeeping officials, with other problems to
attend to, assume that they have been stolen.
</P>
<P>
   And many cars have no license plates at all, indicating that the
cars were either taken from others, including Serbs, or had plates
that would indicate Serb registration.
</P>
<P>
   The normal license plate, the Yugoslav one, has a small Serb
flag among the numbers, which replaced the old Communist red star.
Today people use white paint to cover the star or the flag, or try
to scratch off the color.
</P>
<P>
   But one clever entrepreneur has come up with a better solution:
a small decal of the Albanian flag, bright red with a double-headed
black eagle, that fits neatly over the hated Serb one.
</P>
<P>
   Cycle of Revenge
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the postwar cycle of revenge, fewer than 2,000 Serbs
remain in Pristina, according to the U.N. high commissioner for
refugees, from a prewar population estimated at 40,000. Between
20,000 and 25,000 live in all of Kosovo, down from the 180,000
estimated a year ago. Even those Serbs are being regularly harassed
and pressed to go, sometimes with fake eviction notices delivered
by Albanians with identification cards giving them spurious police
powers.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Serbs found dead in the last three weeks,
peacekeeping officials say, have been executed, often forced to
kneel with their hands bound before being shot in the head. One
elderly Serb woman was drowned in a bathtub.
</P>
<P>
   The refugee agency spokesman, Ron Redmond, said the situation
was worsening for those who remain. ``Old women are now being shot
through the doors of their apartments, including two women in their
70s,'' he said. ``It is highly unlikely that these people were
involved in the persecution of Albanians. But that doesn't seem to
matter to the thugs who are now terrorizing them.''
</P>
<P>
   Peacekeeping soldiers are now putting metal grilles over Serbs'
windows and doors to protect them, and sometimes even moving into
buildings where Serbs lived.
</P>
<P>
   In general, inevitably, Albanians here do not have much
sympathy, agreeing with a British newspaper headline: ``Serbs you
right.'' But U.N. officials find themselves forced at least to act
embarrassed, since they are committed to building a democratic,
multi-ethnic Kosovo with equal rights and security for all
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The former political representative of the Kosovo Liberation
Army, Adem Demaci, who spent more than 29 years in Yugoslav prisons
for his work for an independent Kosovo, described the departure of
his own Serb neighbors, an elderly couple.
</P>
<P>
   Some Albanians ordered them to go one night. ``I knew these
people were good, but how to prove it?'' Demaci said. He said that
peacekeeping soldiers stood guard until 10 p.m., but that in the
morning, he watched the couple go, probably to the Serb enclave
around the monastery of Gracanica.
</P>
<P>
   ``The anger of the Albanians is so much _ it's too much,''
Demaci said. ``For our future this is very bad.''
</P>
<P>
   As Demaci walked away toward home, a British soldier came up,
asking for someone who spoke English. He asked if anyone had heard
a brick go through the window of Serb house just a few minutes
before. No one had.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
