<SLUG> BC-RWANDA-DEPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RWANDAN IN GENOCIDE CASE MAKES LAST PLEA TO STAY IN U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (mk) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Rwandan under indictment for genocide by an international war
crimes tribunal in Africa made a final plea to the Supreme Court on
Friday to avoid deportation from the United States, American
officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Rwandan is Elizaphan Ntakirutimana, a Seventh-day Adventist
pastor and a Hutu accused of inciting the massacre of hundreds of
frightened Tutsi hiding in his church compound in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   He is the only suspect sought by either the Rwanda or Balkan war
crimes tribunal who is in American custody.
</P>
<P>
   His deportation to the International Criminal Tribunal for
Rwanda, which the State Department has fought for since 1996, would
be the first such action by the United States. Several African
nations have turned over suspects to the court, which is based in
Arusha, Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   Kingsley Moghalu, a spokesman for the tribunal, which was set up
by the U.N. Security Council, says that all nations are required to
cooperate in making arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Legal hurdles raised over the last three years to prevent
Ntakirutimana's deportation have been an unexpected embarrassment
to the Clinton administration. The United States had been
instrumental in forming the tribunal in 1994, after hundreds of
thousands of Tutsi and moderate Hutu were killed in Rwanda
following the death in a plane crash of a Hutu president.
</P>
<P>
   The United States blocked Security Council efforts to intervene
while the genocidal campaign was in progress, a policy for which
President Clinton has since apologized to Africans.
</P>
<P>
   Ntakirutimana was living with a son, Eliel, an anesthesiologist
in Laredo, Texas, when he was arrested by federal marshals in 1996.
In Rwanda, he had been the chief pastor of a large church with an
affiliated hospital in Mugonero, in the western region of Kibuye.
</P>
<P>
   There, in the spring of 1994, the Rwanda tribunal prosecutors
charge, he first encouraged Tutsi families to seek shelter in his
church compound, then led a Hutu militia into the area to attack
them. Another son of Ntakirutimana is already in custody in Arusha
under indictment in the same attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Ntakirutimana case was taken up by Seventh-day Adventists in
Texas, where the pastor was portrayed as the innocent victim of
Tutsi revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Before the State Department could arrange the elder
Ntakirutimana's deportation, a Texas magistrate released him in
1997, calling the agreement under which he was to be turned over
``unconstitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   The action sought by the State Department is not an extradition,
normally carried out under pacts between countries, but a unique
procedure that Congress authorized in a 1996 law intended to open
the way for American cooperation with the ad hoc tribunals.
</P>
<P>
   Ntakirutimana was rearrested last year and has been appealing
the case. He lost the appeal in a U.S. district court earlier this
month. That left him with only an appeal to the Supreme Court. As a
preliminary move, his lawyers asked the Supreme Court on Friday for
a stay of deportation while an appeal is considered.
</P>
<P>
   Ntakirutimana's defense has been led by a former U.S. attorney
general, Ramsey Clark, who served in the administration of
President Johnson. Clark has challenged the legality of the
tribunals and sees nothing in the U.N. charter that allowed for
them to be set up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 1405EDT &QL; 
