   NOTE: Photos are available to go with this story.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-MADRAZO _ MEXICO CITY _ Roberto Madrazo has a grin and a
gleam in the eye that reflect a politician who knows he's on top.
Madrazo wants to be the first man democratically elected on Nov. 7
as presidential nominee for Mexico's Revolutionary Institutional
Party. The PRI, which has provided Mexico with its presidents for
70 years, has never had a primary election until this year. And
Mexicans have never seen a bruising attack campaign -- via
television and campaign slogans - like the one Madrazo launched
this month against his closest rival, Francisco Labastida, who is
perceived as the PRI establishment's favorite. As Madrazo, who
recently resigned as governor of Tabasco state and is slightly
ahead or even with Labastida in polls, works his way through
barrios here, he cultivates a ``man of the people'' image, tapping
into deep anger over the economy and other problems. (Ferris, Cox
News Service). 30. WITH PHOTO. EDs: To move by noon (EDT) Fri.,
Aug. 13.
</P>
