<HEADER>
A7266 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-14 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WILL YOU, WARREN? 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ I can tell you in one word why Warren Beatty won't
run for president: lighting.
</P>
<P>
   The man is a master at putting himself in the most flattering
light, literally and figuratively.
</P>
<P>
   He can instruct the technicians on the Larry King show about the
best way to light him. Once, while I was interviewing the star at
his candle-lit dinner table in Hollywood, he wanted to read me
something about Tennessee Williams. Instead of turning on a lamp,
he fetched a tiny flashlight. You've got to like a guy who cares
about chiaroscuro.
</P>
<P>
   The 62-year-old movie man is just as finicky about his image.
Other than ideologically, he is far from the rollicking, fearless,
reckless politician he created in ``Bulworth.'' Beatty is a
connoisseur of shadows. The elliptical is his element. He believes
in the power of the unseen.
</P>
<P>
   He kindles to the game of cat-and-mouse with reporters,
manipulating the way he is portrayed. He scrupulously weighs every
word for every possible effect. He dissects every question,
flashing an ankle only when the angle is propitious.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who enjoys control, anyone who can retreat behind his big
gate, would hate to be plunged into the uncontrollable insanity of
a campaign, trapped in a boring primary with bad production values,
pigs, bales of hay and reporters rooting around in your private
life.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it's a nutty season, a time when Jesse
Ventura and nonpoliticians are cherished. The instant Beatty said
he might consider considering, he racked up 25 percent in an ABC
News poll on the Web, following Bill Bradley's 29 percent and Al
Gore's 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And the actor has long been passionate about politics. Growing
up in a Washington suburb, he dreamed of becoming president. But he
was never that comfortable addressing the public. Campaigning for
McGovern in 1972, he confessed he sometimes felt ``silly'' and
``embarrassed'': ``I think the public is innately suspicious of the
self-forwarding, publicity-seeking, capricious artist who would
like to attach some mood of seriousness to his persona by
participating in public affairs.'' (Yup.)
</P>
<P>
   The Beatty boomlet seems a mere late-summer diversion for his
pal Pat Caddell, the apocalyptic prognosticator who has long been
disillusioned with the Democrats, and columnist Arianna Huffington.
</P>
<P>
   On MSNBC, Caddell, an adviser on such fiascoes as President
Carter's malaise speech and New Coke, was gassing up the Beatty
bandwagon: ``Is there a need? Is there a vacuum? ABSOLUTELY!''
</P>
<P>
   He has a point. In a world where Gary Bauer and Bob Smith think
they can be president, where W. is still learning his foreign hot
spots and Al is learning how to keep audiences awake, where Steve
Forbes can bankroll a vanity candidacy, why not Bulworth? In an
airless and funless and substanceless race, Beatty could inject
some useful mischief.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Beatty to enter the race and draw all of this attention
would be the most emphatic statement about the hollowness of
politics now,'' says Ron Brownstein, the L.A. Times columnist who
wrote the book about the Hollywood-Washington nexus, ``The Power
and the Glitter.'' ``It would be a wonderful agitprop way of
showing how entertainment values are eating away at the political
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Beatty is aiming more for idealism than cynicism. But Brownstein
was reminded of a story from his book: In a 1972 publicity stunt
for ``The Candidate,'' Robert Redford went on a mock whistle-stop
tour through Florida, attracting larger crowds than the
presidential candidates. He would go to the back of the train and
declare: ``I appreciate your coming out. I only ask you to think of
this, my friends: I have absolutely nothing to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Beatty's brazen liberalism, reflected in the raps and rants of
``Bulworth,'' seems anachronistic. But he has a hankering to ignore
polls and make liberalism chic again, the way another actor
rekindled conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   He is most offended by what he sees as a movement toward ``a
plutocracy'' _ the corrosive influence of campaign money on
American politics.
</P>
<P>
   It's a peculiar message from a rich, pampered star. But in our
culture, politicians can be celebrities and celebrities can be
politicians. However provocative a Beatty campaign would be, even
he must worry that it would go straight to video.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
