<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7269 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-14 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: AMERICA'S TWIN EVILS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buford O. Furrow Jr. is the symptom. We can deal with him. Lock
him up. Convict him. Kill him.
</P>
<P>
   But how do you deal with that sickness in the nation's soul that
will still be there even after a fiend like Buford Furrow is gone,
a sickness that is already spawning future Furrows?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, it's a sickness all right. There is something very wrong
when you have youngsters barely out of the toddler stage looking
warily over their shoulders as they head into day care. Two of the
children shot last Tuesday in Los Angeles were 6 years old, and the
other was 5.
</P>
<P>
   A teen-aged girl and a 68-year-old woman also were shot. Furrow,
who intended the wounds to be fatal, said he wanted to send a
``wake-up call to America'' to kill Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Even now we are not paying enough attention to this. A bullet in
a Jew is a bullet in every American. Violence and hate are the
perennial threats to America from within. If a grown man
deliberately shooting Jewish children is not enough to make us do
something real about these twin evils, I'm not sure what will.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years we have tended to throw up our hands and behave
as if we were helpless in the face of cauldrons of violence and
hate like Furrow. We distance ourselves. We ask questions. Was he a
loner? Was he crazy? Was he part of a conspiracy? Whatever. It's
the death penalty for him _ the electric chair, or the gas chamber,
or that marvelously lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   We express our horror and indignation and move on, carefully
avoiding that something in ourselves that nurtures the attitudes
that create the environment that produces the man with the gun.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago in Billings, Mont., someone threw part of a
cinder block through a window in which a menorah was displayed.
Glass from the shattered window landed on a child's bed. Jewish
families were thus faced with a dilemma _ give in to the haters and
hide a symbol of their religion or display it and risk becoming a
target.
</P>
<P>
   The response of thousands of non-Jewish families in Billings was
to express solidarity with their Jewish neighbors by putting paper
menorahs in the windows of their own homes.
</P>
<P>
   It is the responsibility of all of us to rise up against
intolerance wherever it manifests itself. That might be in our own
homes, or somewhere in the neighborhood, or at school, or among the
politicians who seek our votes, or on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   It takes courage. But when you do nothing you end up with
innocent kids trying to outrun the gunfire of a madman. You end up
with Joseph Ileto, a mailman, lying dead in the street because of
his Filipino heritage. You end up with the United States of
America, a great country, not being nearly as great as it could be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have to really live tolerance, brotherhood and
caring in this country in a real way,'' said Morris Dees, legal
director of the Southern Poverty Law Center, which tracks hate
groups and monitors hate crimes in the U.S. ``But nobody really
thinks it's a major agenda issue. It's not as pressing as budget
matters, or some of these other problems, but it's an issue that
affects the very fabric of this nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in this most prosperous of times violence and hate are
changing the way we live. The lead paragraph in the tead story in
Friday's Times said:
</P>
<P>
   ``At rural schoolhouses and sprawling urban campuses across the
country, millions of students returning to class in the next few
weeks will encounter a steely array of new security measures. In
many schools, lockers are being removed, cameras are being
installed as hallway monitors, and students will have to swipe a
computerized ID card just to get in the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, there is still resistance to comprehensive gun
control, which should be the easiest part of this whole thing. Just
get it done. Licensing and registration should be universally
required, with a photo ID and the gun owner's address on the
license. Purchases should be limited to one gun a month. Dealers
who violate the law or try to thwart the spirit of gun control
should be run out of business.
</P>
<P>
   We should not allow ourselves to be the hostages of violence and
hate. Tolerance is not so bad once you get used to it. And a
healthier society is a lot easier on the children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
