<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7273 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PERU-ECUADOR-ART-NYT &LR;      08-14 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-ECUADOR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTS OF PERU AND ECUADOR END VISIT WITH SHOW OF UNITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ko) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ As recently as one year ago, Peru and Ecuador were
preparing to go to war, something they have done with regularity
ever since the Peruvian Navy blockaded Ecuador's principal port in
1860.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign that the squabbling neighbors are finally learning
to live together, Ecuador President Jamil Mahuad finished a
three-day visit through Peru on Friday, complete with banquets,
honorary university degrees and a triumphal tour through downtown
Lima arm in arm with President Alberto K. Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
   Troubled by a failing economy and increasing protests at home,
Mahuad came to Peru to consolidate the gains won last October when
the two countries signed a peace treaty brokered by the United
States, Brazil, Argentina and Chile to settle a longstanding border
dispute over a 50-mile swath of the Condor Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The two presidents were jeered at on Friday as they drove
through Iquitos, the political and economic center of the Peruvian
Amazon, by hundreds of protesters who say the treaty gives Ecuador
too many commercial rights in their region. But most analysts
called the visit a success that augurs well for future relations.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori and Mahuad dressed in matching red sport shirts and
donned Indian ceremonial headdresses to pose for photographers in a
dugout canoe on an Amazon River tributary. And they met with
residents of the jungle town of Sarameriza to announce the
construction of a port project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patriotism searches for development,'' Fujimori said as Mahuad
smiled widely. Then Fujimori called for a show of hands of those
opposed to opening river commerce to Ecuadoreans. No one voted
against the Peruvian President, Fujimori noted, ``not even
Mahuad.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a backhanded slap at political leaders of the area who
oppose the thaw with Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our friend President Mahuad is Arab and I am half Japanese,''
Fujimori said, ``but we speak the same language.''
</P>
<P>
   The two Presidents announced a wide assortment of joint
projects, including the extension of national parks, forestry
projects and construction of river port installations, bridges,
roads, schools and medical clinics that will total up to $3 billion
over several years. They also signed a free-trade agreement that
will remove tariffs from 585 agricultural, consumer and industrial
goods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
