<HEADER>
A7284 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SPAIN-BASQUE-ART-1000     08-14 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-BASQUE-ART-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASQUE SEPARATISTS EMULATE THE IRA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BILBAO, Spain _ Like the peace talks in Ireland that inspired
them, negotiations between the Spanish government and the guerrilla
movement that has been fighting for independence for the Basque
region have stalled but not stifled hopes for peace in a long and
bloody conflict.
</P>
<P>
   About 800 people have died at the guerrillas' hands in Spain
since 1968; the last victim was killed in a bombing on June 25,
1998. Three months later, the rebels proclaimed an ``indefinite''
cease-fire, one that both Spanish government officials and Basque
politicians in touch with the guerrillas say they expect will hold
despite the lack of momentum in the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Violent guerrilla struggle is not what Bilbao wants to be known
for today. A million people a year come from all over the world
just to see Frank Gehry's stunning new Guggenheim Museum Bilbao,
bringing a new cachet of sophistication to a city built on a gritty
economy of heavy industry and shipping.
</P>
<P>
   The political wing of the guerrilla movement is also changing
its image, bringing in articulate young leaders like Esther Agirre
Ruiz, a 29-year-old lawyer, to explain itself to the world after 23
grizzled, veteran chiefs were thrown into prison two years ago.
They were accused of collaborating with the rebels by spreading
propaganda favorable to the violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought, if it's possible in Ireland, why not in the Basque
country?'' Ms. Ruiz asked during an interview in the Bilbao
headquarters of her Herri Batasuna _ or Popular Unity _ party,
whose older leaders were recently freed by Spain's Constitutional
Court. ``As long as all the nationalist parties, trade unions and
other movements stay together, the cease-fire will be maintained,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The ETA guerrillas, known by the initials of the Basque words
for Basque Homeland and Liberty, have never had the support of the
majority of the people here for the violent tactics they have used
in their drive for independence for the ``Basque Country.'' It is a
region of rugged green hills straddling the French and Spanish
border at the Atlantic end of the Pyrenees, where people speak a
language that may have originated in the Stone Age.
</P>
<P>
   A particularly appalling assassination in July 1997 hardened
public opinion all over Spain against the guerrillas. They had
kidnapped and then killed a Basque town councilman, Miguel Angel
Blanco, after giving the authorities in Madrid 48 hours to transfer
jailed terrorists to prisons closer to their families, a demand
that Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar's conservative government
refused to consider.
</P>
<P>
   Six million people took to the streets after the killing in
revulsion against the seemingly unending series of Basque bombings
and killings. Last September, after a long police crackdown, the
guerrillas changed their strategy, agreeing with moderate Basque
nationalist parties and labor unions to try to follow the Irish
model and begin a process of ``dialogue and negotiation'' instead
of violence, though still insisting on self-determination for the
2.6 million people who live in Spain's four historic Basque
provinces and 250,000 others in the French part of the Basque
country. Four days later, on Sept. 16, the guerrillas called the
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   Running in Basque regional elections last October under a new
name as the Euskal Herritarrok coalition, the Basque independence
movement won 18 percent of the vote, up from 12.5 percent two years
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ETA is looking for a way out after 40 years,'' said Xabier
Arzalluz, head of the moderate Basque Nationalist Party, which
governs in Spain's Basque region and, since last December, has been
doing so with the support of the movement that backs the
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Arzalluz, himself often a harsh critic of the central government
in Madrid, said in an interview at his party's headquarters here,
``I think the ETA has decided to stop the armed fight, but that
doesn't mean it couldn't act again in situations it considers
provocations.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the guerrillas have moved closer to the moderate
nationalist movement or Arzalluz's nationalists have moved closer
to the guerrillas is a question politicians of other parties here
sometimes ask, but they also agree that the tide has turned against
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every passing day makes it harder for the ETA to
return to violence,'' said Nicolas Redondo Terreros, leader of the
opposition Socialist Party in the Basque region.
</P>
<P>
   Leopoldo Calvo-Sotelo Ibanez-Martin, a member of Aznar's
Conservative Party and an official of Spain's Interior Ministry,
said of the guerrillas: ``They realized they were down a blind
alley. They were fighting a losing battle on the terrorist side.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It paid off politically,'' Calvo-Sotelo conceded, with
nationalist gains in the regional elections last fall, followed by
Aznar's announcement in November that he had authorized his
government to talk with people close to the guerrillas to see how
sincere their pledge to forswear violence really was.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to go back to violence when you do well in political
terms,'' Calvo-Sotelo said, but he added that what the government
really wanted was ``not only a renunciation of violence, but a
condemnation of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Irish Republican Army, the Basque guerrillas did not
agree to disarm at the start of the peace process. And, as in
Ireland, agreeing to talks was easier than the talks themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The first and so far only encounter took place over four hours
this past May _ in Switzerland, according to Arzalluz.
Calvo-Sotelo, whose immediate superior in the Interior Ministry,
Ricardo Marti Fluxa, was one of the participants, said he could not
talk about the details.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ETA sent out a one-page summary, in Basque, of the
questions that were discussed,'' Arzalluz said. ``ETA asked whether
the state would recognize the right of self-determination for the
Basques, and the government representative said, `We don't
represent the state, we represent the prime minister.' ETA also
asked if the government recognized the right, and they answered
that the government would never accept the excision of a part of
Spain or the right of the Basques alone to decide it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Arzalluz said the government delegation was led by Javier
Zarzalejos, a top aide to Aznar, and also included the prime
minister's pollster, Pedro Arriola. One of the new, younger
guerrilla leaders, Mikel Albizu _ who uses ``Antza'' as his nom de
guerre and is the son of a founder of the movement _ spoke for
their side, said Arzalluz, with one of the veterans, a woman whose
name he said he could not remember, backing up her younger
colleague.
</P>
<P>
   Arzalluz said a second round of talks was unlikely any time
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who have not budged, after a year without any
killings, are the central government,'' he said. Supporters of the
guerrillas have also continued low-level street protests against
the government's refusal to bring some 400 prisoners closer to
where their families live.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is European case law saying there is no such thing as a
right to serve time near home,'' said Calvo-Sotelo, the Interior
Ministry official.
</P>
<P>
   But he and Ms. Ruiz agreed in separate interviews that they did
not expect much movement in the stalled negotiations until after
national elections that Aznar must call before his minority
government's term runs out next April.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
