<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Aug. 15, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Drier conditions will spread into the Northeast on Sunday as the
low-pressure system responsible for this weekend's precipitation
moves slowly off the Maine coast. Showers will occur during the
morning near the New England coast with drier air arriving in the
afternoon. Residual moisture in the lowest portions of the
atmosphere, however, will cause clouds to linger most of the day
from southeastern New York to eastern Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, spotty thunderstorms will douse the Southeast and
eastern Gulf of Mexico coasts as a southward-advancing cool front
lifts the very sultry air over the region. Intervals of clouds and
sun will rule the skies of Florida. Scattered thunderstorms will
occur, especially during the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Morning clouds will yield to afternoon sun from the eastern
Great Lakes through the Appalachians. Meanwhile, sinking currents
associated with high pressure will promote clear skies from the
western Great Lakes to the middle Mississippi Valley. Farther
south, torrid conditions will continue over Texas as abundant
sunshine propels readings above 100 degrees in many places.
</P>
<P>
   A corridor of moist air circulating into the Southwest will
bring patchy clouds and scattered thundershowers to the southern
Rockies. Onshore breezes will promote mainly cloudy and cool
weather in western parts of Washington and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   A potent jet stream disturbance will spark isolated strong
thunderstorms across eastern Montana today. Elsewhere, unusually
hot weather will spread into the western high Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: A Drop in the Bucket
</P>
<P>
   The weekend rain across the Northeast and Middle Atlantic States
has brought some relief to the current drought. Prior to the rain's
onset, statistics indicated that parts of the region required about
12 inches of rain to eliminate the current deficit. The several
inches that fell in some places helps. Not all rainfall, however,
is created equal. If a 2 inch rain occurs in a few hour period,
much of the rain drains into streams or municipal sewer systems and
is not absorbed into the ground. Farmers prefer rain to fall over a
longer duration, assuring more absorption into the soil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 1505EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
