<DOCNO> NYT19990814.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7287 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-SPY-(TRIM)-NYT &LR;      08-14 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-SPY-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPY'S EX-WIFE IS SUING CUBA OVER HIS DECEPTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RICK BRAGG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ To Ana Margarita Martinez, an avowed anti-Communist
Cuban-American, the dashing young jet pilot seemed to have dropped
from heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Pablo Roque, a disenchanted officer in the Cuban air force,
escaped the Communist-controlled island by swimming to the U.S.
Navy base at Guantanamo Bay in February 1992. He denounced Cuban
President Fidel Castro and quickly became a vocal militant in the
Cuban exiles' pro-democracy movement in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   He even flew planes for Brothers to the Rescue, a group of
Cuban-American pilots who cruised the Florida Straits searching for
refugees fleeing Cuba on rafts. He met Ms. Martinez his first year
in Miami, in church, and they fell in love. They were married in
1995, as he established himself as one of the city's more visible
anti-Communists. He wrote a book called ``The Deserter.''
</P>
<P>
   It was all a lie.
</P>
<P>
   Roque, in reality a spy for the Cuban government sent to
infiltrate exile groups like Brothers to the Rescue, vanished from
Miami on Feb. 23, 1996, and returned to Cuba, four years after his
swim to Guantanamo.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Cuban jets shot down two small planes flown by
Brothers to the Rescue, just outside Cuban air space in
international waters. Law-enforcement authorities in Miami and
Cuban exiles blamed Roque for the deaths of four fliers.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban exiles who had trusted Roque felt violated.
</P>
<P>
   To Ms. Martinez, the betrayal was rape. She never would have
married him, never would have shared a bed with him, Ms. Martinez
said, if she had known the man she thought was an anti-Communist
was actually an agent of the Castro government.
</P>
<P>
   Now, saying that her consent to have sex with the man over the
11 months of their marriage was based on a lie, she is suing the
Cuban government for sexual battery _ rape.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used me,'' Ms. Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   In a complaint filed earlier this month in Miami-Dade Circuit
Court, Ms. Martinez contended that Roque used her as part of his
cover, and that his decision to court and ultimately marry her was
done only to establish himself within the exile community.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is the fifth victim of the downing'' of the two planes,
said Jose J. Basulta, president of Brothers to the Rescue. ``We
were all victimized but perhaps she was the person with whom there
was the most cruelty.''
</P>
<P>
   When she filed the court papers, Ms. Martinez described the
lawsuit as her only way of fighting back. She has since had the
marriage annulled _ Roque, now in Havana, did not contest _ and has
not heard from him since he left the country in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in an appearance on Cuban television soon after
returning, Roque told an interviewer that the thing he missed most
about living in Miami was his sport utility vehicle, said lawyers
for Ms. Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   That man was not the one Ms. Martinez thought she had married.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very attentive,'' she said. ``He made me feel protected
and secure. He was the kind of man who went to work and came home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted a family,'' she said, and helped her raise two
children from a previous marriage. Now she says it was just part of
his disguise.
</P>
<P>
   ``She would not have given her consent, had she known'' who
Roque really was, said one of her lawyers, Scott W. Leeds of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her `husband,''' Leeds said, using the word derisively, ``was
a spy in the employment of the Cuban government. She was victimized
and was powerless to do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Roque, who also served as a paid informer for the FBI and
supplied information about Brothers to the Rescue, has been named
in a federal indictment that accuses him and 13 others with spying
and trying to sabotage the efforts of Miami's Cuban exiles. He is
also charged with conspiracy to commit murder in connection with
the attack on the Brothers to the Rescue planes.
</P>
<P>
   One week before the two planes were shot down, two members of
the alleged spy ring were warned not to fly in any Brothers to the
Rescue planes near the island between Feb. 24 and Feb. 27,
according to the federal indictment. The warning apparently came
from an agent of the Cuban government.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Roque appeared on CNN from Havana. That was how
Ms. Martinez learned where her husband had gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just disappeared,'' said Ms. Martinez, an executive
secretary in Coral Gables, Fla. ``He told me he was going on a
business trip, and the next thing I knew he was in Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Martinez is hoping for a moral victory and any financial
reward is secondary, her lawyers said. Getting money from the Cuban
government has proved difficult in the past.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The families of the four fliers who were killed also sued the
Cuban government and were awarded almost $188 million by the
federal District Court in Miami, money they hoped to recoup from
frozen Cuban assets.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
Atlanta, denied the families access to what had seemed the most
likely source of damages, $6.2 million in payments from American
telephone companies to the Cuban telecommunications company,
Empresa de Telecomunicaciones de Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   That case, a complicated legal tangle, has been in the headlines
in Miami for years.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Martinez's case, at least on the surface, seems simpler.
</P>
<P>
   In the complaint, her lawyers point out that sex cannot be
consensual if it is derived by ``fraud and concealment.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the complaint, Roque was under orders from Cuba's
ministry of the interior to become a member of the Cuban exile
community, and _ while leading ``a normal life'' _ to infiltrate
Cuban-American organizations.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his cover, he was told to become active in church,
where he met Ms. Martinez. His marriage to her was part of his
directive, the complaint said. Meanwhile, he doubled as an informer
for the FBI, also part of his directive from Cuba, the complaint
said.
</P>
<P>
   While the lawsuit does not contend that Roque was under orders
to marry Ms. Martinez ``specifically,'' he used her as part of his
disguise, said Leeds, the lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Cuban-Americans here either defend her lawsuit or shake their
heads at its seeming strangeness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a legitimate way of defending herself,'' Basulta
said.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts have said the case will be difficult, since Cuban
officials are unlikely to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cuban exiles have one bit of satisfaction. Wherever
Roque is, knowing the economic straits and shortage of good
automobiles on the island, he is probably not driving a quality
vehicle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
