<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7288 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     08-14 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGAINST ALL ODDS, THE GARDEN IS STILL THE GARDEN, AT LEAST FOR
NOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It has taken us a quarter of a century, but sports
fans are finally adjusting to the reality that free-agent athletes
jump ship at whim.
</P>
<P>
   Is it too much to ask, however, that the names of our stadiums
and arenas stay constant from one season to the next?
</P>
<P>
   I am referring to several dozen sports dens losing local,
traditional names in favor of airlines or banks or, worse yet,
companies that give no clue as to their function. What is a
Qualcomm? What is a 3Com?
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Madison Square Garden has been owned by so many
faceless corporations that one little theater in the complex went
from being called the Felt Forum to the Paramount to the Theatre. I
believe it is currently named the Mosh Pit.
</P>
<P>
   Sports are reflecting the frivolous anarchy of financial
institutions blowing each other out of the water for the sport of
it.
</P>
<P>
   We can all agree that one of the most hideous moments in
contemporary life is discovering that our bank or mortgage company
or insurance company has been taken over by some new gang of
swashbucklers. The hostile captors promptly force us to fill out
new forms, which are then mangled by a clerk unfamiliar with a
computer or the English language itself.
</P>
<P>
   Now the temples of sport are being affected by the whims of
these corporate pirates. One city being menaced is Buffalo, where
the Sabres play hockey in an arena built ostensibly as the
Crossroads, which had a nice, energetic civic ring to it. But
before the arena opened in 1996, a bank with roots in upstate New
York paid $8.5 million to have the new joint called Marine Midland
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Sabres fans were getting used to that name this spring when the
team reached the Stanley Cup finals. Now the company that swallowed
up Marine Midland last year, the HSBC Group out of London, wants to
put its rather uninteresting corporate initials on the arena. (For
the record, they stand for Hongkong Shanghai Banking Corporation.)
</P>
<P>
   Bless their hearts, the Sabres are not going for it. They've got
season tickets to sell, skyboxes to rent, schedules and brochures
about to be printed, all with Marine Midland Arena on them.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, HSBC filed a breach-of-contract suit in state court,
claiming the company had automatically acquired the naming rights
by buying the arena. The Sabres say a name change is not in the
contract. All of this may be mere lawyerly jockeying to see who
pays for the changeover, but, as a traditionalist, I am rooting for
Marine Midland, extinct as a banking institution, to somehow
prevail as a hockey arena. Then again, I'm hoping Yankee Stadium
can outlast this grubby trend.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time a corporate name has changed faster
than coaches are fired. In Philadelphia in 1994, the new arena was
named after the Corestates Financial Corp., which had roots in the
region. One of the stipulations in the contract was that future
naming rights were included for the price of $40 million over 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``As volatile as the banking industry has been, they said, `We
may acquire _ or we may be acquired,''' recalled Peter Luukko, the
president of Comcast-Spectacor Facilities, which runs the arena in
South Philly.
</P>
<P>
   The Corestates executives must have had a premonition. In 1998,
First Union of Charlotte, N.C., staged a $17 billion takeover,
gaining the naming rights for the Corestates Arena as well as the
Corestates Spectrum next door. First Union dutifully paid another
$2 million for the complete changeover.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how many things have the name on it _ stationery,
signage, brochures, garbage cans, uniforms,'' Luukko said. ``We had
two signs that said Corestates _ one facing Broad Street, one
facing I-95. The last thing I wanted was one saying Corestates and
one saying First Union. They got it all done in time for last
season, with green letters 10 feet high, saying First Union.''
</P>
<P>
   Luukko said there had been ``little antipathy'' to the change _
``but it's not something you're too excited about, either. You  &UR; are
 &LR; changing the name of the business.''
</P>
<P>
   That name could change again. As The New York Times has written,
``The towering First Union facade cloaks a failure to attain the
financial goals promised in its merger binge, mounting managerial
woes and low morale amid the layoff of thousands of workers _
layoffs deemed necessary for the bank to meet earnings goals
associated with acquisitions.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   There are strong rumors that First Union itself could be
swallowed up by some other outfit on the make.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine if they were acquired by First Boston,'' joked Luukko,
a Boston native. ``Then they could name it the Boston Garden'' _ a
reference to the ancient den, now demolished in favor of the Fleet
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Get used to the grim corporate touch. Fred Wilpon, the otherwise
sentimental co-owner of the Mets, has informed us that the
projected new ball park in Queens will neither be named for his
late father, Nathan Wilpon, who took him to many games in Ebbets
Field, nor for Jackie Robinson, who helped win six pennants in that
holy place.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Wilpon warns us, the new stadium will be named for the
highest bidder. The naming rights will, of course, be written into
the contract _ pending the inevitable takeovers, buyouts, sales,
transfers, mergers, bankruptcies and all other forms of financial
instability that so define our age.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 1509EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
