<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7292 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-JOHNSON-     08-14 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-JOHNSON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JIMMY JOHNSON TAKES HIS BEST (LAST?) SHOT
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ On the surface there is little different about
Miami Dolphins Coach Jimmy Johnson. The hair remains perfectly
layered, and nothing short of a hurricane can disturb it. The tan
is something out of Melrose Place. His attitude is still there as
well: Johnson thinks he is the baddest coach on the planet. And it
could indeed be argued that Johnson remains the best at what he
does.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there are the other usual suspects. Mike Shanahan has won
two consecutive Super Bowls, Dennis Green is one of the brightest
coaches in the game, and no one has to ask how smart Bill Parcells
is because he'll tell you himself. But when it comes to a coach who
can win _ a lot _ and do so with an attitude and no political
correctness, Johnson is the guy. There are probably five coaches
who could take the sorriest team in football and by pure force of
their will push that franchise into the post-season. Johnson is one
of them.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson believes his Dolphins team is the most talented in the
American Football Conference East. He may be right. With more
weapons on offense than he has had since joining Miami for the 1996
season, Johnson is poised to advance deep into the playoffs. His
Dolphins have a swagger, like Johnson's old Dallas Cowboys teams
that won two Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Everything seems perfect. Quarterback Dan Marino is as excited
as he has been in five years, the defense is a top five unit, and
the team believes it is special.
</P>
<P>
   Yet something hovers over the franchise like the blistering
Florida sun. In his ninth year of coaching in the National Football
League, there are strong indications, some of which come from
Johnson himself, that this could be his final season.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 56, does not come right out and say what he is
thinking, but what he does not say is equally important. Johnson
refuses to say he will definitely be back after this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how long I'm going to coach,'' Johnson said after
a recent practice. ``I really don't think about it. I probably
think about it less now than in past years for the simple reason
that I'm going to coach my rear end off, go as hard as I can go,
and then after the year is over I'll pull back and say, `OK, do I
want to do this again?'''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson says he has the insight of all the positives and
negatives he has been through, has been financially secure for 15
years and knows where he is heading. ``In light of all of that,''
he said, ``you do take it one year at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he could talk ``about how I'm going to coach until
I win another Super Bowl,'' but the truth is ``I don't know what
I'm going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   His thinking is a result of an episode after last season that
can only be called a football midlife crisis. Extremely emotional
over the death of his mother, the firing of a number of other head
coaches, including his good friend Dave Wannstedt by the Chicago
Bears, and a disappointing 10-6 season, Johnson quit the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is unaccustomed to not meeting expectations. In Dallas
he single-handedly built the Cowboys and then won consecutive Super
Bowls, becoming only the fourth head coach to do so. He also was
the first head coach to win a college national title (with the
Miami Hurricanes) and an NFL championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins' record improved in each of Johnson's seasons, from
8-8 in 1996 to 9-7 and then to 10-6 last year. But Johnson felt the
Dolphins had enough talent to win a Super Bowl, and part of the
reason Johnson hurriedly quit was that the Dolphins' progress was
slower than expected. It was only after a long night of
soul-searching and extensive talks with the team's owner, H. Wayne
Huizenga, whom Johnson likes, that he decided to return to
football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaches are somewhat emotional,'' Johnson said. ``We had just
come off an emotional season. My mother had just passed away, and
that was the first time in my life someone in my immediate family
had passed away. I had made plans to get married. It was a
turbulent time.''
</P>
<P>
   What Johnson did after his personal crisis was vow to change the
way he lived. He started spending less time around the office to
allow for a personal life.
</P>
<P>
   That lasted about a week. Johnson is too addicted to his work to
live a 9-to-5 life, so he is back to his old routine, staying up
late working on game plans and personnel moves. ``My wife said to
me, `You haven't changed, you still stay in the office until two in
the morning,''' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   But he is more relaxed than perhaps ever before. He smiles and
jokes more. On the field, Johnson has allowed veteran players like
Marino to take an occasional training camp practice off, something
he had never done as coach of the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   The kinder, gentler Johnson has surfaced because his good friend
and jogging buddy, Wannstedt, is around, just like the good old
days in Dallas when he was Johnson's defensive coordinator.
Wannstedt has a soothing effect on Johnson and is his sounding
board.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't hurt that Johnson has a cache of talented backs, good
receivers and an improved offensive line. ``For whatever reason I
think I'm more relaxed,'' he said. ``I've always been optimistic,
but I think I'm even more optimistic this year for the simple
reason we've got a lot more talent. When you've got better players,
maybe that makes you happier. You tend not to smile as much when
you don't have good players.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson made it clear he came back to the Dolphins because he
owes a debt to Huizenga and his coaches, but his return was also
because of pride. After he does retire _ whenever that is _ he
plans to live in the Miami area. Johnson can already get a seat at
the best restaurants on a Friday night without calling ahead, but
imagine his popularity if he brought the city its first Super Bowl
championship since the 1972 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to be able to walk around this city when I'm done
and stick out my chest and say we won it all,'' he said. ``Now, is
that going to happen? I don't know, but I'm going to make a run at
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The team Johnson sees as the biggest threat to his becoming the
king of Miami? The Jets. That's the team Johnson constantly thinks
about.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jets are the team to beat,'' he said. ``We shouldn't be
the team to beat because we didn't win the division last year. We
may have the best team in the division, but the Jets hold the
title. They're the team to catch.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is the man to watch because his team could very well get
to the Super Bowl. If that happens, look for him to definitely
retire. It would be a pivotal moment in football because the league
would lose one of its most talented and entertaining coaches ever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 1526EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
