<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7299 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      08-14 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAW POLL NO-SHOW WITH A PLAN  
 CONTRARIAN OREGON  
 OLYMPIAN TAX RATES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., N.H., S.C., Calif., Texas, Utah)  (mk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., was the only one of the 10 Republican
presidential hopefuls to pass on Iowa's straw poll this weekend. So
what's his game?
</P>
<P>
   For the last month or so, while the other candidates scoured
every corner of Iowa in search of poll participants, McCain, who
called the poll a ``sham,'' focused his campaign on New Hampshire,
South Carolina and California. Those states, he says, offer him the
best opportunity to break to the front of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   The way he figures it, whatever national polls show and whatever
the statistical outcome of Saturday's straw poll in Ames, he is the
genuine No. 2 in the Republican contest, the candidate the party
will turn to should the campaign of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   And, he says, he has a plan to hasten the collapse of the Texan:
Close in on the governor in New Hampshire's first-in-the nation
primary next year (tentatively set for Feb. 8), overtake him a
couple of weeks later in South Carolina and home-state Arizona,
then put him away in the March 7 Super Tuesday primaries, when the
biggest prize of all will be California.
</P>
<P>
   That is a tall order. Very possibly too tall. But while the
campaign spotlight has been on Iowa, the senator has been doing his
own scouring.
</P>
<P>
   He has made more trips to New Hampshire in the last few months
than any other candidate _ 14 in all this year _ and in recent
polls there has climbed to second place, his stated short-term
goal. Bush leads by a solid, perhaps insurmountable 30 points, 40
percent to 10 percent, but that said, McCain is the only candidate
besides Bush to achieve a double-digit standing.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, McCain begins a two-week sweep through California,
with the focus on veterans at many stops. As a survivor of North
Vietnamese prisoner of war camps, he is relying heavily on fellow
veterans to help promote his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   After California, he heads for New Hampshire and a five-day bus
tour that he hopes will mirror the success of the tour he made
earlier this month of South Carolina. When that trip was over _ it
was his 10th visit to that state _ one of South Carolina's most
seasoned political writers, Lee Bandy of The State in Columbia,
wrote that McCain had been enthusiastically received and was
``rapidly emerging here as a solid alternative'' to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the matter of fund raising. And again McCain has
been hard at work, raising more money, $6.1 million, than any
Republican candidate except Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Steve Forbes, the publisher, has much more than $6.1
million for his campaign. But it has mostly come out of his own
pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Which is fine by McCain, for the moment. He figures Forbes will
use it to hammer down Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing fine,'' McCain said a few days ago. ``The money is
coming in OK. The support is there. I'm enjoying it.''
</P>
<P>
   Oregon Advances by Retreating
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years and more ago, when most states relied on caucuses
to help choose presidential nominees, Oregon was one of those
relative rarities that held a primary. The voting usually took
place on the third Tuesday in May and the results were considered
more clear-cut and indicative than the outcome of caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon, though no megastate when it came to population, took on
an outsized role in the nominating process, and the state's voters
grew accustomed to being wooed up close by the likes of Thomas
Dewey, Nelson Rockefeller, Robert Kennedy and Eugene McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   No more.
</P>
<P>
   Today, dozens of states hold primaries. And many of those
states, particularly many that are larger than Oregon, schedule
their votes in March, or even sooner, in an effort to gain early
clout in the primary process.
</P>
<P>
   Tired of eating their political dust, Oregon joined the
``front-loading'' rush in 1996 and moved its primary date to the
second Tuesday in March, just a bit behind New Hampshire's opening
primary. But to little avail _ only Bob Dole, the eventual
Republican nominee, dropped by to campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson in that, Jim Edmunson, the Oregon Democratic
chairman, later observed, is that ``if a state can't be first, it
better be big.''
</P>
<P>
   So now, for Election 2000, the Oregon Legislature has moved the
state's primary back to its original date, the third Tuesday in May
_ a step so contrarian, as primary scheduling currently goes, that
Oregon surely qualifies once again as a political rarity.
</P>
<P>
   Election officials say, however, that it was not difficult to
sell the Legislature on the need for the reversion.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, they note, only the date of the presidential primary
was moved up, not the date for state and local primaries. When the
second round of voting took place in May, the officials say, the
turnout was unusually low, in good part because the draw of the
presidential primary was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the officials say, it was too costly to run two separate
rounds of primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Oregon's shift back to the May date for the Election
2000 presidential primary removed a possibility that the state, if
it stuck with the March date, might run afoul of a special
Democratic National Committee rule. That rule authorizes New
Hampshire not only to hold the first primary, always, but also to
hold it at least a week before the next state votes, including
states, like Oregon, that allow advance voting by mail.
</P>
<P>
   Mayoral Candidate Would Tax, Tax, Tax
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of contrarian politics, how about a candidate whose
main pitch is a call to raise taxes, and raise them ``shamelessly
high?''
</P>
<P>
   Read Jim Bradley's lips.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is one of 13 people running for mayor of Salt Lake City.
And like the other candidates, he is spending a lot of time talking
about the 2002 Winter Olympic Games, which will be held in Salt
Lake City, and which the city bid for so heavily that it was
accused of trying to ``buy'' the event.
</P>
<P>
   Having won the bidding, many city officials and residents are
now worried that if the games are not a success, Salt Lake might be
stuck with any bad debts.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley, a former county commissioner and unsuccessful
Democratic candidate for governor in 1996, says he has a plan:
Raise extra income by increasing taxes on rooms, rental cars, food
and everything else needed by the thousands of visitors who will
come to the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hotel transient room tax has to be jacked up as high as we
can possibly do it,'' Bradley argued in a recent candidates debate.
``We have to raise the car rental tax as high as we can possibly do
it _ even shamelessly high _ to generate revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Jones, another mayoral contender, called Bradley
``insensitive'' and argued that Salt Lake City ``isn't a place to
come and get fleeced.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, considered one of the front-runners in the race,
countered that however high Salt Lake City taxes and prices were
raised, the city would still seem a bargain to most visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a mean-spirited idea,'' he said. ``All I'm looking
for are ways that the city's not left holding the bag.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
