<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7303 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NY     08-14 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: QUESTIONING EVERYTHING FOR THE RECORD AND BEYOND
</HEADLINE>
   (ko) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I think I may be suffering from record fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   A diagnostician from the Elias Sports Bureau would probably find
the first symptoms deep in my childhood, while I was trying to
flawlessly field a pink rubber ball 100 times as it bounced off a
brick wall. Even when I succeeded, I felt a certain emptiness, an
``Is this all there is?'' I wondered if I would feel relief at 200,
euphoria at 20,000.
</P>
<P>
   I felt the recurrence of that childhood pathology 10 days ago
when Mark McGwire hit his 500th home run. I might also have been a
little surprised. Only 500? Will I feel better when he hits his
800th? His 1,000th?
</P>
<P>
   Then nine days ago Tony Gwynn got his 3,000th hit. By the time
Wade Boggs reached 3,000 a day later, my lack of caring was
disturbing. I knew how meaningful this was to Boggs, how he had
once kept batting charts so detailed that they included not only
the types of pitches he faced but also what he was eating that day
and whom he was sleeping with. The consummate pro deserved to
celebrate his numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Is it mean-spirited of me not to share this excitement, I
wondered? Or is it record fatigue, one form of the many low-level
contemporary diseases caused by the information overload? Instead
of treating it as a swarm of locusts to be sprayed away, we welcome
the relentless assault as a kind of mental lottery. We consume all
the bits, sure that one of them will contain the germ of wisdom.
And what could be a better bet than that bit of information called
a record, all-star information with a pedigree, with a history,
with a ranking?
</P>
<P>
   Millennial sum-ups, catch-ups and best lists are part of the
problem; this is a way of putting the century to bed. Also, we seem
to have reached a critical mass of numbers along with the computers
to sort them quickly. This at a time when a highly competitive
sports media is scrambling to concoct news events out of scheduled
entertainments, to give some human meaning to otherwise meaningless
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   My record fatigue, indolent since childhood, flared when Cal
Ripken Jr. approached Lou Gehrig's record of consecutive games. So?
A player stays healthy, competent and on one team long enough to
surpass a player who contracted a fatal disease. Ripken's record
was given weight by right-wing conspirators who wanted to embarrass
workers who took Mondays off, left early on Fridays and used their
sick days.
</P>
<P>
   When I publicly suggested that Ripken take a day off, the only
national commentator who understood I might be joking was Rush
Limbaugh. This turned me rightward; I gave away my Tommy, Willie
and Angela Davis T-shirts. But I also felt isolated in my rare
condition. Just when I was fatigued, most other people couldn't get
enough records. And soon we'll have Ripken again with his 3,000 _
if he can get healthy enough to get back in the lineup long enough.
</P>
<P>
   Record fatigue makes you question everything. McGwire, Gwynn and
Boggs stacked up their statistics with noncontending teams; does
that mean they don't have to face top pitchers? Five grand slams in
five games last Monday, the first time in history that so many were
hit in one day; a return to the rabbit ball?
</P>
<P>
   I should be happy that records are back. In the 1980s,
golf-style rankings in which athletes were listed, like day traders
and orthopedic surgeons, by their incomes, replaced batting
averages, yards gained and points per game as measures of man. By
the '90s, however, with more multimillionaires than All-Stars on
every roster, money rankings made no sense. Salary records were
routinely broken every season, and resentment grew among fans and
sportswriters. Back to hard figures that could gauge achievement.
Let's make sports pure and simple again.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. Pete Rose got 4,256 hits and he's not good enough for
the Hall of Fame. Lawrence Taylor, who left a statistically
verifiable trail of blood and tears through the National Football
League, almost didn't make his Hall because of conduct unbefitting
a man who knocks other men down for a living.
</P>
<P>
   And the significance of records keeps changing. When Roger
Maris, who was not Mickey Mantle, hit 61 home runs in one season,
we were told that Babe Ruth's really important record was his
lifetime tally. Then Hank Aaron, who was not white, hit 715 and we
were told that Joe DiMaggio's 56-game hitting streak was the one
true record. Maybe if we ever learn to embrace McGwire, we can go
back to the single-season home run record.
</P>
<P>
   But just what does a record mean?
</P>
<P>
   A certain selfish drive, to be sure. Unless it's a record for
assists (but then you just might be someone's co-dependent or were
afraid to shoot), we can figure you were thinking about your
scoreboard numbers a lot. Hitting records often depend on who is
batting around you in the order. Touchdowns thrown or caught are a
two-man operation. Track and field records have lost a certain
precision unless they are accompanied by the types and amounts of
chemical helpers.
</P>
<P>
   Is this just me? Too many records in a record-breaking span of
time? Or are we counting the wrong numbers? Maybe Wilt Chamberlain
was right; foul shots sunk are not as human a statistic as women
slept with (20,000). Now that's worthy of record fatigue. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
