<HEADER>
A7307 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BOSTON-COLLEGE-FEMINI     08-14 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-COLLEGE-FEMINIST-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING FORCED RETIREMENT, ICONOCLASTIC PROFESSOR KEEPS ON
FIGHTING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs to correct time element to last week in 4th graf. No
pickup.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For nigh on 20 years, Mary Daly, who is widely
considered the world's foremost radical feminist philosopher and
theologian, has barred men from her classroom at Boston College,
arguing that they marred the learning experience of women.
</P>
<P>
   For 20 years, too, the university objected to her separatism and
penalized her with reprimands and denial of promotion, but never
fired her. Nor could it change the strong mind of a woman who has
three doctorate degrees, has inspired reviewers of her seven books
to use words like ``genius,'' and so defies the powers that be _
including church and university powers _ that she even uses her own
lexicon, with words like phallocracy and academentia.
</P>
<P>
   And so the conflict went, flaring and dying down depending on
the year _ until now. In what some consider a telling sign, Daly
appears to be going down _ swinging, swinging all the way _ to
defeat, a forced retirement at age 70. At least, so it would seem,
judging by recent legal and administrative moves.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Boston College, a Jesuit-run Catholic university,
officially took Daly's office back from her, as sure a sign as any
of academic nonbeing. And though she called a press conference and
complained of a ``lockout'' (prompting university officials to
protest that they had not locked her out but were indeed
reassigning her office), it did not change the bureaucratic fact
that after decades, 467 Carney Hall was no longer hers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's symbolic, isn't it?'' Daly said. ``A lockout. Think of
Virginia Woolf, `A Room of One's Own' _ that's what women have
always needed under patriarchy, and can't be creative without. They
took away my classroom, and my status to teach, and now they have
taken away my office, and all of it is giving the message that
Virginia Woolf and I are losing what I call `womenspace.'''
</P>
<P>
   A Boston College spokesman, Jack Dunn, said that Daly had made a
commitment to retire rather than admit male students _ though she
has since renounced that commitment _ and thus lost her tenured
post. The university plans to fight her in court for as long as it
takes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just feel it's dangerous to condone intolerance,'' Dunn
said. ``You can't make an exception for discrimination or
intolerance. It's a slippery slope, it's dangerous ground, and we
refuse to do it. If this were a white professor saying, `I don't
want black students in my classroom,' obviously we'd take the same
position. The difference is, the world would have out-shouted us
first. This is a harder case, but it's the same issue. It's
fairness. It's accessibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more ominously for Daly, she lost the preliminary round in
her legal battle against Boston College. She sued the university in
May for breach of contract and violation of her tenure rights and
asked a judge to immediately order the university to reinstate her
in this fall's course catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Martha B. Sosman of Superior Court refused, saying
in part, ``There is no question that the school has adequate cause
to terminate Daly if, for some reason, her promise to resign turns
out to be unenforceable.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge added: ``A coeducational institution of higher
learning may insist that all courses be open to both male and
female students. A professor's defiance of that policy _ in this
case, a vehement and very public defiance _ would give the school
ample grounds for her termination.''
</P>
<P>
   That early ruling does not cow Daly's lawyer, Gretchen Van Ness.
She says the case, which is scheduled to go to trial next summer,
is on ``the cutting edge of Title IX,'' the 1972 law barring sexual
discrimination at schools that receive federal money.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing that says what she's been doing is per se
against the law,'' Ms. Van Ness said, ``and in fact, Title IX has
said that when you are making up for past discrimination and have a
pedagogical reason for what you're doing, it might be
permissible.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Ms. Van Ness said, Title IX is meant to combat
discrimination based on stereotypical views like ``women can't play
sports.'' Daly, she said, ``came to decide to teach the way she
teaches not based on stereotypes or intentional discrimination but
on her very, very real experience of what it meant for her students
for her to teach in a mixed class rather than separate classes.''
</P>
<P>
   In a women-only class, said Megan Niziol, a former student of
Daly's who graduated this year, ``being together creates an energy
that Professor Daly calls `gynergy.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``In my experience, when there are male students in a class,
that gets suffocated,'' Ms. Niziol said.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for the Center for Individual Rights in
Washington, which has successfully challenged affirmative action
practices in several states recently, questioned the legal _ and
moral _ basis of women-only classes.
</P>
<P>
   The law permits single-sex institutions to teach single-sex
classes, said Terence J. Pell, senior counsel for the center. But
``what Title IX does not contemplate is a particular professor at a
coed institution simply refusing across the board to even consider
the possibility of men in her class.''
</P>
<P>
   The trigger for Daly's current problems came in the person of
Duane Naquin, a male student who was denied access last year to her
class in feminist ethics and complained to university officials and
to the center.
</P>
<P>
   Pell and Dunn questioned Daly's recent statements that she was
willing to teach men, but in separate classes. Dunn said that
according to the registrar's records, no male student had completed
one of Daly's classes since she began separate teaching in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   In the Boston news media, recent editorial opinion has leaned
against Daly, and though she has been supported by some students
wearing ``Where's Mary Daly?'' pins, there has been nothing like
the ground swell of 1,500 students _ all men _ who rallied behind
her when she was first denied tenure in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   To Daly and her supporters, the powerful opposition looks like
part of a national backlash against both feminism and affirmative
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question of all-women classes has been on the agenda for
20 years,'' said Letty Russell, a colleague of Daly's and professor
of theology at Yale Divinity School. ``So the fact they could bring
it up now and make an issue of it, I think, reflects change both in
the climate of the country and the approach to getting rid of
affirmative action.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly, who took on the male-dominated hierarchy of the Roman
Catholic Church in the 1960s and has not stopped her ideological
assaults on male power and her elevation of female virtues ever
since, looks unlikely to back down.
</P>
<P>
   Past conflicts with the university were ``not entirely painful,
because when I fought back, I always won,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time is the first time it appears they have won,'' she
said. ``But they haven't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
