<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-STRAW-POLL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LADIES AND GENTLEMEN, STEP RIGHT UP AND PICK A PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Will update with results.)  
(nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMES, Iowa _ Politics can be a circus, and there was no better
example of that than here Saturday, where Republican presidential
candidates competed not over tax or education policy but who could
erect the biggest tent, serve the tastiest barbecue and provide the
best country-and-western music.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people swarmed to the campus of Iowa State
University in this central Iowa town to participate in a straw poll
devised as a money-making operation by the state's Republican
Party. In a practice that critics say is meaningless because it
verges on outright vote-buying, the campaigns bused Iowans here,
fed them, entertained them and then paid their $25 entry fee.
</P>
<P>
   The hope was that, in return, the sated participants would cast
a vote for the candidate who treated them the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this the way to pick a president?'' asked former Rep. Bill
Zeliff of New Hampshire, as he stood amid a huge, state-of-the-art
playground erected by Steve Forbes' campaign. ``If it is, we're in
bad shape.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Zeliff's candidate took part; Zeliff is national
chairman for former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander. Alexander's
enticement for voters: singer Crystal Gayle.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that in the 2000 campaign, this, indeed, may be a
way to pick a candidate. Because the campaign has started so soon,
with many states moving up the dates of their primaries, the straw
poll here could have the effect of winnowing the field. Because
Texas Gov. George W. Bush has so dominated the polls and amassed so
much cash, some campaigns said that Ames might be the site of their
last stand.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the revelry on this bright and festive Saturday
afternoon, the campaigns were partaking in high-stakes politics.
Aides to the campaigns scurried about with walkie-talkies and cell
phones, doing all they could to insure that their candidates would
grab the most votes.
</P>
<P>
   The event was an organizational test to see which campaigns
could convince the most people to travel far and wide to this event
_ and then take the next step to support their candidate. Any Iowa
resident of voting age could participate, a change in the rules
that gave this event more credibility than it had four years ago.
Then, candidates turned this grass-roots exercise into the campaign
equivalent of the Berlin airlift, flying in supporters from around
the country.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday's spectacle was by far the most extravagant ever.
Republicans sometimes call themselves the party of the Big Tent
and, certainly, the event was a sea of big and small tents.
</P>
<P>
   If sheer resources were any guide to who would triumph, Forbes
would win hands down. No one here could stop talking about a
mammoth, air-conditioned tent (with French doors) erected by the
campaign of Forbes, the multimillionaire publisher who is dipping
into his fortune to finance his White House quest.
</P>
<P>
   Marveling, perhaps, at the competition, Benjamin Ginsberg, the
Bush campaign's legal counsel, called it ``Chateaux Malcolm,'' a
reference to Forbes' father.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of people coming here to get cooled off,'' Greg
Muller, a spokesman for Forbes, said approvingly as people swarmed
into the tent. ``In the Bush tent they come off a little stodgy.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the pivotal Iowa caucuses nearly six months from
now, when people will actually vote in a binding contest, Muller
said, `'This is all a down payment for a cold night in February.''
</P>
<P>
   One Forbes supporter who was cooling off was Joanne Pohlman, 62,
a retired schoolteacher from Webster City who clutched a Forbes
gift bag. ``It's like a carnival,'' she said. ``But it's fun. Great
fun. Great sport. Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   Max Eckstein, 22, a college student from Boone, Iowa, who was
surveying the band in one of the Bush tents, said the governor and
other candidates ``must be kicking themselves'' for not
air-conditioning their tents. But, he said, that would not in
itself sway him to back Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do food and entertainment make a difference?'' Eckstein asked.
``Maybe for the common person.''
</P>
<P>
   But some of the partygoers, while not shy about eating the food
and accepting the free rides on hot air balloons, denounced the
extravagance, saying the campaigns should spend their millions on
more than just staging a big party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forbes is trying to appeal to the side of us that says, `OK,
we can play, so he must be good,''' said Tanya Bignell, a data
entry worker from Bettendorf who is backing Sen. Orrin Hatch,
R-Utah. ``I don't think so,'' Ms. Bignell said in Hatch's
sweltering tent, picking over a modest spread of chicken and baked
beans.
</P>
<P>
   The campaigns who forked out the most cash were a bit worried
that some people they transported here would use their ticket to
vote for another candidate. So before anyone could extract their
ticket from the Forbes organization, they had to sign a pledge
saying, ``I, the undersigned, pledge to support Steve Forbes.''
</P>
<P>
   D. Jim Moore and Greta Moore, farmers from Thornburg, Iowa,
peered into the Hatch tent but said they were backing Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But as far as entertainment goes, ``Forbes is probably the
best,'' Moore, who is 69, said. ``He had Debby Boone in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Boone, who is 68, interjected, ``It was packed, I'll tell
you.'' She said she was not put off by the hefty spending, saying,
``That's their business. You spend your money where you have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Endicott, 34, an English teacher who lives near here,
said he is a Democrat but voted for Elizabeth Dole in the hope that
she will take votes from Bush _ and make him seem less intimidating
to the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get her more points against Bush to keep her in the
race,'' he said. Endicott said he was ``turned off'' by some of the
tents, even by the low budget operation of former Vice President
Dan Quayle. ``Quayle's corn cobs and hay stacks, it's just too
hick,'' he complained.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, others agreed. While the Forbes and Bush tents were
packing in hundreds and hundreds, the Quayle tent was fairly empty
before lunch. A band played to only a handful of people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 1553EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
