u a BC-COLUMBINE-REOPEN-1STL     08-14 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMBINE-REOPEN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMBINE STUDENTS _ WARY, YET EAGER _ PREPARE TO RETURN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (CORRECTS Rashid to Rashad, $18,000 to $40,000 in 2nd graf of 2nd
take; ADDS name of race; CORRECTS that race is run across city, not
over bridge.) 
(ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service      
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Inside Columbine High School, where two
teen-agers shot and killed a dozen other students and a teacher
last April 20, the library, where much of the mayhem occurred, has
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Once pockmarked by bullets and splattered with blood, it now
remains hidden behind a wall of blue-painted lockers as part of
efforts by local officials to remove evidence and memories of one
of the deadliest school shootings in American history.
</P>
<P>
   When students return to classes on Monday for a new school year,
not quite four months after the chaos ended with the young gunmen
turning their weapons on themselves, Columbine faces the rather
daunting challenge of seeking normalcy in a place that could never
be the same after what happened there.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are experiencing a range of emotions, the most
universal of them, anxiousness,'' said Krista R. Flannigan, a
victim counselor from Idaho Springs, Colo., who worked with many
families of Columbine students over the summer. ``Some students are
really looking forward to going back. Others are afraid. Some think
something could happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Some students, like Kasey Ruegsegger, a junior last year who was
shot in the shoulder as she hid behind a desk in the library, grew
so uncomfortable with the prospect of returning that they have
transferred to other schools or turned to home-schooling. Ms.
Ruegsegger said she planned to attend a small private school for
``a fresh start,'' adding, ``But I'm happy for the ones going back
to Columbine.''
</P>
<P>
   The shootings traumatized a town and stunned a nation that is
fast growing accustomed to episodes of savagery in which the
victims are young and only loosely connected, if at all, to their
attackers. At Columbine, the teen-agers who armed themselves with
four weapons and a cache of bombs, Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan
Klebold, 17, members of the so-called trench coat mafia, were known
to many other students as relatively unremarkable, which made their
final exploits that much more chilling.
</P>
<P>
   Yet to say that their crimes changed much in the nation would be
an exaggeration. While Congress raised the specter of Columbine and
other school shootings in the long debates on tougher gun-control
measures, the last session ended with no new legislation. Nor have
sociologists, psychologists and other experts agreed on the reasons
that teen-agers from apparently stable, financially secure families
would act out aggressions against peers in such a violent manner.
</P>
<P>
   Here at Columbine, school officials have invited parents,
teachers and other residents of Littleton to form a ``human chain''
outside the school early Monday morning to project a sense of
support and safety for the 1,900 new and returning students who are
expected. A 45-minute rally in the student parking lot has been
scheduled to follow, with Columbine's principal, Frank DeAngelis,
planning to urge the students to ``take back our school.''
</P>
<P>
   A flag that has stood at half-staff since the shootings will be
raised; a ribbon wrapped around the school will be cut.
</P>
<P>
   But even with changes intended to make Columbine safer than ever
_ a $1 million investment by the Jefferson County school district
that includes a new surveillance system, student identification
badges and additional mental-health workers _ anxieties persist
among many Columbine parents and students.
</P>
<P>
   The conflicting feelings within the Wilson family are typical.
Stuart, a 10th grader who is trying out for the football team as a
defensive end, said he and many of his friends were eager to
reconvene as a group, forget what happened last April and ``be back
like normal again.''
</P>
<P>
   But his mother, Annie, a native of South Africa who brought her
family to Littleton six years ago ``to be safe,'' described herself
as ``extremely anxious'' about sending Stuart and her two other
children back to Jefferson County schools this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids are fine, but I'm neurotic about this,'' she said,
standing outside Columbine one day last week with Stuart, 14, and
his siblings, Cameron, 13, and Holly, 8, after Stuart registered
for the new school year. ``I admire the kids' courage, coming back,
but for me, it's been really hard.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to psychological scars, the shootings left a wide
path of destruction well beyond bullet holes in walls and library
books stained with blood.
</P>
<P>
   Beside the 15 who died, nearly two dozen students were wounded
by gunshots, three of whom remain paralyzed below the waist and
face the almost certain prospect of life in a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Anne Marie Hochhalter, 17, who was shot in the
back, left the hospital only last week to join her family living in
temporary quarters until they move soon into a house that is
wheelchair accessible. A spokesman for Craig Hospital in Denver,
where the most seriously injured people were treated, said Ms.
Hochhalter was planning to return to Columbine for her senior year,
although not right away.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth student, Patrick Ireland, 17, who escaped from the
library by climbing out a window after he was shot in the head,
still has a bullet lodged in the back of his brain. Ireland, who is
expected to return to classes on Monday, has partial paralysis on
his right side and problems speaking.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Many of the families of injured students were caught with
insufficient medical coverage and are struggling to pay bills.
Churches and other local community groups have helped raise money
to defray the costs, and a ``healing fund'' was created to
distribute the $3.8 million that was collected for families of
people who were killed or injured.
</P>
<P>
   But in a few cases, support arose from unlikely sources. Rashad
Williams, a 15-year-old student in San Francisco who had previously
never met Lance Kirklin, 16, raised $40,000 in pledges to help him
by running in the Bay to Breakers race across the city. Lance was
shot five times at close range, causing major damage to the left
side of his face.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ruegsegger suffered a less serious injury. As the shootings
continued, she said, she drew herself under a desk and pulled a
chair in front of her. ``I heard a lot of it,'' she said. ``I
wouldn't let myself watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she was shot in the right side of her body, and this
summer, therapy is helping her regain full motion of her arm.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings also led to a swirl of activity by law-enforcement
agencies investigating how the killers got their guns. The
authorities decided not to prosecute Robyn Anderson, a Columbine
student who bought a shotgun _ legally, they determined _ used in
the shootings. Ms. Anderson went to the prom with Klebold three
days before the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   But two others involved with getting weapons for the gunmen,
Mark Manes and Philip Duran, who were not students at Columbine,
face gun charges and have arraignments scheduled this month.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   For all the measures undertaken to heal the mental and physical
wounds of the Columbine community, Dr. Donald Bechtold, a child
psychologist at the University of Colorado School of Medicine, said
it was unlikely anyone affected by the shootings would soon forget
them.
</P>
<P>
   He said some students would prove ``remarkably resilient'' but
that others would continue to be haunted by the tragedy, emotions
triggered by a sight, a sound or even a smell.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason to expect them to resolve their feelings 3
1/2 months after the fact,'' Bechtold said. ``I don't think any of
them have completed the recovery process.''
</P>
<P>
   That possibility has left teachers and administrators expecting
a wide range of emotions when the rally ends on Monday and students
re-enter the building as a group for the first time since the
shootings. Students finished out the spring semester at nearby
Chatfield High School.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Johnson, a psychology teacher who taught both of the gunmen
and was a close friend of the teacher who was killed, Dave Sanders,
said he was looking forward to returning when classes resume. But
he conceded that he did not know what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe there will be some tears for friends and the
memories of what happened,'' he said. ``But I also think that kids
are geared up to do what they need to do to have a real school
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
