<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7331 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-N     08-14 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECIDING ON THE MANAGER, AND MAKING IT WORK
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Always candid and first class, Phil Garner said the Milwaukee
Brewers were justified in firing him as their manager last week.
The same cannot be said for all decisions to fire managers or
general managers, or to retain them. This season offers various
evidence of that reality.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A: Fourteen months ago the Fox regime fired Fred Claire
as general manager and Bill Russell as manager of the Los Angeles
Dodgers. Certainly a new owner has the right to bring in new people
to replace those who ran the operation for the previous owner. But
what a disaster Fox has produced.
</P>
<P>
   Playing with the major leagues' second most expensive payroll,
the Dodgers have raised the bar for the measurement of
underachievement. Fox gave Kevin Brown the most lucrative contract
in baseball history, instantly affecting the entire industry, and
thought that clinched their trip to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the capable hand of Davey Johnson has been able to
avert the disaster the Dodgers have become. Barring a late surge,
they will spoil Johnson's record of never having finished below
second place in the 10 complete seasons he has managed.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit B: After six seasons, the Colorado Rockies decided that
Don Baylor was no longer good enough to manage their team. They
fired him and lured Jim Leyland to the Rocky Mountains with a $2
million-a-year contract. To their naive surprise, they have
discovered that their team is no better than it was under Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies entered Saturday's game in last place with a 49-67
record. At the corresponding stage last season they were in fourth
place with a 52-64 record. Leyland obviously can't do any more than
Baylor did without a decent pitching staff. The pitching staff, in
fact, is headed for a league-worst earned run average for the sixth
time in the team's seven-year existence, and with its highest ERA
ever, perhaps over 6 for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit C: After Johnson led the Baltimore Orioles to two
postseason appearances in two seasons as their manager, they
accepted his resignation, which he tendered before he could be
fired. The Orioles have been a $150 million (two-year payroll)
wasteland since.
</P>
<P>
   With Ray Miller as the manager, handpicked by the owner, Peter
Angelos, the Orioles have compiled a 130-147 record this season and
last and have staggered an insurmountable distance from the
Yankees, an aggregate of 55{ games before Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Angelos has resisted firing Miller during the season, but now
that Garner is available, Angelos may pursue him and make the
change if and when he catches him.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit D: The Detroit Tigers fired the popular Buddy Bell as
manager last Sept. 1 and replaced him with Larry Parrish. But as
disappointing as they were last year under Bell, the Tigers are
more disappointing under Parrish this season.
</P>
<P>
   At this point last season the Tigers had a 46-69 record and were
in last place, 18{ games from first. They reached Saturday with a
46-69 record, in last place and 24{ games from first. This is not
how the Tigers planned to march into their new park next season.
</P>
<P>
   This season has not gone the way the Anaheim Angels planned,
either. After a flap over some players' view toward the manager,
Terry Collins, the Angels made a Disney-like move, showing the
players who was in charge by giving Collins a contract extension.
Now, after plunging 13 games in the standings in a recent 18-game
stretch and losing 23 of their last 27 games, the Angels staggered
into Saturday's game 21 games behind the first-place Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels players feel Collins is too frantic, makes changes
too hastily and does not let them do their jobs. Collins
encountered similar problems in Houston, and the Astros fired him
at the end of the 1997 season. They hired Larry Dierker, a
broadcaster of all things, to replace Collins, and they are in
position to win their third consecutive division championship under
Dierker.
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto Blue Jays fired their manager, Tim Johnson, during
spring training, an unusual time for such a move. But they were
concerned about the continued fallout from his fanciful tales about
service in Vietnam. Some people in baseball feel the Blue Jays
treated Johnson badly, especially after they had insisted he
apologize for his behavior, but the Blue Jays are pleased with the
results. Under Jim Fregosi, they are contending for the wild-card
spot.
</P>
<P>
   The Oakland Athletics are contending for that spot, too, and
they are doing it under Art Howe, whom they considered firing but
did not. There's a saying in baseball that some of the best moves
are the ones you don't make. In this instance, the Athletics are 10
games better than they were last year, 62-53 compared with 52-63.
</P>
<P>
   The Cincinnati Reds made a similarly wise decision in retaining
Jack McKeon as their manager, despite the feeling in at least one
quarter that he was too old. Joe Morgan, player turned author,
wrote in a recently published book that ``at 69 his time has
passed,'' and that McKeon would not be able to relate to the Reds'
young players.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds' players, young and old, love McKeon, and the front
office loves where he has the team, in first place when play began
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Post-Season Blues
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Valentine is trying to be No. 1, but for now he'll have to
settle for being No. 3, though on a different list. With the Mets'
game in San Francisco on Saturday, Valentine will have managed more
games in the major leagues without finishing first than all but two
managers: Paul Richards (1,837) and Jimmy Dykes (2,962).
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Banks knows what that's all about. He played in 2,528
games, more than any other player, without ever playing in a
postseason game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really?'' Banks said when told about Valentine. ``I know how
that feels. I know how he feels. My heart goes out with him.''
</P>
<P>
   And then Banks remembered _ how could he forget? _ that it was
the Mets who deprived him of his best chance of playing in the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mets were the team that kept me from getting there with my
last chance,'' he said, alluding to the Chicago Cubs' collapse in
1969. ``Those were rugged times for all of us. Sometimes you can
feel you have something in the bag and the bag breaks. It was my
last chance. I was 40. The Mets were so good. They just overtook
us. That was it for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks, who played for 19 years, was reminded of the void in his
career last month when he was in Boston for the All-Star Game and
the announcement of the plans for voting for the MasterCard MLB
All-Century Team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was talking,'' Banks related, ``and we were enjoying
each other. I looked around and said gosh, I'm the only one here
who didn't play in the playoffs or the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   That scene reminded him, too, of other times, other gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elston Howard and I talked about it a lot,'' Banks said.
``He'd be in the World Series all the time. I said, `Elston, my
main mission in life is to get to you guys in October.' He would
laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the old-timers games. ``I'd ask the guys what
it's like to play in the World Series. Willie'' _ Mays, of course _
``started laughing. They had fun with me. I became the focal point
of the games.''
</P>
<P>
   And Hall of Fame induction weekends. ``Those guys used to tell
me that those games are totally different than any games. I think,
what would I have been like playing in those games, when the
pressure's on, when you're representing your city? You really miss
that opportunity, that feeling. You don't know how good you could
have performed under those conditions, to be in a World Series.
It's very special. I missed that. I miss that a lot. There is
nothing to take the place of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting Stirred Up to Start
</P>
<P>
   After Esteban Loaiza served as a starting pitcher in his first
four seasons in the major leagues, the Texas Rangers made him a
reliever this season. He didn't like the role, however, and four
weeks ago he pointedly asked why Ryan Glenn, a rookie, and not he
should be starting against San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Loaiza, a 27-year-old Mexican, pitched in the
game, 42/3 innings to Glynn's 41/3, and was the winning pitcher.
When that slot in the rotation came up five days later, it was
Loaiza who had it. He has now started four games, winning three and
compiling a 3.04 ERA. The Rangers won his fourth start in extra
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it put a little fire under him,'' General Manager Doug
Melvin said, referring to the game Loaiza didn't start. ``That's
one thing he has lacked. We've tried to challenge him. I challenged
him earlier this year. I said, `People don't understand why you're
not doing as well as Jose Lima; you have as good an arm.' Sometimes
the light has to click on.''
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza, Melvin said, responded by acknowledging that he needed
to be more focused in games. ``He loses his concentration at
times,'' Melvin said. ``He has to take it a little more seriously.
He's shown some signs of doing that. He's got a durable arm. He
could be a good long guy for us, but he pitched well and deserved a
shot in the rotation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who have one of the best relief corps in the
majors, need a solid starter and will give Loaiza all the starts he
wants as long as he continues to pitch effectively.
</P>
<P>
   The Myth of Letdowns
</P>
<P>
   Since the advent of free agency, owners and general managers
have grumbled that players with multiyear contracts don't play as
well as they do under one-year contracts. They feel players let
down in the first years of their long-term deals.
</P>
<P>
   So consider some of these recent performances in the first year
or years of multiyear contracts:
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire, first year, 70 home runs. Sammy Sosa, first year,
66 home runs. Ken Griffey Jr., first two years, 56 home runs each
season. Roger Clemens, first two years, two Cy Young awards.
</P>
<P>
   And how about this season with Bernie Williams in the first year
of a seven-year contract, Robin Ventura in the first of five and
Roberto Alomar in the first of four? These are not exceptions, just
examples.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
