<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7336 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-CAMP-LIFE-ART-NYT     08-14 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CAMP-LIFE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 OFF THE FIELD, GIANTS ARE LIKE ANY OTHER SUMMER CAMPERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some are millionaires, all are living a boyhood dream of playing
professional football, but during four weeks every July or August
they are summer campers with all the ordinary problems of dormitory
life _ snoring roommates, clashes over bathroom etiquette,
arguments over who gets to watch what on television.
</P>
<P>
   Take Giants cornerback Jason Sehorn and quarterback Kerry
Collins, two of the team's most prominent players and the Felix
Unger and Oscar Madison combination of this year's Giants training
camp.
</P>
<P>
   Sehorn received an advance scouting report on Collins. ``I told
him I was a borderline slob,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Sehorn went to the Giants' camp at SUNY-Albany prepared. ``I
brought about five extra sponges for cleaning up after him,'' said
Sehorn, who is always meticulously groomed and orderly.
</P>
<P>
   But life in their portion of the Freedom Hall dorm has been
without incident. Sehorn, in fact, has not used any of his extra
sponges.
</P>
<P>
   Players have their own bedrooms, but share a living room area
and a bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought maybe I was making him nervous when some of my stuff
was starting to pile up near his stuff,'' Collins said. ``So I
grabbed it and hid it in my closet. Everything's been fine since
then.''
</P>
<P>
   That they are rooming together at all is a bit odd because
Collins replaced quarterback Danny Kanell, who was Sehorn's best
friend on the team. But Sehorn welcomed Collins from the start. And
when coach Jim Fassel was going over room assignments, he thought
it natural that Collins take Kanell's place in every way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He spends most of his time on his laptop and I spend mine on
the telephone,'' said Collins, who makes nightly hours-long calls
to his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised they've gotten along,'' Fassel said. ``They
are teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Strahan and Cedric Jones are teammates, too, and the
Giants' starting defensive ends. That does not mean they get along
on everything as roommates. The heart of their quarrel is
television programming choices, and it can be best described in
initials: PBS versus WWF.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to watch educational programs or maybe a sitcom,''
Strahan said. ``He wants to watch pro wrestling or Jerry
Springer.''
</P>
<P>
   They have roomed together before, and Strahan and Jones knew
enough to bring two televisions this summer, one for each bedroom.
But this arrangement has brought about only a certain measure of
peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to take a nap and Cedric is yelling to me,
`Michael, turn on Channel 33, they're throwing chairs on Jerry
Springer!''' Strahan said at camp last week. ``I said, `Cedric,
excuse me, I'm trying to sleep in here.'''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jones, ``Well, I didn't know he was asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones has complaints of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``His phone is ringing all day and night,'' he said of Strahan,
who recently concluded negotiations for a $32 million contract
extension. ``And he's not just watching educational programs, he's
watching those music videos all the time. He does tell me my TV is
too loud.''
</P>
<P>
   Strahan called that an understatement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too loud? I can hear it coming down the hall,'' Strahan said.
``And one night I had to get up at 3 a.m. and go turn off his TV
because he forgot to set the sleep timer.''
</P>
<P>
   But the two are good friends. They travel in Strahan's car back
and forth to practice, and to lunch and dinner daily. ``Oh yeah, I
love him,'' Strahan said. ``Cedric is easy to get along with.''
</P>
<P>
   In the suite where safeties Sam Garnes and Percy Ellsworth and
wide receiver Ike Hilliard live, boisterous rancor is the attitude
that keeps them happily together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a loud place,'' Garnes said. ``A lot of trash talking.
You've got to have a thick skin to be in our league. We say, `Don't
come in there if you can't take it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Garnes is not talking about their existence together as much as
the three or more video basketball games they play each day. They
plan to play an entire National Basketball Association season.
Garnes was the doormat of the video league last season, so this
off-season he went into a heavy training regimen to improve his
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked on my game every day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's winning big.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam is hot right now,'' Hilliard acknowledged glumly.
</P>
<P>
   It's something Garnes reminds his roommates about constantly.
``I'm gloating. They don't even want to talk to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One thing they don't do is talk football.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, the point is to take your mind off football for a while,''
Ellsworth said. ``We get enough of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The players' schedule is hardly carefree. There is no time for
sailing on the Hudson River or getaways to nearby Saratoga Race
Course. There is a two-hour practice around 9 a.m., followed by
lunch. Most players take a nap before the 3 p.m. practice. After
dinner, the players are in meetings until almost 10 o'clock nearly
every night. Most are asleep by 11:30 p.m. or midnight.
</P>
<P>
   To listen to linebackers Pete Monty and Scott Galyon, bedtime is
when their problems with Derek Engler, a center, begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He snores,'' Monty said of Engler. The two are teammates and
friends from their days playing at the University of Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Adds Galyon: ``I can hear him through his door and my door. He's
got a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Engler dismissed the complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, we're in our separate rooms,'' he said. ``The problem
is those two nuts jumping up and down and yelling while they play
that James Bond videogame. It's a circus. I'm the one not getting
any peace and quiet. Pete is screaming much louder than he does on
the football field.''
</P>
<P>
   And from one floor below, where backup quarterback Mike Cherry
occupies the room beneath Monty, Galyon and Engler, came another
party to the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can hear somebody snoring up there,'' Cherry said. ``Then
again, that whole room is pretty loud with guys jumping on my
ceiling. They must be having fun up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, what else is summer camp for?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 1655EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
