<DOCNO> NYT19990814.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7343 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-NUDE-COLONY-NYT &LR;      08-14 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NUDE-COLONY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 NUDISTS GATHER TO SHED CARES, PRETENSES, EVERYTHING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORAVIA, N.Y. _ At Empire Haven Nudist Park, visitors leave
their pretenses at the door, along with their clothes. Especially
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, hundreds of people began filtering into the private
park for this year's Northeast Naturist Festival, billed as the
largest gathering of nudists in New York state and the
second-largest in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of folks think that you have to be beautiful to run
around naked, but if you walk around here for a while, you'll see
almost the opposite is true,'' said Nancy Casey, a child counselor
from Rochester who strolled about the park with her husband,
Darrell, both wearing nothing but sandals.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the 300 or so nudists gathered here this weekend
seem not to be slaves to Stairmasters. Mostly in their 40s and 50s,
they are forklift operators, police officers, accountants,
ministers, teachers and grandparents. They have come from as far
away as Illinois, Florida and parts of Canada to be naked with one
another.
</P>
<P>
   Though Empire Haven, the first and oldest nudist park in the
state, has been open for 40 years, recreational nudism is not quite
a mainstream movement. Wary of being labeled perverts or sex
maniacs, nudists (many now prefer to be called naturists) felt
compelled to keep their hobby a secret.
</P>
<P>
   Such fears are rapidly melting away.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much more acceptance in society,'' said Morley
Schloss, 57, a retired Rochester school administrator who helped
organize this weekend's festival. ``People tried it and found out
they didn't lose their jobs.'' As nude guests sat down to a dinner
of steamed vegetables with roast beef or whitefish, Schloss
strolled about nude, save for three strings of colored beads around
his neck.
</P>
<P>
   Through the park's expanses of grass and trees, cherubic young
children held hands and cavorted in the buff under their parents'
watchful gaze. Such is life at the 97-acre park, located in the
Finger Lakes region of western New York: relaxed, unhurried and,
for the most part, naked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of a better way to de-stress myself,'' said
Steve P., who would not give his last name but said he was an
ex-Marine who works as an accountant for a Big Five firm in lower
Manhattan. Friday afternoon, he sat naked in the clubhouse, typing
an electronic spreadsheet on a laptop computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come here to shed my worries, shed my clothes, shed
everything,'' he said. ``It's a form of honesty. You see me
standing there nude, you don't know if I'm a plumber, a truck
driver or a Wall Street financial guy. There's nothing to hide
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many people come here unaware of what they are getting into.
The nearest paved road is miles away, the entrance is gated and a
wall of pine, oak and maple trees is so thick that many folks in
downtown Moravia, four miles away, don't know the nudist park
exists.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine with Al and Marlene Robinson, Empire Haven's
friendly husband-and-wife owners. Robinson's father bought the
land, which used to be a mix of cow pastures, apple orchards and
strawberry fields, and opened the park in 1959. Robinson pretty
much grew up a nudist, and raised his children the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good for my kids, because they grew up knowing that no
one is different from anyone else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The park is open from May through October. Visitors and the
handful of trailer home owners who live here over the summer have
the clubhouse, a pool, a volleyball court, a private pond and acres
of meadow at their disposal. Nudity is optional everywhere except
in the pool area, sauna and hot tub.
</P>
<P>
   Photography is not permitted without permission, and no one is
allowed to drive in unchecked. Under a white tent near the entrance
gate on Friday, Mrs. Robinson, topless, registered guests and
collected camping fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't really know what a nudist park is until you get
here,'' said Al Robinson, 60, clad in shorts and a T-shirt. Before
driving off to buy 50 pounds of potatoes for that night's dinner,
he added, ``It's a way of life, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Empire Haven guests are members of the Naturist Society,
the sponsor of this weekend's festival and one of two factions of
American nudism that have emerged over the years. The Naturist
Society _ or TNS, as it is known here _ is more political, and its
members are known to take an activist approach to challenging the
clothing requirements at public beaches. The American Association
for Nude Recreation, on the other hand, tends to be less
confrontational about nudity, preferring to gather in private.
</P>
<P>
   Both organizations have prospered in the last 10 years, as
nudism's negative stereotype fades.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say there are not plenty of misconceptions about
nudity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a general perception in the public that if you're
nude, you've got to be having sex,'' said Mrs. Casey, stepping,
nude, inside her trailer home with her husband, who was also nude.
``Nudity and sexuality are not connected in this park.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in ways the park embodies family wholesomeness, with
children playing tag, couples dancing to music and Mrs. Casey
leading a ``hug workshop'' for 25 naked older people seated in lawn
chairs. Inhibitions don't seem to exist around here.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be surprised how many people secretly enjoy being
nude,'' said Jack Will, a retired Rochester police officer,
lounging naked next to the pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are quite a few of my friends on the force that go
nude,'' he said. ``It's like a fraternity,'' he said, gesturing to
other nude sunbathers. ``Everybody's equal when you don't have your
clothes on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
