<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CAPTAIN CRENSHAW'S TWO FOR THE MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also GLF-PGA, GLF-PGA-NOTEBOOK) 
(mk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ Now for another Ryder Cup controversy: Ben
Crenshaw's two captain's choices to fill out the 12-man U.S. team
that will try to recapture the trophy from the European pros Sept.
24-26 at The Country Club outside Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Ten automatic members, led by David Duval and Tiger Woods, will
be determined by the final point standing after Sunday's conclusion
of the Professional Golfers' Association Championship. Duval,
Woods, Payne Stewart, Davis Love III and Mark O'Meara have clinched
berths. Hal Sutton, Justin Leonard and Jim Furyk are virtually sure
of confirming their reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``But after that,'' Crenshaw said before the PGA started, ``I'll
be looking at the others, starting with Phil Mickelson.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson was ninth in the standing, followed by Jeff Maggert in
the 10th and last automatic spot, then Tom Lehman, Steve Stricker,
John Huston, Chris Perry, Bob Estes, Steve Pate and Fred Couples.
But the outcome of the PGA will likely change that order.
</P>
<P>
   Stricker and Huston wrecked their chances by missing the 36-hole
cut while Perry, Estes, Pate and Couples could move up.
</P>
<P>
   If Jay Haas, Stewart Cink, Skip Kendall or Estes emerges as the
PGA champion, Crenshaw will be almost obligated to choose him. But
if there is no shuffle in the standing, Lehman and Couples will
appear to be the captain's likely choices, if only for their
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking,'' Crenshaw said, ``for that player that has that
solid game and can hit sound shots and can play that golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples won seven matches, lost nine and halved four with the
last five Ryder Cup teams; Lehman was 3-2-2 with the last two
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman, who stopped at The Country Club recently for a practice
round, endeared himself to Crenshaw, a Ryder Cup traditionalist, by
saying some pros ``should be ashamed of'' themselves for stirring a
controversy over their request for payments by the PGA of America
that would be donated to charity.
</P>
<P>
   The European team standing, led by Colin Montgomerie, Lee
Westwood, Darren Clarke and Paul Lawrie, won't be finalized until
after next weekend's BMW International Open in Munich, Germany.
Mark James, the European captain, is expected to choose Jesper
Parnevik of Sweden and Sergio Garcia, if the 19-year-old Spanish
prodigy whose 66 led the PGA's first round stays outside the top
10.
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw will gather most of the American team at The Country
Club on Aug. 30 for what he described as a ``reconnaissance
rehearsal'' on a course that the pros haven't played since the 1988
U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to know that golf course,'' the captain said. ``It's
rustic. It's natural. It has every conceivable shot. I think it's
going to be a classic match-play course. But knowledge is going to
be a factor. It's very much up and down with New England terrain,
rocky outcroppings. It's a wonderful approach-shot course. You must
have the right club in your hand. And the greens are wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw has fond memories of the greens. Growing up in Austin,
Texas, he had always putted on Bermuda-grass greens.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went to the 1968 U.S. Junior Amateur at The Country
Club,'' he said, ``I was putting on bent-grass greens for the first
time. I thought: `This is easy. All you have to do is get the ball
on line.'''
</P>
<P>
   Easy for him as one of the best putters in golf history, but not
necessarily easy for mere mortals, even a Ryder Cup mortal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greens are beautifully shaped with some puzzling rolls in
them,'' Crenshaw said. ``They're sufficiently undulating. You've
got to know where not to put the ball. But they're beautiful
greens, a good test of putting.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Ryder Cup's match-play format, the holes will be decided
on and around what are relatively small greens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want our players to really work hard on their short games
because that's how you win holes, and when you do, you also
confidently go on to the next hole,'' Crenshaw said. ``It seems
like in the last few meetings the Europeans have done a beautiful
job of getting that ball up and down in tough situations. In order
for us to do well, we'll have to be sharper in the short game.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods won't be there on Aug. 30 because of a prior commitment,
but he plans to stop there sometime before the team officially
arrives in Boston for that week's practice rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who have not been there have a lot to learn,''
Crenshaw said. ``It's not a course you can grasp in a few days. I
want them to understand where they're going to compete. It's a very
special place that means a lot to the history of the game. I want
them to experience that and learn the course as best they can. It's
anything but a straightforward American-type course.''
</P>
<P>
   And with the money dispute still simmering, this will be
anything but a straightforward Ryder Cup match.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
