<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SANFRAN-PAPERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: SAN FRANCISCO'S MEMORABLE NEWSPAPER WARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ELEANOR RANDOLPH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shortly after a premature obituary of The San Francisco Examiner
several years ago, the paper's executive editor, Phil Bronstein,
issued staff T-shirts emblazoned with the boast ``We're Still
Here.'' Fairly soon now, by the sound of it, the T-shirts will be
stuffed into packing boxes along with old press passes and expiring
antacid tablets. San Francisco is beginning to look like another
one-newspaper town.
</P>
<P>
   Closing a daily newspaper in this country is no longer news, of
course. What makes the San Francisco story worth registering is the
flamboyant rivalry between The Examiner and The San Francisco
Chronicle, a news duel that lasted more than a century. The
competition produced some of the more colorful chapters in American
journalism and helped define the character of one of the country's
most distinctive cities.
</P>
<P>
   William Randolph Hearst's raucous news empire began when he took
over The Examiner in 1887 and proved that nothing is really new in
the news trade, even today's ``infotainment.'' The paper was a
graduation present from his father, a kind of rich kid's business
toy. Fresh from Harvard, the youth vowed to be ``alarmingly
enterprising'' and ``startlingly original.'' On these promises, at
the very least, Hearst delivered.
</P>
<P>
   When the city could not rescue five fishermen marooned on a rock
outside the entrance to San Francisco Bay in 1890, Hearst and
several staff members borrowed a tug, braved the storm, saved the
men and brayed at the competition, which still had the fivesome
languishing at sea.
</P>
<P>
   When the actress Sarah Bernhardt came to town, Hearst reporters
quickly ``escorted'' her away from members of the competing press.
Even then, The Examiner's report of her tour of an opium den in
Chinatown seemed to suffer from a faint whiff of fiction.
</P>
<P>
   The McGinty ``orphans,'' fabricated one slow news day by The
Examiner's staff, brought tears to the eyes of many readers,
including Hearst's own mother. She donated a sporting $100, a good
percentage of which ended up at the local pub where editors met to
discuss their predicament. They finally bathed a few young
volunteers and renamed them McGinty for the occasion. When the
competition found out, Hearst's newspaper, once again, made news.
</P>
<P>
   If it was not great journalism, this loose, jingoistic, carnival
of a newspaper was lucrative, at least for a while. After more
difficult times, The Examiner and The Chronicle entered a joint
operating agreement in 1965, generally a sort of two-headed cash
cow that allows struggling newspapers to share profits and business
expenses while keeping their editorial departments separate.
</P>
<P>
   The Examiner also became an afternoon paper, a news form that
became endangered in this country at about the same time television
invented the evening news.
</P>
<P>
   The Examiner steadily lost circulation even as Hearst's
grandson, William R. Hearst III, took over in the 1980s and tried
to reconstitute some of the old flair. Young Hearst hired his own
eccentrics, including Hunter Thompson, whose missives were
sometimes so mysterious that editors once suspected that his hands
had accidentally shifted a few keys on the keyboard. Thompson, for
his part, says it was ``a little bit like working in a paper on the
moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank McCulloch, a respected editor lured out of retirement to
help run the paper, recalls publishing a few important stories,
but, as he says now, ``I would have hated to run the Examiner when
I was still serious about journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   With The Examiner at 114,000 readers and The Chronicle at about
475,000, San Franciscans have made their choice. What adds to the
Hearst family drama, however, is Hearst Corp.'s decision to buy The
Chronicle and sell Hearst's flagship paper. As a business move,
this may be sound, but for newspaper buffs, it feels like Pillsbury
putting a fork in its own doughboy.
</P>
<P>
   While some readers suspected that The Chronicle would close shop
after the columnist Herb Caen died in 1997, San Franciscans have
remained fairly loyal to a paper that has specialized in provincial
news since it appeared in the city's boomtown saloons over 130
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, its fare feels easy and light, much like the city it
serves. As Martin Nolan, a Boston Globe columnist living in San
Francisco, explains, ``The late-breaking recipe takes precedence
over the Ways and Means Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle's future flavor is a mystery, except that readers
probably cannot expect an ``alarmingly original'' paper like the
first one created by Citizen Hearst.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
