<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-IRAQ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BREAKING THE IRAQ DEADLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Sunday, Aug. 15:
</P>
<P>
   When Richard Holbrooke takes over as America's representative to
the United Nations, one of the most important issues he will face
is the stalemate over Iraq. The Security Council has been in
disarray on Iraq, and Saddam Hussein has been taking advantage.
With no international arms inspectors present, he has been free to
rebuild his purchasing networks and resume production of toxic and
nuclear weapons and missiles to deliver them.
</P>
<P>
   Since December, American and British jets have launched more
than 1,000 missile strikes answering challenges to enforcement of
Iraq's two no-flight zones.
</P>
<P>
   But these attacks are no substitute for on-site arms inspection.
When the Security Council resumes discussions on Iraq next month,
Holbrooke must apply his talents to uniting its members around a
new plan for sending inspectors back with full authority to carry
out the requirements imposed on Iraq after the 1991 Persian Gulf
war.
</P>
<P>
   Recent accounts by Richard Butler, the former chief weapons
inspector, Scott Ritter, who led inspection teams inside Iraq, and
Tim Trevan, a former inspection commission spokesman, offer sharply
competing interpretations of how inspections broke down in 1997 and
1998.
</P>
<P>
   But one theme common to all three accounts is Iraq's successful
campaign to manipulate divisions on the Security Council. Those
divisions ultimately thwarted efforts to hold Iraq to its
disarmament obligations.
</P>
<P>
   The council lineup pits France, Russia and China against the
United States, Britain and a large majority of other members. All
agree that resuming inspections is necessary and all are willing to
offer Baghdad the suspension of some U.N. sanctions if it provides
substantial cooperation. But the three main holdouts would concede
too much financial relief in exchange for too little cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   The majority position is reflected in a British draft, which
Washington provisionally supports. It would create a new inspection
commission that would hand Baghdad a list of the most important
remaining disarmament requirements.
</P>
<P>
   If Iraq readmitted inspectors and complied with these
requirements, export sanctions would be suspended for four months,
with the revenues going into an internationally supervised account.
If Iraq kept cooperating, the suspensions would continue. If it
cheated, sanctions would be reimposed.
</P>
<P>
   Washington would prefer that no sanctions relief be granted
until Iraq had met all of its obligations in full and Saddam
Hussein was out of power. But the White House has rightly been
willing to compromise to rebuild international unity. France is
demanding a less onerous list of initial disarmament tasks, wider
sanctions relief and looser controls over Iraqi revenues.
Washington must insist on a strict task list and financial
controls.
</P>
<P>
   Passing a new U.N. resolution will not guarantee that Iraq will
readmit inspectors or provide consistent cooperation. Saddam
Hussein has a long record of defiance. But even he has generally
shied away from confronting a united Security Council.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990814.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7348 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-RACISM-NYT &LR;      08-14 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-RACISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE HATEFUL AGENDA OF IGNORANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Sunday, Aug. 15:
</P>
<P>
   Buford Furrow Jr., the man who attacked a Jewish community
center in Los Angeles last Tuesday, is something of a throwback,
even among white supremacists. The trajectory of his simple,
malevolent faith is expressed in two photographs, one taken of him
wearing an Aryan Nations uniform in northern Idaho, the other of
him wearing police handcuffs in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   It is doubtful that Furrow would have prospered as a campus
recruiter for Aryan Nations. It is also unlikely that he could have
done much to further the supremacist movement's growing presence on
the Internet, except, of course, as hero and, if convicted and
sentenced to death for the murder of Joseph Ileto, as martyr.
</P>
<P>
   Furrow embodies the attributes, amounting nearly to stereotype,
that have made it all too tempting to regard white supremacy as a
fading, peripheral irruption within normal society.
</P>
<P>
   But not Benjamin Smith. He killed himself after wounding several
people and murdering two in a series of racially motivated attacks
in Illinois and Indiana in early July. He was 21 and from a
prosperous family, but he was also a frenetic college recruiter for
the white supremacist World Church of the Creator.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was the kind of young man who tried to twist his message
to conform to _ or lie concealed within _ the canons of ordinary
society. He never lived in a supremacist enclave or wore an Aryan
Nations uniform. Furrow, an unpersuasive figure, was dangerous to
himself and his immediate victims. Smith was dangerous in a far
more insidious way.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has sampled the hate sites on the Web cannot help but
notice a striking thing. The more extreme the doctrine, the firmer
its reliance on what passes for logic and historical evidence.
</P>
<P>
   It is as though, recognizing the absurdity of their racist and
inherently violent conclusions, men like Smith insist upon the
logical, evidentiary steps by which they arrive at them. The utmost
that white supremacists achieve in argument is the appearance of
plausibility, and this is achieved only on the premise of the
reader's ignorance. In their literature, false notions of evolution
coexist with false ideas of revelation. Invented histories support
insupportable conceptions of culture.
</P>
<P>
   But for too many people, now as always, and especially for the
young, plausibility is often more compelling than fact, the
explanatory power of a sinister theory more satisfying than the
circumstances of living in a complex, rapidly shifting world.
</P>
<P>
   The only real argument the white supremacists make is at the
point of a gun. Speech, of their kind, is scarcely separable from
violence, which leaves us with the conundrum of distinguishing what
the American Civil Liberties Union calls ``abstract beliefs'' and
their legitimate expression, which deserve protection, from the
actual crimes they sometimes generate.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the ideas behind these shootings sound hateful to any
reasonable person. But it is more dangerous to shut them out _ to
ignore them, pretend they do not exist, or prosecute the holding or
articulation of such beliefs. Hateful as it is, the sound of such
ideas in the air is the mark of this democracy's vigilance and
tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   There will always be racists and supremacists of one kind or
another among us. They are the legacy of a violent history from
which we have only recently, in this century, begun to think of
absolving ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Their methods and tools will change, as will the circumstances
that motivate them, but their arguments will always be the same. It
does not take logicians or historians or anthropologists to confute
them. One only needs to know that any argument, any solicitation,
that ends in division, exclusion and hatred is by its nature evil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 1723EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
