u a BC-NY-COL-ISLAND-NYT &LR;      08-14 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-ISLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A JOURNEY TO AN ISLAND THAT FEELS FAR AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FISHERS ISLAND, N.Y. _ Residents of this tiny squiggle of land
three miles off the Connecticut coast could not feel more
disconnected from their local government. Then again, isolation is
what brought them here in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The government is the town of Southold, way down on the North
Fork of Long Island. It's a 12-mile trip by water. But to get back
and forth, you have to ride two ferries, stopping in New London,
Conn., to change boats. The trip takes about four hours each way.
Few people ever bother.
</P>
<P>
   One day every August, though _ out of guilt or curiosity or
boredom, or simply because someone started doing it decades ago and
no one has ever stopped _ politicians and bureaucrats and a handful
of other dignitaries from Southold, Suffolk County and New York
state pile into a chartered ferry and cruise over here for a peek,
to take care of a little business and, most thoughtful of all, to
give island gadflies and busybodies who've been saving up a year's
worth of gripes a chance to vent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to touch the people,'' said Alice Hussie, a
councilwoman making the trip the other day for the eighth time.
</P>
<P>
   Just before noon, about 100 name-tagged officials in Bermuda
shorts and windbreakers stepped off the ferry. A dozen residents
were waiting to whisk the visiting horde off for a spin around the
island.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Hunt, president of the island's civic association, drove
off with the town engineer, eager to point out roads that needed
reflectors, trees that needed trimming and streets that could use
no-parking signs.
</P>
<P>
   Any tour leads from the old fort on the west end, where the
year-rounders live and work, to the eastern end of the island, a
moneyed paradise of mansions invisible even from the private road
and country clubs that are accepting no new members.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the two ends of the island get along quite well _ a
good thing, since they depend on each other so heavily. The 275
year-rounders _ lobstermen, telephone workers, caretakers and
schoolteachers _ do all the work, volunteering in the fire
department and taking turns on the Sea Stretcher, which roars over
to the hospital in New London in 17 minutes flat.
</P>
<P>
   The 3,000 or 4,000 summer people _ folks with nicknames like
Twig and Bobsie, last names like DuPont and Luce _ hold
fund-raisers, sit on boards and write checks. In the late 1980s,
when the year-round population was dropping like a yacht anchor,
threatening the labor pool that keeps the golf greens mowed and the
ferries running, they underwrote the construction of affordable
housing for 12 year-round families.
</P>
<P>
   Lately they've been paying for a campaign to protect the
depleted lobster stocks around Fishers Island from big fishing
outfits based in Montauk and Connecticut. The eight lobstermen left
here say they are being squeezed out of the business, and most are
thinking about moving away. But with their families and employees,
they account for a tenth of the island's year-rounders and about a
fourth of the fire department.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut and New York fought over Fishers Island for 200
years before a committee representing both states awarded it to New
York in 1879. But now neither state seems to show much interest.
``Last year the town board did a resolution to do everything they
can to help us,'' said Chris Edwards, a lobsterman, summer-home
caretaker, firefighter and school-board member. ``They haven't done
anything since.''
</P>
<P>
   On this year's Town Fathers Day, as Fishrs Islanders call the
yearly rite, the Southold council had some serious business to
attend to: interviewing constables. The part-time job pays around
$12,000 and involves little more than responding to false burglar
alarms. Two state troopers posted on the island during the summer
take care of real crime, like speeding.
</P>
<P>
   After a lunch of white-bread sandwiches in the gym of the
island's K-12 school, where the graduating class this year was
three students, everyone settled in for the meeting. As usual, the
visitors outnumbered the islanders by more than three to one. The
visitors introduced themselves, as did the island residents. The
Southold town supervisor, Jean Cochran, announced that she planned
to include a third constable in next year's budget.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was nearly 3 p.m. _ time to catch the ferry home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
