<HEADLINE>
DUCKS WILL DARKEN THE SKY THIS FALL
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By NELSON BRYANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A record number of ducks will be flying south this fall,
according to Ducks Unlimited and the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service.
</P>
<P>
   The service began surveying breeding duck populations in North
America in 1955. This year, the service estimates that there were
43.8 million ducks in the survey area. That was the highest count
since the survey's start _ 12 percent more than last year, and 34
percent higher than average.
</P>
<P>
   These annual surveys, which take place in May, have
traditionally covered the north-central United States, from,
roughly, the Dakotas and Montana up through Canada's prairie
provinces, Saskatchewan, Alberta and Manitoba, an area in which
most North American ducks breed. Since 1995, the survey has also
included eastern Canada and portions of the northeastern United
States. Ducks Unlimited, a private, nonprofit waterfowl
conservation organization founded in 1937, says that hunters,
wildlife watchers and conservationists in North America ``should
expect a spectacular fall flight,'' perhaps the largest in more
than 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   The key to this happy prospect is that much wetland and pothole
breeding habitat in this country and Canada was in good or
excellent shape this spring and early summer when the birds were
nesting. Steve Adair, Ducks Unlimited's manager of habitat
development, notes that the Wildlife Service also counts the number
of ponds _ many of which dry up during drought _ in the survey
area; the count this year was 6.7 million. Last year it was 4.6
million.
</P>
<P>
   Mallards, by far the continent's most common duck, increased 15
percent since the 1998 survey, to more than 11 million birds.
Green-winged teal were up 35 percent, to 2.8 million, and
blue-winged teal went to 7.2 million from 6.4 million. Both species
of these little, fast-flying birds are at record highs. Even scaup
and pintails, species that have been in trouble the past decade,
showed increases of 27 and 21 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Gadwalls and redheads were exceptions to this success story,
down 14 and 3 percent, respectively, and another species, the black
duck, continued its decline.
</P>
<P>
   Held in high esteem by New England gunners for its sagacity and
its edibility, the black duck remains in trouble, its populations
down 28 percent from 1998. Waterfowl biologists speculate that the
reason is that the mallards are outcompeting the black ducks for
habitat and also hybridizing with them. On the Eastern seaboard,
where black ducks seem to be holding their own, New Brunswick is
the species' prime breeding area. It is estimated that the breeding
populations of all ducks that visit the northeastern United States
are up by 5 percent, Adair said.
</P>
<P>
   Adair also noted that Atlantic populations of migratory Canada
geese have rebounded this year, up 84 percent over last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ducks Unlimited's executive vice president, Matt Connolly, who
is retiring this summer, is leaving in a blaze of glory. In its
fiscal year 1999, which ended last February, the organization
raised over $118 million, more than any other year in its history,
and its membership increased 30,000 to more than 700,000.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest and most influential wetlands and waterfowl
conservation organization, Ducks Unlimited protected and restored
more than 300,000 acres of wildlife habitat in the United States
alone during fiscal year 1999. Adding land conserved by its sister
organizations in Canada and Mexico, the total area conserved during
that period was nearly 500,000 acres. Since Ducks Unlimited's
inception, it has raised more than $1.2 billion to conserve some
8.8 million acres in North America.
</P>
<P>
   As one might expect, most of the organization's members are duck
hunters. It is with both ducks and hunters in mind that the group
sponsored three retriever training clinics in New England this
summer. One remains: Aug. 28-29 at the Nod Brook Wildlife
Management Area in Simsbury, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The clinics include a Saturday training procedure seminar ($60)
and a hands-on Sunday session ($125) open to owners of retrievers
six months or more old. Only 12 dogs will be allowed to attend. For
reservations, call Craig Ferris at (203) 426-2466.
</P>
<P>
   A good dog can make the difference between success and failure
when waterfowling, finding downed birds in thick cover or
retrieving those that fall far out on lake or bay when the wind is
offshore. Even with a well-trained retriever, a hunter will not
recover all the birds he shoots, but a dog sharply reduces such
losses.
</P>
<P>
   And there's a bonus for the waterfowler who uses a dog: the
presence of a companion always eager to shiver beside you in a
wind-ripped blind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
