<P>
   CAR-NASCAR-SERIES _ ATLANTA _ NASCAR SERIES/LIFE AFTER THE FAST
LANE: When Winston Cup champion Jeff Gordon pocketed more than $11
million at NASCAR's awards banquet in New York last December, it
spoke volumes about the sport's lucrative rise into the world of
big business. But it hasn't always been that way. In the first of a
series of articles, staff writer Al Levine examines the impact that
NASCAR careers had on six drivers _ all with Georgia connections _
who raced in every decade since the 1940s. THE 1940s: Frank Mundy,
81, participated in the first meeting between drivers that formed
NASCAR in the late 1940s. He later parlayed his NASCAR background
and connections into a financially successful real estate and
business career. He and his wife are living the good life in
Atlanta. (Levine, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 50. WITH PHOTO.
MOVED.
