<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFL-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETWEEN DRAFT AND CAMP, A ROOKIE HAS A CHANGE OF HEART
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The strange story of defensive lineman Dimitrius Underwood took
an odd turn after he signed his five-year, $5.3 million contract
with the Minnesota Vikings on Aug. 1. At that time, Underwood was a
smiling, proud man who showed no indication that he was having
second thoughts about playing professional football.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't said exactly what happened, but something changed in
the mind of the former Michigan State star that would soon result
in a nearly two-week drama.
</P>
<P>
   The day after he signed his contract Underwood went to his first
Vikings practice. He was out of shape and was manhandled in his
first encounter with the team's outstanding offensive line. The
next day he left camp, and the Vikings did not hear from him for
almost a week.
</P>
<P>
   The speculation among National Football League executives is
that Underwood felt he was too physically overmatched to play in
the pros. But Underwood later explained his absence by saying he
was having a crisis of conscience and was uncertain if he could
balance football with his religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Underwood was the 29th pick in the April 16 draft. While it is
now in vogue to say that the Vikings should have drafted a
different player, six teams contacted last week said they had
Underwood rated approximately where the Vikings selected him.
</P>
<P>
   Although Underwood's decision to leave camp took the team by
surprise, he had not had a smooth transition into professional
football. Between the draft and the start of Vikings camp on Aug.
2, Underwood fired two agents, told the Vikings he needed to miss a
minicamp because of school obligations, which they said turned out
not to be true, missed a flight to his introductory news conference
and then missed three days of another minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the Vikings decided they had had enough. Underwood has
agreed to return his $543,562 signing bonus, and once he does the
Vikings will officially release him.
</P>
<P>
   As Minnesota Coach Dennis Green said, Underwood is not the first
player to walk out of camp and he won't be the last. Several years
ago an Oakland Raiders rookie, on his first day of camp, got into a
fight with another player and then left the team. Since 1994, the
Jets have watched a handful of veteran players quit during training
camp, including tight end Johnny Mitchell and offensive lineman
Erik Norgard this month.
</P>
<P>
   Rookies, naturally, have the most difficult time adjusting to
the rigors of the NFL, on and off the field. Ricky Williams, the
New Orleans Saints rookie running back, recently expressed dismay
at how some players are in professional football only for the money
and how rude some fans are when asking for autographs. Such
revelations threw Williams into a funk last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people just throw stuff in your face and give you a pen
and don't say `please' and `thank you,''' Williams said. ``It makes
you feel that you are not a person, you're just something to sign
an autograph. That's kind of tough to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Capers Changes Defense
</P>
<P>
   The most impressive off-season pickup for the Jacksonville
Jaguars wasn't a player, it was defensive coordinator Dom Capers,
who has changed the makeup of the team's defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars have one of the most explosive offenses in the
league, and if they can improve a defense that ranked 25th in the
league last season they will be one of the top teams in the
American Football Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Capers, the former head coach of the Carolina Panthers, is
trying to upgrade the defense by installing a more aggressive
zone-blitz attack along the lines of the one he directed so
successfully with the Pittsburgh Steelers in the early 1990s. The
players are so impressed with Capers that they look at him as a
sort of co-head coach. He runs the defense and head coach Tom
Coughlin runs the offense.
</P>
<P>
   The secondary centers around the newly acquired safety Carnell
Lake, who left the Steelers for a four-year, $18 million contract
with the Jaguars. Lake, who starred under Capers and his
predecessors in Pittsburgh, is one of the best blitzers in the
league and should continue to do well with the Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   Problems Down Under
</P>
<P>
   While the Denver Broncos and the San Diego Chargers were putting
on a solid performance in the American Bowl in Australia last week,
league officials were busy putting out several small fires behind
the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   First, the league does not allow its teams to put gambling
advertisements in stadiums. But the NFL does not control stadiums
in Australia and there was a gambling ad inside the stadium before
the Broncos-Chargers game. The NFL was able to intervene and remove
the advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was another dispute between the NFL and Experimental
and Applied Sciences, the Colorado firm that makes nutritional
supplements. Last year the league's drug adviser on steroids, Dr.
John Lombardo, warned each team about the use of Andro-6, an EAS
product that is said to boost testosterone levels and increase
strength and muscle mass. Use of the product put players at risk
for failing drug tests, Lombardo wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Broncos players use EAS products and endorse the
company. When EAS attempted to get both their personnel and
promotional products into the Denver locker room in Australia, the
NFL kept both out.
</P>
<P>
   There are sure to be other disagreements. EAS considers the
Broncos some of their most valuable clients, while the NFL does not
like the company or its products.
</P>
<P>
   Caution on Sanders
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Deion Sanders could return from his toe surgery in
two weeks. The team will approach his situation cautiously and
probably not play Sanders until the last preseason game on Sept. 2
against Jacksonville. ... Quarterback Akili Smith and the
Cincinnati Bengals remain miles apart in their contract
negotiations. Smith could miss at least another week and probably
longer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
