u s BC-BBO-COMPLETE-KEOUGH     08-14 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-COMPLETE-KEOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEOUGH RECALLS HOW MARTIN DEPENDED ON THE A'S STARTERS  
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Also see BBO-COMPLETE-GAMES) (ko) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Billy Martin had one simple instruction for his starting
pitchers when he managed the Oakland Athletics in the first three
seasons of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to tell us don't even look at the bullpen; there won't
be anyone down there,'' Matt Keough said, recalling those years
with some fondness. ``Billy's whole philosophy was, why should I
bring in someone from the bullpen, lefty or righty, when they're
not as good as the guys I have on the mound now?''
</P>
<P>
   The Oakland starters, young and full of pride, Keough said,
pitched 94 complete games in 1980 and 60 in the strike-interrupted
1981 season. Just about every member of Martin's starting rotation
wound up injured, and he was widely blamed for overusing the
pitchers. But Keough offered a different view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody looks at it as negative,'' he said of the multitude
of complete games, ``but Billy didn't get us hurt. I don't think
the complete games caused the injuries, the way we were used.''
</P>
<P>
   But _ and there was a big but _ Keough added: ``After we got
hurt, Billy convinced us to keep pitching. Our egos bought into
it.''
</P>
<P>
   And on second thought, he said, it was possible that Rick
Langford, who led the team with 28 complete games in 1980 and 18 in
'81, suffered his elbow problem because of all of the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick was a sliderball pitcher,'' Keough said. ``I'm sure the
wear and tear of throwing a lot of sliders and sinkers would have
been difficult for him. He pitched a lot toward the end of that
season to try to win 20.''
</P>
<P>
   Langford won 19 games in 1980 and then faded, making it through
the next two seasons before injury sent him into a career-ending
spiral. Mike Norris, who Keough said had shoulder and elbow
problems that preceded Martin, pitched two more seasons after he
worked through 36 completes games in 1980-81.
</P>
<P>
   ``People make a lot out of all the complete games, but we kept
our pitch count low,'' said Keough, who tore the labrum in his
right shoulder when he slipped on a muddy mound in Baltimore in
1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also had a lot of off days because we had a lot of
doubleheaders on Sunday. Billy never skipped the fifth starter, so
it would be common for us to pitch on four days' rest and sometimes
five and even six.''
</P>
<P>
   But Keough also recalled that the starters pitched four complete
14-inning games in 1980 and were used in other ways, too, relief
appearances and assorted extracurricular activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pitched a 14-inning complete game in Toronto,'' Keough said,
``and two days later Billy wanted to know if I could pitch to a
group of right-handers instead of throwing on the side.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 14-inning game, he also recalled: ``Billy never asked me
after the 11th how I was. He knew that after 11 I wasn't going to
give it up. I was going to win or lose. I won.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
