<SLUG> BC-YACHT-U.S.-TEAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S CUP TEAM APPEARS TO BE OVERCOMING SLOW START 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ It was all-white polo shirts and preppy faces
here Friday when the Young America team announced its official
challenge team for the 1999-2000 America's Cup trials. The
gathering on the rolling lawn of the New York Yacht Club annex
looked more like a crisp advertisement for Helly Hansen, the team's
apparel sponsor, than a sweaty gathering of sports jocks. But make
no mistake, America's Cup crews have their combative side, too.
</P>
<P>
   Take Ed Baird, skipper for the New York Yacht Club's entry,
Young America. ``We've started calling him Ward Cleaver, after the
'50 TV dad,'' Jerry Kirby, the bowman on Young America, said.
``Ed's the nicest guy on the planet. He's truly a super-dad with
his little kids, and he really cares about what the old lady on the
street thinks. But once you take the dock lines off, Ward Cleaver
disappears, and Ed becomes the Terminator.''
</P>
<P>
   It may seem like a harsh description of a balding, 41-year-old
yacht racer with a quiet voice and ready smile. But the competitive
niche in his personality makes him unexpectedly aggressive on the
race course.
</P>
<P>
   He was not able to find much time last year to compete on the
world match-racing circuit. But it did not seem to matter. Baird
came up with an impressive second-place finish last month at the
Swedish Cup match-race series in Marstrand, Sweden, with several
members of the Young America team, including the highly competent
Kirby, on board the 37-foot sloop with him. Finishing first was
Peter Gilmour of Australia, the No. 1-ranked match racer in the
world and skipper of Japan's America's Cup challenge entry. But the
New York Yacht Club team's real coup in Sweden was beating Russell
Coutts, the New Zealand sailor whose team beat Dennis Conner, 5-1,
in the 1995 America's Cup match off San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a very happy position right now,'' Baird said last
week. ``We have two new boats that are ready to hatch, and it's
very exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   For a time, it seemed that New York was not moving forward at
all. A money crunch last winter forced Young America officials to
decide in favor of technology over manpower. It had lost out on a
$2.5-million sponsorship deal with the Fox Sports Network that took
a sizable chunk out of the team's proposed $40-million budget. To
make it worse, other corporate donations seemed slow to surface.
</P>
<P>
   Laying off much of its crew for the spring and summer, the
yachting syndicate focused its limited resources on technology. It
appears now that the early disjointed effort may be coming
together. More than 40 scale-model sailboats _ each one-third of an
actual 75-foot cup yacht's actual size _ have been built for
testing. And one of the top naval architecture firms in the
business, Farr Yacht Design Ltd. of Annapolis, Md., is eager to
prove that its boat can win the America's Cup as it has almost
every grand prix event in international racing.
</P>
<P>
   Kirby, a three-time cup veteran, decided on the Young America
team after being wooed by other United States syndicates. But when
he decided on New York, he decided big: he came along with four
other seasoned America's Cup sailors, all of whom were on Bill
Koch's America3 team when it successfully defended the cup off San
Diego in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York made a really good decision because the most
important dollars you spend are in design,'' the 43-year-old Kirby
said. ``We would have been burning really important dollars if we
had spent it to keep on crew this last year. Money for rigs, boat
appendages and sails far outweigh any practice time this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Even New York's adversaries are noticing. ``They have the
ingredients to be dominant,'' Ken Read, the helmsman for Conner's
one-boat America's Cup program, said. ``There's no doubt about
that. You'd be naive to say that Young America doesn't have the
upper hand right out of the box. But can they put all of the
ingredients in the right order?''
</P>
<P>
   Read says the answers ought to be readily apparent in the
beginning of the Louis Vuitton Cup, the four-month challengers'
trial series that begins Oct. 18 in Auckland, New Zealand. ``It
will be apparent come the first beat of the first race,'' Read
said. ``I think a lot is told in a short time. Boat speed rules.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
