<HEADLINE>
ROBERT JONES, 89, INNOVATOR IN JET-WING DESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Miss., Tenn.)  (lb) 
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert T. Jones, an innovator in aircraft design at NASA who
played an important role in developing the high-speed swept wing,
died on Wednesday at his home in Los Altos Hills, Calif. He was 89.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, as the designers of combat aircraft sought
ever-greater speeds, German manufacturers such as the Messerschmitt
and Junkers companies developed and built the first jet fighters
and bombers with swept wings. The swept-wing Me 262 was the first
jet fighter to fly in combat.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics, the
predecessor of the National Aeronautics and Space Administration,
later said the design agency had failed to develop jet engines or
swept wings at a time when Germany was the clear leader in
high-speed aircraft design.
</P>
<P>
   After the war the United States rushed to catch up, and Jones
played a crucial role.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement on Thursday, William Berry, deputy director of
NASA's Ames Research Center at Moffett Field, Calif., described
Jones as ``one of the world's most highly acclaimed aeronautical
engineers.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides developing swept wings to reduce the drag imposed on
aircraft flying faster than the speed of sound, Jones' innovations
included a wing designed for oblique flight, with one side swept
forward and the other backward. It was believed that a supersonic
transport plane based on the peculiar-looking design would be
particularly efficient, and a large model was successfully tested
five years ago, but so far the design has not caught on.
</P>
<P>
   Jones never obtained a bachelor's degree, but his college
training at Catholic University in Washington included a course by
Max Munk, a prominent German aerodynamicist.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Jones retired from NASA in 1981 he had acquired a
host of awards and honors, including an honorary doctorate from the
University of Colorado. In 1973 he was elected to the National
Academy of Engineering, and in 1981 he was elected to the National
Academy of Sciences. In the same year he was presented with the
President's Award for Distinguished Federal Civilian Service. He
also received the Smithsonian Institution's Langley Award, which is
bestowed only on leading aeronautical pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is survived by his wife, Megan More of Los Altos Hills;
two daughters, Harriet Jones of Berkeley, Calif., and Patricia
Jones of San Diego; and four sons, David of Corinth, Miss., Edward
of Murfreesboro, Tenn., and Gregory and John, both of Los Altos.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 1731EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990814.0166 </DOCNO>
