</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-KLEILER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANK KLEILER, 85, FORMER DEPUTY ASSISTANT SECRETARY OF LABOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Mass. Wis.)  (mk) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frank Kleiler, a retired deputy assistant secretary of labor and
a former executive secretary of the National Labor Relations Board,
died on Aug. 8 at a nursing home in Silver Spring, Md., where he
lived. He was 85.
</P>
<P>
   In the Johnson and Nixon administrations, Kleiler served as
chairman of a task force within the Department of Labor that
drafted proposed legislation resulting in the Employment Retirement
Income Security Act. He also administered major portions of the
Labor-Management Reporting and Disclosure Act and the Welfare and
Pension Plans Disclosure Act.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in his career, Kleiler played a small role in President
Truman's unsuccessful effort, during a labor dispute in the early
1950s, to nationalize the steel industry, as well as in federal
efforts to block Major League Baseball players from unionizing in
the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   Kleiler was born April 17, 1914, in Green Bay, Wis., and grew up
in Shorewood, a suburb of Milwaukee. He graduated from Antioch
College in Yellow Springs, Ohio. Moving to Washington after
college, he was a reporter for The Evening Star. A year later, he
moved to Boston to work for The Boston Herald.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to Washington in 1937, working for the National
Mediation Board, and, in 1939, he was transferred to the National
Labor Relations Board. Over the years, he worked in several cities
for the board.
</P>
<P>
   During the Korean War, he worked for the Wage Stabilization
Board, but he returned to the Labor Department in 1953. He became a
deputy assistant secretary in 1969, and stayed in that post until
1973, receiving the department's distinguished career service
award.
</P>
<P>
   In retirement, he worked with a Chicago publisher on employment
benefits plans. In 1974 and 1975, he led a team from the Federal
Mediation and Conciliation Service to supervise tribal elections on
the Ogalalla Sioux Indian Reservation at Pine Ridge, S.D. He also
wrote a book, ``Can We Afford Early Retirement?'' (Johns Hopkins
University Press, 1978).
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Frances, died in 1982. He is survived by two sons,
David of Brookline, Mass., and James of Kensington, Md., and two
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 1731EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990814.0167 </DOCNO>
