<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-YOUTH-MARCH-645&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARLEM RALLY PLANNED, DESPITE LAST YEAR'S MELEE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The organizers of last year's Million Youth March,
which ended in a violent confrontation with the police, are
planning a similar event next month and are again encountering
resistance from city officials.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Police Department's legal affairs office are
negotiating with organizers on the location, security and
logistical details for the event, which the organizers want to hold
on Sept. 4 on Malcolm X Boulevard in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   However, the chief organizer, Khalid Abdul Muhammad, warned:
``We will march with or without a permit, and black youth will come
from throughout the country. And if they thought it was a volatile
situation with a permit, it would be much more dangerous without
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's event was a rally rather than a march, and was held
along six blocks of Malcolm X Boulevard. It drew about 6,000
participants, according to police estimates. For this year's event,
Muhammad is seeking march and rally permits, and has announced
plans to march down Malcolm X Boulevard to a rallying area at 125th
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the police shut down the No. 2 subway line and had
more than 1,600 officers in attendance and another 1,600 in
reserve, including dozens on horseback.
</P>
<P>
   As police officers in riot helmets began to inch toward the
stage near the rally's scheduled 4 p.m. conclusion, Muhammad told
participants that they should use force to defend themselves from
any police attack. At 4:05 p.m., as Muhammad asked participants to
go home peacefully and uttered the last words of his speech, metal
folding chairs were hurled at officers.
</P>
<P>
   A melee followed in which at least 30 people were injured,
including 16 police officers. Six people were charged with
attempted assault and reckless endangerment.
</P>
<P>
   Given what happened last year, civic leaders from Community
Board No. 10 in Harlem have refused to support Muhammad's
applications for permits.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Gleaton, the board's president, said on Friday that last
year's event ``really left a bad taste in our mouths.'' He added:
``There is a general consensus that an event like this would be
best held in a better spot. It is not about whether we agree with
their views, but we just felt it should not take place in the
middle of Harlem.''
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad, a former senior official in the Nation of Islam, said
he hoped an agreement could be worked out with city officials. But
if it cannot, he said, his first step would be to file suit in
federal court.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Police Commissioner Howard Safir said, ``We will work
with the organizers and we will hold them to any permit
requirements and city ordinances.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, after the city administration refused to grant a
permit for the rally in Harlem, organizers obtained a U.S. District
Court order forcing the city to let them hold the event.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview on Friday from St. Louis, where he was
looking for participants, Muhammad said he planned to give a speech
at the rally attacking city officials, the Police Department, Jews
and many of the city's black civic and political leaders. He also
said he planned to call on black city residents to take up arms and
form militias to protect themselves from the police.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad was dismissed as a spokesman for the Nation of Islam in
1994 after a speech in which he referred to Jews as
`'bloodsuckers'' and made other inflammatory remarks against Roman
Catholics, whites and homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   He later founded the New Black Muslim Movement and the New Black
Panther Party, both based in New York. It is unclear how large
Muhammad's following is and whether he can deliver the 50,000
participants he has promised.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad is billing this year's event as a show of strength and
unity among black teen-agers from across the country, patterned on
the 1995 Million Man March on Washington.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Virginia Fields, the Manhattan borough president, said on Friday
of plans for the event: ``Instead of speaking about hate, we as a
city should be speaking about healing and working together. Instead
of speaking about taking up arms, we should focus on getting as
many guns as possible off the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Foxman, the national president of the Anti-Defamation
League, said on Friday that he supported Muhammad's right to march,
but that he hoped Muhammad would find little public support. ``This
time, the leadership has said no, the community has said no, and if
nobody goes, it is nothing, except a bigot standing alone,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhood leaders also expressed concern about police
tactics, fearing that the event could again shut down Harlem,
hurting commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Eric Adams, the president of 100 Blacks in Law Enforcement
Who Care, a group that was critical of the police tactics in last
year's rally, said on Friday that he hoped the city would learn
from its mistakes. He said the police response was too large and
aggressive, adding that he believed, from talking to senior police
commanders, that it was motivated more by politics than safety
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the tendency of reshooting ourselves in the foot, as
if losing a toe the first time was not enough,'' Adams added. ``I
am hoping that better minds will prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, the executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, said on Friday it was unlikely that opposition
would prevent the event from being held. ``The fact that people
fear the protesters' rhetoric or potential misconduct of the Police
Department does not warrant the suspension of the First
Amendment,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 1747EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990814.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7366 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-RUTGERS-MCMAHON-N     08-14 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-RUTGERS-MCMAHON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RUTGERS, A QUARTERBACK WHO WANTS TO LIVE IT UP
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PISCATAWAY, N.J. _ Mike McMahon tells you that he does not want
to be a vocal leader, that he just wants to have fun. Looking at
how casually he works his way through the waves of cameras and
reporters, you believe him.
</P>
<P>
   But the way McMahon pictures himself is not the same way the
Rutgers Scarlet Knights see him. They are counting on the
quarterback to emerge this season as one of the leaders who will
carry Rutgers to an elusive bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his leadership, the junior recounted a story about
gathering teammates for a trip to the beach, which fits with the
shell necklaces he wears over his jersey. And he maintained that
fun should be an objective for Rutgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football is a game,'' McMahon said as the Knights went through
an interview session before beginning their first official practice
of the season. ``If you aren't having fun, why are you playing it?
I want to go out there, improve a little bit more and bring home
the bowl championship this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are goals that would fit in for the Scarlet Knights. After
being pushed into the lineup midway through his freshman year, an
0-11 season, McMahon guided Rutgers to a 5-6 record last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't believe in us still,'' McMahon said.
``They said that our schedule was easy last year. Compared to this
year, it was a lot easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely a crossroads. We showed people. We went 5-6
last year and they say we're a program just ready to turn the
corner. Well, if we don't turn that corner, we're back to where the
0-11 team was. So I think, definitely, this is a big year for us.
We have to make something happen.''
</P>
<P>
   McMahon is a big part of that. He is ranked the eighth-best
underclass quarterback in the nation by one magazine and named an
honorable mention all-American by another.
</P>
<P>
   When told about the accolades, McMahon shrugged and searched for
a response.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, all-American; you sure about that?'' he said.
``Whatever. I'd rather get the bowl championship. That would mean
so much more to the university. That's what I came in here to do,
to turn this program around.''
</P>
<P>
   His performance may have played a part in Rutgers' recruiting,
too, with the school getting an oral commitment from the first
quarterback they offered a scholarship to, Chris Dapolito, a highly
rated quarterback from Matawan (N.J.) High School.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon spent extra time in the film room this spring and
summer, time that he hopes will pay even more dividends this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always had a strong arm,'' said Walter King, a junior wide
receiver who sat out last season with a back injury. ``He had that
big-play capability. But now he has it all put together. Now he
knows the plays; now he knows the receivers to go to. I think most
of all his confidence level is up. That's the main thing. I think
the way he carries himself, you can just tell.''
</P>
<P>
   McMahon has already carved a niche in the Rutgers record book,
ranking in the top 10 in school history in yardage, touchdowns and
completions. But Rutgers needs not only numbers, but also someone
to help lift it through a harsh schedule, which begins at
California on Sept. 4.
</P>
<P>
   What he went through as a freshman is in the past now, but not
forgotten. McMahon will be throwing to an inexperienced receiving
corp that may include a pair of freshmen, Antoine Lovelace and
Aaron Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's hard to come in as a freshman,'' McMahon said. ``I
had a tough time. I remember one night crying to go home. No matter
how many all-star games you play in, people say freshmen come in
cocky, but you feel intimidated. With the receivers coming in, I
really wanted to welcome them in, get them used to everything, and
let them know that people are here for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
