<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7369 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ATL-SKULSREOPEN15-COX     08-14 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-SKULSREOPEN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two schools, rocked by shootings, share similarities as new
academic year starts
 &HT;    By Leon Stafford
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You'll have to look long and hard to find any evidence
of the shootings almost four months ago at Heritage High School in
Rockdale County, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The holes left by bullets fired from the .22-caliber rifle
accused gunman Anthony ``T.J.'' Solomon used to shoot six of his
classmates May 20 are no longer visible in the pillars in the
school's commons area, as students discovered when they returned to
school last Wednesday. They have been filled.
</P>
<P>
   The metal frame near the door of the school's south entrance
also has been repaired. It was struck by a bullet police said
Solomon fired from a .357 magnum at fellow student Brandon
Mitchell, who pursued him after the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Half a continent away at Columbine High School in Littleton,
Colo., the scene of the nation's deadliest school shooting can't be
viewed at all. At the request of the families of the 13 people
killed by Columbine students Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold, the
library at the school has been sealed off and will not be available
for use when students return to school Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how long we will keep it that way,'' said
Marilyn Saltzman, manager of community services for the Jefferson
County, Colo., school district. Saltzman said the library will be
relocated to two doublewide trailers. ``That is something we are
still trying to work out.''
</P>
<P>
   The measures are part of the recovery of the two schools, thrust
into the national spotlight last spring when disturbed students
opened fire on their classmates.
</P>
<P>
   Though Columbine's tragedy was far larger in scope than Heritage
High's, the schools and school systems share many similiarities as
they begin the 1999-2000 school year. Both will:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Require students to carry photo identification cards.
Jefferson County has introduced the photo IDs in response to the
shooting at Columbine. Rockdale County Schools had instituted the
photo ID requirement prior to the Columbine shooting, though at the
time their main purpose was for use in checking out library books
and purchasing school lunches.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Have psychologists in the schools to counsel students.
Columbine had six following last year's shootings, while Heritage
will have its first this year.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Place resource officers in their middle schools. In the past,
the law enforcement officers have only been assigned to the high
schools. The change is a direct result of the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restrict visitor access to one door. This is new for Jefferson
County schools, but Rockdale schools have had such a policy for
years.
</P>
<P>
   How residents in the two communities responded to the shootings
was dictated by the magnitude of the violence.
</P>
<P>
   In Jefferson County, residents created new programs aimed at
youth, while numerous churches reached out to those needing
spiritual guidance. Students and adults lobbied for stricter gun
controls. In Rockdale, the only visible outreach was through a
handful of churches.
</P>
<P>
   Heritage Principal Lowell Biddy said the reason is simple:
Police in Rockdale were able to wrap up their investigation quickly
and arrest Solomon; and Heritage was the site of summer school, so
it has been continuously in use by students since the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students have already been in it after the shooting,'' Biddy
said. ``It has not caused a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbine students attended classes at a neighboring high
school, where they ended their school year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the differences, students from both schools have one
thing in common: They did not want to give up on their schools.
</P>
<P>
   Columbine student Rusty McPhail, 16, spent his summer at the
Ascot Center, a youth hangout created in answer to the shootings.
He said going back to Columbine is important because if he turns
his back on the school, the shooters _ Harris and Klebold _ win.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Lynch, who is a junior at Heritage this year, said the
response to the shootings there actually bought her friends closer
together. They looked forward to going back to school and think
that it will be safer than ever, she said.
</P>
<P>
   And while she admitted that the shooting has made her feel more
vulnerable, she said she refuses to be a hostage to fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``A day does not pass that I don't think someone is waiting
behind a corner to jump out at me, holding a gun,'' she said. ``But
I must not let that run my life, and I refuse to let him (Solomon)
run my life!''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she said, she would like to reach out to Solomon, who a
Rockdale juvenile court judge ruled last Wednesday should be tried
as an adult. She said she wants to understand him better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not hold a grudge against him, and I would like to talk
to him, actually,'' she said. ``I would like to see how he is
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 1751EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
