<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7370 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ATLANTA-CHINA15-COX     08-14 3623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-CHINA15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Atlanta-China connection:
 &HT;    Weapons dealer used Southern city
 &HT;    as ``beachhead'' to spread influence
 &HT;    WITH SIDEBAR
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The exploits of shadowy Chinese arms dealer Wang Jun
have captured national headlines and the attention of federal
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   But one aspect of this intriguing story has been largely
overlooked in the recent scrutiny _ Wang Jun's Atlanta connection.
</P>
<P>
   Wang's Atlanta operations were, in his own words, his
``beachhead'' in America.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators say Wang, son of a former Chinese vice
president, formed at least a half-dozen companies in the Atlanta
area with just 20 employees. Still, investigators say some of these
companies bought, sold and in at least one case smuggled
sophisticated weapons, funneled money to suspicious offshore bank
accounts, and bought up land across the country.
</P>
<P>
   But in addition to making money, playing golf and reveling in
the Atlanta lifestyle on his visits to Georgia, Wang came to
America, investigators suspect, to bring home U.S. technology and
military secrets to his employers _ the Chinese armed services.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is little doubt that Wang Jun was in this country to
acquire sensitive technology,'' said Rep. Christopher Cox
(R-Calif.), who headed a Congressional investigation into Chinese
espionage.
</P>
<P>
   While it is unclear what role Wang's Atlanta companies played in
that mission, federal investigators have unearthed evidence of
questionable business practices.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Wang's operations in Atlanta, which began in the
spring of 1987 and continued for nine years, has been pieced
together from court and land records, financial documents from
Wang's companies obtained by The Atlanta-Journal Constitution, and
interviews with top law enforcement officials and others familiar
with Wang's operations.
</P>
<P>
   It's a story with many improbable twists and turns.
</P>
<P>
   Thorny legal problems generated by Wang's Atlanta activities,
for example, involved two of the city's most prestigious law firms
in escapades that one lawyer compared to a John Grisham novel.
</P>
<P>
   In another plot line, a former Chinese naval intelligence
officer who ran Wang's Atlanta operations was indicted in 1996 for
his alleged role in smuggling 2,000 AK-47s into this country. The
guns, netted in a sting by federal agents posing as Florida
mobsters, were the single largest cache of automatic weapons ever
seized by U.S. authorities. The Wang associate, Robert Ma, remains
a fugitive and is believed to be in China. Federal investigators
suspect he had been tipped off that the indictments were coming.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the treasure chest of arms sale profits stemming
from Wang's Atlanta operations that mysteriously ended up in the
Cayman Islands, Bermuda and the British West Indies, according to
internal company records, court documents and interviews with
former employees.
</P>
<P>
   But most unsettling for federal investigators are signs that
Wang may have been involved in espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Wang is the chairman of the Poly Group, a Beijing-based arms
trading company which is part of the People's Liberation Army. The
army makes money by selling weapons _ from assault rifles to
ballistic missiles _ around the world. Poly occupies a glittering
two-tower high-rise on almost a full block near Beijing's Forbidden
City. It's board members include the sons and daughters of
prominent Communist Party members. As the head of Poly, Wang
reports directly to the so-called Staff Department of PLA, which
oversees China's military intelligence. Wang also runs China
International Trust &AMP; Investment Corp., a powerful company with
interests in industry, finance and trade.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators believe that both companies took part in a
plan to station workers at companies throughout the United States
to gather sensitive information that would be helpful to the
military. Cox and other federal investigators estimate there are as
many as 3,000 such ``front'' companies in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Cox report states that some of the companies are set up to
acquire sensitive technology under the guise of a subsidiary of a
Chinese company; others are set up to provide cover to government
agents who enter the United States to gather technology and
military data; still other companies are set up to launder money.
</P>
<P>
   F. Michael Maloof, chief of technology security operations at
the Defense Department's U.S. Threat Reduction Agency, has been
investigating Wang's activities for more than 18 months. He has no
doubt about what Wang has been up to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wang Jun's operations are part of an overall Chinese system
that is integrated to target and acquire militarily critical
technologies,'' Maloof said.
</P>
<P>
   Maloof said the technology China has acquired has made it
possible to modernize its navy, improve its fleet of long-range
cruise missiles and build better long-range fighters and bomber
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   But the full impact of Chinese technology and military
acquisitions won't be felt until more advanced weapons are
designed, Maloof said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have basically auctioned off the security of our
children,'' said Maloof. ``We won't realize for the next ten years
the full impact of these technology acquisitions.''
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach Wang in China were unsuccessful. Congressional
committees have requested his appearance to answer campaign
fundraising and espionage charges for the last two years. They have
little hope he will appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy is bad news,'' said Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), who sits
on the House panel investigating campaign fund-raising misdeeds.
``The fact that he has been able to operate with impunity is very
disturbing. This fellow has ties that go directly to the Communist
Party in Beijing. He is right there, smack in the middle of the
campaign finance scandal and (involved with) U.S. corporations that
are in the middle of the spy scandal. Apparently this comes as a
surprise to our law enforcement officials and that's a problem.
It's outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Connection
</P>
<P>
   Wang's enterprises eventually stretched across the United
States, but they began in Atlanta in 1987 as PTK International
Inc., a joint venture with a suburban Atlanta company, Keng
Firearms Specialty Inc. Two other companies controlled completely
by Wang _ Dynasty Holding Co. and Poly USA, Inc. _ soon followed.
Four additional companies were incorporated in Atlanta, but never
conducted any kind of business. Most of the companies listed the
same officers and the same address.
</P>
<P>
   Wang's companies in Atlanta devoted themselves mostly to
importing guns from China and reselling them to dozens of American
distributors. But Dynasty bought a lot of commercial property
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Claude Collins, an Atlanta businessman who was the chief
financial officer at Dynasty and active in several of the
companies, says Wang began to cut back on his Atlanta operations
after President Clinton's 1994 ban on importingassault guns and
ammunition from China. All of the companies were dissolved by the
summer of 1996 soon after Ma's gun smuggling indictment, according
to Collins, who remains on good terms with his former Chinese
employer.
</P>
<P>
   Collins was involved from the beginning with Wang's enterprises
in Atlanta, helping set up the joint venture between Wang and the
Keng family.
</P>
<P>
   David Keng and his family immigrated to the Atlanta area from
Taiwan in 1973. They initially settled in Riverdale, just south of
Hartsfield International Airport. Keng, his wife and two sons
worked at a Chinese restaurant and jewelry import business that he
shared with his brother, always struggling to make ends meet. But
David Keng always kept looking for a way to merge his love for gun
collecting with business opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he got the chance: He would sell Chinese guns to
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   After several years of discussions, Poly and Keng signed an
agreement in Beijing in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Poly would export AK-47 assault rifles and SKS semi-automatic
rifles from China to Keng Firearms, which would sell the guns to
PTK, the joint venture between Wang's Poly and Keng in Atlanta. PTK
then would sell to American distributors.
</P>
<P>
   That arrangement was legal until the 1994 ban on importing of
assault weapons (Ma's indictment on smuggling charges came two
years later).
</P>
<P>
   Poly's agreement with Keng was marked by a celebration at an
exclusive Japanese restaurant in Beijing. Some sons and daughters
of the so-called Taizi _ the hardline Communist revolutionaries
_were there, including the daughter of the late Chinese leader Deng
Xiaoping. These children of Chinese leaders _ often called
``princelings'' _ are now in positions of power themselves, and are
using it to make capitalistic fortunes. As they dined and
celebrated their good fortune, Wang stood and raised his glass,
allowing a wide smile to cross his face. His new Atlanta venture
would be the company's ``beachhead'' in America, he told the
gathered guests. It would be just the beginning of a vast fortune
for them all to enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta lawyers threatened in Beijing
</P>
<P>
   The first years of business brought great rewards for both Wang
and the Keng family. By 1992, five years after its incorporation,
Poly had sold a total of $200 million worth of assault rifles to
various U.S. wholesalers and distributors. Company records show
that U.S. dealers paid PTK $18.4 million for guns in 1989. PTK
reported profits of $7.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the bloody Tiananmen Square massacre in 1989 and the
resulting U.S. crackdown on trade with China, the relationship
between Poly and the Keng family soured and a legal battle ensued
over money.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta federal court, the Kengs and Poly tangled over
shipments and legal issues over theirpartnership. The court fight
soon turned nasty, involving two of the city's biggest law firms _
Long, Aldridge &AMP; Norman representing Poly and Alston &AMP; Bird
representing the Keng family. Court records show a flurry of
unusual legal actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I practice law until I am 80 years old, I will never have a
case like this again,'' attorney Johnny Stephenson of Alston &AMP; Bird
said in an interview from his office overlooking Piedmont Park at
One Atlantic Center. ``If someone had told me this was the truth, I
wouldn't believe them.''
</P>
<P>
   After much haggling, Stephenson and his partner, Peter Bassett,
went to Beijing in the spring of 1991 to depose Ma and a handful of
others. On the third day of their visit, the lawyers said they were
accosted by three men at the top of the escalator at the China
World Hotel. They warned: ``We know who you are, where you are and
what you are doing. Watch your step. Beijing is a small place.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephenson and Bassett were so rattled that they immediately
returned to their hotel room and called the U.S. embassy. No
answer.
</P>
<P>
   So, they left and walked over to the lounge of the Shangri-La
Hotel, where they sat in a stunned daze for hours, thinking about
what to do next. The men who had accosted them knew too much _
their names and businesses _ to be mere street thugs. Was their
hotel room bugged by the government? Should they try to leave on
the next flight? What would happen if they got thrown in jail in
China?
</P>
<P>
   As they listened to a Filipino singer belt out American folk
songs, the attorneys said they sunk deeper into their seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like Alice going down the hole, it was so surreal,''
Stephenson said. ``There we were in Beijing, worried about our
lives, out of touch with the American embassy, listening to a woman
who couldn't speak English sing like Judy Collins.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephenson and Bassett say their suspicions about the incident
were only heightened a year later when he learned from the American
Embassy in Beijing that a high-ranking Chinese official had _ the
day before their arrival in China _ sent a letter to the embassy,
objecting to their taking depositions of potential witnesses. The
Chinese official noted that it was in violation of their tourist
visas, which the Atlanta lawyers saw both as a warning and a way to
pave the way for their possible arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked,'' Bassett said. They felt cornered by Wang and
his friends because they were traveling on a visa that Poly had
strongly suggested they use, rather than a business visa that would
give them permission to do legal work in China.
</P>
<P>
   When Stephenson and Bassett returned to the United States they
decided they had had enough.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Stephenson told Atlanta federal Judge Charles
Moye in court documents that ``individuals have been threatened
with punishment in the event (Poly) learns of their involvement.''
He said it would be impossible to call future witnesses, some of
them employees of Wang, because he feared that the Chinese
government might ``subject individuals in China to the danger of
retribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Poly attorneys responded by alleging that the Keng family had
threatened to kill Ma.
</P>
<P>
   Collins still wonders how a basic civil dispute spun so far out
of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a simple collection suit,'' said Collins, defending
Poly. ``We wanted what was owed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This case was no more a 'simple collection suit' than the
bombing of Pearl Harbor was a little diplomatic misunderstanding,''
Stephenson retorted. J. Allen Maines, the former Long &AMP; Aldridge
attorney representing Poly, declined to comment on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenson said Poly abruptly dropped its suit after he started
tracing millions of dollars of Dynasty's money to a ``mail drop''
in the Cayman Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that money, Stephenson alleged, accumulated in off-shore
accounts through an illegal ``dual billing'' practice to hide gun
sale profits from China's Ministery of Foreign Trade and Economic
Relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were shipping money from Dynasty to an insurance company
in the Cayman Islands, ostensibly for insurance premiums,''
Stephenson said. ``We are talking about a mail slot in a bank. ...
They were expensing these premiums for tax purposes, so they didn't
show their full income on their business activities here.''
</P>
<P>
   This practice made it possible, the suit alleges, for Ma and his
comrades to live ``extravagant'' lifestyles in America and to
invest in other ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenson compared his investigation of those off-shore
accounts to a John Grisham thriller. ``I'm reading 'The Firm,'
thinking, `That's nothing; come be me for six months.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean this guy (in the book) isn't being threatened by a
Communist country. He's down in the Cayman Islands on some little
tax scam. I'm down there tracing money from the Chinese government
and having my life threatened. It was unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins, too, found the Cayman Islands operation suspicious.
``That was as flaky as a homemade biscuit,'' he said. ``We were
paying a million-dollar premium for a million-dollar policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins, chief financial officer of Dynasty, said he was left in
the dark about the insurance deal. It was only after it was
operating that he began to ask questions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   After the Poly lawsuit was abruptly dropped, the Keng family
stayed in the import business. They now sell accessories and parts
for rifles and pistols from China. They also import small arms and
ammunition from France and Austria. But times are tougher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a much smaller operation now,'' said Da Keng, the eldest
son. ``We've had to fight to stay in business, to be smarter. Ten
years ago it was very easy money. Now it's a real dog fight.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, another Chinese government-run firm, China North
Industries Shenzhen Corp. is suing Keng for a breach of contract,
charging that the Kengs owe the company $723,000 _ a charge that
the Kengs adamantly deny.
</P>
<P>
   White House connections
</P>
<P>
   Wang first caught the eye of congressional investigators when he
visited the White House on Feb. 6, 1996, with Charlie Trie, a
former restaurateur and friend of the Clintons from Arkansas. Trie
figured prominently in the 1997 campaign fund-raising
investigation, having raised $640,000 in disputed donations for a
special fund started to help the president with his spiraling legal
expenses. Those funds were returned amid controversy over whether
they originated from foreign or otherwise improper sources. Trie
later pleaded guilty to violating campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   When news of Wang's trip to the White House first surfaced,
President Clinton went out of his way to say that it was ``clearly
inappropriate'' for a Chinese arms dealer to appear at the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Clinton aides said they had no prior knowledge of
Wang's gun dealing background, nor did they know of his close ties
to the Chinese army.
</P>
<P>
   But Collins said he gave top White House aides detailed
information about Wang at a private White House luncheon in early
May 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Collins was asked to speak to a small gathering of business
leaders at the White House luncheon after escorting Deng Xiaoping's
son, Deng Zhifang, to some of America's premier corporate centers.
</P>
<P>
   At the gathering, Collins said, were former White House Counsel
Thomas ``Mack'' McLarty and former senior aide Mark Middleton, who
later became a target of the campaign fund-raising probe.
</P>
<P>
   McLarty did not return phone calls about the lunch. Robert
Luskin, an attorney representing Middleton, said his client had
``absolutely no recollection of the lunch,'' adding that that is
not unusual given the hundreds of people that Middleton met with in
his White House post.
</P>
<P>
   After the lunch, Collins said, Middleton called for more details
about Wang. Collins said he told Middleton that Wang is the son of
former Chinese Vice President Wang Zhen and that his companies were
connected with the Chinese military.
</P>
<P>
   ``He grilled me and grilled me ... It's hard to believe that
they didn't know who he was,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   If White House aides didn't know then who Wang was, they soon
would learn.
</P>
<P>
   Wang's visit drew sharp criticism from lawmakers, including some
Democrats, who said it was an example of the lengths the White
House would go to raise a campaign dollar.
</P>
<P>
   If the White House had simply reviewed Poly's annual report, it
would have found that Poly's annual report lists its defense system
sales.
</P>
<P>
   The English version of a recent Poly annual report notes that
the company is in the business of ``import and export of defence
equipment in the areas of aviation, transportation and
communication of civilian products.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about reports that Wang was involved in arms dealing and
espionage, Collins sighed deeply and said, the only thing he found
suspicious in his seven years working for Wang was the off-shore
bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything (Wang's companies) did was legal, right down to the
bone,'' Collins said. ``We all knew what was fish and what was
fowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Espionage and arms dealing?
</P>
<P>
   However, Wang used Poly to arm Third World countries and funnel
American military technology back to China, internal company
records and interviews show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wang's Poly Group is Communist China's worst worldwide
proliferator of deadly weapons, having brokered the sale of cruise
missiles to Iran and nuclear weapons to Pakistan,'' Cox explained.
Congressional investigators believe that Poly also sold M-9
nuclear-capable missile technology to Syria and arms to both sides
of the Iraq-Iran war in the 1980s. Burma was another customer.
</P>
<P>
   And evidence of espionage continues to grow. In a recently
unclassified document, Maloof, the Defense Department official
investigating Wang, wrote, ``cumulative exports of selected
sophisticated U.S. technology to China ... has provided the Chinese
military with a nationwide integrated command, control,
communications, computers and intelligence encrypted network that
will serve it well into the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say it is not clear whether Wang's Atlanta-based
companies were involved in espionage, but there were several
disturbing incidents in which equipment that could have had a
military purpose was secretly sent back to China.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Poly asked PTK officials to place a shipment of
high-tech computer equipment in brown paper and ship it in unmarked
wooden crates back to China. Company documents indicate that
company officials were asked to draft documents that would conceal
the equipment, making it appear that it was actually radio
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Memos turned over to federal investigators show that Poly
officials in Beijing wrote memos to Poly employees in Atlanta
instructing them in Chinese to ship $19 million worth of militarily
sensitive high tech radar equipment through a state-owned shipping
line.
</P>
<P>
   It's over
</P>
<P>
   After the lawsuits were dropped and things settled down in
Atlanta, Stephenson went to the Atlanta offices of Wang's
operations in 1994 on behalf of the Kengs to review documents
pertaining to a federal tax issue.
</P>
<P>
   Ma and Collins were on hand to supervise Stephenson as he went
through the documents. After several hours, Ma asked Stephenson,
``The lawsuits are all over, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Stephenson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I have a gift for you,'' said Ma, leaving the room.
</P>
<P>
   Ma returned with a red leather-bound book with its title in gold
embossed lettering: ``What You Should Know About the American Legal
System.''
</P>
<P>
   The author? Ma Bao Ping _ Robert Ma's Chinese name.
</P>
<P>
   When Stephenson opened the book he found 300 blank pages and
Ma's autograph _ a sarcastic dig at the U.S. legal system.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenson still keeps the book on his shelf at Alston &AMP; Bird.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another bizarre episode in this fantastical tale,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
