u a BC-BLACKFARMERS15-COX     08-14 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKFARMERS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Black farmers doubt USDA probe to end aid bias
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Alan Judd
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Federal authorities are investigating whether black
farmers in two Georgia counties were denied disaster reliefbecause
of their race.
</P>
<P>
   But black farmers who recently settled a $2 billion
discrimination suit against the U.S. Department of Agriculture
contend the investigation is too narrowly focused and should be
broadened to examine whether the withholding of disaster aid is a
prevalent problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is typical of the USDA,'' said J.L. Chestnut, a civil
rights lawyer in Selma, Ala., who represented the farmers in the
discrimination case. ``They're looking in selected counties when
the problem is universal. I doubt they can find a county where
blacks live and there is not discrimination in the awarding of
disaster aid.''
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture officials declined to identify the counties where
their investigation is focused. Laura Trivers, a USDA spokeswoman,
would say only that the department's civil rights office and
inspector general are examining allegations about disaster relief
practices in two Farm Service Agency county offices in Georgia and
three in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take such complaints very seriously, and we will
investigate them thoroughly,'' Trivers said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the agency's state office in Athens did not
respond to requests for an interview. The state Agriculture
Department said it has no role in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Black farmers say the problem lies in the USDA system for
distributing aid. In each county, an advisory committee of farmers
_ typically wealthy and white, black farmers claim _ decides how to
disburse a lump sum of money allocated to its county.
</P>
<P>
   After weather-related disasters such as droughts or floods, the
committees typically settle claims by white farmers first, said
Melvin Bishop, president of the Georgia chapter of the Black
Farmers and Agriculturalists Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to black farmers, they aren't contacted until
the money has already run out,'' said Bishop, who raises beef
cattle in Putnam County.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Adams, a beef and poultry farmer in Greene County, said
black farmers suffer from a cycle of racism. The USDA committees
justify giving less disaster relief to black farmers because they
generally have smaller farms, Adams said. But that's the case, he
said, only because black farmers often have trouble getting loans
to expand. Then when disasters hit, he said, they don't get enough
aid to resume their previous level of farming, which causes them to
qualify for even less assistance the next time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only get the crumbs,'' Adams said. ``We don't get the
benefits we're due.''
</P>
<P>
   The USDA admitted to discrimination in disaster relief when it
settled the black farmers' class-action lawsuit last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Under that settlement, the department will pay as much as $2
billion to about 20,000 black farmers, each of whom will receive
$50,000, plus $12,500 to pay taxes. In addition, their debts to the
USDA will be written off.
</P>
<P>
   But the settlement doesn't prevent the USDA from continuing
discriminatory practices, said Gary Grant, national president of
the North Carolina-based black famers association.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest complaints we have is no one has been
terminated for the actions they've taken,'' Grant said. ``So why
should the folk be changing now? ... The department has admitted
it's guilty, but has not done one thing to rectify it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What have we got here?'' he said. ``A bittersweet victory that
yields nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie Adams, 47, talks to a reporter outside one of his chicken
houses in Greensboro, Ga., on Tuesday, March 24, 1998. The poultry
farmer paid $125,000 each for two of his chicken houses through a
lease purchase agreement because he could not borrow the money from
the federal government. He is now one of the plantiffs suing the
USDA for discrimination. (AJC Staff Photo/STEVE DEAL)
</P>
<P>
   STEVE DEAL / Staff
</P>
<P>
   Boldword Caption here for Willie Adams outside one of his
chicken houses in Greensboro, Ga. more here please for this more
hre please for this more here.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
