<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7372 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ATLANTA-CHINASIDE-COX     08-14 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-CHINASIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SIDEBAR TO ATLANTA-CHINA CONECTION
 &HT;    In Atlanta, Collins was `go-to' man for Wang
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Claude Collins sinks into a plush chair at the
Ritz-Carlton Hotel in downtown Atlanta, the light reflects off of
his solid gold wristwatch with Chairman Mao etched on the front.
</P>
<P>
   ``A gift from my Chinese friends,'' Collins says with a touch of
pride. ``There are only 1,000 like this in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   When Collins visits Beijing, his tall frame and flowing gray
hair are so well known that he's greeted like a dignitary in the
grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   But Collins' friends in Beijing extend far beyond grocery
shoppers. They go straight to the top of the Chinese Communist
Party's ruling elite.
</P>
<P>
   When the son of the late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping wanted a
tour of America's premiere financial houses, it was Claude Calvin
Collins of Atlanta who escorted him.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, 61, once a workaday computer consultant, says he ended
up becoming one of the Chinese government's ``go-to'' people in
America through Wang Jun, a well-connected member of the sons and
daughters of Communist revolutionaries who now run the country.
</P>
<P>
   Wang, the son of former hardline Vice PresidWT Wang Zhen, is a
power in China, running both the country's largest investment
conglomerate and the largest weapons trading company owned by the
Chinese military.
</P>
<P>
   Even Collins found the experience a bit heady.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times in China, I'd find myself in high-level meetings
pinching myself, saying: 'How did I get here? Why isn't George
Shultz or Alexander Haig here? Why me?'''
</P>
<P>
   Collins had lived in Atlanta since 1969, when a credit card
processing company he started in Texas was acquired by National
Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, Collins went off on his own, working for Mid-Atlantic
Fuel, a coal brokerage company based in South Carolina. After that,
he got a taste for international work as the U.S. representative
for Eckman Co. in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Collins started doing business with Wang through the owners of
Keng Speciality Firearms Inc., an Atlanta gun trading company that
asked Collins to help set up a joint enterprise with Wang. That
introduction made it possible for Collins, who never graduated from
college, to enter the high-stakes world of international trade.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he started to learn about China after meeting Wang
and his associates: ``Up until that point, I had not been that
interested. But I realized that this would permit me to see what
was going on in China economically from a box seat.''
</P>
<P>
   When Wang decided to open other companies in Atlanta, Collins
helped set up and run them. When other Chinese entrepreneurs wanted
to do business in America, they called Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Collins was doing everything from driving Wang and
his Atlanta-based Beijing employees around to helping them buy a
three-story stucco town house in Buckhead to setting up their
computer system at their swank East Paces Ferry Road offices. As
they trusted Collins more, he was given the responsibility of
overseeing export licenses and trade of high-tech avionics
equipment to Wang's companies in China.
</P>
<P>
   And winning their trust was not easy. Robert Ma, who ran most of
Wang's operations in Atlanta, was said by American colleagues to
have such a distrustful nature that he would keep a hair in his
diary to monitor whether anyone was reading it behind his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they first came over, they couldn't find the barber
shop,'' Collins said. ``It was an incredible experience to have
gotten to know them and their customs. We are so ignorant in
America about the way they do business.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Atlanta businesses are long shuttered, Collins
still carries a Samsonite travel briefcase with a sticker from the
Beijing Hilton Hotel emblazoned across the front. ``My home away
from home,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Collins estimates that he has taken 20 trips to China over the
last decade. The connections have paid off. After Wang closed his
companies, Collins says he received a lucrative contract to install
e-mail in the People's Hall in Beijing, among other contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
