<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7374 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ROADSTUDY-SIDE-COX     08-14 2225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROADSTUDY-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What were they doing in the road?
 &HT;    Family cites racism in death of schoolteacher, boyfriend
 &HT;    EDs: Sidebar to ROAD-STUDY15-COX
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEAGROVE, N.C. _ Up ahead on the dark highway, the
tractor-trailer swerved sharply. Its taillights flashed red, and
Richard Clark slowed down.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling home from a vacation in Myrtle Beach, S.C., the
44-year-old Pennsylvania businessman figured the 18-wheeler had hit
a deer darting across the road. The last thing Clark wanted to do
was spatter his 1997 Holiday Rambler motor home with road kill.
</P>
<P>
   Then, out of his left window, he glimpsed a tennis shoe on the
pavement.
</P>
<P>
   Clark turned on his CB radio, as passing vehicles rumbled over
the carnage.
</P>
<P>
   Truck driver Levy Giles shouted, ``I hit something,'' and began
pulling over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was it a deer?'' Clark asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I believe it was a person.''
</P>
<P>
   An unresolved tragedy
</P>
<P>
   Two people died on the pavement of U.S. 220 that night, Sept.
18, 1998. North Carolina's Department of Motor Vehicles classified
them as ``killed while lying in the roadway,'' a peculiar but
surprisingly common fatality on North Carolina's highways.
</P>
<P>
   The statistic bolsters unflattering stereotypes that linger from
the South's legacy of rural poverty. Generally speaking, somebody
gets drunk late at night, stretches out on the warm blacktop, and
gets run over.
</P>
<P>
   But the deaths of longtime sweethearts Tina Armstrong and Deon
Ledbetter defy such circumstances. The mystery of how they wound up
on the four-lane highway that slices across piedmont North
Carolina's hardscrabble peach belt has sparked a controversy
involving allegations of drug abuse, brutality and racism.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a year later, the accident illustrates how haunting _ and
divisive _ an unresolved tragedy can be.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran police are still baffled. The highway offered them no
clues _ no skid marks, no broken glass. Today a roadside bouquet of
purple and yellow plastic flowers, left by Ledbetter's sister,
Portia, marks the spot where the rain washed away the stains.
</P>
<P>
   Torn by grief, the victims' families are desperate for details.
The lack of answers has made the survivors impatient and suspicious
that somebody is hiding information about the accident. Armstrong's
family, in particular, has criticized the North Carolina State
Highway Patrol's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   When she closes her eyes, 73-year-old Evelyn Armstrong can see
her daughter. But she can't imagine why she was down in the road
with her fiance.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the midnight hour, I wake up and say, `Tina, where are you?
What happened to you?''' said Armstrong, who learned of her
daughter's death from a knock at the back door. ``I still have so
many unanswered questions.''
</P>
<P>
   The family says it believes racism tainted the inquiry. North
Carolina's Highway Patrol, already under legislative scrutiny for
allegedly targeting black motorists in traffic stops, denied the
charge of racism in investigating the deaths of Armstrong and
Ledbetter, who were black.
</P>
<P>
   The mysterious circumstances have led to speculation in this
rural county where the couple, both 29, had dated since their
teens. They were headed to Greensboro to see a movie and to visit
Ledbetter's sister.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was a popular fourth-grade teacher at Candor
Elementary School. The petite woman with shoulder-length brown hair
lived with her parents. Her soft-spoken mother still called h(er
``Baby'' because she was the youngest of her six children.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's smiling school portraits are scattered throughout
her family's modest brick house in the Dry Creek community, outside
Candor.
</P>
<P>
   Ledbetter seemed headed down a different road. A part-time
construction worker, he was well known to local police. Between
1989 and two months before his death, he faced more than 60 charges
in Montgomery County, including assaulting police officers and
resisting arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's relatives said Ledbetter was well behaved around
them. The last time Evelyn Armstrong saw him at her home, just
hours before he died, Ledbetter asked for a piece of chicken on the
way out the door. They hugged before he left.
</P>
<P>
   But Ledbetter also used cocaine shortly before he died. A state
medical examiner's report disclosed ``potentially lethal'' levels
of the drug in his body. Testing found no evidence of drugs in
Armstrong's body.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous theories _ a domestic fight, revenge by drug dealers, a
police setup _ have surfaced. None has been proved.
</P>
<P>
   Under the influence of cocaine, Ledbetter could have suffered a
``psychotic episode,'' which could have made him act irrationally
and disregard his own safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is just a theory,'' said state toxicologist Ruth
Winecker, who echoes the most common question: ``What in the world
were they doing there?''
</P>
<P>
   Witness told of fight
</P>
<P>
   It seems nobody saw Armstrong and Ledbetter get out of her
pearl-white 1992 Lexus sedan on U.S. 220, a heavily traveled
summertime route to the Carolina beaches. That September night,
traffic was relatively light.
</P>
<P>
   First Sgt. J.R. Williams, a 25-year patrol veteran who
supervised the investigation, said investigators talked to a woman
who said she was driving behind Armstrong's car when it pulled on
to the right-hand shoulder. The woman then went on to an exit ramp
to stop at Hardee's. In the five minutes it took her to get back on
the highway, the accident had happened.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, a truck driver talking on the CB radio said
he had seen a couple chasing a dog across the grassy highway
median.
</P>
<P>
   In nearby Asheboro, a grocery store clerk told an off-duty
highway patrol officer she overheard a man saying he had seen two
people fighting in the highway. Investigators told the clerk to
keep an eye out for the tipster, but that lead never panned out.
</P>
<P>
   Public speculation by state troopers that Armstrong and
Ledbetter might have been fighting has enraged Armstrong's family.
They accuse investigators of seizing upon Ledbetter's criminal
record prematurely as a reason to suspect he was fighting with
Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think people know they are practicing racism,'' said
51-year-old Gloria Lewis, Armstrong's sister. ``It is just a way of
doing things.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis discounted one theory that Armstrong stopped her car
because she wanted to get away from Ledbetter. Perhaps angry that
she was trying to break up with him, Ledbetter might have chased
her into the highway and knocked her down.
</P>
<P>
   Had the couple been about to end their relationship, said Lewis,
``I do not think Tina would have been gracious enough to drive him
to Greensboro.''
</P>
<P>
   That night, investigators found a pair of earrings _ one on the
driver's side floorboard and the other on the seat _ in the car,
which Armstrong kept meticulously clean. Police suggested the
earrings as possible evidence that Ledbetter had hit Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and other family members said she may have simply taken
them off. Over the next few days, Lewis said investigators provided
her family with conflicting information, such as whether the truck
driven by Levy Giles was the first to hit the couple. She also
complained that the state patrol has refused to return her sister's
clothing. The patrol said the garments are evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that could possibly be done in this investigation
was done,'' said Williams. ``Race was not a factor. I can only
guess that they are having trouble bringing closure to this.''
</P>
<P>
   Two black troopers, he noted, were among the first to arrive on
the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who heads the county's council on aging, complained in a
letter to North Carolina Attorney General Mike Easley about ``a
possible coverup of facts by investigating officers.''
</P>
<P>
   Easley's office referred the complaint to the state Highway
Patrol. The agency's now-retired commander, E.W. Horton, replied
last December that supervisors investigated Lewis' complaints, but
that state law prohibited the agency from divulging whether it took
any ``personnel actions.''
</P>
<P>
   The head of the patrol's Asheboro office, Williams said troopers
invested more time in this case than usual because of the elusive
details. Three officers took the unusual step of traveling to
Chapel Hill seeking details from the medical examiner's office.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking information to prove that the wreck wasn't accidental,
Armstrong's family listed the incident on a Web page for unsolved
crimes _ www.unsolvedcrimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis believes that the massive head injuries that Ledbetter
suffered in the accident could have masked blows from a beating.
The autopsy stated that his right thumbnail had been torn off,
suggesting to Lewis he could have been tortured.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are hit by an 18-wheeler, it could do a lot of
things,'' said Sharon Fuqua, a supervisor in the state Office of
the Chief Medical Examiner. ``Neither of them had any kind of
gunshot wounds or knife wounds.''
</P>
<P>
   The medical examiner's office concluded that both victims
probably died from ``multiple injuries'' after being struck by
numerous vehicles. Fingerprinting of Armstrong's car disclosed no
evidence of foul play, said Williams, the state patrol supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could give the family an answer, tell them what
happened,'' he said. ``The only people who know why they were out
there was them and the good Lord above.''
</P>
<P>
   The car was still running
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's family has cobbled together details leading up to
the accident. Armstrong left home, driving past Candor's peach and
apple orchards and tumble-down fruit stands. She picked up
Ledbetter in nearby Biscoe, and they turned north on U.S. 220 for
the nearly 60-mile drive to Greensboro.
</P>
<P>
   After the couple went to a movie, Armstrong planned to drop off
Ledbetter at his sister's home in Greensboro. The next morning, he
was to take a bus to Pittsburgh. That night, Armstrong planned to
return home.
</P>
<P>
   The couple never made it to Greensboro. Twenty-six miles from
Armstrong's house, her car pulled off the highway, parking on the
right-hand shoulder just past the exit ramp to Seagrove.
Investigators believe Armstrong was driving.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow _ and that is a big part of the mystery _ they wound up
outside the car about 20 feet away, down in the left-hand passing
lane.
</P>
<P>
   The car's engine was still running, and the lights were on.
</P>
<P>
   Cruising along at the posted speed of 65 mph, trucker Giles was
climbing a steady hill when he spotted the Lexus pulled on to the
shoulder. He eased into the left-hand passing lane to distance his
truck from the parked car.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Giles saw something down in the road, in the same lane
in which he was driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was right on top of it, it looked like I saw the face
of a person,'' said the longtime driver for Pillowtex, a textile
maker based in Eden, N.C. He now believes that was Ledbetter. ``I
can't say I hit a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Police did not charge Giles in the accident. He said he is not
convinced that he was the first to hit the couple, despite
investigators' conclusion that he was. ``I just prayed to the Lord
that I did not take anybody's life,'' Giles said recently. ``If I
did, I did everything to avoid it. It was an accident.'' A neighbor
of Armstrong's, 21-year-old Damon Green, drove through shortly
after Armstrong and Ledbetter apparently were first hit. He heard a
thump and thought he had hit a dog. Later, he said, ``I think it
was Tina.''
</P>
<P>
   The week afterward, he washed his Chevy Cavalier three times a
day to get rid of the smell of flesh singed by the heat of
tires.``He don't sleep,'' said Green's mother, Edith. ``He don't
stay still.''
</P>
<P>
   `God wanted it like that'
</P>
<P>
   After learning of Armstrong's death after midnight, her
relatives drove to the hospital in Asheboro. They crossed the
northbound lanes of U.S. 220 where the couple had died. Sand spread
by emergency workers hissed against the bottom of their car. At the
hospital, an attendant urged the family not to view Armstrong's
broken body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to find somebody who had seen my baby,'' her
mother said. ``Was she standing up, or was she lying down?''
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred people attended Armstrong's funeral last
September at the local high school. The casket was closed. She was
buried on the rocky hillside of First Congregational United Church
of Christ, her family's longtime church near her home.
</P>
<P>
   Seven months later, on a Sunday morning in April, Armstrong's
mother wept for the first time. She took her seat in the choir, as
usual. This morning, she heard preacher Johnny Jones humming
through the closed door of his study.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will understand it better by and by/By and by when the
morning comes/When the saints of God are gathered home/we'll tell
the story of how we've overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Others in the small congregation cried along with Evelyn
Armstrong, reassured that someday she'll know what happened. She
also found comfort in an arrangement of white silk roses. Somebody
left them in her carport after her daughter's funeral. They now sit
on the kitchen table. A ribbon on the vase reads, ``God wanted it
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the roses were so beautiful,'' she said. ``I'd like
to know who sent them. There was no message, no name, no card.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
