<P>
   STRAW-IOWA _ The first voting of the 2000 election occurs
Saturday, in Iowa. The Iowa straw poll is far from democratic, but
it's an early indication of how the field is shaping up.
(Greenberger, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ Color and commentary from the Iowa Straw Poll.
(Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-BARAKSTYLE _ JERUSALEM _ He spent most of his career as a
soldier in secret elite units. Now Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak is running Israel like a commando. He has pushed most of the
traditional doves from key roles in government and brought in
colleagues from his army days. They talk of their ``mission'' and
keep plans so hush-hush that even traditional allies are either
baffled or angered. He favors discipline over politics, even to a
nearly authoritarian degree. For example, when Cabinet ministers
engaged in the usual practice of leaking their proposals to the
press before cabinet meetings, Barak sent word that any proposals
leaked to the press would not be brought up in the meetings.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service) EDs: Moved Thu., Aug. 12.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS _ MOSCOW _ The end of the world is near, warned
some superstitious Russians, who trusting in the country's mystical
folklore saw a bad omen in the final solar eclipse of this
millennium. Russia survived the cosmic phenomenon; it is coping,
too, with last week's Kremlin phenomenon. President Boris Yeltsin,
and his inner circle of political operatives and business tycoons
produced yet another shock by naming ex-spy Vladimir Putin as
Russia's fifth prime minister in the past 18 months. At work in
Russia isn't some strange alignment of the stars, but gritty,
down-to-earth politics that has slowed progress on key issues with
the United States _ namely arms control and reviving the Russian
economy. The campaign season has begun, with national parliamentary
elections scheduled for December and the vote for president to take
place next summer when Yeltsin's term ends. (Holmes, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Wed., Aug. 11 in the (i) International and (k)
Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CRISIS _ MOSCOW _ How's this for spin? Russian officials
recently delivered the good news that the country's economy will
not expand this year. In a sign of the times, the government issued
the promising forecast that the economy would remain flat in 1999,
compared to earlier estimates that predicted the downward spiral
that commenced last summer would continue. One year into its
deepest economic crisis since the Soviet Union collapsed, Russia's
outlook is assessed not so much by what's going right, as by the
horrible things that could have _ but haven't _ gone wrong. Even
last week's abrupt firing of the government by President Boris
Yeltsin barely made a ripple on the economy. (Holmes, Cox News
Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Updated and re-sent in the (i) International and Financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Photos are available to go with this story.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-MADRAZO _ MEXICO CITY _ Roberto Madrazo has a grin and a
gleam in the eye that reflect a politician who knows he's on top.
Madrazo wants to be the first man democratically elected on Nov. 7
as presidential nominee for Mexico's Revolutionary Institutional
Party. The PRI, which has provided Mexico with its presidents for
70 years, has never had a primary election until this year. And
Mexicans have never seen a bruising attack campaign -- via
television and campaign slogans - like the one Madrazo launched
this month against his closest rival, Francisco Labastida, who is
perceived as the PRI establishment's favorite. As Madrazo, who
recently resigned as governor of Tabasco state and is slightly
ahead or even with Labastida in polls, works his way through
barrios here, he cultivates a ``man of the people'' image, tapping
into deep anger over the economy and other problems. (Ferris, Cox
News Service). 30. WITH PHOTO. EDs: Moved Fri., Aug. 13.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA-CHINA _ ATLANTA _ The exploits of shadowy Chinese arms
dealer Wang Jun have captured national headlines and the attention
of federal investigators. But one aspect of this intriguing story
has been largely overlooked in the recent scrutiny _ Wang Jun's
Atlanta connection. Wang's Atlanta operations were, in his own
words, his ``beachhead'' in America. Federal investigators say
Wang, son of a former Chinese vice president, formed at least a
half-dozen companies in the Atlanta area with just 20 employees.
Still, investigators say some of these companies bought, sold and
in at least one case smuggled sophisticated weapons, funneled money
to suspicious offshore bank accounts, and bought up land across the
country. (Carr, Cox News Service). 116. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Package moving in (a) general news and (w) Washington
categories.
</P>
