<P>
   SHOOT-FUNERAL _ Scott Webb becomes the last of the Atlanta
massacre victims to be buried. Funeral is in Ladue, Mo., a St.
Louis suburb. Update on condition of other vcitims of the Atlanta
shooting. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SMUGGLE _ Authorities are questioning the 132 Chinese men
who were discovered in the secret compartment of a ship in Savannah
Thursday. This is the biggest and most sophisticated smuggling case
immigration and port officials in Georgia say they have
encountered. (Bixler, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   WORKERS-INJURED _ SMYRNA, Ga. _ Eight workers were injured,
three critically, when cleaning chemicals exploded at a job site in
the Atlanta suburb of Smyrna. Developing. (Schrade, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   ADOPT-FOREIGN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Gina Dunn holds a picture of a
baby girl with a furrowed brow, bundled to her chin in a heavy
sweater. She brings it to eye level, and coos: ``Hi, sweetie.
Mama's going to come see you pretty soon. Gonna come get you.'' For
months Gina, 43, has talked to the picture of her
soon-to-be-adopted daughter. The number of international adoptions
has doubled since 1990, according to State Department figures for
immigrant visas issued to orphans coming to the United States. A
look at one couple's journey. (Lee, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ADOPT-MIXED _ DAYTON, Ohio _ White couples who adopt Asian
children face a philosophical struggle. Some parents say their
daughters will be All-American, just like them. Other parents
believe teaching their children about their heritage will prepare
them for racism they surely will face as minorities in America.
Often, even husband and wife don't agree on which strategy makes
sense. (Lee, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ADOPT-AGENCY _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Carefully choosing an adoption
agency is an important step in the process. (Lee, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ROADSTUDY _ CHAPEL HILL, N.C. _ North Carolina and South
Carolina are the only two Southern states that keep tabs on the odd
phenomenon of people ``killed while lying in the road,'' and North
Carolina has begun a formal study of the issue. Especially common
during the summer, the incidents typically happen on either side of
midnight and often involve intoxicated victims who apparently like
the idea of sleeping on the warm pavement. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ROADEAD _ SEAGROVE, N.C. _ Late one Friday night, trucker Levy
Giles spotted a car parked on the right shoulder of U.S. 220, so he
moved into the left-hand lane. Unknown to him, the car's two
occupants were lying in the highway. The tractor-trailer ran over
them, adding two more victims to a peculiar category of North
Carolina's highway deaths: killed while lying in the road. But the
deaths of longtime sweethearts Tina Armstrong and Deon Ledbetter
remain a mystery and have become a major controversy involving
allegations of drug abuse, brutality and racial discrimination. A
detailed account of the incident and the aftermath. (Burritt,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKFARMERS _ The U.S. Department of Agriculture is
investigating whether black farmers in two Georgia counties were
improperly denied disaster assistance. But farmers who won a
settlement in a lawsuit against the government over other
discrimination issues say the disaster-aid problem exists in
virtually every county in Georgia and other states. The situation
may lead to another class-action lawsuit by black farmers against
the agriculture agency. (Judd, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTO. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HUNT-COUNTRY _ MIDDLEBURG, Va. _ The essence of Hunt Country was
captured on the Virginia license plate: POLO MOM. In this historic
piedmont in the shadows of the Blue Ridge Mountains, the scents of
money and manure have long mingled. (Dart, Cox News Service). WITH
PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Monday in (a) national and (l) lifestyle categories.
WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-AGE _ WASHINGTON _ Though one of the youngest presidents
in U.S. history, Bill Clinton, who turns 53 this week, still shows
the wear and tear of
</P>
<P>
   six and a half years in one of the world's toughest jobs. A look
at how the presidency wears down its occupants. (Nesmith, Cox News
Service). WITH PHOTO
