<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7377 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-DEHYDRATE15-COX     08-14 0248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEHYDRATE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Children urged to take frequent water breaks
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ To any sports coaches and band directors who
don't believe in frequent water breaks during summer practices, a
health expert has a few words of advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's ridiculous,'' says Dr. Norman Schneiderman of Miami
Valley Hospital. The words ``insane'' and ``dangerous'' came up
during the discussion, too.
</P>
<P>
   Most kids whose activities require outdoor practices this month
are in good health, but Schneiderman says healthy people get
dehydrated, too. ``We do sometimes see these healthy people just
drop, and it can be a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   People who exercise outside in oppressive heat should be
drinking liquids to replace their body fluids ``every 15 to 20
minutes,'' he says. Not only are they sweating away those fluids,
but they also lose fluid every time they exhale.
</P>
<P>
   ``So these people need to be constantly drinking, drinking,
drinking,'' he says. ``And the point is, it's hard to practice when
you're doing that. So you probably shouldn't have practice. You
probably should make that practice in the early morning or night.''
</P>
<P>
   It was hot enough during last month's heat wave at 6:30 a.m.,
when Schneiderman went jogging. ``But 3 o'clock in the afternoon?
When it's that hot? That's insane. It's dangerous. You've got to
use some common sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 1806EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
