<SLUG> BC-NY-BUILDING-BOOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST CONSTRUCTION BOTTLENECK: SHORTAGE OF SKILLED WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Mass., La., Ill., Conn.)  (mk) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Carroll is among the most wanted men in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   A lean, red-haired electrician at a building project on 42nd
Street, Carroll and thousands of skilled construction workers like
him are suddenly in short supply as the real estate boom finally
ends what many in the industry describe as a brutal seven-year
depression.
</P>
<P>
   There are no unemployed workers at Carroll's union, the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, Local 3, where a
short time ago many electricians were out of work for six months
out of the year. Many are now working what they call ``six 10s,''
or six days a week for 10 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, there are no men on the bench,'' Carroll said.
``Everybody's at full employment. You can more or less pick your
job. I worked just about every day in July. I've been working for
11 years and I've never been able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything seems to be on a fast track as contractors advertise
for workers and scour the union halls for journeymen. There may be
fewer skyscrapers under construction today than a decade ago, but
there are many residential and commercial buildings being built, as
well as billions of dollars in public works and lots of
rehabilitation work.
</P>
<P>
   These projects range from an $87 million face lift for the
Hilton Hotel on the Avenue of the Americas in midtown to the $237
million renovation of the 1.5 million-square-foot office building
at 2 Broadway in lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   And contractors want the work done now, especially in Times
Square, where everything from a new 50-story hotel at Broadway and
47th Street to the World Wrestling Federation's theme restaurant at
43rd Street is rushing to open by year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Electrical contractors estimate that there is an immediate need
for 1,000 to 2,500 electricians in New York today, and that does
not take into account projects starting in the coming year or two.
</P>
<P>
   The labor shortage is most keenly felt among electricians, but
builders say it is also hard to find enough tin knockers and
sheet-metal workers, who install duct work and put together heating
and air-conditioning systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are facing serious shortages,'' said Ray McGuire, general
counsel for the Contractors Association of Greater New York, a
trade association. ``There's a shortage of elevator construction
mechanics, steamfitters, sheet-metal workers and electricians. In
the short term, the industry is dealing with it by working a lot of
overtime. But that is not a long-term solution, because we see, if
anything, increased construction activity in the next two years.''
</P>
<P>
   It does not help that the situation is no better elsewhere in
the United States. John Kirberg, president of Kirberg Roofing in
St. Louis, cannot find enough experienced roofers to expand his
family business. Some builders are offering bounties for operating
engineers in Boston and electricians in New Orleans, Chicago and
Fairfield, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Construction companies in New York are luring badly needed
project managers and superintendents from rivals with $20,000
bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Contractors say the shortage of electricians, who make $34 an
hour, became acute in May and June. ``There is such a strong market
that many employers are really stretching to get the number of
skilled craftsman they need,'' Coletti said. ``The unions are, if
not at 100 percent employment, as close as they've ever been in 20
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The demand for labor has been exacerbated by changes in the
construction industry as well. The corporations and retailers
building new homes now demand accelerated schedules. They want a
job that used to take 20 weeks done in 10 or 12 weeks. New
buildings, as well as renovation projects, also require more
electrical work than a decade ago, with computer cables, fiber
optic lines and redundant power systems.
</P>
<P>
   That means more workers and lots of overtime, which pleases many
workers anxious to pay off mortgages and debts accumulated during
the lean years. But it is also wearing.
</P>
<P>
   At a hotel project in Times Square, Ed Garvey, a veteran
electrician, has been working six eight-hour days a week and
expects his workweek to grow to 60 hours in the final push to open
before New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of 30 guys working for 6 months, they now load up with
100 guys for 2 months,'' Garvey said. ``It's chaos. Chaos means
cash, but it also leads to accidents. They're looking to push the
jobs a little too much.''
</P>
<P>
   To combat the shortage and expand the union share of the labor
market, Local 3 and the sheet-metal workers' union have organized
nonunion contractors, while the Mason Tenders union has recruited
immigrant workers. The steamfitters have doubled the size of their
apprenticeship programs, but that is a long-term investment because
it takes three to five years to attain journeyman status.
</P>
<P>
   Local 3 has taken in unemployed electricians from Long Island as
well as 300 temporary college helpers, but it has been reluctant to
open up to travelers, electricians with union cards from
out-of-town locals. But the local may soon have no choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've requested that the unions bring in travelers, or
out-of-towners, to make up the shortfall,'' said Ken Colao, chief
executive of York Hunter, a construction management company.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, builders have had to make do. Milo Riverso, president
of the School Construction Authority, said that sheet metal
delivered to some job sites lies unused for days because there are
not enough skilled workers to go around.
</P>
<P>
   Some contractors have turned down jobs. Only two of eight
electrical contractors responded to requests for bids from one
hotel developer, according to Raymond Quartararo, president of
Quartararo &AMP; Associates, a construction manager on the Ernst &AMP;
Young building and a project at 770 Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Cettina, first vice president at Tishman Construction, said
his company had resorted to dividing the electrical contract for
its projects among several subcontractors rather than relying on a
single company.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to get into a situation where you have a ton of
overtime at the end of a job,'' he said. ``It wears people out and
you don't have the ability to bring in a fresh crew. They don't
exist.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
