<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7384 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NJ-RIVERWALK-REAL-3TA     08-14 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-RIVERWALK-REAL-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: A RIVER WALK'S PIECEMEAL BIRTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DENNIS HEVESI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The concept is grand: preserve a ribbon of land by the water's
edge, 30 feet wide and 18 miles long, to bind and adorn the
imposing package of developments now rising above the old mud flats
and desolate rail yards of New Jersey's Hudson River shore,
creating for strollers and bikers an unimpeded path from Bayonne to
the George Washington Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hudson River Walkway, dependent on a state requirement
that the developer of each new office tower, condominium complex
and rental building by the river build and maintain his particular
link to the whole, remains a tattered necklace of short strands and
detached pearls.
</P>
<P>
   And with home builders challenging the state requirement in
federal court, the public walkway through their private property
has become a source of contention over the issues of eminent
domain, illegal ``takings'' and _ harking as far back as ancient
Roman law _ the people's right to get to the water.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing to the complications, said Robert Janiszewski, the
Hudson County executive, is that the walkway is like the proverbial
camel, ``a horse designed by a committee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's the challenge,'' Janiszewski said, noting that there
are nine towns along the walkway route: ``Multiple jurisdictions,
each with its own planning board; dozens of property owners,
different designs, nonexistent designs; some sites occupied by
governmental agencies, abandoned sites.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing in common is the width,'' he said. ``Some
developers with deeper pockets create lovely paths, others, an
asphalt path; others, a dirt path, and some communities are walled
off. So it's incoherent for someone who would want to explore the
walkway from end to end.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrice Vare, an artist's representative who recently moved from
New York City to the River Club, a rental complex in Edgewater,
N.J., sees past the incoherence. With her dog, Bimini, by her side
on the walkway one recent weekday, Ms. Vare said, ``Isn't it a
great idea to be able to go from here all the way to Hoboken by
bike, walking?''
</P>
<P>
   It is that issue of access that concerns many residents of the
towns along the river: the ability to meander by the water, to
fish, to sit on a bench and do nothing slowly. And with buildings
on the rise, to still see the spikes and spires of the New York
skyline.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are residential developments that have fenced the ends
of their property from the walkway,'' said Doug Harmon, president
of the Friends of the Weehawken Waterfront. ``There's limited
perpendicular access, meaning the staff at the gatehouse doesn't
permit you through unless you are the guest of a resident. And
because some of these developments are linked arm in arm, there's
almost no parking for waterfront walkway users.''
</P>
<P>
   A different set of access issues troubles the builders: concerns
about vandalism, and the safety of residents whose homes abut the
walkway, their windows and patios a few feet above the path.
</P>
<P>
   And there is that constitutional question _ already argued and
awaiting a decision in U.S. District Court in Trenton _ contesting
whether government can force developers to build and maintain,
permanently, at their own expense, a public amenity on their own
property.
</P>
<P>
   ``This public walkway requirement is an unconstitutional taking
under the Fifth Amendment, which says that property can't be taken
without the payment of just compensation,'' said Duane Desiderio,
litigation counsel for the National Association of Home Builders,
which joined the New Jersey Builders Association in filing the
federal suit. ``The bottom line is that under any argument that has
been asserted, it violates the Constitution to allow people
willy-nilly access to private land.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ann Alexander of the Rutgers Environmental Law Clinic
contends that the shoreline belongs to the people, ``and no one can
take away from the builders what they don't own.'' The Rutgers law
clinic is one of seven conservation groups that have voluntarily
joined the New Jersey Department of Environmental Protection as
defendants in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The friction of public-private proximity was clear one recent
sultry Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   On a paved-over pier that is part of the walkway, fledgling
roller skaters strode and stumbled; a fisherman dropped his line
and waited.
</P>
<P>
   On the adjacent lot, behind a fence, a backhoe stood still, its
bucket dug into a hillock for a long weekend in mid-bite. And the
gantry of a construction crane, tilted toward the top-floor girders
of a building on the rise, also awaited the start of another work
week.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north on River Road _ the sometimes narrow route that
winds below the cliffs of the Palisades parallel to the walkway _
there were other indications of things to come. A billboard read:
``Half Moon Harbour, 176 Luxury Apartments, Coming Soon. Phase
One.'' In West New York, N.J., a bouquet of balloons bobbed atop a
``Now Leasing'' sign at the Landings, a 276-unit development.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, in Edgewater, Dr. Mark Wardlow, 32, a
radiologist, stood on the patio of his two-bedroom duplex at
Mariner's Cove, overlooking the walkway. ``Only once,'' he said
when asked whether having the public so close was troubling.
``There was a bunch of kids, 14-, 15-year-olds, throwing debris in
the water. I pay too much money for people to come in here and
throw beer cans.''
</P>
<P>
   Wardlow has lived in Mariner's Cove, where apartments rent for
$2,200 to $3,000 a month, for a year and a half. ``I was told it
would be gated,'' he said, and it is _ but only at the entrance on
River Road, not along the walkway.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was a lot of trespassing, I wouldn't be thrilled,''
Wardlow said. ``When the place is done and there are benches, there
might be trouble. Yes, I would have a problem with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Stamm, past president of the New Jersey chapter of the
Hudson River Fishermen's Association, has a problem with the way
some communities bar the public from the walkway.
</P>
<P>
   Stamm likes to reel them in at the waterfront. ``Have you ever
had a 20-pounder pull on your line?'' he said. ``It's thrilling.
You catch them, take a photograph and watch them swim out of your
hands. Just don't eat them.'' Last month, Stamm went to Roc
Harbour, a condominium development by the water in North Bergen.
``They wouldn't let us onto the pathway,'' he said. ``And the
pathway that they built had a chain-link fence with a padlock.''
</P>
<P>
   The contradictions were clear at Jacob's Ferry, a community of
183 town houses in West New York, where one banner advertises the
walkway and another promises ``Private Gates.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There has long been a tendency toward privacy along the
riverfront.
</P>
<P>
   During the late 1800s and through the first half of this
century, a maze of train tracks, bridges fashioned from boulders
and tunnels through the cliffs transformed the land along the river
into the mainland terminus for four of the nation's major rail
lines. And much of the property was fenced off from the public.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1950s, however, the rail freight business had been
decimated by containerization, making it possible to move shipbound
cargo directly onto trucks. And so, after two decades of tortuous
bankruptcy proceedings, the rail yards and their environs became
public property _ a swath of weeded-over tracks, lonely freight
cars, rotting piers and stilled factories.
</P>
<P>
   The walkway was first conceived in the 1960s by the Regional
Planning Association to bring the public to the river. But it was
not until 1980 that Gov. Brendan Byrne formed a Waterfront Advisory
Commission, now called the Hudson River Waterfront Conservancy, a
nonprofit government advisory and advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, a consultant hired by the New Jersey Department of
Environmental Protection offered a preliminary plan for the
walkway. By then, developers were brimming with interest in the
waterfront and Byrne's successor, Gov. Tom Kean, proposed that each
municipality along the river be given control over its own section
_ the only stipulation being construction of the walkway.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1988 that the Department of Environmental Protection
formalized the concept by adopting the Coastal Zone Management
Rules, which defined the role of developers in building the
walkway.
</P>
<P>
   It is those rules that are now being contested in the courts.
Patrick O'Keefe, chief executive of the New Jersey Builders
Association, believes his members have a right to be compensated
for the public use of their property.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a series of U.S. Supreme Court decisions in recent
years,'' O'Keefe said, ``that have refined the takings clause of
the Fifth Amendment,'' which, in essence, says that government
cannot take private property without compensating the owner.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, a 1994 Supreme Court decision in the case of
Dolan vs. City of Tigard, Ore., has ``better defined'' the legal
tests determining when compensation is due, O'Keefe said. ``And
among those tests,'' he said, ``are requirements that the permit
program, such as the walkway, make individualized determinations
and impose the regulatory burden on the owners in proportion to the
impact their property is having on the publicly regulated
resource.''
</P>
<P>
   As a condition for its approval of a proposed development, the
Department of Environmental Protection requires a property owner to
grant a permanent easement for the walkway, and agree to maintain
the path to the department's standards in perpetuity.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations do not make individualized determinations,
O'Keefe said, ``nor is the imposition that they make on a property
owner proportional to the impact of the development.'' The
department, he said, ``is less concerned with completing the
walkway than with extorting selected private parties to pay for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Alexander of the Rutgers law clinic contends, however, that
the developers do not own the waterfront. ``And the reason they
don't have the right to exclude the public,'' she said, ``is
something called the Public Trust Doctrine'' _ a legal principle
dating back through common law to a codification of ancient Roman
statutes called the Justinian Institutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can exclusively own the seashore or the waterfront;
people are allowed to use the seashore for traditional purposes
such as fishing and navigation,'' Ms. Alexander said. ``And in
modern times, that's been interpreted by courts, including the New
Jersey Supreme Court, to also give the public a right to
recreational use, such as swimming and beach strolling.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court also recognized the Public Trust Doctrine
in an 1892 case, Illinois Central Railroad Co. vs. State of
Illinois, Ms. Alexander said, ``when it not only held that the
public had the rights to the waterfront but that the government
didn't have the power to give those rights away.''
</P>
<P>
   The developers have already benefited from concessions in the
state regulations, Ms. Alexander argued. ``Usually when you develop
the waterfront, the regulations say you can't develop at all within
100 feet of the shore, unless your use is water-dependent, like a
dock or a marina,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the walkway, in order to encourage development in that
formerly industrial area, the developers were allowed to construct
to within 30 feet of the water's edge. But in exchange for the
concession, the regulations required that they build the walkway to
make sure that the public can access the water.''
</P>
<P>
   The practical effect of a decision in favor of his members,
O'Keefe of the builders' association said, would be a redrafting of
the state regulations to meet the standards of Dolan vs. Tigard,
``that the responsibilities of each builder be determined
individually and proportionally.'' Such a ruling would only affect
future development, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Michelle Marean, president of the Hudson River Waterfront
Conservancy, said: ``The conservancy believes that if the builders
prevail, it will effectively stop all future development of the
walkway. It would weaken the regulations significantly, because
then what standards will be used for determining walkway
requirements?''
</P>
<P>
   A decision in favor of the owners ``would also allow all current
walkway portions to be closed to the public,'' Ms. Marean
contended, ``because the other owners will seek equal relief.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are speaking a good game,'' she said, ``but the bottom
line is that they don't want to build any walkway and they
absolutely don't want the public to have access to it.'' Arguments
in the builders' suit ended in June, and a decision by Judge
Garrett Brown Jr. of U.S. District Court is awaited.
</P>
