<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 08/14/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Aug. 14, 1999 -- OBIT- KIRKLAND, 8-14 --
Lane Kirkland, who was president of the AFL-CIO from 1979 to 1995
and who resigned after an unprecedented revolt of union presidents
against him, died Saturday morning at his home in Washington. He
was 77. The cause of death was lung cancer, said his wife, Irena
Kirkland. Together, Kirkland and George Meany, his predecessor as
president of the AFL-CIO and his longtime friend and mentor, led
the U.S. labor movement for nearly 45 years. (Don Hogan Charles/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Aug. 14, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS-OLDTIMERS-FLOAT,
8-14 -- Jim Spencer, right, a former New York Yankee first-baseman,
teasing Richard ``Goose'' Gossage, after Spencer hit a run-scoring
double during Saturday's Old-Timers game at Yankee Stadium. The
Yankees had a moment of prayer for Jim ``Catfish'' Hunter,
diagnosed last year with Lou Gehrig's disease, before playing the
53rd Old-Timers day. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) DAVIE, Fla. -- Aug. 14, 1999 -- FBN-DOLPHINS-JOHNSON-3,
8-14 -- Miami Dolphins Coach Jimmy Johnson, looking as serious as
ever at the Dolphins training camp in Davie, believes his team is
the most talented team in the American Football Conference East.
With more weapons on offense than he has had since joining Miami
for the 1996 season, Johnson is poised to advance deep into the
playoffs. His Dolphins have a swagger, like Johnson's old Dallas
Cowboys teams that won two Super Bowls. (Gary I. Rothstein/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) DAVIE, Fla. -- Aug. 14, 1999 -- FBN-DOLPHINS-JOHNSON-2,
8-14 -- Miami Dolphins Coach Jimmy Johnson with his new defensive
coordinator Dave Wannstedt, fired last season by the Chicago Bears,
at the Dolphins training camp in Davie. A kinder, gentler Johnson
has surfaced because his friend and jogging buddy, Wannstedt, is
around, just like the good old days in Dallas when he was Johnson's
defensive coordinator. Wannstedt has a soothing effect on Johnson
and is his sounding board. (Gary I. Rothstein/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) DAVIE, Fla. -- Aug. 14, 1999 -- FBN-DOLPHINS-JOHNSON-1,
8-14 -- The head coach of the Miami Dolphins, Jimmy Johnson, at the
teams' training camp in Davie, believes his players form the most
talented team in the American Football Conference East. With more
weapons on offense than he has had since joining Miami for the 1996
season, Johnson is poised to advance deep into the playoffs. His
Dolphins have a swagger, like Johnson's old Dallas Cowboys teams
that won two Super Bowls. (Gary I. Rothstein/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) ALBANY, N.Y. -- August 14, 1999 -- FBN-CAMP-LIFE, 8-14 --
At the NFL's version of summer camp, Giants cornerback Jason
Sehorn, left, and quarterback Kerry Collins, two of the team's most
prominent players, at the Giants' camp at SUNY-Albany. Sehorn and
Collins are roommates who don't share a sense of orderliness.
Players have their own bedrooms, but share a living room area and a
bathroom. Sehorn received an advance scouting report on Collins.
``I told him I was a borderline slob,'' says Collins. (David
Jennings/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) LITTLE FALLS, N.J. -- Aug. 14, 1999 --
BBO-LEMKE-COMEBACK-2, 8-14 -- Mark Lemke, 34, who used to play
second base for the Atlanta Braves, warming up as a pitcher for the
New Jersey Jackals. Lemke is attempting a comeback by embarking on
the most offbeat path known to the sport, a path that requires
years of practice and the ability to embrace the mystical. Lemke
wants to be a knuckleball pitcher. (Michelle V. Agins/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) LITTLE FALLS, N.J. -- Aug. 14, 1999 --
BBO-LEMKE-COMEBACK-1, 8-14 -- Mark Lemke, who used to play second
base for the Atlanta Braves when it won four National League
pennants and a World Series, pitching for the New Jersey Jackals
against the Waterbury Spirit from Connecticut. At 34, Lemke is
attempting a comeback by embarking on the most offbeat path known
to the sport, a path that requires years of practice and the
ability to embrace the mystical. Lemke wants to be a knuckleball
pitcher. (Michelle V. Agins/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) PRISTINA, Yugoslavia -- Aug. 14, 1999 -- KOSOVO-NOTEBOOK,
8-14 --In a calmer Kosovo, Albanians shop freely at night in
Pristina while the Serbs hide. Now, with the postwar cycle of
revenge, fewer than 2,000 Serbs remain in Pristina, according to
the U.N. high commissioner for refugees, from a prewar population
estimated at 40,000. Peacekeeping soldiers are now putting metal
grilles over Serbs' windows and doors to protect them, and
sometimes even moving into buildings where Serbs lived. (Tyler
Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ROSEVILLE, Calif. -- Aug. 14, 1999 -- CATHOLIC-RADIO,
8-14 -- Dan Lungren, the former Attorney General of California,
broadcasting on the Catholic Family Radio network, from his home in
Roseville. Lungren has joined other politicians, psychologists and
pundits as hosts of the network's talk shows. The network began
broadcasting in January and has already bought stations in eight
cities and expects to take over stations in six more next month.
The format is all-talk, and the hosts include pundits,
psychologists and politicians. (Don Preisler/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOSTON -- August 14, 1999 -- BOSTON-COLLEGE-FEMINIST,
8-14 -- Prof. Mary Daly, who is widely considered the world's
foremost radical feminist philosopher and theologian, has barred
men from her classroom at Boston College for some 20 years, arguing
that they marred the learning experience of women. Daly who has
long defied the administration at Boston College, is challenging
her forced retirement at age 70. (Pat Greenhouse/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LITTLETON, Colo. -- August 14, 1999 --
COLUMBINE-REOPEN-3, 8-14 -- Crosses and American flags for the
victims of the Columbine shooting grace the Chapel Hill Cemetery in
Littleton. Columbine High School will open its doors on Monday for
the school year, just four months after the deadly attack in which
two teen-agers shot and killed a dozen other students and a teacher
last April 20, and then took their own lives. Columbine faces the
rather daunting challenge of seeking normalcy in a place that could
never be the same after what happened there. (Joe Poellot/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LITTLETON, Colo. -- August 14, 1999 --
COLUMBINE-REOPEN-2, 8-14 -- Jack Swanzy, the architect for
Jefferson County Schools, describes how lockers were used in
Columbine High School to seal off the library, the site of the
shooting that left 15 dead, including the gunmen, Eric Harris, 18,
and Dylan Klebold, 17, members of the so-called trench coat mafia.
Columbine High School will open its doors on Monday for the school
year. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) LITTLETON, Colo. -- August 14, 1999 --
COLUMBINE-REOPEN-1, 8-14 -- Crosses for 13 victims of the Columbine
shooting grace the Chapel Hill Cemetery in Littleton. Columbine
High School will open its doors on Monday for the school year, just
four months after the deadly attack in which two teen-agers shot
and killed a dozen other students and a teacher last April 20, and
then took their own lives. Columbine faces the rather daunting
challenge of seeking normalcy in a place that could never be the
same after what happened there. (Joe Poellot/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
