<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NJ-RIVERWALK-REAL-3RD     08-14 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-RIVERWALK-REAL-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: is awaited.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The federal court case is not the only legal skirmish on the
issue. On July 9, ruling in an action brought by Shelter Bay, a
279-apartment condominium in Edgewater, the Appellate Division of
New Jersey Superior Court affirmed an environmental department
order that fences blocking access to that community's stretch of
the pathway come down.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Benjamin Goldman, an author of books on
development and the environment, stood beside the padlocked,
barbed-wire-topped fence that blocks the walkway at Shelter Bay's
southern edge. Yanking on the padlock, Goldman, a recent resident
of Weehawken, five miles to the south, said, ``This is what we want
to avoid in our town.''
</P>
<P>
   Weehawken, he said, ``is just about the last stretch of
undeveloped land along the river _ 1.5 miles of blank slate.'' Two
developments with 1,643 units in six- to eight-story buildings
along with 40 town houses have been proposed for construction on
the Weehawken waterfront, right up to the walkway.
</P>
<P>
   The key, Goldman said, is to separate the public space from the
private space by building a road between any new development and a
waterfront park. ``An example of it done right is Riverside Park in
Manhattan,'' he said, ``and the only other place along the Jersey
side of the Hudson where this has been done is Hoboken _ the
waterfront park and walkway there.''
</P>
<P>
   Janiszewski, the Hudson County executive, has a grander plan,
one he believes would bring peace to the public-private fight while
finally threading all the gems on the waterfront necklace.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for the towns along the river to enter into an
inter-local government agreement, permitting the county to oversee
construction of the entire walkway _ a project that Janiszewski
guesses would cost about $80 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``In return,'' he said, ``the municipalities get input into a
common design, and a walkway in their lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, all the property owners would have to sign
easement agreements with the county. ``Developers get an asset,''
Janiszewski said. ``It's easier to market the property with the
walkway present. And instead of a cash outlay at the beginning of
their project, the walkway would be constructed by Hudson County as
a public entity with access to tax-exempt bonds.''
</P>
<P>
   The county could also apply for state and federal grants,
including money from New Jersey's Open Space Trust Fund, ``which
could, in turn, write down the estimated cost, probably by $20
million to $40 million,'' Janiszewski said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will describe the walkway as a linear park,'' he said,
``and whatever the gap between grant dollars and the bottom line
cost will be made up by the developers. That is their incentive for
the easement agreement; they still own the land at the end of the
day.''
</P>
<P>
   One last piece of the puzzle. ``My proposal would be,''
Janiszewski said, ``that the walkway be given over to a
conservancy, some nonprofit entity responsible for maintaining the
walkway.'' Revenues generated along the walkway _ from refreshment
kiosks, for example _ ``would go to the conservancy, and the
difference in maintenance costs vs. revenues received would be
rolled into developers' costs,'' the county executive said.
</P>
<P>
   Seated in a swing chair in her zig of the zigzag building line
of attached town houses at Jacob's Ferry _ an architectural device
developers employ to maximize the number of views of the waterfront
_ Alexandra Kehayas said she favored public access. But she did
have some concerns, she said, ``that once the walkway is all
connected there may be through traffic on bikes, Rollerblades,
while children are playing in the area.''
</P>
<P>
   Many an evening, Ms. Kehayas, a nutritionist, and her husband,
Peter, chief operating engineer for an insurance company, ``sit on
the deck, read the paper and relax after work.''
</P>
<P>
   From there they can gaze at New York and the night-lit glitter
of the city's silhouette. ``I'm so lucky that I can see this,'' she
said. ``It's a beautiful skyline; it should be shared by all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
