<HEADER>
A7388 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-GUNBERGER-NYT &LR;      08-14 0362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GUNBERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEZIDER GRUNBERGER, 77, CANCER RESEARCHER AND COLUMBIA PROFESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dezider Grunberger, a cancer researcher and professor emeritus
of biochemistry, molecular biophysics and public health at the
Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons, died on
Aug. 7 at a nursing home in Cresskill, N.J. He was 77 and lived in
Teaneck, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was colon cancer, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Grunberger's investigations focused on chemical
carcinogens and the mechanism by which they cause cancer.
</P>
<P>
   He studied the correlation between the structure of DNA as
modified by carcinogens and types of mutations induced in multicell
organisms.
</P>
<P>
   He helped develop antitumor drugs based on propolis, also known
as bee glue, a brownish, waxy substance collected by bees from the
buds of certain trees and used to caulk beehives. Propolis has long
served as a folk remedy for various ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Grunberger helped to explain the active elements in propolis. He
also shed new light on unusual DNA bases and atypical conformations
of DNA itself.
</P>
<P>
   Dezider ``Dijon'' Grunberger was born in the ancient town of
Kosice, then part of Czechoslovakia and now part of eastern
Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
   He earned a master's degree in inorganic chemistry at the
University of Prague in 1950 and a Ph.D. (1956) and D.Sc. (1968) in
biochemistry at the Czechoslovak Academy of Sciences in Prague,
where he later became the founding director of the academy's
radioisotope laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   In 1964, he made his first trip to the United States, to work
for the National Institutes of Health for a year, and began his
long association with Columbia's Comprehensive Cancer Center.
</P>
<P>
   He settled in this country in 1968 and rose through the academic
ranks to become a professor of biochemistry and biophysics and
deputy director of the cancer research center.
</P>
<P>
   Grunberger is survived by his wife of 50 years, Marta Herman
Grunberger; two sons, Dr. George Grunberger of Grosse Pointe,
Mich., and Dr. Ivan Grunberger of Cresskill; a sister, Edith Taus
of Munich; and five grandchildren. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
