<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-FORT-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: CAVALRY POST NEAR CHICAGO DONS CIVVIES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JILL SCHACHNER CHANEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIGHLAND PARK, Ill. _ As a child growing up in this North Shore
suburb outside Chicago, Richard Stein used to sneak up to the
perimeter of the Fort Sheridan Army base on the north end of town,
press his face into the fence and wonder what went on inside the
military property. Now he knows.
</P>
<P>
   Stein, 60, is one of three developers helping to revive the
shuttered military base by turning Fort Sheridan into a residential
community along Lake Michigan. When completed, the Town of Fort
Sheridan, as the base will be called, will have 551 residences,
including new and renovated single-family homes, town houses and
apartments. More than half of the units are being created inside
the one-time cavalry base's century-old structures.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a singular opportunity for a developer to create a
new community on the lakefront,'' said Stein, senior managing
director of Mesirow Stein Real Estate Inc., a division of the
Chicago-based Mesirow Financial. Stein bought an ammunition storage
bunker last year and converted it into a 6,500-square-foot,
three-bedroom residence that he now calls home.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 220 units in the $220-million development have been
built and sold. Bruce Abrams, president of the LR Development
Co &UR; . &LR; , another of Fort Sheridan's developers, says that the
developers are using $25 million of their own money and traditional
construction loans from banks to finance the rest of the project,
which should be completed within the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   Built at the end of the 19th century, Fort Sheridan was
decommissioned and closed in 1993, leaving behind the only
undeveloped large parcel of land on Chicago's affluent North Shore.
Because the 240-acre base has national historic landmark status,
the developers were faced with integrating 94 protected structures
into the development, including officers' quarters, cavalry stables
and barracks.
</P>
<P>
   The base received landmark status in part because many of its
buildings represented the first work of the Chicago architectural
firm of Holabird &AMP; Roche, among the originators of the Chicago
School of Architecture. The firm's other buildings include the
Palmer House Hotel in Chicago and the Chicago Hilton and Towers.
</P>
<P>
   Ossian Simonds, an influential turn-of-the-century Chicago land
planner, worked with the architects to incorporate elements of
Prairie theory _ using native plants and trees in a cultured
landscape _ in the overall design of the base, said David Hoffman,
chairman of the Red Seal Development Corp &UR; . &LR; , a principal in the
development team.
</P>
<P>
   As originally designed, Fort Sheridan was a series of rank- and
function-based neighborhoods centered around a parade ground.
Residential structures bordered the parade ground, with the
stables, ammunition storage bunkers, warehouses and other support
buildings hidden behind the soldiers' barracks on the south end of
the fort.
</P>
<P>
   As the mission of the Army base changed over time from a cavalry
base to a temporary hospital to an administrative center, so did
the historic structures. Most were reconfigured internally for
nonresidential uses. New buildings were also built, with little
thought given to the fort's design or the preservation of its
history, said Howard Decker of DLK Architecture in Chicago, the
project's historian and master architect.
</P>
<P>
   When the developers acquired the property, their first priority
was to restore a sense of history lost over the years. They used
the original neighborhood designs and land planning as guideposts
in creating different types of housing. The five neighborhoods will
have common building materials and colors _ with a total of $6
million in landscaping _ based on the writings of Simonds, the land
planner. The design includes a restored ravine, a bird rookery and
indigenous plants and flowers. The parade ground will be
incorporated into a new golf course designed by Robert Trent Jones.
</P>
<P>
   To further restore the fort's historic character, the developers
narrowed the roads to the width they were when horses were the only
mode of transportation on the base. Street lighting and signage are
similar to the types used when the base was first built.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Sheridan's most exclusive neighborhood, as both an Army
base and as a new residential community, sits on a wooded bluff
overlooking Lake Michigan to the east of the parade grounds. There
a visitor will find the 28 original married officers' quarters, set
on three cul-de-sacs.
</P>
<P>
   Red Seal Homes, a developer of upscale housing on the North
Shore, is building 22 estate homes on new cul-de-sacs on lake-view
property surrounding the mansions. The homes, with 3,000 to 5,000
square feet, will range from $815,000 to more than $1 million. Six
have been sold, with construction to begin in the fall, Hoffman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman also found a strong market for the historic officers'
mansions. All of them were sold in ``as is'' condition for $300,000
to $1 million. The Romanesque Revival-style houses ranged from
3,600 to 8,000 square feet and are distinguishable only by the
number of windows on the third floor: One window signified a
lieutenant's home; two windows a captain's.
</P>
<P>
   Because the mansions required significant rehabilitation, many
of the homes have been sold to other developers who are renovating
them on a speculative basis, says Neil Fortunato, president of
Fortunato Builders in Chicago, who recently moved into a
3,600-square-foot lieutenant's mansion that he renovated for
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunato, whose father was once stationed at the base, bought
his home for $370,000 and invested $300,000 more in the renovation.
``The fort is a spectacular property,'' Fortunato said. ``It is
right off the lake. You can hear the waves. It is an amazing
setting.''
</P>
<P>
   From his living-room window, Fortunato can see the fort's
barracks and kitchen buildings, which are being transformed into
loft apartments. When completed, the lofts will range from 1,296 to
2,753 square feet, with prices beginning at $260,000. Many of the
apartments have lofted second floors and exposed brick walls and
wooden trusses.
</P>
<P>
   Marci Morrison and her husband, Greg, bought a
2,500-square-foot, three-bedroom home in the Ravinia neighborhood
of the fort after looking for houses in the surrounding suburbs.
They had found nothing comparable to the development.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fell in love with it as soon as we saw the area,'' Ms.
Morrison said. `` Plus, we are in the middle of history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
