<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7394 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NEWYORKER-MOVE-NYT &LR;      08-14 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWYORKER-MOVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW YORKER JOINS GLOSSY NEIGHBORS IN NEW TIMES SQUARE TOWER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Friday at noon, the phones at the offices of The
New Yorker rang for the last time.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 p.m., Certified Moving vans arrived at 20 West 43rd Street,
and movers began loading several hundred boxes of books, galleys,
correspondence, manuscripts, rejection notices, artwork and memos
from some of the country's most august writers.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the magazine will reopen in new quarters on Times
Square.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time the magazine will share office space with
any other publication, let alone its fat, glossy compatriots at
Conde Nast, titles like Vogue and Allure that tend to evoke J.
Peterman more than S.J. Perelman.
</P>
<P>
   The move, and all that it seemed to symbolize, caused at least a
minor flash of panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not talk about it,'' said one editor. Pausing for
several seconds between words, in mock horror, he added: ``I ... am
... in ... complete ... denial.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Conde Nast bought The New Yorker in 1984, S.I.
Newhouse Jr., the chairman of the company, has allowed the magazine
to remain on its own turf: first, in the magazine's famously grubby
offices at 25 West 43rd Street, and since 1991, in a more polished
environment _ slightly more corporate but still redolent with
writerly gentility _ across the street at No. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the magazine that has published the socially significant
writing of E.B. White, Dorothy Parker, James Baldwin, J.D. Salinger
and scores of other famous authors will inhabit the gleaming
citadel of Conde Nast, a chrome-and-glass lipstick tube of an
office building.
</P>
<P>
   The prized possessions left early: the plaster walls bearing
sketches by James Thurber, now encased in Plexiglas, were moved
last Monday and remain under the watchful eyes of security guards
at their new home on the 21st floor of 4 Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   The staff members were both nostalgic and nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Garrison, an editor who has worked at both the 25 West
43rd Street and 20 West 43rd Street offices, was packing her
belongings early Thursday morning. Even though her new office is
appreciably smaller than the one she was vacating (complete with
panoramic views of the New York Public Library and the lush
greenery of Bryant Park), Ms. Garrison nevertheless planned to take
along her Correction Selectric III typewriter circa 1975, a box of
Case Duplicating Supply Inc. carbon paper and a stack of pink
routing slips, items of arcana that date back to the days when
William Shawn was editor.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Garrison also planned to bring along ``the shrink couch'' _
so named ``because sometimes you'd come in here and find distraught
writers curled up on it in the morning,'' she said _ but wondered
aloud whether it would be allowed into the sleek new headquarters
unless it was stylishly slipcovered beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were traumatized about moving here,'' she said, placing
heavy emphasis on the word ``here'' and gesturing to the
soon-to-be-vacant hallways. ``But at least this was a similar
prewar building, with rambling offices, and felt like a dusty
English department.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Garrison looked westward and uttered something that sounded
an awful lot like, ``I guess now we'll be corporatized.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday afternoon, David Remnick, the editor of The New
Yorker, made a short speech to the magazine's staff in the
16th-floor reception area. Some people drank champagne, and some
drank Corona beer, but all heard Remnick's message loud and clear:
The New Yorker is not about brick and glass. It's about the spirit
of the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't help but feel a pang in your heart whenever you move
from a place that's been home, but bricks and mortar are not the
soul of The New Yorker,'' Remnick said in an interview. ``The soul
is its writers and artists and everyone who contributes to it. Our
readers will see that the soul of The New Yorker will flourish,
too, on Times Square.''
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult, however, to flourish without bookshelves. When
Remnick and The New Yorker's deputy editor, Pamela Maffei McCarthy,
inspected the standardized new space, they discovered a serious
lack of bookshelves, and had to request that architects design and
build four times as many bookshelves for their offices. There are
also fewer offices for writers, so staff writers like John McPhee
and Kurt Andersen gave up their spaces and said they would write
from home.
</P>
<P>
   And the writers, for the first time, will inhabit the same floor
as The New Yorker's business staff, which one editor said made him
feel ``a little queasy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The New Yorker staff has other practical issues to worry about.
Since the other Conde Nast magazines have moved in, their staff
members have complained heartily about problems as various as the
standardized file cabinets in every office, which are built for
European-size file folders, and the lack of restaurants that will
construct and deliver custom-made, dressing-free salads.
</P>
<P>
   But there seemed to be some higher power at work in the offices
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The day before, a color-Xeroxed photograph of Harold Ross, The
New Yorker's first editor, was Scotch-taped to the door frame of
Ms. McCarthy's office. When Ross died in 1951, rumors abounded that
The New Yorker would die with him, so the sudden unexplained
appearance of his ghostly portrait _ like an urbane, literary
Shroud of Turin _ seemed portentous.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCarthy said she had no idea how it got there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appeared there during the night,'' she said Friday, as she
placed one of the final phone calls before her phone was
disconnected at noon. ``I think it is someone's idea of a quiet
homage to Harold Ross. And you know what? I'm going to leave it up
there. It will be the only thing left of me and my time here when I
walk out the door.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 1836EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
