<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7404 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-HUNTER-NY     08-14 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-HUNTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.) 
FORMER TEAMMATES RECALL AILING HUNTER'S CLASS AND QUIET INFLUENCE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They talked the most about the teammate who wasn't
there. Not Joe DiMaggio, who before he died in March had become a
fixture at the Yankees' old-timers' days. Not Thurman Munson, whose
death 20 years ago in a plane crash deprived them of part of the
heart of their team. No, the teammate they talked about was Jim
(Catfish) Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being at Yankee Stadium on Saturday swapping old war
stories about the Yankee teams of the '70s, Hunter was lying in a
North Carolina hospital, his body not only deteriorating from Lou
Gehrig's disease but his brain also suffering from the bruise he
incurred when he fell down concrete steps at his home in Hertford.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the subject of a lot of conversation at dinner last
night,'' Rich (Goose) Gossage said. ``Everybody was very concerned
about him. To see what he's going through now is a killer. It
brings tears to your eyes. No one should have to go through that.''
</P>
<P>
   But no tears were shed in the Yankees' clubhouse before the
old-timers ceremonies. Hunter's former teammates talked glowingly
and lovingly of him and wished he could have been there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just doesn't mean the same,'' Ron Guidry said of
Old-Timers' Day without Hunter. ``I enjoy coming here, but when you
think of him, it doesn't mean as much as it used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Guidry and Gossage, two of many ``old-timers'' from the World
Series championship teams of the '70s, both spoke of what Hunter
meant to them as pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was a better class guy that you ever saw pitch, I
haven't seen him yet,'' Guidry said. ``He was probably the
consummate class guy. I used to kind of emulate him. I watched that
man pitch for years. When I watched him walk in that door, I didn't
know if the game was over, if he was winning, 1-0, if he was
losing, 10-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd watch him walk over there, take his glove, lay it down,
sit down, undress. I never saw him come in here firing, cussing,
screaming and hollering. It was a lesson learned. It's not your
fault if you give up runs or you lose the game. He didn't feel he
had to take it out on anything if it didn't work out. It's just
that it didn't work out today. I learned a lot just watching him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage learned from Hunter even before they became teammates
with the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember him with the Oakland A's,'' the former relief
pitcher said. ``For a young pitcher like myself, watching him go
about his business, that's how I learned to play the game, from
guys like him. When Catfish was on the mound, we were there to
watch, take notice and learn something. The way he conducted
himself on the mound was the way he represented himself off the
field, too. And he never wanted the light; just let me do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Guidry especially recalled how Hunter did his job when he came
back from an arm ailment for the latter part of the 1978 season.
That was the season in which Guidry established himself as the best
pitcher in the American League, winning 25 games and losing a mere
three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even as good as my year was,'' the Louisiana left-hander said,
``I still say it wasn't because of me; it was because of him that
we won. He came back when we had nobody. Who would we have had
pitch in his place if he wasn't here to win the games that he won?
The only game he lost after he came back was the last day. If we
had lost one game in there, we would never have won.''
</P>
<P>
   Guidry said he and Hunter were more than teammates. They were
good friends, much of the relationship stemming from their love of
hunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I pick up a shotgun to go hunting, I automatically think
about Jimmy,'' Guidry said. ``I wonder what he's doing today. I
wonder if he's hunting this morning. I wonder if he's thinking
about me hunting. That's a good thing to think about early in the
morning. It would bring some good thoughts into my head.''
</P>
<P>
   As a teammate, Hunter was noted for more than his pitching. He
was considered the best at needling other players. He saved his
best arrows for Lou Piniella.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the best at getting on people,'' said Mickey Rivers,
who was pretty good himself, especially with Reggie Jackson as his
target. ``When he started on Lou, we just took it from there. He
knew exactly how to hit the nail.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage fondly recalled the verbal scraps between Hunter and
Piniella.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and Lou used to go at it on the bus rides and the plane,''
Gossage said. ``They'd go back and forth. Cat was all over Lou. Lou
would always do this'' _ run his hand through the hair on the back
of his head _ ``and smell his fingers. Cat would be all over him.
He'd say, `Lou, what's that smell like, man?'''
</P>
<P>
   His former teammates would welcome the opportunity to hear
Hunter's North Carolina voice needle anybody just one more time.
</P>
</TEXT>
