<SLUG> BC-PERU-ECUADOR-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTS OF PERU AND ECUADOR END VISIT WITH SHOW OF UNITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: ADDS two grafs with background on treaty, last war.) (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ko) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ As recently as one year ago, Peru and Ecuador were
preparing to go to war, something they have done with regularity
ever since the Peruvian Navy blockaded Ecuador's principal port in
1860.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign that the squabbling neighbors are finally learning
to live together, Ecuador President Jamil Mahuad finished a
three-day visit through Peru on Friday _ complete with banquets,
honorary university degrees, tropical river fishing and a triumphal
tour through downtown Lima arm in arm with President Alberto K.
Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
   Troubled by a failing economy and increasing protests at home,
Mahuad came to Peru to consolidate the gains won in October when
the two countries signed a peace treaty brokered by the United
States, Brazil, Argentina and Chile to settle a longstanding border
dispute over a 50-mile swath of the Condor Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The two presidents were jeered at on Friday as they drove
through Iquitos in the Peruvian Amazon by hundreds of protesters
who say the treaty gives Ecuador too many commercial rights in
their region. But most experts called the visit a success that
augurs well for future relations.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori and Mahuad dressed in matching red sport shirts and
donned Indian headdresses to pose for photographers in a dugout
canoe on an Amazon tributary. And they met with residents of the
jungle town of Sarameriza to announce the construction of a port
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patriotism searches for development,'' Fujimori said as Mahuad
smiled widely. Then Fujimori called for a show of hands of those
opposed to opening river commerce to Ecuadoreans. No one voted
against the Peruvian President, Fujimori noted, ``not even
Mahuad.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a backhanded slap at political leaders of the area who
oppose the thaw with Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our friend President Mahuad is Arab and I am half Japanese,''
Fujimori said, ``but we speak the same language.''
</P>
<P>
   The two presidents announced an assortment of joint projects,
including the extension of parks, construction of river port
installations, bridges, roads, schools and clinics that will total
up to $3 billion over several years. They also signed a free-trade
agreement that will remove tariffs from 585 agricultural, consumer
and industrial goods.
</P>
<P>
   The October treaty sets a permanent border along the Cordillera
del Condor mountain range, as Peru always demanded. Ecuador gained
access to a piece of territory on the Peruvian side to commemorate
its war dead at a memorial site in Tiwinza, as well as navigation
and trade rights in the Peruvian river ports of Sarameriza and
Pijuayal.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the two countries went to war _ in 1995 _ 100
people were killed in four weeks of conflict. The fighting led to
an expensive arms buildup in both Peru and Ecuador. Experts say
peace will allow them to reduce the size of their militaries, which
will help their economies and strengthen civilian rule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
