<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7432 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-DAGESTAN-BOS-F     08-14 1581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-DAGESTAN-BOS-FIRST </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA WARNS MUSLIM STATES ON DAGESTAN 
</HEADLINE>
 LEDE WRITE THROUGH  
( Eds: Corrects Muslin to Muslim   in 3rd graf)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Saying it had proof of Islamic financial support to
separatist rebels in Russia's strife-torn Caucasus, Russia issued a
blunt warning Saturday to Muslim states: Hands off Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   But as the fighting widens along Russia's volatile southern rim,
analysts said the focus on foreign scapegoats overlooks Moscow's
broader problem: It has neglected the vast extremes of the world's
largest nation, and Dagestan's uprising may just reflect the
tensions that could tear Russia apart, bit by bit.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement that highlights Moscow's concern over the armed
uprising in its strategically important Caucasus region, Russia's
acting foreign minister, Igor Ivanov, lashed out at unspecified
foreign backers of the militants who have occupied parts of
Dagestan and declared the area an independent Muslim state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that any form of support for the terrorists'
actions will be viewed as rude interference in the internal affairs
of the Russian Federation, with all the logical consequences,''
Ivanov wrote in a letter addressed to the UN Secretary General Kofi
Annan, major Western nations and several Muslim states. Ivanov
urged Islamic countries to condemn those who are ``trying to use
Islam to camouflage open banditism.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov said Moscow had hard evidence that the rebels were
receiving aid from abroad, although he offered none of it.
Speculation has been rife that foreign backers were behind the
rebels ever since up to 2,000 well-armed militants crossed into
Dagestan from neighboring Chechnya on Aug. 7. The Russian media has
reported, without substantiation, that reputed Saudi terrorist
Osama bin Laden has spent $25 million training and equipping the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The reports overshadow experts' warnings that Moscow caused its
own problems in the Caucasus by neglecting to solve the volatile
regions' complex ethnic, social and economic problems until it was
too late. They say the federal government is too weak, too poor,
and too distracted with its own internal battles to spend the time
and effort need to in restive regions like Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a foreign problem, this is all a result of the
extreme weakness of the state in Russia,'' said Nikolai Petrov,
political analyst at the Moscow Carnegie Center think tank.
``Dagestan is the weakest link, and it has specfic problems _ but
that doesn't take away from the fact that this problem is a result
of a problem that affects the whole country.''
</P>
<P>
   Petrov said it was characteristic that as heavy fighting broke
out between federal troops and the rebels last Monday, Moscow was
absorbed with a new political crisis caused when Yeltsin abruptly
toppled his fourth government in 17 months.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, politicians have begun to sound the alarm. The
apperance of Muslim separatists on its own territory is a nightmare
scenario in a Russia that views radical Islamic expansion as its
main regional security threat.
</P>
<P>
   An uprising in the country's most restive region throws a wrench
in Russia's geopolitical dreams of controlling Caspian oil riches
through pipelines that run through Dagestan and thus maintaining
influence over its former Soviet neighbors in Central Asia and the
Transcaucasus. Oil analyst Euan Craik said Russia ``risks
completely being sidelined'' as oil companies turn to alternatives
to the Dagestan route.
</P>
<P>
   And after Moscow failed in a bloody 1994-1996 campaign to put
down a separatist rebellion in next-door Chechnya, many in Russia
believe the losing control any more territory could shatter the
fragile federal system upon which this vast, nuclear-armed country
is built.
</P>
<P>
   ``The breakup of Russia is knocking at the door,'' remarked
Yegor Stroyev, the speaker of Russia's upper house of parliament,
the Federation Council.
</P>
<P>
   The house's members, made up of leaders of Russia's 89
constituent regions and republics, have been calling for tough
action from the Kremlin to halt the rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin has obliged, launching heavy air and artillery
strikes against the insurgents that military officials say have
begun to take their toll. Interior Minstry spokesman Yevgeny
Ryabtsev said in Makhachkala, Dagestan's capital, that the
militants were beginning to show signs of ``panic'' after
sustaining the loss of over 200 men in fighting. But he added that
four Russian paratroopers had been killed and another 13 wounded in
the course of a seven-hour battle on Dagestan's rugged, mountainous
border with Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels, who have their own Internet site and supply daily
footage of their operations in Dagestan to Russian television
companies, say Russia has lost dozens of men while only five rebels
have died. On Saturday, the rebels' Web site said their Islamic
council, or Shura, had decided to open a criminal investigation
against acting Prime Minister Vladimir Putin and other senior
Russian officials.
</P>
<P>
   Federal commanders say they will be able to drive the rebels
from Dagestan within two weeks. But they say the conflict is been
complicated by the help they say the separatists are getting.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are dealing with is a massive invasion by bandit
formations,'' Lieutenant General Igor Zubov of Russia's Interior
Minister said last week. ``They have been nourished with the help
of money received from abroad. The sums are roughly known to us _
millions of dollars have been invested in this operation. All the
participants have already received their renumeration. There is a
big number of mercenaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian media have repeated the allegations that the rebels'
Chechen commanders, Shamil Basayev and Khattab, have received
foreign financing for the operation in Dagestan. Respected
newspaper Kommersant Daily reported last week that individual
fighters receive $100 per day and $300 if they are wounded, huge
sums in the impoverished mountain villages of Dagestan and
Chechnya, where unemployment is over 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment is the spark inflaming this fight, critics say.
Alexander Iskandaryan, director of the Institute of Caucasus
Studies, said Russia may be able to fight off Basayev and Khattab,
but a successful police and military action against the rebels will
not end the malaise that fuels radical Islamic movements in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many young people with no land, no jobs, no
prospects and little education,'' Iskandaryan says. ``People in
South America in such conditions turn to Marxism. People in the
Caucasus turn to radical Islam.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Chechen-led rebels arrived in Dagestan, a
radical Muslim sect known as the Wahhabis had taken control of
entire regions, establishing Muslim Sharia rule and refusing to
obey Russian laws.
</P>
<P>
   Khattab and Baseyev will go away, but the people in these
villages will still be there, ``and central authority will become
weaker and weaker,'' Iskandaryan said.
</P>
<P>
   He says the solution would be for the federal government to help
fund jobs and education, and to support mainstream Islamic groups.
But he acknowledges that the state has no money for such projects.
And he added it was hard to imagine Russia's Orthodox Christian
majority supporting the idea of spending state funds building
Islamic schools.
</P>
<P>
   For many Russians, the Caucasus are a foreign, frightening
place. Opinion polls routinely show that most Russian distrust
their countrymen from the Caucasus. And few Russians can tell the
difference between Chechens and and any of the 40 ethnic groups
that make up Dagestan's population. This was the point the Moscow
newspaper Vremya MN made when it printed a photograph of a bunch of
tough looking, heavily armed men in combat fatigues and dark
glasses. ``These are not Islamic militants,'' read the caption.
``They are Dagestani police.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, people from the Caucasus have trouble travelling to
Russia to find work, according to Fiona Hill, director of Harvard
University's Strengthening Democratic Institutions project. They
are often the victims of racist police and residence requirements.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Chechnya. Fighting there ended in 1996, but
Chechnya remains isolated, blockade and unreconstructed _ and
therefore a lawless place where armed gangs hold sway.
</P>
<P>
   Dagestanis do not want this, and many did not welcome the
militants' invasion. Mukhu Aliyev, speaker of Dagestan's National
Assembly, said Thursday that anti-Chechen sentiment is far stronger
than anti-Russian moods among the region's two million mainly
Muslim residents.
</P>
<P>
   That could all change if Russia's military starts killing
civilians and destroying towns and villages, the way it did in
Chechnya in 1995 and 1996, where 80,000 people died. So far,
Moscow's forces have avoided that.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia may have already committed a deadly mistake by
sanctioning the arming of Dagestan militias that have volunteered
to help federal troops fight off the intruders.
</P>
<P>
   Such handouts of weapons could ignite a larger conflict among
Dagestan's ethnic groups spreading to neighboring regions along
Russia's border with Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an open road to civil war,'' Major General Nikolai
Bezborodov, a member of the Russian parliament's defense committee,
told The Moscow Times last week. ``It will simply turn the whole
area into a battlefield.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
