<HEADER>
A7435 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-COLOMBIA-COMIC-BOS &LR;      08-14 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-COMIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOMBIANS SHED TEARS FOR A CLOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIRK SEMPLE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA _ In a country where conflict characterizes daily life,
Colombians of all classes and occupations came together Saturday to
pay final respects to a beloved humorist who was assassinated
Friday on his way to work.
</P>
<P>
   Social and political satirist Jaime Garzon, who also worked as
an intermediary between the government and leftist rebels, was
slain during increasing violence between the government, rebels,
and right-wing paramilitary forces.
</P>
<P>
   In an event that had many of the trappings of a state funeral,
tens of thousands thronged Bogota's main square, many of whom had
passed by Garzon's coffin in the colonnaded entranceway of the
Capitol. The crowd demonstrated against the civil strife that has
claimed 35,000 people in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   So many people showed up under overcast skies that officials at
the main cathedral moved his Mass outside, before the body was
taken for burial Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The slaying awoke a people numbed to the killings and
kidnappings of a nation at war. ``They Killed The Laugh, What
Next?'' read Saturday's headline in El Tiempo newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``This killing is horrible because we can't understand who did
it,'' said Mariana Shuk, an artist who stood on the Plaza de
Bolivar during the brief Mass. ``Before, there were the good guys
and the bad guys. But with all the forces at work now _ the army,
the paramilitary, the guerrillas _ we don't know where it came
from.''
</P>
<P>
   Garzon, 38, was one of the few Colombians who managed to bridge
all sectors of this stratified society. He was friends with the
president, yet played comic characters such as a shoeshine man and
a doorman. He impersonated and lampooned the nation's famous yet
was not too cynical to help with a nascent peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   No one was spared his acerbic wit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made fun of everybody,'' Shuk said. ``This guy was a friend
of everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in the crowd of 60,000 or so carried small white flags that
said ``No More'' _ a reference to the civil war, in which the US
military has played a role working with the Colombian military.
Washington's main concern in the war is
</P>
<P>
   the rebels' protection of cultivators, producers, and US-bound
smugglers of cocaine and heroin.
</P>
<P>
   Many Colombians already despair of a peaceful end to the
violence, a goal of President Andres Pastrana.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard the news'' of Garzon's killing, said magazine
editor Ana Maria Londono, ``I thought, `Where is this country
going?' I don't want to have children here!''
</P>
<P>
   A cabbie who gave his name as Jorge said Garzon's death
reinforced another lesson about life in Bogota. ``Here you can't
speak about anyone because they'll kill you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Garzon was shot by two gunmen on a motorcycle Friday morning as
he was driving to the Radionet station in downtown Bogota, where he
hosted a popular morning program, police said. Police have
impounded nearly 1,000 motorcycles in the investigation and are not
ruling out any suspects in the slaying, which several politicians
have attributed to the right-wing paramilitary groups.
</P>
<P>
   Shrines took form at several locations in the capital.
Throughout Friday and Saturday, mourners placed flowers, written
eulogies, candles, and religious images in front of the comedian's
apartment, at his favorite restaurant, and near the scene of the
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the night, listeners from around the country and the
world called Radionet to offer their condolences and remembrances.
</P>
<P>
   Among the thousands who waited in a two-hour line to pass by
Garzon's coffin was Senen Fernandez, 33, who said the comic helped
make a depressing nation tolerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had it up to here,'' he said. ``I'm a chef, but I'm
working these days as a messenger. I've been thinking about moving
to France.''
</P>
<P>
   His is a common impulse these days in Colombia. The US Embassy
in Bogota has seen a doubling in requests for visitors' visas as a
growing number of Colombians try to flee with plans to remain
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   At Saturday's event, Cesar Osma, a 33-year-old performance clown
by trade, compared the public outpouring to the uproar that
followed the murders of other populist Colombian heros, including
presidential candidates Luis Carlos Galan in 1989 and former
guerrilla Carlos Pizarro in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kill those who fight for the poor,'' he muttered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
