</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SMUGGLE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Detained Chinese staying mum
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Investigators Saturday questioned some of the 132
Chinese men and boys found on a ship in Savannah last week in what
authorities said was the most sophisticated immigrant smuggling
operation in recent Georgia history.
</P>
<P>
   Agents plan more interviews today and Monday with the illegal
immigrants, who are being held in detention facilities in Fulton
and DeKalb counties in suburban Atlanta. Investigators hope to
decide within the next few days whether to file criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service said the
interviews so far have yielded no answers to key questions: Where
were the Chinese going? Was an employer waiting for them?
</P>
<P>
   INS District Director Thomas Fischer said the agents collected
names, dates of birth and other information from the men. The
agency flew Chinese-speaking agents to Atlanta from New York to
help, but Fischer said it was slow going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically the Asians have been very secretive,'' he said.
``They tend not to be as verbose as some other nationalities
regarding their family and anyone who assisted them.''
</P>
<P>
   INS agents found the 132 men and boys Thursday in a secret
compartment on the Prince Nicolas, a ship registered in Cyprus.
Fischer said the ship had sailed from China around the southern tip
of Africa and docked in Stockholm, Sweden, and Copenhagen, Denmark,
before crossing the Atlantic for Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   He said a ship's officer stayed in Stockholm and told Swedish
authorities about the hidden Chinese. The message was relayed to
the U.S. State Department and an INS office in Rome before the
telephone rang in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Cmdr. James Hanzalik of the U.S. Coast Guard, which searched
the ship unsuccessfully before the INS became involved, said crew
members ``were pretty evasive'' when questioned. He said the
illegal immigrants were ``pretty frightened.''
</P>
<P>
   Fischer said he thinks some crew members _ 26 Chinese, a
Lithuanian and a Filipino _ helped smuggle the Chinese. He said
smuggling ships often have an ``enforcer'' aboard to keep
passengers in line.
</P>
<P>
   The INS said Chinese usually pay $30,000 to $50,000 for a trip
to the United States, often living in squalid conditions on voyages
that can take weeks. Organized crime groups in China have been
linked to immigrant smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people weren't just traveling solo,'' Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the INS plans to keep the passengers and crew in custody
until it deports them. Officials will consider any requests for
political asylum, but an INS spokesman said the agency typically
considers Chinese who are being smuggled into this country as
``economic migrants'' ineligible for asylum.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at least five lawyers have volunteered to help the
Chinese navigate the legal maze.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Marshall, a retired lawyer who volunteers at an immigration
clinic sponsored by Catholic Social Services in Atlanta, said he
plans to work with some of the 51 boys ages 14-17 who were among
the detainees on the Prince Nicolas. He said he would explain
immigration law, appear in immigration court on their behalf and
answer their questions about the legal process.
</P>
<P>
   He said he also has helped some Chinese youngsters detained
after authorities busted a smuggling ring near Guam recently. He
said those teenagers have been in custody in Georgia for at least
four months. Based on their experience, he said, the 132 Chinese
found in Savannah probably will be in custody for several months
until an immigration judge decides their fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can take a long time. The INS is just so swamped with all
kinds of work,'' Marshall said. ``This is a very lengthy process.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
