<SLUG> BC-IOWA-POLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWA GOP GETS IT SAY   IN STRAW POLL 
</HEADLINE>
  ( Eds: will update later with results)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMES, Iowa _ There were bikers for George W. Bush and bicyclists
for Lamar Alexander. There were church groups for Gary Bauer and
farmers for former Vice President Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   And there were so many people wearing orange shirts for Steve
Forbes that a campaign supporter suggested they resembled a giant
pack of Reese's Pieces.
</P>
<P>
   This was the quadrennial Iowa Republican straw poll, which
attracted so many voters, candidates and media that it was poised
to live up to the hype _ bigger, louder, and more outrageous than
any before it. Republicans came from across Iowa, using every bus
in the state and many from beyond the borders, to vote for their
favorite candidate.
</P>
<P>
   As the candidates gathered on stage Saturday evening to deliver
their speeches inside the Iowa State University basketball arena,
the crowd of more than 15,000 packed inside Hilton Coliseum roared
when the announcer said: ``On this stage is the next president of
the United States!''
</P>
<P>
   Although the contest is nonbinding, the event seemed destined to
have a significant impact on the race, which until now has been
dominated by the story of front-runner Bush. Forbes aides, watching
a long line of supporters seep into the Bush compound, were looking
for the kind of vote that could recast the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message to the lobbyists and politicians is very clear,''
Forbes, who is self-financing most of his campaign, told a cheering
crowd inside his white, air-conditioned tent. ``Their days are
numbered!''
</P>
<P>
   Fifty or so yards away, Bush, fresh from a morning of fishing at
a nearby park, beamed before a large outdoor crowd feasting of
campaign-supplied barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush aides clearly were nervous about the overflow from the
neighboring Forbes site, especially because Bush has repeatedly
raised expectations by saying that he would place a strong first in
the straw poll.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle launched some of the most direct shots at Bush,
castigating the son of the man who was his running mate in 1988 and
1992. ``The Washington establishment wants to tell you who to vote
for,'' Quayle said. ``They say that issues don't matter. Let's send
them a message.''
</P>
<P>
   The organizers appeared overwhelmed by the turnout, which seemed
larger than the 15,000 expected.
</P>
<P>
   Bus after bus wound through the maze of campaign tents, dropping
off new batches of voters. Dozens of people wore the red shirts of
the Alexander campaign. Over there were a sea of yellow shirts, a
sign of support for Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   The process turned chaotic Saturday, as thousands of people
could barely move along the concourse where party aides took
ballots and stamped the hands of voters with indelible ink in an
effort to prevent the sort of double-voting that has occurred in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush paid $43,000 for his tent site just outside the
Hilton Coliseum, it was Forbes who put on the most elaborate show.
In addition to the air-conditioned tent, the Forbes campaign looked
after children in a giant ``moon bounce'' machine and erected a
climbing wall.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, a former Reagan domestic adviser and head of the
conservative Family Research Council, drew a large following from
church groups, many of which bused in supporters. The Bauer
campaign featured a religious brand of rock, with lyrics such as
``We need to get back to the basics of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Orrin Hatch of Utah, trying to make up for his late
start, brought along Karl Malone, the superstar of the NBA's Utah
Jazz, as well as singer Vic Damone. Quayle, Alexander and Patrick
Buchanan _ all familiar names in Iowa _ were hoping for a big
turnout. Otherwise, their campaigns might in trouble, especially
with fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Radio host Alan Keyes, whose antiabortion views drew sizable
support in the 1995 straw poll, drew strong applause for his attack
on President Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
