u a BC-POLICE-PROFILING-NYT &LR;      08-14 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-PROFILING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE ASSOCIATION SPONSORS DEBATE ON RACIAL PROFILING
</HEADLINE>
  (nk)  
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ When police officials from around the country gathered
here Saturday for a debate on racial profiling, many were surprised
to hear that one side of the issue would be argued by someone with
a white separatist background.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker, Jared Taylor, said at the annual meeting of the
National Association of Police Organizations that law-enforcement
officers were justified in using racial profiling during traffic
stops.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, president of a research organization in Virginia and a
white separatist, said federal statistics showed that a higher
percentage of blacks commit violent crime than whites, and that
officers would be ignoring common sense if they did not take that
into consideration.
</P>
<P>
   That view and Taylor's background were assailed by his debate
opponent, John Crew, a lawyer with the American Civil Liberties
Union in San Francisco, who also chided the group for inviting
Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can throw away proper cause,'' Crew said of stops,
``then I'm wasting my time here.''
</P>
<P>
   Racial profiling, or the targeting of suspects by race or ethnic
background, has become a highly charged issue in the last few
years, after a rising number of complaints that black motorists
were being pulled over by the police in disproportionate numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Conyers Jr., D-Mich., introduced a bill last year that
would have required the police to record the race and ethnicity of
drivers stopped. The bill died.
</P>
<P>
   But after New Jersey Gov. Christie Whitman conceded in April
that some state troopers singled out drivers who were black or
Hispanic for traffic stops and were three times more likely to
search them than white drivers, Conyers reintroduced his bill.
</P>
<P>
   In June, President Clinton ordered federal law enforcement
agencies to compile data on the race and ethnicity of people they
question, search or arrest to determine if certain minorities were
being singled out.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Police Organizations, a nonprofit
group that represents 4,000 law-enforcement unions and
associations, argues that Clinton's directive and Conyers' bill
duplicate federal laws and that the vast majority of officers use
probable cause as the basis for stopping motorists. But the group
offered Taylor and Crew a platform to debate racial profiling as a
component of traffic stops.
</P>
<P>
   Crew told the audience that Taylor's approval of racial
profiling was influenced by his long-held white separatist beliefs.
Crew read the audience several excepts of Taylor's writings from
the Web site of the organization he heads, the New Century
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said on the Web site, in part, that whites face ``the
prospect of oblivion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To celebrate diversity, as we are so often urged to do, is
nothing more than to celebrate our own dwindling numbers and
influence,'' he wrote. ``It is utterly unnatural and will,
ultimately, destroy us.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said he did not recall writing those exact words, but
added, ``I agree with the sentiment.''
</P>
<P>
   He also confirmed that he is a board member of the Council of
Conservative Citizens, a group that includes white supremacists and
received widespread publicity last winter when Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi addressed it.
</P>
<P>
   Crew began his remarks by calling Taylor ``an avowed white
separatist,'' and he chided his hosts by saying, ``inviting an
avowed white separatist here only adds fuel to the fire'' of the
national debate on the targeting of minority motorists.
</P>
<P>
   Robert T. Scully, executive director of the National Association
of Police Organizations, said he was unaware of Taylor's background
when he invited him to debate Crew. Scully said he invited Taylor
to attend after seeing him discuss his views on profiling on
C-Span.
</P>
<P>
   Scully also said the police organization did not subscribe to
Taylor's views.
</P>
<P>
   Nor, apparently, did many of those who listened to the debate,
which lasted about an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found him very offensive,'' said Paul Stewart of the Detroit
Police Officers Association, who is black. ``He was condoning
profiling.''
</P>
<P>
   Pete O'Leary, president of the Suffolk County Detectives
Association on Long Island, a white officer, said: ``His statements
were very inflammatory. They stereotype police officers as racists.
When he was talking, I turned to a colleague of mine and asked him,
`Where's this guy from, the white Aryan Nations?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
