<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-SWORD-DANCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONOR GLIDE WINS SARATOGA'S SWORD DANCER  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ This is what they mean about favorites
and champions walking the gangplank at Saratoga. The 3-5 favorite
to win the $400,000 Sword Dancer Invitational and continue on to
become the country's champion grass horse was Yagli, owned by Allen
Paulson, trained by Bill Mott and ridden by Jerry Bailey, the
people who brought Cigar to his glory.
</P>
<P>
   But it rained heavily Saturday after weeks of drought, the turf
course turned soft, the pace was tantalizingly slow and Yagli
finished seventh and last. In the confusion, the 6-1 shot Honor
Glide won the race by 3\ lengths over Val's Prince.
</P>
<P>
   Yagli had won three straight Grade I stakes this year, and only
two weeks ago won the United Nations Handicap at Monmouth Park. But
Honor Glide, a 5-year-old bay owned by Robert Schaedle and the
Bonnie Heath Farm, had raced only twice this year, both times at
Belmont Park, finishing second in an allowance race in June and
winning the Bowling Green in July.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed to be thriving under his new trainer, Christophe
Clement, though, and his new jockey, Jose Santos. And he thrived
Saturday in the biggest race of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he won the Bowling Green, I said he was very
impressive,'' Clement said, ``and I was pretty sure he would run
well today. The one horse to beat, to me, was obviously Yagli. But
I thought Yagli was vulnerable because I thought it was difficult
to run at that level two weeks apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to run him on a soft turf course, but I was
amazed that the course was `good' to `firm' when I walked it at
2:30. We didn't have enough rain to make it `soft.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, who leads all jockeys at Saratoga in winners, especially
in stakes races, concluded that the turf seemed softer to Yagli
because he was carrying high weight of 125 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He handled the turf reasonably well,'' Bailey said. ``He
bobbled once going into the first turn. The thing that soft ground
does with 125 pounds, it seems more like 130. Down the backside, I
was ready to start creeping up on them. But he wasn't ready to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused, reached back to Cigar for support and added:
``There's only been one horse that I've been around that could win
16 in a row. You've got to give them one bad race, then turn the
page.''
</P>
<P>
   Honor Glide ran the mile and one-half in 2:28 1/5. But Santos
moved Honor Glide into the lead when they turned for home, and he
scored with daylight over Val's Prince, who had another length on
Chorwon. The winner paid $14.60 for a $2 bet to win, and earned
$240,000 for his upset.
</P>
<P>
   FINISH LINES
</P>
<P>
   The three-day auction at Saratoga this past week showed that the
boom in horse sales is still booming. Prices rose 24 percent, to an
average of $251,456 for the 162 horses sold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
