<DOCNO> NYT19990814.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7443 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-TOP25POLL-COX     08-14 0298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TOP25POLL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Voters picking 'Noles, Vols to finish on top
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Florida State and Tennessee ended the 1998 college football
season by playing for the national championship in the Fiesta Bowl.
If you believe the polls, the same two teams will meet for all the
marbles again, this time in the Sugar Bowl on Jan. 4, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State and Tennessee were ranked 1-2 when the 1999
preseason Associated Press poll was released Saturday. The poll
receives votes from 70 sportswriters and broadcasters nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State received 48 first-place votes, while Tennessee got
15 and No. 3 Penn State got four. No. 4 Arizona, No. 5 Florida, and
No. 13 Virginia Tech each received one first-place vote.
</P>
<P>
   The first six teams in Saturday's AP poll were the same as the
USA Today/ESPN coaches poll which was released Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech, ACC co-champs with Florida State in 1999, was
ranked 11th, while Georgia was 14th.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State, which lost to Tennessee 23-16 in the Fiesta Bowl,
returns 16 starters and 58 lettermen. The Seminoles will be going
for their 13th consecutive season of 10 wins or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were close last year but came up short,'' said coach Bobby
Bowden. ``The good thing is I think the guys are pretty hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   With the return of running back Jamal Lewis and a veteran
offensive line, Tennessee has a good chance of winning its third
straight SEC title and getting back into the national championship
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has shown a lot of maturity and that's good,'' said
coach Phillip Fulmer. ``We know what it feels like to win a
championship. Now we want to feel that way again.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
