<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7444 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-VOLS-PREVIEW15-CO     08-14 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-VOLS-PREVIEW15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Road to College Football
 &HT;    Tennessee turns to power game for '99
 &HT;    One in a series on SEC teams
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE _ When Tennessee opens the 1999 season on Sept. 4
against Wyoming, the Volunteers will be trying to become only the
second team since 1979 to repeat as national champions. They'll try
do it by emulating the last team to win back-to-back titles _ the
University of Nebraska (1994-95).
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Tennessee, which lit up the scoreboard through the
air in the 1990s, is going to turn to smash-mouth football as the
decade draws to a close. Coach Phillip Fulmer and the rest of the
Volunteers can hardly contain their glee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait,'' said running back Jamal Lewis, who returns to
the team after missing most of the 1998 season with a knee injury.
``When you look at the running backs we have and our offensive
line, we have to try and pound people. It makes a lot of sense and
we are looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee was a very good running team in 1998. Despite the loss
of Lewis, who missed the last nine games, the Volunteers led the
SEC in rushing, averaging 211.3 yards per game. That was 35 yards a
game better than any other team in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   But a recent visit to campus revealed several reasons why
Tennessee should be good enough to grind it out even more against
SEC opponents in 1999:
</P>
<P>
   _ An offensive line that could be Tennessee's best ever. There
are two strong All-America candidates in guard Cosey Coleman (6
feet 5, 315) and tackle Chad Clifton (6-6, 320). There are two
other strong veterans in center Spencer Riley (6-3, 295) and tackle
Josh Tucker (6-4, 305). Sophomore Fred Weary (6-4, 290) was moved
over from defense and is pushing junior Toby Champion (6-4, 305)
for a starting guard spot. This is also the second year for this
group under offensive line coach Mike Barry, one of the best in the
business.
</P>
<P>
   _ The deepest backfield in the SEC. Lewis ran for 477 yards on
just 73 carries (6.8 avg.) before hurting the knee against Auburn.
In his place, sophomores Travis Henry and Travis Stephens combined
for 1,447 yards on 283 carries (5.1 avg.) All three players have
rushed for more than 100 yards in an SEC game.
</P>
<P>
   _ The team's overall improvement in the areas of strength and
conditioning. All but a couple of players stayed in Knoxville this
summer and went through a grueling weight-training program. Lewis
is in the best shape of his life at 225 pounds with significantly
more muscle. Clifton is a rock-solid 320. Even quarterback Tee
Martin has gotten stronger, setting a school record for
quarterbacks when he bench pressed 405 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be a smash mouth team,'' said Martin, the senior
from Mobile. ``Just about every guy on the offense is bigger,
faster, and stronger than he was a year ago. With Jamal coming back
we're even better. We should have a lot of confidence in our
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a reason why Tennessee has chosen to bulk up and get
physical.
</P>
<P>
   If this team is going to win its third consecutive SEC
championship, it will need victories in three very difficult road
games at Florida, Alabama, and Arkansas. A team that can control
the ball and take the crowd out of the game has a better chance of
wearing down the opponent and winning in a hostile environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would certainly like a few finishes that weren't so
close,'' said Fulmer. ``It would keep us all from aging so fast.''
</P>
<P>
   If you think Fulmer, the old offensive lineman, is looking
forward to fielding this kind of team, you'd be right. His 1997
team faced Nebraska's national champions in the Orange Bowl and got
its doors blown off, 42-17. Since then, Fulmer has wondered what it
would be like to have a team that could physically overpower people
like Nebraska did when it won three national championships (1994,
'95, '97) in four years. This season he may find out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a chance to be that kind of football team and
if you're going to emulate somebody, Nebraska's not a bad place to
start,'' said Fulmer. ``There is a reason why they are the only
team in 20 years to repeat as national champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the people who are saying that about us are right.
We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, we will.
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE
</P>
<P>
   Location: Knoxville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Enrollment: 25,612.
</P>
<P>
   Coach: Phillip Fulmer, 67-11 in seven years at Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Nickname: Volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Stadium: Neyland (102,854).
</P>
<P>
   Record: 690-286-53 (.696).
</P>
<P>
   SEC titles: 13.
</P>
<P>
   1998 record: 13-0, 8-0 SEC (1st, Eastern); defeated Mississippi
State 24-14 in SEC championship game; defeated Florida State 23-16
in Fiesta Bowl for the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule: Sept. 4 vs. Wyoming; Sept. 18 at Florida; Sept. 25 vs.
Memphis; Oct. 2 vs. Auburn; Oct. 9 vs. Georgia; Oct. 23 at Alabama;
Oct. 30 vs. South Carolina; Nov. 6 vs. Notre Dame; Nov. 13 at
Arkansas; Nov. 20 at Kentucky; Nov. 27 vs. Vanderbilt.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
