<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7446 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-OMAGH-ANNIVERSARY-BOS     08-14 1525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OMAGH-ANNIVERSARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ULSTER TOWN TORN BY BOMB CARRIES ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAGH, Northern Ireland _ For seven years in the 1970s, Michael
Gallagher, a Catholic, and Stanley McCombe, a Protestant, lived
next door to each other, friendly but not really friends.
</P>
<P>
   They occupied a familiar patch in Northern Ireland where most
Catholics and Protestants are civil to one another but are still
distant, separated by national identity and segregated by school
and culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drifted apart,'' Gallagher recalled, ``but tragedy reunited
us.''
</P>
<P>
   One year ago &UR;  &LR; Sunday at 3:10 p.m., a car bomb planted by Irish
republicans opposed to the peace process exploded in the center of
this County Tyrone town as it was crammed with back-to-school
shoppers. The bomb killed 29 people and injured 382.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dead were Gallagher's 21-year-old son, Adrian, who had
gone into town to buy a pair of jeans, and McCombe's 49-year-old
wife, Ann, who worked in a clothing store.
</P>
<P>
   Now Michael Gallagher and Stanley McCombe are close friends,
relying on each other to get through ``the bad days,'' when
memories and the sense of loss overwhelm them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never had that much in common,'' McCombe said. ``We've
become very good friends. We feed off each other, for strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Their friendship, and their vocal advocacy for those killed and
injured by the bomb, captures both the vulnerability of people here
and their determination to carry on.
</P>
<P>
   Their mutual dependency is also something of a metaphor. The
first anniversary of the worst atrocity in Northern Ireland
coincides with a stagnant peace process, increasing violence on the
fringes, and a creeping sense that the progress of the last few
years is threatened by inertia, intransigence, and extremists who,
like those who planted the bomb here, are determined to exploit the
vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   As Gallagher put it, ``We have to stand together, or we'll all
fall.''
</P>
<P>
   If one of the bombers' goals was to drive a wedge through Omagh,
where about 65 percent of the 25,000 residents are Catholic and 35
percent Protestant, it hasn't worked. A study carried out by David
Clarke, a professor at the University of Oxford, found people felt
closer as a town since the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   David Bolton, the director of social work at The Bridge Center,
a counseling unit set up after the bombing, said his counselors
have found similar signs of solidarity and an absence of blaming
the Catholic community for the bombers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was potentially divisive because militant republicans did
it. But people are holding together,'' Bolton said.
</P>
<P>
   While most atrocities in Northern Ireland have tended to
victimize one side or the other _ Protestant unionists who want to
remain British citizens or Catholic nationalists who aspire to
unity with the Irish Republic _ the Omagh bomb was remarkably
indiscriminate. Its victims included those from both religions, of
all shades of political opinion, some who were apolitical, and two
visitors from Spain, the only tourists ever killed here in the
Troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Among the victims were six children age 12 or younger, six
teenagers, and two unborn twins of Avril Monaghan, who was killed
alongside her 1-year-old daughter, Maura, and her mother, Mary
Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   The forlorn figure of Michael Monaghan is a reminder of the
devastation wreaked on so many families, none more than his.
</P>
<P>
   With his wife gone, Monaghan is raising his three surviving
children alone. ``Avril has three,'' he told a friend recently,
``and I have three.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no shortage of heroic stories here. Michelle Mimnagh, a
teenager who lost her right leg in the explosion, learned how to
ski over the winter and walks the town with a newly fitted
artificial limb.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for all the outward displays of strength, this is a
wounded place. Like the mist that often shrouds Omagh on winter
mornings, sadness hangs over the town.
</P>
<P>
   So does frustration. Aside from the arrest of an allegedly
peripheral player, the biggest cross-border manhunt ever in Ireland
has failed to result in charges against the bombers even though
many people seem to believe they know who was responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Locals bitterly resent that the bombers have been able to recast
the town's identity for the outside world _ that Omagh is now known
as the place where the worst atrocity in 30 years of the Troubles
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people want to move on, but there are others who are
still hurting,'' said Bolton, who believes more people than the 470
his team has counseled need help.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Byrne, who was elected to represent Omagh in the Northern
Ireland Assembly, said the town ``is still subdued.'' Many people
were dreading Sunday's memorial service, fearful of the memories
that will be dredged up.
</P>
<P>
   ``People go into town, do their business, and get out,'' he
said. ``There's less conversation on the street. A lot of people
have this sense of unease.''
</P>
<P>
   The unease is exacerbated by the political stalemate that led to
the assembly's suspension last month. Gallagher said many of those
whose loved ones were killed took some consolation from the fact
that the bomb seemed to make more people more determined to see the
peace process succeed.
</P>
<P>
   The peace process is stalled because unionists refuse to form a
power-sharing government with nationalists until the Irish
Republican Army begins disarming. Many here believe the IRA missed
a golden opportunity to make a token gesture just after the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the time to do it, and we would be well beyond this
impasse,'' Gallagher said.
</P>
<P>
   Bolton said the political stalemate is feeding anxiety, and that
a collapse of the cease-fires by the main paramilitary groups would
cause a relapse for many here who have been treated for stress and
depression. He said there has been an increase in suicides in the
area, but it was too early to determine whether that trend is
because of the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   As he drew hard on one of the cigarettes that have become his
constant companions, 51-year-old Stanley McCombe said he often
finds it hard to not be consumed by his grief.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life's over,'' he said, sitting in the small office where
he and Gallagher run the Omagh Support and Self-Help Group. Before
the bombing, ``I took early retirement, for a better future with
Ann. Now there's no future. There's only tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   He worries for his sons, Clive, 23, and Colin, 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clive is very unsettled. He's taken three different jobs this
year. Colin's gone back to work, but there are days when he can't
be bothered,'' he said. ``The boys don't say an awful lot. When
Colin talks about it, he gets angry.''
</P>
<P>
   McCombe said he constantly battles his emotions. One day, while
driving, he saw Francis Mackey, leader of the political wing of the
group that carried out the bombing. He said he had to resist an
urge to run Mackey down.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher seems less susceptible to fits of anger, but says it
is a conscious effort not to give in to darker impulses. He and his
son ran a garage together. But he quit that to devote his time to
representing the interests of the families who were bereaved. All
but a few of the families have come together, determined that they
will control the memory of their loved ones. Those who chose not to
get involved are too hurt to emerge from their seclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt it was important to come together,'' Gallagher said.
``The people who planted the bomb did so cynically, to destroy the
peace process and split the town. We won't let them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the families have been buoyed by the support they have
received from people in Ireland, Britain, and abroad. But he says
Omagh residents are upset by the inability of the police to arrest
the perpetrators and by the compensation process that forces them
to argue for the monetary worth of their loved ones' lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a degrading process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watterson's clothing store in the town center used to be a
bubbly place, in large part due to the presence of salesladies like
Ann McCombe and Geraldine Breslin. They chatted up customers and
traded jokes.
</P>
<P>
   When the bomb threat was phoned into police, most of the two
dozen employees at Watterson's were evacuated to the rear of the
store. But McCombe and Breslin stayed behind to help a woman with a
baby carriage down some stairs.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers at the front of the store shepherded the women,
and two other employees returning from lunch, Veda Short and Doreen
Preston, down the street. Because of inaccurate information called
in by the bombers, the police unwittingly brought them and dozens
of others to stand next to the car that held the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   McCombe, Breslin, and Short were killed. Preston lost a leg and
part of her hand.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the bomb, Watterson couldn't imagine
reopening the shop his father founded in 1938 and that he has run
for 35 years. But customers insisted he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll never be the same,'' Watterson said. ``But we've
surprised ourselves. We've struggled through and keep going. Like
the town itself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
