<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-LEAD15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Young guns aim at history
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ So much for the old guard. They've moved out of
the way at the 81st PGA Championship and back to reality. Led by
the always-dominant presence of Tiger Woods, there's a lineup of
young guns ready to shoot it out today at Medinah Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, 23, and Canada's Mike Weir, 29, are tied for the lead at
11-under-par 205. Two shots back at 9-under 207 are former Georgia
Tech player Stewart Cink, 26, of Duluth and Spain's 19-year-old
Sergio Garcia. All but Woods, the 1997 Masters champion, are in the
hunt for their first major championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't go out there and think about what those other guys are
shooting,'' said Cink, who shot 4-under 68 Saturday under blue-sky,
low-humidity conditions in the Chicago suburbs. ``I'm just going to
dig down deep coming down the stretch and try to finish as high as
I can. I've been close in a few U.S. Opens. I know how to act and
what I have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who started the day two shots off the lead, also shot a
68, storming into contention with three straight birdies (Nos. 5, 6
and 7) _ highlighted by a 50-footer from way off the fringe at the
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Eagling the 14th hole and then making a 6-footer at 18 to hold
his share of the lead, Weir is trying to become only the second
left-hander to win a major.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, who opened with a 66 Thursday then slipped to a 73,
rooted home putts with a pump of his fist during a 68.
</P>
<P>
   There's a $630,000 first prize available today plus Ryder Cup
considerations. Garcia, 12th on the European standings, most likely
already has secured at least a captain's selection.
</P>
<P>
   Eight times Woods has owned the 54-hole lead since turning pro
in 1996 and seven times he has prevailed. It's a seven-event
streak, since losing to Ed Fiori in the 1996 Quad City Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who bested Weir in the final round of the Western Open,
has only once before led a major championship after three rounds _
the 1997 Masters, where he won by 12 shots.
</P>
<P>
   For the elder contenders it was a long day. Second-round leader
Jay Haas, 45, who started at 9-under, slipped to a 75 and five
shots behind Woods and Weir.
</P>
<P>
   Hale Irwin, 54, who shocked everyone with rounds of 70-69,
three-putted the first hole for bogey on the way to a 78.
</P>
<P>
   LEADERS
</P>
<P>
   Mike Weir
</P>
<P>
   68-68-69_205 -11
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods
</P>
<P>
   70-67-68_205 -11
</P>
<P>
   Stewart Cink
</P>
<P>
   69-70-68_207 -9
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Garcia
</P>
<P>
   66-73-68_207 -9
</P>
