<HEADER>
A7449 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBO-MCHALE-COLUMN-LAD     08-14 2022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MCHALE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH NOON FOR THE SHERIFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; It was well past bedtime, but this was not pillow talk.
</P>
<P>
   The phone lines were raging on the Dodgers' postgame show as
Ross Porter played host with a whip and a chair. The fans had
snacked on Raul Mondesi throughout Friday's 7-3 loss to Atlanta and
now it was Kevin Malone's turn.
</P>
<P>
   The townsfolk were desperate to learn how this Dodgers mess can
all be undone, the bad attitudes and finger-pointing, the
multi-year contracts and lousy ERAs.
</P>
<P>
   As the calls Ping-Ponged from Van Nuys and Santa Ana and Malibu,
the anger began to shift from Mondesi's midweek tirade to a much
bigger theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want my kids to be Dodger fans the way I was,'' one
caller said. ``That isn't happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone's task is daunting, but if he is the one to lead this
club out of this mess, he'd better get cracking. This winter, he
will be the most important name in L.A. sports. Bigger than Shaq
and Kobe, bigger than Michael Eisner or Michael Ovitz.
</P>
<P>
   At some point he'll have to call some general manager and say,
``You know, Carlos Perez just wasn't a good fit in L.A., but a
change of scenery is all he needs. All you need to do is pick up
the final $12 million on his contract and you can pencil in 240
innings next season.''
</P>
<P>
   Or ``Gary Sheffield? Yeah, he threatened to retire and demanded
to be traded, but it's just because he wants to win so badly. He's
a steal at $39.5 million and just think how he'll bond with your
fans during the next four years. I'm telling you, those 85 RBI are
as guaranteed as the contract.''
</P>
<P>
   And it will have to be done with feeling.
</P>
<P>
   The perception now is that Malone will make the calls, but he
won't make the CALL. Fox hasn't decided how many salaries it will
eat in the name of progress. That will be the first step. Getting
Malone to stop saying he inherited all the problems is second.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers need to budget another Kevin Brown, free-agent
contract and use the money to help loosen the burden. For the same
$15 million they'll annually give Brown over the next six years,
they can unburden themselves of the Eric Young, Eric Karros and
Todd Hundley salaries for the year 2000. Or Mondesi and Perez. Or
Sheffield and Devon White.
</P>
<P>
   Any combination will help.
</P>
<P>
   But Malone needs to set the tone and that hasn't happened. Last
spring an off-handed ``There's a new sheriff in town'' brought
giggles to the rest of baseball. The Dodgers' brutal season has
turned those giggles into roars of laughter.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, he did not meet with Mondesi, saying he hoped his
troubled right fielder would someday apologize personally for all
the expletives that appeared in Thursday's sports section.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson got his meeting out of the way and claims
he has moved on. Sadly, Johnson looks in Mondesi's eyes and sees a
lot of Darryl Strawberry. But the fact that Malone and Johnson did
not sit down with Mondesi together and settle the dispute could
have long-term implications.
</P>
<P>
   Malone talks about needing the team on the same page, but by
taking a different approach to Mondesi, the bigger question is
whether the manager and GM are even in this together.
</P>
<P>
   Say what you will about the players Tom Lasorda and Fred Claire
let slip away, they confronted player issues as one. They weren't
very fond of each other: Lasorda because Claire got the job he
wanted, Claire because of the Lasorda bombast that so enthralled
Peter O'Malley.
</P>
<P>
   But together they left a big mark on baseball. Claire got Kirk
Gibson for 1988, which led to Lasorda's second World Series title
and his ticket to the Hall of Fame. Lasorda pushed every right
button and molded a champion from a team that was at least as
splintered as this bunch.
</P>
<P>
   It happened in part because the kids in the clubhouse couldn't
play one parent against the other.
</P>
<P>
   You don't see that now. The impression is that if Johnson really
wants a player he can go over Malone's head and straight to Fox. It
is certain that Rick Welts, Fox's new man at Dodger Stadium, has
been taking notes the past few days.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was Fox's hire, not Malone's, who was jilted by Felipe
Alou. Johnson is far more mellow than he was during his heyday with
the New York Mets and the approach has not clicked with his new
team.
</P>
<P>
   Malone has to get through all that and finally make this his
team. He can't agree with Gene from Redondo that Hundley has no arm
but a lot of guts.
</P>
<P>
   It might have been almost midnight on the airwaves Friday, but
it is high noon for the sheriff. &QL; 
NATIONAL LEAGUE
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers mess has masked the fact that most of the rest of
the NL West is playing terribly. The San Francisco Giants are
fading, the San Diego Padres lost 17 of 20 and suddenly were being
pushed by the Dodgers for third place.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Diamondbacks entered the weekend 17-4 since July 19,
a better record than any team in baseball. Only the Cleveland
Indians have a bigger division lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see anybody that can beat us right now, to tell you
the truth,'' Arizona catcher Damian Miller said. ``We're playing
that good a baseball. It's only the middle of August, but it's
awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   The big lead will help the Diamondbacks get healthy before the
playoffs. Center fielder Steve Finley and leadoff hitter Tony
Womack recently missed games with injuries. Todd Stottlemyre, out
two months with shoulder trouble, is expected back next weekend in
Pittsburgh. &QL; 
__ Wild, wild card
</P>
<P>
   In two of the three full seasons since wild-card teams were
added to baseball's playoffs, amassing 90 victories _ a .556
winning percentage _ was enough for clubs to capture a league's
extra postseason berth. But with Atlanta, New York, Houston and
Cincinnati hovering at or near .600, Reds manager Jack McKeon
doubts that 90 wins will be enough to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   McKeon said that playing .500 for the rest of the season _ which
would give Cincinnati 91 victories _ won't do. The Dodgers (90-72)
won the wild card in 1996, followed by Florida (92-70) in 1997.
Chicago (90-73) won it last year after a one-game playoff with San
Francisco. &QL; 
__ Poor Sammy
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa entered this weekend's series against the Cardinals
at Wrigley Field just 3 for his last 28, with one homer in his last
eight games. Although there is a natural boost in any showdown with
Mark McGwire, Sosa has little else to think about with the Cubs so
far out.
</P>
<P>
   His defense has been terrible this year, with six errors and
many misplays. The Cubs have to get Sosa out of center, where he
has played more games this season than any year since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation doesn't look good,'' Sosa said. ``But it's not
going to stop me from what I need to do. I'll continue doing my
job.'' &QL; 
__ Welcome home
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, four outs away from providing a nice homecoming for
former Marlin Livan Hernandez, suffered their most-devastating loss
of the season on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez took a shutout into the eighth, then talked manager
Dusty Baker into letting him pitch the inning. Hernandez loaded the
bases with two out and Baker went to John Johnstone, who allowed a
grand slam to Mike Lowell, tying the game at 4-4. The Giants lost
5-4.
</P>
<P>
   Baker blamed himself, but it was a stinging loss for Hernandez.
He bolted out of the clubhouse moments after the game ended, with
two Spanish television stations in full pursuit. He sat alone in
his Range Rover in the players' parking lot for about 10 minutes
before leaving. &QL; 
__ Not just Drew
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of subplots in J.D. Drew's first visit to
Philadelphia, the place where he refused to sign two years ago.
Drew obviously drew the most attention, including boos and
batteries hurled from the stands on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But in that game, former Cardinal Ron Gant, who insinuated in
spring training that St. Louis manager Tony La Russa was racist,
won it for the Phils with a three-run double off Ricky Bottalico,
an ex-Philly.
</P>
<P>
   In the final game of the series, the Phillies were beaten 5-1 by
another former teammate, Garrett Stephenson, whose work habits were
questioned by staff ace Curt Schilling early last season.
Stephenson pitched the way he did two years ago when he beat the
Cardinals and struck out 12 in his first major-league start.
</P>
<P>
   He retired 14 straight at one point and allowed just a solo home
run _ to Gant. &QL; 
AMERICAN LEAGUE
</P>
<P>
   Good teams don't bicker, especially the New York Yankees, which
is why a little dissension last weekend in Seattle was so
surprising.
</P>
<P>
   It came during a bench-clearing brawl with the Mariners when
several Yankees became angered that Derek Jeter stood on the side
and clowned around with his buddy, Alex Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Curtis, in particular, took offense to Jeter's
light-hearted approach and confronted him. Not once but twice. The
first time was on the field. The second time was in the clubhouse.
Jeter tried to walk away, but Curtis persisted.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be interesting to see if Curtis' oral attack on Jeter
costs him his roster spot in two weeks, when Darryl Strawberry is
scheduled to return from Triple-A Columbus. &QL; 
__ Hot and hotter
</P>
<P>
   With a comfortable lead in the West, the Texas Rangers' only
battle is with the elements. Thursday, the Rangers finished a
13-game homestand during which the average nightly temperature was
98 degrees. One day it reached 106.
</P>
<P>
   The most concern is for catcher Ivan Rodriguez, who has made 99
starts, most by any catcher in the league. Before this year,
Rodriguez batted .317 in his career before the All-Star break and
.272 afterward.
</P>
<P>
   But Rodriguez, who didn't start Thursday, was hitting .405 with
seven homers and 21 RBI in 25 games since the All-Star break.
Rodriguez attributed some of that to honoring the club's request
not to play winter ball last offseason. &QL; 
__ Rhodes less traveled
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles have cooled on a long-term extension with
left-handed reliever Arthur Rhodes, creating the possibility that
Rhodes will explore free agency at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   He'd like a four-year, $16 million deal, but it seems highly
unlikely that anyone will give him that to be a middle reliever.
The only way he gets that type of money is if a team wants to use
him as a co-closer/setup guy or convert him back into a starting
pitcher. Trouble is, he never had much success as a starter and he
seldom throws more than two games in a row because of arm and knee
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if Rhodes ends up in New York as a free
agent, setting up Mariano Rivera. The Yankees attempted to acquire
him before the waiver deadline. &QL; 
__ Wright is all wrong
</P>
<P>
   This has turned into a lost season for Indians pitcher Jaret
Wright, whose spot in the postseason rotation is in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   First he had to deal with a headhunter label after an incident
with Detroit and then he changed his mechanics under the advice of
pitching coach Phil Regan.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Wright is back on the DL for the second time since the
All-Star break, having upset manager Mike Hargrove twice by not
telling him about pain in his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Wright came off the DL on Aug. 3 and threw 42/3 innings against
the Red Sox. He started again last Sunday against Tampa Bay and was
gone before getting an out in the third. Wright usually throws his
fastball between 92-95 mph but was hitting only 85-89. &QL; 
__ Power outage
</P>
<P>
   Barring a late rush, Frank Thomas will see his power numbers
drop for a third consecutive season. He hit 40 homers in 1996, 35
in '97, 29 in '98 and has 15 this year.
</P>
<P>
   It's bad enough that the White Sox dropped seven consecutive
games entering the weekend, but manager Jerry Manuel is having
trouble convincing Thomas not to become a full-time DH. Manuel
feels Thomas has trouble staying in the game when he is not playing
first and the numbers back it up. From 1996-98, Thomas hit .352 at
first; .274 at DH. This year he's hitting .346 at first and .286 at
DH.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank has convinced himself that he can't play first, so what
used to be his greatest asset _ his will _ is sort of an enemy
now,'' Manuel said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
