<HEADLINE>
IT'S DOG DAYS OF SUMMER, SO BULLDOG PIAZZA GETS HOT  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mike Piazza had been struggling coming into this
series, and he was back to being booed at home earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza knew the feeling well. But he may have seemed unfazed by
all the fuss because it was about this time last season that he
began to heat up after a summer full of boos at Shea Stadium. And
if the last few days are any indication, Piazza is about to explode
again.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday afternoon at 3Com Park, Piazza had four hits to tie his
career high and give him 10 hits in the last three games. The
All-Star catcher also hit his 25th homer of the season, one day
after belting No. 24 at the lame-duck park formerly known as
Candlestick. Saturday's two-run shot ignited a five-run rally in
the fourth inning as the Mets blew past the San Francisco Giants,
6-1, on a windy day on the bay.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets (71-47) had dropped out of first place on Friday night,
falling a game behind Atlanta, and the victory edged them closer to
the Braves, who had a late game in Los Angeles. But the better news
might be that Piazza _ who batted .361 in the final two months of
last season with 14 homers and 52 runs batted in _ finally seems
poised to once again strap the team on his back.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last season, Piazza has some help this time.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the last month and a half of last season, Piazza
carried the Mets offensively as they drove toward their first
post-season berth since 1988, a goal they fell a game short of.
This season, however, with their revamped offense, the Mets have
not had to depend so much on Piazza's bat.
</P>
<P>
   Even with his two home runs in the last two days, Piazza still
does not lead the team. (Ventura has 26.) Until Wednesday, when he
caught up with Edgardo Alfonzo, Piazza was not even second on the
team in runs batted in. (He now has 83; Ventura leads the club with
93.)
</P>
<P>
   But Manager Bobby Valentine has never seemed worried, even as he
watched Piazza struggling with his swing the last couple of months.
And Piazza seems to have found his timing again, at just the right
time.
</P>
<P>
   His home run Saturday off Kirk Rueter (10-7), came after a walk
to John Olerud. Even with the wind blowing hard from left to right,
the ball cut through the jet stream and sailed into the left-field
seats.
</P>
<P>
   Rueter, who had breezed through the first three innings, never
recovered. Ventura doubled to right, and then Benny Agbayani hit a
run-scoring double, the first of his three hits. Agbayani moved to
third on a Luis Lopez groundout. One pitch later, Agbayani scored
on a perfectly executed suicide squeeze by Rey Ordonez, whose bunt
was so well placed up the first-base line that Rueter could not
field it and Ordonez was safe at first with an infield hit.
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez moved to second on an Orel Hershiser groundout and then
scored on the third of Rickey Henderson's four hits on the day as
the Mets batted around, taking a 5-1 lead. Piazza's single during a
fifth-inning rally set up Agbayani's second run-scoring double of
the afternoon for the Mets' sixth run.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser (12-9), seeing the Dodgers for the first time since he
pitched for them last season, departed after six innings with the
Mets ahead, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza grounded out meekly in the eighth, the only blemish on a
4-for-5 day. Piazza had four hits in a game for the 16th time in
his career, and in his last three games he was 10 for 14 with two
homers, a double, three runs scored and five runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   And to think the fans at Shea were booing him on Tuesday. The
crowd here Saturday certainly was. The former Dodger probably felt
right at home.
</P>
</TEXT>
