<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS LETS THE CHIPS FLY, SEIZING A SHARE OF THE LEAD 
(HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ Tiger Woods drew the loudest roars Saturday at
the PGA Championship, but Mike Weir gained the most respect.
</P>
<P>
   Battling head to head for the second time this summer, but this
time for a major championship, Woods and Weir shared the lead
heading into Sunday's compelling final round. Woods and Weir were
11 under par for the tournament (205), two strokes ahead of Stewart
Cink and 19-year-old Sergio Garcia, who were tied for third place
at nine under.
</P>
<P>
   Those four players separated themselves from the field, but four
others were tied at six under par and remained in the hunt _ Nick
Price, Jim Furyk, the second-round leader Jay Haas and Skip
Kendall. But Woods, who shot a 68 Saturday, and Weir, who shot a
69, will start Sunday at Medinah Country Club as the front-runners,
paired together in the final group, as they were last month at the
Motorola Western Open, which Woods won by three strokes.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday will not be the Western Open. The atmosphere will be
more intense, the pressure will be higher and the reward will be
greater. For Woods, it will be a chance to win his second major at
age 23, a chance to silence those who have wondered when he will
win his next major. For Weir, a 29-year-old native of Canada, it
will be a chance to change his life, to win one of golf's most
coveted prizes against the game's most celebrated player.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into Sunday, Woods will be the favorite, and he seemed
comfortable with both his game and his position. ``I've learned
from my mistakes and my successes,'' he said. ``I'm ready, but I
need to play my own game. The guys at nine under par are right in
it, and the guys at six under could also win it with a great round.
So I have to take care of my own business before I start worrying
about trying to win my second major.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Weir will benefit from his head-to-head battle with
Woods in July at the Western. Woods started that day with a
four-stroke lead, but Weir cut it to one stroke before Woods
prevailed. Weir showed he was not intimidated by Woods that day,
and he proved Saturday that he was not intimidated by his first PGA
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   How many people think Weir will prevail? As long as Weir
believes, he has a chance. ``Tiger's a great player, but playing
with him in the last group before will be beneficial,'' said Weir,
who chipped in from 30 yards for eagle at No. 14, made a 20-footer
for birdie at No. 17, then made an eight-foot par-saving putt at
No. 18 after hitting his approach shot into the bunker. ``I know
I'm going to be nervous, but I have to settle down and play my
game, just like I did today, to give myself a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point Saturday, it appeared Woods might take control, as
he made consecutive birdies at Nos. 5, 6 and 7 to reach 10 under
par and tie Weir. Woods took the lead with a birdie putt at No. 11,
hitting a beautiful approach shot to within three feet for an easy
putt.
</P>
<P>
   It was a vintage run by Woods, and the electricity could be felt
in the gallery. When Woods begins surging up the leader board, the
atmosphere resembles a train pulling into a subway station. The
closer he gets to the lead, the louder the sound becomes, as does
the commotion in the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere was enough to unnerve his playing partner, Lee
Westwood, who shot a 74 and fell to four under par, shooting
himself out of contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing good about shooting a 74 is that I don't have
to play with him tomorrow,'' Westwood said of Woods.
</P>
<P>
   But just when it looked as if Woods might pull away, he cooled
off. He bogeyed No. 13, missing a five-foot par putt, although he
came back to make a spectacular birdie at No. 14, hitting a great
bunker shot from 35 feet that nearly went into the hole for an
eagle. When the ball barely slid past the cup, Woods covered his
face in anguish, not wanting to believe that the ball stayed out.
Woods tapped in for the easy birdie, but he made pars the rest of
the way.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Weir's eagle at No. 14 moved him from eight under par
to 10 under and set the tone for his surge into a tie for the lead.
Weir floated a delicate shot over a greenside bunker, rolled the
ball toward the pin, then heard the gallery roar as the ball fell
into the hole. He raised his arms in celebration, and it was the
clearest signal of the day that he had no intention of folding.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was huge,'' Weir said. ``I had played great up to that
time, but I was only even par. To get an eagle in that situation
can really change your day.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an impressive performance by Weir, a 29-year-old native
of Canada, who is one of only six left-handed players on the PGA
Tour. While Haas, who started the day with a two-stroke lead,
struggled to a 75, Weir was steady, calm and determined.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday will be a special day with Woods sharing the lead, Garcia
in the hunt and a talented group still in contention. But Woods,
who wants to secure a special place in history, will go a long way
toward setting the tone for how his 1999 is remembered with a
victory here. He has already won four times worldwide this year,
including three times on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   When Woods won the Masters in such dramatic fashion at age 21,
many thought he had a legitimate chance to equal or surpass Jack
Nicklaus' total of 18 professional major victories. But that record
looks more imposing with each passing major.
</P>
<P>
   Woods would have to average at least one victory in a major for
17 more years just to equal that mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at Jack's career,'' Woods said. ``Jack finished second
many times in majors. How did he feel about losing that many times?
But he also won 18. The key is to keep giving yourself enough
chances, and eventually you're going to win a few.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
