<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Funerals for shooting victims end
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The funerals for victims of Mark O. Barton's killing
rampage in Atlanta ended Saturday as services were held near St.
Louis for Scott Webb, 30.
</P>
<P>
   Webb was among the nine people Barton killed July 29 in the
worst mass shooting on record in Georgia. Barton, who had also
beaten to death his wife and two children, killed himself as police
closed in.
</P>
<P>
   Webb had moved to Atlanta from Chesterfield, Mo., a St. Louis
suburb, and worked at Momentum Securities, a stock day-trading
firm, in the fashionable Buckhead section of Atlanta. Momentum was
one of two day-trading companies that Barton, an unsuccessful
trader, targeted in his spree.
</P>
<P>
   Another former St. Louisan, Bradley T. Schoemehl, 24, was also
shot, but has since been released from the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   TV cameras and reporters surrounded St. Peters Episcopal Church
in Ladue, Mo., where Webb's funeral was held, but members of the
press were not admitted to the church for the service. Webb's body
was cremated.
</P>
<P>
   Webb's family declined to speak to reporters. Friends have
described him as having a ready smile. He lived until recently with
his father, Roy Webb, in Chesterfield.
</P>
<P>
   Two people remained hospitalized in Atlanta Saturday, more than
two weeks after the shootings, which left 13 wounded. Yuzef
Liberzon, shot in the head as he day traded at Momentum Securities,
was in fair condition at Grady Memorial Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Meredith Winnitt, 22, was listed in good condition at Northside
Hospital. Winnitt was an employee of All-Tech Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
