u a BC-WORKERS-INJURED15-COX     08-14 0458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKERS-INJURED15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suburban Atlanta explosion injures 8
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Brad Schrade
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMYRNA, Ga. _ An explosion Saturday afternoon at a Georgia Power
plant in the Atlanta suburb of Smyrna injured eight workers _
including three critically burned on much of their bodies and
another with severe burns to his face.
</P>
<P>
   The 1 p.m. EDT explosion at Plant McDonough-Atkinson occurred in
the sub-basement of the large coal-burning plant dominated by an
834-foot smokestack.
</P>
<P>
   Three employees were working on one of 10 coal pulverizers and
cleaning in the area, said plant manager David Garrett. An apparent
flash from the cleaning solvent, naphtha, ignited coal powder in
the air, causing a large explosion, said Cobb County fire spokesman
Stephen Mize.
</P>
<P>
   The effects of the blast could be seen above ground. The blast
ripped a hole in the plant's metal wall on the ground floor,
shattered windows in upper floors and caused small fires throughout
the sub-basement, Mize said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is black down there,'' Mize said. ``It is hard to
tell the extent of the damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Six of the eight injured, were taken to Grady Memorial Hospital
in Atlanta with burns. One worker was treated at the plant with
burns, and an eighth employee was transported to a hospital with
inhalation problems, Mize said.
</P>
<P>
   None of the victims' identities was released.
</P>
<P>
   The three critically injured workers had severe burns over much
of their bodies, Mize said. Another had severe burns to his face
and head, but wasn't listed in critical condition, Mize said. One
worker was treated and released from Grady.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours after the explosion, firefighters were still trying to
put out the flames in the sub-basement. About nine Cobb fire trucks
were called to the scene, as well as the county's hazardous
materials unit.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion occurred in Unit 2 of the plant, which was shut
down after the burst. The shutdown was not expected to affect power
service, Garrett said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Georgia Power, the plant was built in 1963. It is
the utility's sixth largest producer of power. In 1998 it had a
capacity of 490,000 kilowatts from coal and 78,800 kilowatts from
oil and gas.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett said the plant has had a good record for safety. None of
its 165 employees have required medical treatment from a
job-related injury in nearly two years, he said. Two of the men
injured Saturday were mechanics. Their department in July
celebrated its seventh year without a serious injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very disturbed about what happened,'' Garrett said.
``We'll find out what happened and correct the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
