<HEADLINE>
WHEN IT COMES TO SEX, HISTORY REPEATS ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's ask and answer the obvious question first: Is there any
nudity in ``The History of Sex,'' the five-hour documentary on the
History Channel?
</P>
<P>
   Yep. Plenty. Less than 30 seconds into the first hour, we see a
naked breast, for example. By the time it's over Friday, we'll see
more _ much, much more. Naked men, naked women, the occasional
codpiece and chastity belt, that kind of thing.
</P>
<P>
   But the nudity in ``Sex'' is not especially sexy. More academic
than prurient, which is the point. This is the History Channel,
after all, not the Playboy Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Not to stretch a conceit, but this ``Sex'' is more functional
than passionate. And I didn't feel like smoking a cigarette
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean I didn't enjoy it. For the most part, I did.
Let's face it, an attempt to squeeze the entire history of anything
into a mere five hours is necessarily going to be a little shallow
(unless it's the history of Gap commercials). And people have been
having sex since . . . well, as long as there have been people. So
there's plenty of ground to cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex'' is presented in reverse chronological order. Monday
night's opening hour concerns sex in the 20th century, while the
following nights march back through time.
</P>
<P>
   One of the things we quickly learn is that nothing has changed
all that much, as evidenced by a few seconds of a porno film _ made
in 1915. (Actually, some things have changed. The Mayan practice of
piercing the penis with the spine of a stingray, dripping the blood
on a piece of paper and then burning it, for instance, no longer
exists. This is a good change.)
</P>
<P>
   One of the weirdnesses of ``Sex'' is its attempt to graft sex
onto every important moment in history. Dec. 7, 1941, for instance,
is usually thought of as the day the Japanese bombed Pearl Harbor,
the day the United States was thrust into World War II, a day that
will live in infamy.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not all. According to Peter Coyote, who narrates
``Sex,'' it was also ``a day that changed intimate relations from
coast to coast in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knew?
</P>
<P>
   Must be true, though _ according to ``Sex,'' 80 percent of U.S.
soldiers stationed overseas for two years or more had some sort of
sexual activity abroad. A lot of grandpas watching this show with
their families are going to have some explaining to do.
</P>
<P>
   The first hour suffers from popular but somewhat knuckleheaded
``experts,'' such as Hugh Hefner, the ubiquitous Dr. Ruth and Helen
Gurley Brown doing most of the talking. (Brown's appearance is
shocking; her skin is stretched so tight by what appears to be a
number of face lifts that if she wanted to lick the back of her
head, all she'd have to do is open her mouth.)
</P>
<P>
   Things pick up once we leave the 20th century and academic types
take over the talking-head roles.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Berkin, a professor at Baruch College, wins the Shelby
Foote Award for most entertaining talker in a documentary. (Foote,
you may recall, was an excellent but little-known writer until his
winning appearances in Ken Burns' ``Civil War'' documentary made
him a star.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent many a happy hour in an archive,'' Berkin says,
``reading about family incest, about potential lesbian
relationships, about adultery, about men and farmyard animals,
about women who had casual sex on the road going between their farm
and someone else's farm, about love on the woodpile, so that, yes,
Virginia, there was sex in Colonial society.''
</P>
<P>
   My fourth-grade Virginia history teacher never mentioned any of
this.
</P>
<P>
   Also included is the famous advice Queen Victoria supposedly
gave her daughter on how to endure sex: ``Close your eyes and think
of England.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, in fact, much humor in ``Sex,'' not all of it
intentional. For some reason, the producers felt the need to have
actors re-enact segments they didn't have illustrations for.
(Nothing explicit. Mostly just stupid.)
</P>
<P>
   And occasionally an actor reads, usually with a heavy accent,
some crucial writing about sex. When a fellow with a thick German
accent intoned in a grave manner about ``some sort of device or
implement in the shape of the male member of a size to match your
sinful desire,'' the guffaws were non-stop.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the most interesting parts of ``Sex'' concern the
Eastern world. India, after all, is where the ``Kama Sutra,'' the
most famous sex manual in history, was written _ written, by the
way, by an ascetic who likely never had sex. Although that's easy
to believe when you hear his advice for penile enlargement: sleep
face down on a cot with a hole in it, with weights hanging from the
part you'd like to enlarge.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   If it's just facts you're interested in, each commercial break
is preceded by a helpful tidbit. For example: ``Rumors that Julius
Caesar lost his virginity to the king of Bithynia led to his
political foes calling him the ``queen of Bithynia.''
</P>
<P>
   But what you really want in a documentary is information you can
use, and ``Sex'' provides that. For instance, we learn that India
is also home to an absolute gem of a pickup line used there in
ancient times: ``Your breasts are like the sinus lobes on an
elephant's forehead.''
</P>
<P>
   Feel free to use it at a singles bar. And don't forget to duck. &QL; 
 &UR; Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8974, or at
bill.goodykoontz &LR; pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
