<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAILMAN-FUNERAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDREDS REMEMBER SLAIN LETTER CARRIER  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITTIER, Calif. _ In a confession to investigators, Buford O.
Furrow Jr. said he shot and killed Joseph Santos Ileto on Tuesday
because Santos was a ``target of opportunity,'' a man who became a
victim because he was not white and because he was employed by the
U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   But friends, relatives and co-workers revealed so much more
about Ileto, a mail carrier who was born in the Philippines,
Saturday during a funeral attended by several hundred people. They
remembered him by his nickname, JoJo, recalling his passion for
chess, his love of basketball and the laugh that came with such
vigor that he sometimes was the only one who understood his jokes
by the time he finished telling them.
</P>
<P>
   Deena Ileto, Ileto's sister-in-law, said he liked to tell jokes
when the family gathered at his mother's house for dinners. ``He
would be laughing so hard, his laughter would make us laugh with
him,'' Ms. Ileto said.
</P>
<P>
   The body of Ileto, 39, lay in a white-shrouded open casket
surrounded by an explosion of red and white roses, sunflowers and
other floral arrangements in the Sky Rose Chapel at the Rose Hills
Mortuary in this suburb east of Los Angeles. Sunlight filtered in
from large skylights and a picture window that looked out on the
rolling hills beyond.
</P>
<P>
   A fleet of mail delivery trucks sat in neat rows outside, and
dozens of postal workers paid their last respects in their
pale-blue uniform shirts and summer shorts. Mourners sniffled
quietly throughout the hour-long service.
</P>
<P>
   Deena Ileto recalled how Ileto and her husband loved the Los
Angeles Lakers and how they emphasized the importance of each game
they watched on television from the beginning of the season to the
end.
</P>
<P>
   Ileto's sister, Racquel, recalled how unfazed he was when the
haircut she gave him ended up a mess. ``I'll just go to a
barbershop,'' she said he told her. His other sister, Carmina, told
of the time she received a call from him asking for help, when his
car had broken down on the way to work. When she arrived, she found
him helping another woman change a flat tire on her car, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She, too, had trouble understanding his jokes, but laughed along
with him because it was apparent he enjoyed them so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never did get his jokes,'' she said. ``But we would still
laugh because he was the only one who understood. I will never
forget that.''
</P>
<P>
   After spraying the North Valley Jewish Community Center in the
Granada Hills neighborhood of the San Fernando Valley with as many
as 70 rounds and injuring five people, Furrow told investigators he
stole a Toyota from a woman at gunpoint and saw Ileto as he was
driving through nearby Chatsworth. According to the statement,
Furrow approached Ileto, who was on his mail delivery rounds, and
asked if he could mail a letter for him, then drew a Glock 9mm
semiautomatic pistol and shot him twice. When Ileto doubled over
and tried to run away, Buford shot him again in the back and head,
until he fell down. After turning himself in in Las Vegas on
Wednesday morning, Furrow was brought back to Los Angeles, where he
has been charged in the mail carrier's murder. The case carries a
possible death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Brad Sherman, a Democrat whose district includes the
neighborhood where Ileto worked, read condolences from President
Clinton, Vice President Al Gore, Sens. Dianne Feinstein and Barbara
Boxer and Gov. Gray Davis. Noting Los Angeles' diversity, Sherman
called Ileto ``a martyr to the cause of us just living together.''
</P>
<P>
   Ileto's best friend and co-worker, Glenn Ritona, told the
mourners he had wanted Ileto to marry his sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would make Jo my brother-in-law, and a member of my
family,'' Ritona said. ``There just wasn't enough time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
