<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICK PRICE CONCENTRATES ON THE SHOT AT HAND  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ As the co-leaders at 11 under par, Tiger Woods
and the Canadian left-hander Mike Weir will tee off Sunday in the
last pairing in the final round of the Professional Golfers'
Association Championship, but Stewart Cink and 19-year-old Sergio
Garcia are only two strokes behind. Can either win?
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger and Mike Weir,'' Cink, a 26-year-old Georgian was saying
after his 68. ``One of the world's best and a guy who's making a
name for himself. I can't think about what they're shooting
tomorrow. I just have to do the best I can and dig deep coming down
the stretch and try to finish as high as I can. If that's first,
great.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, the Spanish prodigy, will be in contention in the final
round of a major for the first time, but he didn't sound as if he
would be too nervous to play well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I was not really nervous, but a little maybe on the the
last putt, I really wanted that putt for par,'' he said after his
68. ``In my first major, the '96 British Open at Royal Lytham, I
remember I was hitting a 5-iron to the green of a par-3 and I was
so nervous, I didn't think I would hit the ball, but I hit it
good.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was a 16-year-old amateur then. And now that he's 19, can
he catch Woods tomorrow?
</P>
<P>
   ``If he plays like he played today, maybe I finish second
best,'' he said, not realizing that Weir had birdied the 17th hole
to tie Woods for the 54-hole lead. `'I just try to do my best. I'll
try to catch him.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the other serious challengers to the co-leaders, only Nick
Price, the 42-year-old pro from Zimbabwe, has a major title in his
resume, three in fact _ the PGA in 1992, and the British Open and
the PGA in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try to make no mistakes,'' said Price, five
strokes off the lead. ``If I don't make any mistakes, I think I'll
have a shot at it. There aren't many courses that don't suit
Tiger's game, but this one more than others because there's not
much run on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only three or four players in this entire field that
can reach all the par 4's and par 5's in two, and he's one of them.
So that makes it tough for the rest of us. If he drives the ball
well tomorrow, I think we're going to have a tough time catching
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Price added with a smile: ``He's obviously very focused and I
think he's been complaining about how poorly he's putting or how
he's not making as many putts as he'd like to. He'll be saying the
same things in 25 years' time, that he's not making as many putts
as he'd like.''
</P>
<P>
   Price acknowledged that his three major titles should give him
an advantage in experience if he gets within a stroke or two of the
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the leader board making the turn coming into the
last nine holes and see who's in the lead, who's around the lead,
and you figure out what you're going to need to shoot on the back
nine and who the contenders are going to be,'' Price said. ``It's a
different feeling when you're in contention on the last day of a
major. All sorts of things go through your mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the players who do the best are the ones that think
more about what they're trying to do and the next shot at hand.
That seems to be the real secret. That's what I've found out,
anyway. Instead of thinking three or four holes ahead or what it
might be like if you win this championship, you must get intensely
focused on what you're trying to do: hit the next shot. The guys
that haven't won major championships, they don't do that very
well.''
</P>
<P>
   And except for Nick Price, Tiger Woods is the only golfer on the
leader board who has won a major, his 1997 Masters runaway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
