<HEADER>
A7467 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-ART-N     08-14 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWINS BEAT YANKS, 6-3, ON OLD-TIMERS' DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  of old timers at Yankee Stadium is being sent to
NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (HLW)  
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Yogi was actually in uniform. Scooter was there, too.
So was Goose, Guidry and even Dave Winfield. It was another one of
those memorable days that can only happen at Yankee Stadium, so, of
course, David Cone was pitching for the Yankees. Who else would
pitch one of these momentous games?
</P>
<P>
   Even Cone admitted how weird it was that he often started on
eventful days in the Bronx, like Saturday's Old-Timers' Day. With
an army of former Yankees at the Stadium, with a crowd of 55,179
joining them and with the dreary Minnesota Twins occupying the
opposing dugout, Cone had another chance to make a special day feel
like an extraordinary day.
</P>
<P>
   It did not happen. Chuck Knoblauch dropped a pivotal pop fly,
and the Twins used an aggressive approach to score four two-out
runs during a four-pitch sequence against Cone, helping them
deflate and defeat the Yankees, 6-3. There was nothing special or
perfect about Cone and the Yankees on this distinctive day.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was a lazy afternoon when Knoblauch's erratic
defense again became a topic, when the Yankees stranded 10 base
runners and short-circuited three innings with double plays, and
when Cone failed to baffle batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was by far my worst stuff of the year, no bones about it,''
Cone said. ``Even with that being said, I still think I could have
pitched better.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone tried his fastball, his split-finger fastball, his
curveball and his slider, but he found nothing reliable. The Twins
are free swingers who put the ball in play and they harassed Cone.
Sometimes, Cone can wriggle through seven or eight innings without
a crisp repertory. Saturday, he struggled to make it through five
innings while allowing one earned run and seven hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just wasn't there today,'' Manager Joe Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Cone is now 1-3 with a 3.77 earned run average since
pitching the perfect game, and conceded that he has been ``shaky,''
it was surprising to see him fizzle in such a major setting. Cone
tossed his perfect game against the Expos on Yogi Berra Day on July
18; he stifled the Blue Jays on one run and earned a no-decision as
the Yankees honored Joe DiMaggio's memory on April 27, and he won
the home opener against the Tigers on April 9. Cone is used to
large crowds and he is used to winning at the Stadium, where he is
34-11.
</P>
<P>
   But Cone never found a rhythm Saturday and Knoblauch did not
help him. Terry Steinbach began the second inning with a bloop into
shallow right field. Knoblauch darted into the outfield, peered at
right fielder Paul O'Neill and then stopped when he realized he was
under the pop fly. With his back to the plate, Knoblauch stretched
out his glove to make a basket catch and the ball popped off the
heel of the glove for an error.
</P>
<P>
   While Knoblauch had to range about 80 feet, once he got settled,
Torre acknowledged, he should have caught the ball. It was
Knoblauch's 20th error of the season, the most among second basemen
in the major leagues, and it wound up being damaging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked for Paul and then I looked up for the ball again,''
Knoblauch said. ``I just missed it.''
</P>
<P>
   One out later, Chad Allen singled and Cone walked Doug
Mientkiewicz, a .216 hitter, on four pitches to fill the bases.
Torii Hunter seemed too eager when he did not bother taking a pitch
after the walk and popped out to second.
</P>
<P>
   But the Twins kept attacking. Jacque Jones smacked an 0-1
splitter to right to knock in two runs, Denny Hocking followed by
slapping a fastball to center to drive in another and Todd Walker
stroked another single to center off Cone's first-pitch curveball
to put the Twins in front, 4-0. Four pitches, four runs, two
frustrated Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just hope that it ends as soon as it can,'' said
Knoblauch, recalling the annoying inning.
</P>
<P>
   Cone added: ``Four runs with two outs is not good pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone's frustration continued into the fourth inning, when
Mientkiewicz ended an 0-for-24 slump in style by crushing a homer
over the fence in right-center field. It was Mientkiewicz's second
homer in 242 at-bats this season, and Cone bowed his head as the
lead swelled to 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams, who went 2 for 5 and is now 23 for 46 in
August, doubled in the bottom of the fourth and Tino Martinez
followed with a two-run homer off Dan Perkins to make the score
5-2. The Yankees later had runners on first and second, but Bob
Wells struck out Joe Girardi on a 3-2 pitch and Ricky Ledee was
nabbed trying to steal third to terminate the rally.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch tripled and scored in the seventh and the Yankees
loaded the bases with two outs in the eighth, but Mike Trombley
retired Jorge Posada on a sinking liner to center. It was the
second loss in 10 games for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was a flat day,'' Cone said. ``It was a
disappointment.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
