RYDER CUP RACE DOWN TO PGA'S FINAL ROUND (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ Bob Estes estimates that the ``real'' drama of
today's final round _ the tournament within a tournament at the PGA
Championship _ should begin around the 13th hole.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the Austin resident plans to begin checking the
status of Chris Perry, Steve Pate, Fred Couples and Jeff Sluman on
the leader board at Medinah Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   No, you won't find any of those names among the pacesetters
after yesterday's third round. All are at least eight strokes
behind co-leaders Tiger Woods and Mike Weir.
</P>
<P>
   Yet all five remain in the running to land an automatic berth on
the U.S. Ryder Cup team, depending on their finish at the PGA
Championship. And all five remain within five strokes of each other
heading into today's final round.
</P>
<P>
   For each man, the minimum requirement for climbing into the top
10 on the final Ryder Cup standings is different. But the door was
left ajar when Jeff Maggert (10th), Steve Stricker (12th) and John
Huston (13th) missed the cut, preventing them from adding to their
point totals at the PGA.
</P>
<P>
   Estes and Perry find themselves in position to make the most
significant moves. Estes is No. 15 in the Ryder Cup standings and
stands in 14th place at Medinah, at 3-under par. If he can climb
into a two-way tie for fifth by the end of today's round, the
former University of Texas golfer will have enough points to earn a
spot on his first Ryder Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   Perry (2-under) is No. 14 in the Ryder Cup standings and 18th on
the Medinah leader board. By finishing in a two-way tie for sixth,
he can become a Ryder Cup rookie.
</P>
<P>
   The tasks are a little more daunting for Pate (1-under), Couples
(1-over) and Sluman (2-over), the players ranked Nos. 16-18,
respectively, in the Ryder Cup standings. Pate needs a solo finish
of fifth or better, while Couples and Sluman must climb into at
least fourth place to clinch a spot on the roster for the Sept.
24-26 matches in Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Of that group, Couples _ a five-time Ryder Cup participant _ has
the best chance of being an at-large selection by captain Ben
Crenshaw. He sounded fairly confident about his chances yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ryder Cup position, for me, is not based on today's round,
tomorrow's round or this week,'' said Couples, whose third round
deteriorated with what he termed a ``brain-dead'' triple-bogey at
No. 16. ``If I go back to hitting it like I did the first two days,
I can talk to Ben and tell him I'm playing well. If I'm playing
well, I think I might be picked.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lehman, the No. 11 player in the standings, is considered a
lock for another at-large pick if he doesn't crack the top 10. And,
at 56th in the PGA field, he's not likely to add to his points
total.
</P>
<P>
   That makes today's final round a free-for-all for the No. 10
spot, with Estes and Perry the prime beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of doubt I'd be picked. That's unrealistic,'' Estes
said. ``Hopefully, I'll put myself in position so that, over the
last four or five holes, I can treat this \RRyder Cup race\S like a
tournament within a tournament. I'll check what they're doing, so
I'll know what I need to do to get to the finish line.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry plans to adopt a similar strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to put extra pressure on myself,'' Perry said.
``But I know \Rtoday\S is the whole deal for me. I'm not going to
be picked because I don't have a long history of success in major
championships. I've got a lot on the line, personally, and I hope
to give myself a few birdie chances early to get some momentum
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Pate, meanwhile, hopes to recapture a swing that deserted him
when he took three bogeys in his final five holes yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ryder Cup? I'm just trying to hit a stinking green, but I
can't even do that from the middle of the fairway,'' Pate said
after a round of 73. ``I'm going to the range and try to figure out
how to hit a stinking green.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
