<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALING-SHOOTINGS-2ndtake-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY DOMINIC BERBEO 
</HEADLINE>
 
LOS ANGELES: to correct that.'' 
For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  and DAVID R. BAKER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``There will always be lunatics out there, but we're urging
people to reach out and not hide away.''
</P>
<P>
   Another step Jews can take, he said, is to place a traditional
mezuza on their doors.
</P>
<P>
   The small cylinders carry a parchment scroll inside that
contains the basic beliefs of Judaism and symbolize protection for
homes and businesses from wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Lipskier said many of his congregation members do not support
placing more armed guards at their facilities because ``it sends
the wrong message to the children that we're under some sort of
military attack or something.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it's important to keep the perspective that last week's
violent attack is not commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in the Dark Ages anymore. Things have improved
greatly and we can't revert to living in fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Steven Jacobs from Kol Tikvah in suburban Woodland Hills
said he was telling Jews there to avoid creating a ``bunker
mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs was part of a delegation that accompanied the Rev. Jesse
Jackson to Belgrade, Northern Ireland, last May to secure freedom
for three U.S. prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been an outpouring of support from other religious
communities and groups,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Fishel, president of the Jewish Federation, said the great
concern for security at the dozens of facilities the group
coordinates calls for Jewish leadership to come together to
reassess security and modify it if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're planning to hold a series of meetings with the
Anti-Defamation League and various leaders to discuss security,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having armed security at centers is regrettable. It doesn't
give the message of happiness that we would like to have ideally,
but it's a reality we have to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the concerns about safety, however, many in the Jewish
community say they are determined to live their lives. While much
of Saturday's service at Temple Aliyah focused on the shootings,
for example, the congregation had other business at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Perlo and her husband, Sandy, celebrated their 22nd anniversary.
Parents fought back tears through two b'nai mitzvah.
</P>
<P>
   And fidgety children cried in the background, an insistent
reminder of the future.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
