<HEADER>
A7669 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-OZ-KORY-THIRDTAKE-KAN     08-14 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OZ-KORY-THIRDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ who know him.
</P>
<P>
   When the Beach Boys' Love formed a company that bought Sandstone
Amphitheatre and later took over management of Memorial Hall in
Wyandotte County, Kory came to Kansas as the company's attorney. He
and the company projected successes that never came to pass.
</P>
<P>
   And when Kory began pitching his Oz theme park, he told
Wyandotte County officials the resort would be built there. He said
the park would open in 1995 or 1996, then 1997, then 1999. But last
year he moved his project to Johnson County. The opening date is
now 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their biggest impediment is this crude lack of credibility
they have with the public and a fair amount of public officials,''
said Steineger, who is not a critic of Kory's but has observed
other officials' skepticism. ``People refuse to believe them after
all these years.''
</P>
<P>
   Westbrook says theme parks on the Oz scale usually take 10 years
to develop. Even after Walt Disney established Disneyland in
California, he took 16 years to open Disney World in Florida,
Westbrook said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No theme park that's ever been opened has been closed,''
Westbrook said, speaking of projects on the scale of Oz, not
amusement parks. ``They may have taken on new ownership, but they
have not stopped operating.''
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/Kory drew criticism in 1993 when Wyandotte County
officials questioned what had happened to $550,000 in public grants
for the Oz project. The FBI investigated the grant, but no action
was taken.
</P>
<P>
   Kory and other Oz officials said the money was well spent on
feasibility studies.
</P>
<P>
   Oz must repay the $550,000 within a year of starting
construction, as part of the bill Graves signed in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be surprised if we ever see a nickel,'' said Hal Walker,
chief counsel for the Unified Government.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1993, Walker, then the city attorney, told The Star:
``The assurances in reference to Sandstone did not materialize.
Assurances about Memorial Hall never materialized. Certainly it
gives you pause.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker declined to comment further for this story. Other
officials also declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, a well-known real estate agent in Wyandotte County,
questioned Kory's follow-through. Kory hired Roberts in the early
'90s to secure options to buy land in the heart of the county for
the project.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1994, Roberts said he suspected that Kory had no
intention of buying the land tied up in options.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was going to happen tomorrow,'' Roberts said. ``Just like
Oz says of Sunflower, it's going to happen tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts also said he was having a hard time getting paid. For
example, in August 1996, Roberts wrote Oz that he still was owed
$6,500 for 1994 services. Roberts said he wrote off the debt.
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/Westbrook, Kory's spokesman, said Kory did not buy the
land because he decided it was overpriced. He denied that Kory owed
Roberts money, saying Kory disputed the value of the services
Roberts performed.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said Kory would extend the options _ increasing the
promised price per acre _ with a promise that the money was coming.
He'd throw out impressive names of his backers: Michael Jackson or
a Saudi Arabian prince, Roberts said, ``enough to keep me dumb and
doing what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oz lawyer for the real estate transactions, McDonald, tells
a similar story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their word was not always their bond,'' McDonald said. ``They
had deadline after deadline after deadline they told the city and
the landowners and then didn't meet it. I got tired of going out
and telling people why they didn't meet it.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald said he quit because he didn't do business that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my job and my privilege to not work for someone if you
have questions about their authenticity,'' McDonald said, ``and
that's what became apparent to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Westbrook said it was common in land transactions for deadlines
to be extended. He called McDonald's comments a character attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customarily, members of the bar defend their clients against
such attacks in a courtroom rather than engaging in such attacks,''
Westbrook said. ``Mr. McDonald serves his profession and his former
client very poorly when he makes such accusations.''
</P>
<P>
   The day Oz was to close on 122 acres of Frank and Virginia
Gray's land in Kansas City, Kan., Oz officials failed to show,
Frank Gray said. Correspondence from Oz stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of smoke and mirrors,'' Frank Gray said. ``You
could never talk to them about finances, about their finances.''
</P>
<P>
   Westbrook said the closing was called off because Kory didn't
like the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Kory was criticized when a bill his company
helped write was introduced in the Kansas Legislature. The bill was
to lengthen the amount of time Oz had to repay $270 million in
state-issued bonds.
</P>
<P>
   What Kory and his lobbyist didn't tell the Legislature: The bill
also included a 1-cent sales tax increase to get more money from
the paying public to repay the bonds.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview at the time, Kory told a Star reporter the bill
did not include a sales tax increase, even when the language in the
bill was pointed out to him.
</P>
<P>
   Westbrook said Kory was confused about the local tax rates when
he said the legislation did not include a tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the Oz company's investment bankers and lobbyist
repeatedly told the Legislature and the Johnson County Commission
that the project would fail without the sales tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   While Kory has equally passionate critics and supporters, others
say Kory doesn't need to be liked.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not some fly-by-night operation,'' said Tom Page, the
chairman of the Kansas Development Finance Authority, the board
that will vote to issue the bonds for the Oz project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, are these ... guys you'd spend a long weekend with at a
ski resort in Aspen? Uh-uh,'' Page said, shaking his head. ``These
guys aren't Kansans.''
</P>
<P>
   Personality aside, many give Kory credit for launching the huge
project. Vaught, the Unified Government commissioner, said he
thought his investment was gone years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Kory has ``pushed through when a lot of us had given up on the
project,'' Vaught said. ``It's easy to throw stones. But if it
wasn't for him, this project wouldn't be going anywhere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
