<DOCNO> NYT19990814.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7670 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BAXTER-COLUMN17-COX     08-14 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BAXTER COLUMN
 &HT;    GOP hoopla underscores Iowa's clout
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMES, Iowa _ Republicans used to talk about making their party a
big tent. On Saturday, they had several.
</P>
<P>
   Every GOP candidate who competed in Saturday's Iowa straw poll
had at least one tent outside the Iowa State University basketball
coliseum. The more prosperous campaigns had entire tent complexes.
</P>
<P>
   In the steel-reinforced, air-conditioned Steve Forbes tent,
supporters cooled off to the music of Debby Boone and Ronnie
Milsap. Over at Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch's more modest tent, Roger
Williams and Vic Damone performed.
</P>
<P>
   The hungry had their choice of barbecue _ the Taste of Texas in
Gov. George W. Bush's well-placed tents, the Taste of Tennessee at
former Gov. Lamar Alexander's, or the South Carolina 'cue of
Columbia restaurateur Maurice Bessinger at Pat Buchanan's. Then
they could stroll over to Alan Keyes' for an ice cream sundae.
</P>
<P>
   Parents left their kids among the giant inflatable playscapes
provided by Forbes, while thrill-seekers rode a funny car doing
wheelies outside the Elizabeth Dole tent.
</P>
<P>
   This was festival politics, a sort of corn-fed, conservative
Woodstock complete with giant balloons, T-shirt stands, clowns and
fresh-faced kids.
</P>
<P>
   And eventually, candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's votin' time here now! A lot of people are paying
attention to what's happening in Ames, Iowa,'' an upbeat Bush
shouted to his supporters, as his aides eyed an ominous tide of
orange Forbes T-shirts streaming out of buses in nearby lots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm flabbergasted. I stood outside shaking hands for two hours
and never shook the same hand twice,'' Rep. Bob Barr, Georgia
chairman for Forbes and a native of Iowa City, said. Barr and
Atlantan Alveda King, who is a national co-chair for Forbes,
campaigned for their candidate in the air-conditioned tent before
the voting began.
</P>
<P>
   Well before the winner of this symbolic but closely watched
first contest of the presidential season was named, it seemed clear
that overall attendance would set a record for the GOP straw poll,
which was first held in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   The straw poll is ``a good midterm exam'' for the candidates,
Iowa GOP Chairman Kayne Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the tents and the hoopla, the campaigns _ with
the exception of that of Arizona Sen. John McCain, who boycotted
the straw poll _ spent considerable money to prove they have the
organizational ability to prevail in next year's nomination
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, I think we will have demonstrated we
have the will, the organization, the ground forces, as well as the
message to win the presidency,'' said Forbes' national chairman,
Ohio Secretary of State Ken Blackwell.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, the straw poll was so casually treated that the
campaigns brought in supporters from Nebraska to bump up their
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   This year, with so much focus on the event, proof of Iowa
residency was required and participants were stamped with indelible
ink so they wouldn't vote twice.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates were brought before an arena packed with
Republicans like an all-star basketball team, with cheerleaders and
indoor fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Forbes and Bush took their turns to speak, the
atmosphere was similar to that of the old-time floor demonstrations
at national conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes even had his own fireworks and spotlight, but the
exuberance backfired somewhat when the first half of the Fortune
magazine publisher's speech was drowned out by the popping of
balloons.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the candidates took shots in the direction of Bush,
whose fund-raising prowess and family name have made him a strong
early favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``My vision is not raising money, my vision is raising our
children,'' former Vice President Dan Quayle said. Forbes said the
party doesn't need ``a candidate who depends on pollsters and
tutors to tell him what to think.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's speech seemed a response to his rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how to lead. I do not run polls to tell me what to
think,'' the Texas governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said prosperity was not enough to sustain the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prosperity must have a greater purpose. If prosperity were
enough, the wealth of Littleton would have shielded its children,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
