TEAMS TURN UP HEAT AS TEMPERATURES RISE (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The blistering heat is driving almost everybody in baseball
crazy, not just the Rangers' befuddled brass.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I'm just as surprised as they are that 46,000 people
aren't willing to pay top dollar and embrace 100-plus temperatures
every night just so they can catch a flying T-shirt, check out the
breath-taking home-run fireworks and go crazy when that guy who
suspiciously looks like Ed Belfour starts waving the Rangers' flag
on the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers aren't the only ones with problems. ...
</P>
<P>
   Brewers boss Wendy Selig-Prieb decided eight years was enough
for general manager Sal Bando and manager Phil Garner, and she
cleaned house. Not that the House of Selig ever went all-out to
provide a winner _ or even come close _ but Bando and Garner could
never overcome the numerous injuries that always strike the
Brewers' young pitchers, from Teddy Higuera to Cal Eldred and Jeff
D'Amico.
</P>
<P>
   You can only go so far trying to revive the careers of Hideo
Nomo, Bill Pulsipher, Rocky Coppinger, Ben McDonald and Jim Abbott.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers will likely beg Paul Molitor to come back, either as
manager or general manager. Former Pirates general manager Ted
Simmons, who played for the Brewers, could also re-emerge there.
Otherwise, they'll round up the usual general-manager suspects,
including former Indians assistant Dan O'Dowd and Braves assistant
Dean Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Three with Rangers connections ought to be considered: Omar
Minaya, a former scout here and now the Mets' senior assistant
general manager who will be somebody's general manager soon; Dan
O'Brien, who helped the Astros get turned around before becoming
Doug Melvin's top aide; and Wayne Krivsky, Tom Grieve's former aide
who now works with the Twins and has wide experience in scouting,
player development and contract negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Garner could resurface in Detroit, where Tigers manager Larry
Parrish is the first one to say he could be in trouble. The heat is
particularly high in Detroit, now that the Tigers have the worst
record in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday's 8-2 loss to the Rangers, Parrish said, ``For the
year we've had, I can't imagine anyone giving me a vote of
confidence. ... I don't know how much they're going to put up
with.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Tigers do make a move, they'll be paying three managers
next year: Buddy Bell, Parrish and the new guy. That might convince
the Tigers to keep Parrish.
</P>
<P>
   Garner could also end up in Baltimore, where it's all but
official that Ray Miller won't be back next season.
</P>
<P>
   Another hot spot to watch is Los Angeles. The Dodgers' mess got
worse Wednesday when disgruntled outfielder Raul Mondesi went off
on manager Davey Johnson and general manager Kevin Malone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They try to put all of our problems on me,'' Mondesi said.
``They're trying to say that all this is my fault. That's the way
they feel, fine. Just get me out of here. I'm tired of all this. I
told my agent \RJeff Moorad\S to get me out of here as soon as
possible I can't take this anymore. I've tried to deal with this
all year. I told them to trade me because I don't want to be
here.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the G-rated version of what Mondesi said. The club issued
a statement the next day that had Mondesi apologizing. Just blame
it on the heat.
</P>
<P>
   SPOTLIGHT ON J.D. DREW
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies drew 140,446 for their three-game series with the
St. Louis Cardinals last week, but it wasn't all because Mark
McGwire was in town. Phillies fans had long anticipated their first
opportunity to vent their anger at Cardinals outfielder J.D. Drew,
who was Philadelphia's first pick (second overall) in the 1997
draft but refused to sign with the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Drew got the usual ugly Philadelphia reception: plenty of boos,
taunting banners _ ``Greed will be your demise, J.D.'' was one of
the nicer ones _ and the usual assortment of debris thrown at him.
At one point on Tuesday, the Cardinals had to be pulled off the
field until the unruly crowd settled down.
</P>
<P>
   But the Phillie Phanatic caused the biggest stir by driving up
to the Cardinals' dugout and placing three bags with dollar signs
on the turf. Drew's agent Scott Boras said the mascot should be
reprimanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just disappointed,'' Phillies manager Terry Francona
said. ``It was a huge crowd and they were very vocal and that's
good. But then you get a couple of dummies up there and it kind of
ruins it for everybody else. We all have different opinions on J.D.
and where he signed. But no matter what your opinion is, he doesn't
deserve that. That's why I went over and apologized.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew, while admitting he'll never forget the experience, got in
the final say. His home run was the deciding blow in the Cardinals'
5-1 victory Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``God's timing is perfect,'' Drew said. ``He has a will for my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   QUICK HITS
</P>
<P>
   Through the first 40 games, Oakland outfielder Ben Grieve was
hitting .131 with three home runs and 11 runs batted in. Then he
figured out he was holding his hands too high. Since then, he has
been hitting .321 with 16 homers and 49 RBI, helping the Athletics
surge back into the playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers were 21/2 games ahead of the Cubs when Phil Garner
and Sal Bando were dismissed. That doesn't say much for the chances
of Cubs general manager Ed Lynch and manager Jim Riggleman.
</P>
<P>
   A name to watch in the off-season: Arthur Rhodes. He's 29,
left-handed and eligible for free agency in the off-season. A team
like the Rangers could gamble on him as a converted starter and use
him as a left-handed setup reliever if it doesn't work out. It
could cost $16 million over four years _ that's what Mike Timlin
got _ but he could be worth it if he can start.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the free-agent watch: The White Sox aren't thrilled with
Greg Norton at third base and could use someone like Todd Zeile. He
could add power to the lineup and also be a stabilizing influence
for the White Sox young talent.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Diamondbacks pitcher Todd Stottlemyre, on the disabled
list with a torn rotator cuff, hit 94 miles per hour with his
fastball in a medical rehabilitation start last week. He's expected
to return Friday against the Pittsburgh Pirates, probably replacing
Brian Anderson in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa is thrilling people with his home runs, but he's
played poorly in the outfield. He's looking more like a DH every
day in a league that doesn't use one.
</P>
<P>
   Since June 1, when he lost for the first time in a calendar
year, Roger Clemens is 5-5 with a 5.71 earned-run average. The
Yankees have lost seven of his 13 starts since then. Spring
training talk of a contract extension has quieted.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians aren't happy with pitcher Jaret Wright, who is back
on the disabled list with a sore shoulder. Manager Mike Hargrove is
upset Wright wasn't more forthcoming when he first injured the
shoulder in July, then obviously wasn't ready when he came off the
disabled list on Aug. 3. He looked terrible in two starts and was
put back on the D.L. Steve Karsay, who has been a terrific middle
reliever, has taken his spot in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies, having dumped Darryl Hamilton and Brian McRae, are
going to take a two-month look at Edgard Clemente, nephew of Hall
of Famer Roberto Clemente.
</P>
<P>
   Twins manager Tom Kelly, tired of rookie mistakes, dragged
center fielder Torii Hunter back onto the field after last Saturday
night's game in Kansas City. Hunter had missed a hit-and-run sign,
so he had the rookie stand at home plate and stare at third-base
coach Ron Gardenhire while Kelly lectured him. It was after
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees weren't happy shortstop Derek Jeter was seen joking
around with buddy Alex Rodriguez during last week's brawl with the
Mariners. Outfielder Chad Curtis confronted Jeter in the locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Giants have had Barry Bonds, Ellis Burks, Jeff
Kent and J.T. Snow in the same lineup together for 28 games this
season. They are 17-11 in those games.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. asked where's the pitching when he turned down a
contract extension offer from the Mariners. The answer? The
Mariners have nothing to show for sending Mike Hampton to the
Astros, Shawn Estes to the Giants and Joe Mays to the Twins. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
