<HEADER>
A7672 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-OZ-KORY-SECONDTAKE-KA     08-14 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OZ-KORY-SECONDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ the Oz author.
</P>
<P>
   Baum said Kory would simply outlast the Oz skeptics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who've come and gone. And he's come
and he hasn't gone. I give him a shot at it,'' Baum said.
</P>
<P>
   Kory's multifarious knowledge is what impresses his business
partners and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Kory graduated in 1973 summa cum laude from Yale University with
a bachelor's degree in philosophy. He also was named a member of
Phi Beta Kappa. He later graduated from the University of Chicago
law school.
</P>
<P>
   At Yale, Kory developed interests that continue to drive him.
</P>
<P>
   One was transcendental meditation, a passion that became an
occupation. After graduating, Kory set up TM conferences in the New
York metropolitan area and went on to serve as a national vice
president in the movement.
</P>
<P>
   He also wrote six self-help books based on transcendental
meditation, five of which he wrote with a friend from Yale. Titles
include .MDBR/.MDNM/``Happiness: The TM Program,'' ``Psychiatry and
Enlightenment'' and ``Lifemates: The Love Fitness Program for a
Lasting Relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   .MDBR/.MDNM/Kory meditates daily, Westbrook said.
</P>
<P>
   The practice gives him the energy to work 70-hour weeks, live a
moral life and structure his thinking to juggle the many details
involved in the Oz project, said Altbach, who met him in 1975 when
Kory was writing books with a friend of Altbach's.
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/Another interest Kory developed at Yale also feeds Oz:
multimedia art.
</P>
<P>
   Kory met Patrick Clancy, chairman of photography and new media
at the Kansas City Art Institute, at Yale when Clancy was a
graduate student. Kory's interest in Clancy's interactive
multimedia art sparked a friendship.
</P>
<P>
   The two continue to exchange ideas. For instance, Clancy sent
Kory a book on complexity theory, a phenomenon that occurs after
chaos theory, for the two to discuss. Recently, Clancy sent Kory a
book on nonlinear dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   Kory chose Clancy to lead a nonprofit research center that Oz is
helping create adjacent to the park.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy says Kory uses his broad knowledge to stay informed of
the details of the project, while maintaining his vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be able to put these things together and keep them moving
along as they are _ it's really a feat,'' Clancy said.
</P>
<P>
   Kory honed that talent as a lawyer for a large, prestigious
firm. When he graduated from law school, he was rewarded with a job
at Gibson, Dunn &AMP; Crutcher, the law office of such notables as
former U.S. Attorney General William French Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Meiers, a partner at the firm, often chose Kory to work
with him on corporate merger and acquisition matters. He recalled
when a client got a takeover threat. Overnight, Kory needed to
produce a perfect legal document for the client's board of
directors explaining the situation, Meiers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he did,'' Meiers said. ``He was a terrific young lawyer.
No doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kory also surrounds himself with talented people.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy taught at Yale, was a founding faculty member of the
California Institute of the Arts, and has shown his own work in
museums nationwide, including the Museum of Modern Art in New York.
</P>
<P>
   William McKenzie, the company's treasurer, was the chief
financial officer for a leading concert promoter. Skip Palmer, his
theme park president, was operations director at Disneyland in
California before starting his own company.
</P>
<P>
   Even skeptics of the project were impressed when Kory announced
the hiring of Oz Vice Chairman Ron Bension, who built two Universal
Studios theme parks.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say Kory's success in building the Oz team comes from
his ability to win converts.
</P>
<P>
   One convert is Fred Ulrich, a Harvard business school graduate
who is chairman of Buttonwood Capital, an investment bank that is
helping finance Oz. He also serves on the Oz board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Ulrich got hooked on Kory when he called him to check out
Altbach's references for a business venture. He was so intrigued by
the man on the phone that he arranged a meeting to talk about Oz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found something magical about Robert's personality,'' Ulrich
said. ``I sometimes call him the Wizard, not in a sham sense, like
the movie. He's very animated, he likes to talk, to listen. He
likes to attract great people to his venture.''
</P>
<P>
   Others find that Kory's personality can alienate some people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, Robert is the kind of guy, you either like him or you
don't like him, unfortunately,'' said Joe Vaught, a former Kansas
City, Kan., councilman and current member of the Unified Board of
Commissioners of Wyandotte County and Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Chris Steineger of Kansas City, Kan., said Kory came
off as aloof and cool when they first met in the early 1990s. Kory
didn't offer much of a handshake, either. Since then, Kory has
begun to project a more down-to-earth image and ``he gives a good
handshake now,'' Steineger said.
</P>
<P>
   Vaught, who says he is an Oz investor, says Kory is good at
coming up with ideas, but less successful at presenting them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a tough time projecting himself,'' Vaught said. ``He
has too much attorney in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaught likes Kory, he said. But he acknowledges some missteps
Kory took in the project's early years.
</P>
<P>
   For example, promised financial backing from a Saudi Arabian
prince never came through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes he's been too optimistic,'' Vaught said. ``It's made
him say things he could do that he absolutely couldn't do.''
</P>
<P>
   And just as his personality draws and disturbs, the question of
what Kory is able to accomplish polarizes those who know him. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
