FULL OF EXPECTATION, FRANCHIONE HOPES FROGS DON'T FILL WITH DOUBT
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ When last we left them, they were standing on the
field at the Sun Bowl, hugging the tuba players and wiping the
happy tears from their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to long-held belief, TCU beating Southern Cal in
football was not one of the signs of an impending apocalypse. But
it did happen. On that one sunny day in El Paso, the Frogs were
princes.
</P>
<P>
   It was months later, perhaps, when TCU faithful, while wrapping
fish in old copies of the ``Star-Telegram'', noticed the months-old
headlines and gasped, ``Egads. We lost to Rice.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Frogs did (14-12 in November). Barely beat Vanderbilt,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the margarita haze of the Sun Bowl upset, indeed, is the
fact that TCU finished 6-5 during the 1998 season. The record says
both everything and nothing about what Dennis Franchione
accomplished in his first year as head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's Frogs were light years from the half-interested,
1-10 bunch they were in Pat Sullivan's final season. But let's not
make any plans for the Rose Bowl yet, shall we?
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 15 seasons, a TCU team enters the football
season riding a wave of lofty ambition. The Associated Press and
ESPN/''USA Today'' preseason polls both list the Frogs as noble
also-rans, which is fair enough. TCU is being trumpeted as the
class of the scaled-down WAC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing this for 27 years,'' Franchione said, ``and
I've been picked last and I've been picked first. And I guess I'd
much rather be picked first.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the thing I have to guard against is the reality that
maybe people have based a little too much on the success of one
game. We still have some teams we didn't conquer last year.''
</P>
<P>
   As Franchione put it, ``We're not too far removed from that 1-10
season.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't trying to say he only had 1-10 talent. Far from it. He
knows the Frogs return 14 starters, enjoy depth at heretofore
wafer-thin places and have a schedule that, on the whole, looms as
roundly digestible.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione just doesn't want the balloon, for whatever reason,
to burst early. One of the remarkable things about his first season
came in convincing his inherited Frogs that they weren't a 1-10
team. In the end, they never quit. They played with heart _ and if
that sounds corny, well, it was a corny season.
</P>
<P>
   One of Franchione's earliest lessons was teaching his team not
to succumb at the first sign of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Against Oklahoma in the second week, the Frogs squandered a 9-0
lead in the final 21/2 minutes and fell, 10-9. But they bounced
back in the next game and upset 23rd-ranked Air Force, 35-34.
</P>
<P>
   There were tough losses to SMU, Wyoming and Rice to deal with,
but in the final chapter, there was Franchione on the field after
the Sun Bowl, drenched in Gatorade, posing for pictures with Super
Frog.
</P>
<P>
   It is only human nature, the coach conceded, for people _
players, fans and coaches alike _ to have high expectations. But
Franchione admitted, ``I still worry about their fragile emotional
state at times. I just don't want to see that reappear.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't mention Arizona by name. He didn't have to. The
Wildcats are No. 4 in the country in the preseason wire-service
poll released yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   If any foe on the Frogs' 1999 schedule is capable of opening old
wounds, it's Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   But the Frogs and Franchione have been together for a full year
now. Players seem to believe in this coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   As Franchione said, ``I'd like to think that we've been together
enough that if the ship hits a little rough water, we can overcome
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wackier things have happened, all puns intended. The schedule is
stacked so that, if TCU emerges from its Arizona opener with all
vital organs still intact, the Frogs have a chance to start winning
the next week at Northwestern and keep rolling all the way to
December.
</P>
<P>
   From 1-10 to 10-1 in two seasons. Quit laughing.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be a Nebraska to have a top-10 season. Take
Tulane, which rose from college-football purgatory to an undefeated
season and a No. 7 final ranking last year. The Greenies did it
with sparkling quarterbacking and a schedule laced with cream
puffs.
</P>
<P>
   Tulane was last season's poster child for college-football
parity. Franchione doesn't mind the comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe that, other than the top 10 or 15 Division-I
schools, there's not that much difference in any of them,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes a matter of who stays healthy. Who gets off to a
good start and builds the momentum. Who has good feelings about
things. And who has a team that will hold together through
crises.''
</P>
<P>
   That team could be TCU, all giddy expectations notwithstanding.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
