<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GALLOWAYCOLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
RYAN'S THANK YOU TO MILLER WAS LONG OVERDUE (For use by NYTimes
News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While watching television on a recent Sunday afternoon in his
Manhattan apartment, 82-year old Marvin Miller heard his name
mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan Ryan was saying, ``thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   In some quarters, what Ryan did that day became baseball's
version of a political-correctness debate.
</P>
<P>
   Was this the time and place _ standing there on the Cooperstown
podium, giving his Hall of Fame induction speech _ for Ryan to be
recognizing the Godzilla of all union bosses?
</P>
<P>
   Bud Selig was on that same podium. Why make the commissioner
squirm uncomfortably on an otherwise joyous day for baseball?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Selig has always ranked high in style points. Formerly
a long-time owner in the game, Bud had to understand better than
most what Ryan was doing and why.
</P>
<P>
   Thanking Marvin Miller is the least any player can do. Better
still, major-leaguers from the late '60s through today should be on
their knees, uttering a prayer of gratitude every time the man's
name is mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Which these days is seldom, if ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take what we have today for granted,'' acknowledged Rangers
first baseman Rafael Palmeiro. ``There is not nearly enough
appreciation for Marvin Miller. Even on a veteran club like ours,
you don't hear Marvin's name enough. And some of the young guys
probably don't even know who he is.''
</P>
<P>
   When Miller retired in 1982 as the executive director of the
Major League Baseball Players Association, he was undefeated,
untied and unscored on in constantly winning negotiating battles
with baseball owners.
</P>
<P>
   Everything players have today in terms of salaries and
free-agency freedom, it's all because of Miller's work. Small in
stature, and very distinguished looking, Miller was never heard
raising his voice in anger. Miller's weapon was brain power. He
outfoxed the owners at every negotiating turn.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of family and baseball influences, Ryan thanking Marvin
Miller should have been Nolan's next highest priority. Ryan came
from an era, the late '60s, when he pumped gas in the off-season to
make ends meet. Major-league salaries were that low.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very gracious of Nolan to do that,'' Miller said last
week. ``I was shocked ... he's the first inductee to ever do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller retired 17 years ago. As Palmeiro said, with regret, the
players of today seem to forget him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's just human nature,'' said Miller, graciously.
``It's no different than in all walks of life. This is a new
generation of players. I have no regrets.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller was a high-ranking official in the United Mineworkers
union when three desperate major-leaguers approached him in 1966.
That threesome _ Robin Roberts, Jim Bunning and Harvey Kuenn _ ask
Miller to form something totally strange. A players union. As a
baseball fan, Miller agreed. The average pay of players was around
$12,000 a year at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward to 1999, and there are many who will say Miller was
too successful. By drumming the owners repeatedly in negotiations,
he lifted the players from powerless to total power.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Miller disagrees. Ask him when mushrooming salaries
stop, and he answers, ``when the revenue increases for owners stop.
It's a classic case of supply and demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask him about the big-market/small-market canyon, and Miller
answers, ``there is more competitive balance today than at any time
in baseball history. The big-market/small-market thing has been
going on this entire century. People forget when only the New York
teams _ the Giants, Yankees or Dodgers _ made the World Series.
Until the Yankees recently, we went a lot of years without a New
York team winning the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   My long-standing suggestion _ and I defy anyone to tell me I'm
wrong _ is the owners should hire Miller as their negotiator. Stack
so much money in front of him, he couldn't say no. If baseball
owners had done that in the mid-'80s, the situation would be
different today.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Miller plays a lot of tennis, writes a column for a
sports business magazine, has a new book in mind, and is updating
his old book, ``A Whole Different Ball Game,'' which is about to be
reissued.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers pitcher Tim Crabtree has read the Miller book. As the
team's union representative, he also passed out 30 copies in the
clubhouse. This is just Crabtree's fourth major-league season,
``but all of us should know what Marvin Miller has meant to the
players,'' he said. ``We have plenty to be thankful for, and he's
the reason.''
</P>
<P>
   The one thank-you from Nolan Ryan might have raised certain
eyebrows, but it was a long overdue gesture.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
