<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BARNHOUSECOLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
BCS WORKS WELL, FOR NOW, AND THAT'S NO BULL (For use by NYTimes
News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's August, the Hot 100 is not just a list of hit songs, the
Rangers are headed for another division title and the Cowboys are
answering the ``character question.'' All that means college
football season is near.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, dear fan, you will be hearing about the same ol' BCS.
That's short for Bowl Championship Series. In its debut season, the
BCS worked perfectly, if luck can be considered perfect. Instead of
one of three undefeated teams howling about being locked out of the
title game, upsets by Texas A&AMP;M and Miami (Fla.) produced a
serviceable Fiesta Bowl matchup of 12-0 Tennessee against 11-1
Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS rankings that produced Tennessee vs. Florida State also
produced derision. Terms like ``maximum deviation'' and
``quartiles'' sound like they belong in a college level math class
but were key elements in the BCS formula. When Kramer announced the
BCS was adding five computer rankings this season for a total of
eight byte-driven polls to help determine the rankings, the howls
were loud.
</P>
<P>
   I hit the self-mute button. I don't get a ``Blair Witch
Project'' scare when I hear, read or type the letters B-C-S. I've
got no problem with the current system. Maybe you think the BCS is
BS. Maybe it is. But here's the deal: ``There is no playoff.''
</P>
<P>
   The BCS is the best of what Division I-A college football has
and that best is by far better than what it had 10 years ago. No
longer are teams tied to bowl games by conference affiliation. No
longer is the No. 1 team decided only in polls of writers and
coaches whose expertise is limited by ignorance, prejudice and/or
indifference. (Last season, two writers forgot to vote in the
Associated Press poll over Thanksgiving weekend; no big deal, guys.
We're just trying to decide a national championship here, that's
all).
</P>
<P>
   Maybe most fans (and more writers) don't understand how the BCS
rankings work. Perhaps adding more computer polls to the mix adds
to the confusion. The BCS method is better simply because it counts
strength of schedule and uses rankings where performance is
quantified.
</P>
<P>
   If the strength of schedule portion of the BCS formula is the
reason for Arizona at Penn State and Ohio State vs. Miami (Fla.) in
two weeks, then hooray for the BCS and computer chips. If trying to
finish with a perfect record was the only goal, those four teams
would probably be kicking off against Division I-AA teams.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-BCS faction in the media constantly write and harp
about a Division I-A playoff. Frankly, I'd love to see a playoff _
16, eight, four, two teams, whatever. But there's little use
wasting ink about something that's not going to happen any time
soon.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS contract runs for two more seasons and then could be
renewed for at least another three years. The earliest a I-A
playoff could _ ``could'' happen would be for the 2002 season. More
likely, we could see a playoff starting in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   More and more coaches support a playoff. However, these same
coaches say they want to preserve the current bowl system. Aye,
there's the rub, mate. Few in college football believe that the
bowls would survive in a playoff environment. A playoff plan
proposed by ISL, a Swiss-based marketing company, not only offers
$300 million a year (more than twice the current bowl revenue), it
also has a plan to subsidize a limited number of bowl games. Sort
of like basketball's NIT.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how many coaches throw their weight behind a
playoff, the decision will be made by school presidents in the Big
12, Big Ten, Southeastern, Atlantic Coast and Pacific 10
conferences. And while presidents of schools in the bottom half of
I-A are mostly in favor of a playoff (because of share-the-wealth
revenue distribution), the Big Cigars at the Big Schools are not in
favor.
</P>
<P>
   Until there is change among the big schools' leadership, a
college football playoff is a dead issue.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
