<SLUG> BC-OZ-KORY-THREETAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN BEHIND THE OZ THEME PARK GARNERS LOYALTY AND CRITICISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GRACE HOBSON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ On a June day in 1984, entertainment lawyer
Robert Kory was introduced to Mike Love, the Beach Boys' lead
singer.
</P>
<P>
   As they sailed near Los Angeles, Love told Kory about the
Washington concert he intended to play on July Fourth, just weeks
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked him (Love) detailed questions, but there were no
detailed answers,'' recalled Ron Altbach, who introduced the two.
</P>
<P>
   Love immediately hired Kory as his attorney, and Kory began
supplying the answers. In two weeks he hammered out contracts with
sponsors and negotiated agreements to allow the concert on the
grounds of the Washington Monument and to get cable coverage.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Beach Boys celebrated Independence Day in front
of 500,000 to 750,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a typical Robert Kory thing where he said, `Yes, I can
do it,' '' Altbach said. ``He never says, `No, I was mistaken.' He
just keeps trying until he gets it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Kory's drive is the force behind his dream to create something
much greater than a concert: a $771 million Wonderful World of Oz
resort and theme park. He hopes this dream will draw 3 million
people a year to what is now the Sunflower Army Ammunition Plant
near De Soto, Kan. He envisions a project more on the scale of
Disney World than Worlds of Fun _ but even better.
</P>
<P>
   But skeptics point out that Kory, 50, is an entertainment lawyer
who has never built a theme park, that he is new to the theme park
industry and that Kory originally said the park would open in 1995.
The scheduled opening date is now 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm saying, who the heck are these people?'' William Kostar,
the mayor of Westwood, Kan., asked at a Council of Mayors meeting
in March. ``What's their revenue stream? If we were dealing with
Donald Trump or even Wayne Newton, we'd say we have something going
here.''
</P>
<P>
   With more ambition than capital, Kory grabbed onto an idea that
had drifted around the Kansas City area for years.
</P>
<P>
   He secured the rights to the Oz name. He found a huge piece of
unused federal land, the Sunflower site. He attracted a
high-powered firm to sell bonds for the project. He persuaded the
Kansas Legislature to authorize issuance of those revenue bonds and
to direct the park's sales tax revenue to pay off the debt.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of obstacles lie ahead. But Kory's longtime friends and
financial backers are sure he can pull off what naysayers call a
pipe dream.
</P>
<P>
   Oz boosters describe a theme park packed with state-of-the-art
attractions designed to tap the latest technology.
</P>
<P>
   The resort, filling 1,750 acres in the initial development
phase, also is to have a 350-room luxury hotel with 50,000 square
feet of conference space, fine-dining restaurants, an RV park and
an 18-hole golf course.
</P>
<P>
   The park's theme will center on The Wonderful Wizard of Oz by L.
Frank Baum, as well as characters in 39 other Oz books.
</P>
<P>
   Some question whether Kory can make the ambitious project
happen. Kory's critics, including Kory's former lawyer, L.D.
McDonald, and his former real estate agent, Bud Roberts, question
his reliability. Some resent him for his dealings with Sandstone
Amphitheatre in Bonner Springs, Kan. Others begrudge him for
courting Wyandotte County, Kan., with promises to build his
lucrative project there before choosing well-off Johnson County,
Kan., to the south.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Robert Kory is selling, I'm not buying,'' said Bonner
Springs Mayor Ted Stolfus.
</P>
<P>
   But from the Johnson County Commission to the Kansas
Legislature, most politicians are buying. Gov. Bill Graves signed a
bill in May that allows the state to issue $270 million in bonds,
to be repaid with sales taxes generated at the park, to help the
project. The state will not guarantee the bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The bonds would not be issued until the Kansas Development
Finance Authority approves the project, possibly this fall. The
authority may begin the process to establish a redevelopment
district at the Sunflower site on Sept. 10. The taxing district
must be created before any bonds can be issued.
</P>
<P>
   The man at the heart of all this enterprise remains an enigma.
Is Robert Kory the 21st century's Walt Disney, a visionary with
talent enough to transcend the cynics? Or is this dream out of his
reach?
</P>
<P>
   From his days as a Yale University undergrad, his work as a
self-help book author and his later career as a lawyer, Kory has
assembled a devoted band of loyalists who sell the man and his
endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   Kory himself does little of the selling. He declined repeated
requests for interviews for this story. Although the Los Angeles
resident often travels to Kansas City to work on this project, he
has spoken publicly about Oz only three times this year, each time
before a small group, according to his spokesman, David Westbrook.
He skipped two well-attended public forums about Oz and never
addressed the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Westbrook said developers such as Kory often leave the public
relations work to their managers while they build their company and
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Kory's supporters describe him as a workaholic who makes time
for family and church every week. They say he is a man who lives by
a list of values he created for his company, such as truth and
``the highest standards of integrity,'' open communication, a
system of rigorous checks and balances, and the use of conservative
projections to achieve realistic goals.
</P>
<P>
   They see a man who can take an out-there idea and turn it into
reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't quit,'' said Robert Baum of Los Angeles, the
great-grandson of the Oz author. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
