<SLUG> BC-FBC-FSU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA STATE IS AGAIN THE PRESEASON NO. 1, AND THIS SEASON THE
SEMINOLES MIGHT FINISH ON TOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picking Florida State as college football's preseason No. 1 is
more akin to tree-hugging than limb-climbing.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles, with 18 starters returning and quality players at
most key positions, are the ``Star-Telegram'''s choice to win the
national championship. It is familiar territory: Florida State has
been the preseason No. 1 team in 1988, 1991, 1993 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   For all their lofty preseason beginnings, however, the Seminoles
have finished No. 1 once _ 1993. There were near misses in 1995,
1997 and last year.
</P>
<P>
   This could be the Seminoles' year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what it means to be ranked No. 1,'' said Florida State
coach Bobby Bowden, whose team lost 23-16 to Tennessee in last
year's national championship game in the Fiesta Bowl. ``No matter
where you start, you've got to go out and do it. We don't hide the
fact that we are No. 1. In fact, we'd like to be No. 1 all the
time. I tell our players that we want to be No. 1 every day.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being No. 1 in the ``Star-Telegram'' preseason
poll, the Seminoles were selected No. 1 in the Associated Press
(writers) and USA Today/ESPN (coaches) polls. Both polls factor
into the Bowl Championship Series rankings, which are used to
determine the top two teams to play for the title. This year's
national championship game will be played Jan. 4 in the Sugar Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be one of those special years,'' said
27-year-old junior quarterback Chris Weinke, who returned to
football after playing minor-league baseball in the Toronto Blue
Jays organization for six years. ``There is some excitement around
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles' schedule is championship-friendly. They play
eight of their 11 games in the state of Florida. Their first major
test comes Sept. 11 when Atlantic Coast Conference challenger
Georgia Tech visits. On Oct. 9, Miami (Fla.) travels to Tallahassee
to continue a rivalry that is returning to its previous levels of
intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Florida State's most challenging road game comes Oct. 23
when the Seminoles visit Clemson. That game will be the first
father-son coaching matchup in college history _ papa Bobby against
son Tommy. If the Seminoles are undefeated, Bobby Bowden will be
trying to win his 300th game.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State ends the season in the usual manner with a game
against bitter rival Florida. This year's game will be in
Gainesville on Nov. 20. The last time the Seminoles won in The
Swamp was 1993 _ the year they won their national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State has finished in the top four in the final polls
for an NCAA-record 12 consecutive years. Even with that amazing
stretch of success, Bowden doesn't sense any complacency.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go through the off-season program, you look to see a
bunch of kids slacking off,'' Bowden said ``And I haven't seen
that. They look like they have worked real hard. I see the key this
year as being hungry. Is this team hungry? That's the thing about
being around the top all the time, you are always afraid someone is
going to lose their hunger. We haven't seen any indication of it.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 2220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
