<HEADLINE>
THE '90S BELONG TO FLORIDA STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The decade has seen a helmet-full of changes in college football
_ scholarship limitations, overtime, refinement of the postseason
in an attempt to produce a true champion. But there has been one
constant: Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles' 97-13-1 record is the best among Division I-A
teams this decade. If Florida State goes 12-0 this season, its
winning percentage in the 1990s will be .890. Since the NCAA
started keeping track of records by decade, the best has been
Oklahoma's .895 in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   So picking Florida State as the preseason No. 1 is more akin to
tree-hugging than limb-climbing. The Seminoles, with 18 starters
returning and quality players at most key positions, are the
``Star-Telegram'''s choice to win the national championship. It is
familiar territory; Florida State has been the preseason No. 1 team
in 1988, 1991, 1993 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what it means to be ranked No. 1,'' said Florida State
coach Bobby Bowden, whose team lost 23-16 to Tennessee in last
year's national championship game in the Fiesta Bowl. ``No matter
where you start, you've got to go out and do it. We don't hide the
fact that we are No. 1. In fact, we'd like to be No. 1 all the
time. I tell our players that we want to be No. 1 every day.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being No. 1 in the ``Star-Telegram'' preseason
poll, the Seminoles were selected No. 1 in the Associated Press
(writers) and USA Today/ESPN (coaches) polls. Both polls factor
into the Bowl Championship Series rankings, which are used to
determine the top two teams to play for the title. This year's
national championship game will be played Jan. 4 in the Sugar Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But for all their lofty preseason beginnings, the Seminoles have
finished No. 1 once _ 1993. There were near misses in 1995, 1997
and last year.
</P>
<P>
   With Chris Weinke at quarterback, a Heisman Trophy candidate in
Peter Warrick, seven starters returning from the nation's top
defense and a championship-friendly schedule, this could be the
Seminoles' season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be a shocking disappointment if we don't win the
national title,'' tight end Ryan Sprague said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be one of those special years,'' said Weinke, a
27-year-old junior who returned to football after playing
minor-league baseball in the Toronto Blue Jays organization for six
years. ``There is some excitement around here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles play eight of their 11 games in the state of
Florida. Their first major test comes Sept. 11 when Atlantic Coast
Conference challenger Georgia Tech visits. On Oct. 9, Miami (Fla.)
travels to Tallahassee to continue a rivalry that is returning to
its previous levels of intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Florida State's most challenging road game comes Oct. 23
when the Seminoles visit Clemson. That game will be the first
father-son coaching matchup in college history _ papa Bobby against
son Tommy. If the Seminoles are undefeated, Bobby Bowden will be
trying to win his 300th game.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State ends the season in the usual manner with a game
against bitter rival Florida. This year's game will be in
Gainesville on Nov. 20. The last time the Seminoles won in The
Swamp was 1993 _ the year they won their national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State has finished in the top four in the final polls
for an NCAA-record 12 consecutive years. Even with that amazing
stretch of success, Bowden doesn't sense any complacency.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go through the off-season program, you look to see a
bunch of kids slacking off,'' Bowden said ``And I haven't seen
that. They look like they have worked real hard. I see the key this
year as being hungry. Is this team hungry? That's the thing about
being around the top all the time, you are always afraid someone is
going to lose their hunger. We haven't seen any indication of it.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
