<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGANOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
A LITTLE JORDAN MAGIC? (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ Mark Brooks closed locker No. 508 at Medinah
Country Club, the one holding his belongings but assigned on a
permanent basis to the club's highest-profile member: Michael
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if any of Jordan's magic had rubbed off during the PGA
Championship, Brooks laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There must be now,'' Brooks said yesterday, moments after
acing the 17th hole with a 3-iron from 206 yards. ``Two is the best
score you make in golf. But a one is luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks' latest ace, the 15th of his career and first in
competition since The Players Championship in 1997, came on a shot
Brooks thought he had pushed off-line. But the wind carried it
right-to-left, and the ball landed on the collar of the green
before rolling 30 feet and disappearing into the cup.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks exchanged high-fives with caddie Van Nunnally and playing
partner Mark James before parring the 18th hole to wrap up a round
of 70 that moved him to 3-under par for the tournament, eight
strokes off the lead and in a tie for 14th place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see it the whole way,'' said Brooks, who has not
finished better than 38th in a major since winning the 1996 PGA.
``It hit a dead spot on the collar and released right at it. It's
exciting, but it's just a score. It's a lucky deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he'd found anything interesting in Jordan's locker,
Brooks said: ``Not so far. But I'll look again before I check
out.'' CINK RISES TOWARD TOP
</P>
<P>
   In past PGA Championships, Stewart Cink had that sinking
feeling. He'd never made a cut in the event before arriving at
Medinah.
</P>
<P>
   But after matching the lowest score of the third round with
yesterday's 68, he finds himself two shots out of the lead, at
9-under. The difference?
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf is a mental game. Some weeks you have your focus and some
weeks you don't,'' Cink said. ``This week, I've had a good game
plan and a good feeling. And every time I've hit into the trees,
I've made good recoveries.'' BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   Six players on the leader board are well-positioned to continue
a trend that has seen 10 of the past 11 PGA winners make the event
their first major championship. The list: co-leader Mike Weir
(11-under), as well as Stewart Cink (9-under), Sergio Garcia
(9-under), Jim Furyk (6-under), Skip Kendall (6-under) and Jay Haas
(6-under).
</P>
<P>
   Today's champion will own bragging rights about defeating the
toughest field since the advent of the world golf rankings. Of the
top 100 players in the rankings, 92 competed at the PGA, the most
ever in a single event.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Turner (4-under), on the best part of playing at Medinah:
``After Carnoustie and Pinehurst, it's nice to see a little red.''
Between them, the two courses that hosted the past two majors saw
one player finish under par (Payne Stewart, 1-under, U.S. Open).
Heading into today's final round, 30 players are under par at the
PGA.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
