<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLORIES OF YOUTH PERISH QUICKLY BUT ENDURE IN MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: When I was a young man in the Army, duty once obliged
me to attend a reunion of veterans of the unit in which I then was
serving.
</P>
<P>
   The affair was in New York. It was my first time in such a grand
city. But for all the dazzle of the place, I expected the reunion
itself to be a droll affair: a great gang of graying men, trading
memories enlarged and embellished though many tellings.
</P>
<P>
   It was incredible to me that those old soldiers ever had been
young, which only shows the narrowness of youth's perspective. For
actually they were not so old at all.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly they were veterans of World War II. Their unit, the 82nd
Airborne Division, had distinguished itself in the D-Day campaign
and many of the European theater's other key battles. I'd heard the
stories; they were part of the division's lore. But they were
legends of a conflict I thought of as distant history.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the war had ended only a dozen years before. So a good
many of those veterans would have been in their 40s, a few perhaps
in their 50s.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Jim Gavin, who'd commanded the division in combat,
addressed the final banquet, and afterward stood an hour speaking
with the men as they passed through the line to shake his hand and
present their wives. I was astonished how many of them he greeted
by their names.
</P>
<P>
   Then the lights in the ballroom dimmed. And Marlene Dietrich
appeared, magnificent in a sequined sheath, to dance the first
dance with Gavin _ and after that with any soldier who had the
nerve to ask.
</P>
<P>
   That was more than 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the veterans of the 82nd Division held another of
their annual gatherings, a three-day affair just up the road in
Omaha, Neb. A demonstration drop of 400 paratroopers was scheduled,
and because my wife had never seen a parachute jump, we decided to
drive up for one evening and part of a day.
</P>
<P>
   That first night there was a hospitality center, with food and
drink. Of the several hundred men and women in the room, perhaps 50
were young soldiers who'd come from North Carolina, assigned to
various convention duties as I once had been.
</P>
<P>
   They peered at us across a gulf of years, courteous as anything
but clearly wondering whether it was possible any of us had ever
been their age. There wasn't a soul in the room I knew, although we
did meet and share a table with a fine couple, Bill and Sally
Bidleman, who've raised their family on a farm near Kinsley, Kan.,
out toward Dodge City.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning was the jump, and besides the veterans and
their kin, you never saw such a gang of luminaries as those on the
reviewing stand: the governor of Nebraska, at least four mayors, a
whole clutch of three- and four-star officers _ Army, Navy, Air
Force and Marine _ whose various responsibilities I failed to note.
</P>
<P>
   The lesser lights, generals with only one or two stars, sat in a
bunch on folding chairs down below. There were some colonels and
majors, too. And plenty of enlisted folk in camouflage fatigues to
help with the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   And something new since my time, a division choral group _ 20 or
so singers, paratroopers every one. Their first number was a
popular tune, ``My Girl.'' The next, with a more direct connection
to the profession of soldiering, was ``America the Beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came an announcement over the loudspeaker, directing
attention to the sky at right front. Just coming into view was the
first in the line of five large transport planes in which the 400
jumpers, who'd risen in darkness that morning at Fort Bragg, would
now be on their feet and ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``One minute out,'' said the voice on the speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years rolled away. In my mind, I could hear the
jumpmaster's shouted commands over the engine roar, and hear the
excited drumming of boot soles on the plane's floor.
</P>
<P>
   Several passes over the field the planes made. In groups of 20
and 30 at a time, the 400 parachutes opened like pale olive
blossoms against the sky, each one perfect. And when the spectacle
had ended, the jumpers formed up in columns and marched in from the
drop zone to stand before the people in the bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   O beautiful for patriot dream... the lyric had said. ...God mend
thine every flaw ... and crown thy good with brotherhood...
</P>
<P>
   In those ranks could be seen all the very best of the country, a
country still flawed and not yet quite crowned with brotherhood,
but trying: young men and, yes, young women paratroopers, too.
Black, white, brown and every tone between _ alike in their
competence and their wonderful fitness. Alike, above all, in their
splendid and perishable youth.
</P>
<P>
   I found I had to look away, oddly affected by how short a time
it seemed since I'd stood in those ranks. Then, for an anticlimax,
the generals and the politicians spoke, as they invariably will.
And we drove home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
