<DOCNO> NYT19990814.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7681 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKN-TARPLEY-TEX     08-14 3169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-TARPLEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABUSIVE FOG OF COCAINE AND ALCOHOL. FOR NEARLY TWO YEARS, HOWEVER,
HE HAS BEEN CLEAN AND SOBER
</HEADLINE>
 
Ex-MAVERICKS STAR ROY TARPLEY LOST A PROMISING NBA CAREER IN AN(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Surprise, Roy Tarpley is still alive.
</P>
<P>
   And _ considering the former Dallas Mavericks star choked his
career in cocaine and almost drowned his life in alcohol and was
nearly traded to the home(less) team _ relatively well.
</P>
<P>
   At his best, Tarpley was a likable prankster who used his soft
hands and relentless energy to nip at the elite heels of Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar, Patrick Ewing and Hakeem Olajuwon.
</P>
<P>
   At his worst, he was an irresponsible, paranoid, liar hell-bent
on a blameless, guiltless self-destruction.
</P>
<P>
   When a gutted franchise and its fans freed themselves of Tarpley
four years ago, arguably the most talented player in Mavericks
history had just recycled their heartache with an NBA-record second
ejection for drug and alcohol abuse. While the Mavericks gasped at
his departure, he spiraled into an emotionally, physically and
financially bankrupt 7-foot waste of potential perilously close to
slipping right down the drain.
</P>
<P>
   Tarpley didn't die, but for a while he was dead.
</P>
<P>
   Released by a minor-league team on the tiny Mediterranean island
of Cyprus, divorced from his wife, Dawn, and forced to sell his
sprawling house on Lake Lewisville and living in a modest Dallas
apartment paid for by former Maverick-turned-angel Mark Aguirre,
Tarpley spent July 1997-January 1998 in and out of jail. Woozy from
drugs and wobbly from beer, he was arrested six times for abusing
girlfriend Elisha Spacek, whom, according to a Dallas police
report, he once even purposely burned on the arm with a hot clothes
iron during one of their arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Just days after Spacek was killed in an automobile accident in
December, Tarpley passed out intoxicated in a car and was taken to
the familiar surroundings of Dallas' Lew Sterrett drunk tank.
</P>
<P>
   When he awoke this time, however, the player who never knew how
good he was on the court finally realized how bad a person he had
become off it.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time ever, Roy got scared,'' said Aguirre, whom
Tarpley called when he discovered he didn't have enough money to
bail himself out of jail. ``Even through all the stuff before, he'd
always felt invincible. But this was it. He had no money, no food
and no idea where he was going to wind up. That was it for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Scared, but more importantly stimulated, Tarpley immediately
heeded Aguirre's advice and completed another rehab stint, moved in
with his mother and resurrected his overseas basketball career.
</P>
<P>
   So close to flat-lining in his coagulation of red, droopy eyes,
the light behind Tarpley's backboard finally popped on.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he's a two-time loser turned two-bit player in a
fourth-rate Greek league earning one-eighth his previous salary.
But for a player who guzzled and snorted himself out of $32 million
and a promising place in the NBA, staying sober enough to hold a
steady job the last 20 months is a major milestone toward Tarpley's
ultimate rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Roy no news is good news, and I haven't heard from him in
a long time, so I'm encouraged, freaked-out encouraged,'' said
Aguirre, who has matured into a savior for Tarpley. ``But I saw him
hit rock-bottom, and it was very, very ugly. He's got a long way to
go, and I don't know if he'll ever really be over the hump. I hope
so. But I wouldn't be shocked to hear from him needing help
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   With the help of Aguirre and the influence of longtime Mavericks
chaplain Dr. Tony Evans, Tarpley leap-frogged a waiting list two
years long to enter a rehab center in New York. Last summer he
moved in with his mother, in Mobile, Ala., then signed a
swallow-some-pride contract to resume playing in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   After an incident-free, productive season last year, he earned a
promotion _ and a two-year contract worth approximately $1 million
_ to play with Dafni Athens in Greece starting in the 1999-2000
season. In a basketball-rabid country where drug and alcohol
policies are lax, Tarpley has kept his name and nose clean.
</P>
<P>
   Even current Mavericks assistant coach Donnie Nelson, a constant
scout of European basketball, gets reports that Tarpley has been
nothing but impressive lately. Tarpley calls his mother weekly,
hangs out with former Michigan teammate and Cyprus player Richard
Rellford and is winning the fight with his addictions one battle at
a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a bad history, but for us he caused no problems and
performed well,'' said coach Grivas Dimitris, who saw Tarpley score
24 points a game to lead Cyprus' Apollon Limassol to a 19-3 record
last season. ``He is the complete player, running, jumping,
shooting, rebounding. I guess it's a shame because I don't see many
players in the NBA who have what he has. When he was younger, I can
only imagine how good he was.''
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, he is the saddest page in the Mavericks' yearbook
and the Metroplex's most expensive waste of potential this side of
the SuperCollider.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that potential and now the first question about him is,
`Is he alive?''' said former Maverick Brad Davis, who played with
and later coached Tarpley. ``It's just so sad, such a waste. I
honestly believe he had the skills to be one of the 50 best players
of all time. There was nothing he couldn't do on the court. Off the
court was another story.'' TICK ... TICK ... TICK Tarpley's
tumultuous eight-year Mavericks career ended Dec. 6, 1995, when he
yanked the short leash of the NBA's aftercare program by testing
positive for alcohol. Though he's been gone longer than the
Southwest Conference, his absence is still ruining the Mavericks'
decade, and his presence still haunts their memory.
</P>
<P>
   Former team owner Don Carter can't hold back the tears when he
talks about Tarpley, and longtime executive Keith Grant simply
won't address the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted him to succeed so bad I can still taste it,'' said
former general manager Norm Sonju, who keeps a picture of Tarpley
on his desk at home. ``Do I feel some personal responsibility by
him failing? Sure. We all do. No one really understands what went
wrong except Roy, and he'll probably never explain himself. He
never has.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to their public position at the time, the Mavericks
apparently knew all too well about the 21-year-old Tarpley's
addiction problems when they drafted him seventh overall in 1986.
The Mavericks protected Tarpley by having him live with the veteran
Aguirre his first two years in the league, even giving out a phone
number to Tarpley's supposed apartment only to have the line
permanently forwarded to Aguirre's home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all knew he had a massive problem when he got here,''
Aguirre said. ``I think he respected me, and he knew up front that
I wouldn't tolerate any of that garbage in my house. But we had
some hard times. I lost my mom, so when I heard him on the phone
talking to his mother with such disrespect, we came to blows. But
he didn't really flip out until after I was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   While Tarpley stayed straight enough and played well enough to
be named to the NBA's All-Rookie Team in '86-87, the Mavericks
spent sleepless nights leery of a hiccup.
</P>
<P>
   On Christmas Eve '86, they paid an employee to knock on
Tarpley's door with a ribbon-wrapped shovel. When Tarpley asked
about the shovel, the employee responded, ``Just a reminder that
you'll be digging ditches with it if you don't stay clean. Merry
Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Tarpley's first ``strike'' came in July '87 when he
voluntarily entered the league's drug rehab program for cocaine
use. After Aguirre was traded to the Detroit Pistons in '89,
Tarpley moved out on his own.
</P>
<P>
   And trouble moved in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought he was at a point where he could handle it,'' Sonju
said. ``But looking back, it was the beginning of the end. It
turned into one of the worst experiences of my life.'' PLAYING WITH
FIRE
</P>
<P>
   Fans and critics put Tarpley's transgressions on pause in the
summer of 1988. A 250-pounder who ran like a sprinter, dribbled
behind his back, sank 18-foot jumpers and created a trademark of
tipping rebounds away from opponents until he latched onto the
ball, his career peaked when he was named the league's Sixth Man of
the Year.
</P>
<P>
   He became the first reserve in NBA history to finish among the
top 10 rebounders, and his 21-point, 20-rebound performance against
Abdul-Jabbar pushed the Mavericks to a pulsating Game 4 victory
over the Lakers and tied the gripping Western Conference Finals
series (eventually won by L.A. in seven) at two games each.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not kidding, he was physically one of the best ever to
play this game,'' said John Lucas, a recovering drug addict who
last year served as an assistant coach with the Denver Nuggets.
``There were nights when Kareem wanted no part of him, when he
totally outplayed \RSan Antonio Spurs center\S David Robinson. He
was Dennis Rodman as far as loose balls, rebounds and defense, but
he'd also score 20 points.''
</P>
<P>
   Had he not cratered to a multi-million-dollar six-pack, Tarpley
would be a free agent after the 2000 season and likely one of the
best players on a Mavericks team desperately seeking size in the
middle. While still drinking in 1994-95, he averaged 12 points and
8.5 rebounds, numbers current coach Don Nelson would probably love
to have from center Shawn Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad truth is he was a hell of a player even when he wasn't
sober,'' former teammate Jason Kidd said.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of his destruction and disregard, the Mavericks
haven't had a playoff game or even a winning season since Tarpley's
first banishment, Oct. 16, 1991. But instead of a eulogy about his
on-court prowess, etched on his NBA tombstone is the fact that he's
one of only eight players ever kicked out of the league. And the
only one twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had his life in order he could have been Michael Jordan,
because he had that charisma, that talent,'' said former Mavericks
assistant Clifford Ray, assigned solely to keep hourly tabs on
Tarpley from 1988-91. ``I've gotten on my knees many nights to pray
for him to find peace within himself and break free of those
bonds.'' THE MULTI-MILLION MIRAGE
</P>
<P>
   Before Tarpley could market himself as a household name with his
play, he dug himself a reputation with his partying. And
eventually, his immense raw talent was swallowed by his insatiable
drug demons.
</P>
<P>
   In January of '89, Tarpley received ``strike two'' in the NBA's
anti-drug program when he again voluntarily sought help from league
drug counselors for his cocaine addiction. After a string of DWI
arrests, domestic-abuse charges and missed team functions, he was
kicked out of the league for the first time when he refused to take
a drug test in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``He fell victim to the four F's: fame, fortune, free time and a
feeling of invincibility,'' said Lucas, who later coached Tarpley
in '92 in the United States Basketball League. ``His best asset was
also his worst detriment in that he never surrendered on the court
or off the court to drugs. He had a disease, but no one could see
it was terminal because there were no tumors, and no pill or chemo
could get rid of it. It killed him slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   After his first suspension, Tarpley spent three years playing in
Greece, the USBL and the Continental Basketball Association before
petitioning for reinstatement to the NBA in the summer of 1994.
Having sat the minimum two years in the penalty box and then
passing a face-to-face meeting with commissioner David Stern in New
York, Tarpley was allowed back into the league.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a move that ranks as one of the nicest and worst in
professional sports history and earned Carter the label of
``enabler,'' the Mavericks' huge-hearted owner not only welcomed
Tarpley back, but rewarded him with a six-year, $26 million
contract in October '94. While critics blamed Carter for risking
tomorrow's promise on yesterday's problem, the sentimental man in
the 10-gallon hat rejoiced in Tarpley's return.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was like a son to me,'' Carter said. ``I got second chances
in life, and I thought Roy deserved another chance, too. I felt
with all my heart that he could change, that he would change.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of changing, Tarpley only switched addictions from
cocaine to alcohol. Three weeks after signing his contract, he got
a ticket for driving 92 mph on the Dallas tollway. An hour later,
he plowed his Mercedes into a light pole, then denied he had been
driving the car that night.
</P>
<P>
   Despite injuries and suspensions after blow-ups with Grant and
coach Dick Motta, Tarpley became a key performer on Dallas' best
team of the 90s _ one that went 36-46 and seemed to be assembling
impressive pieces in Jim Jackson, Jamal Mashburn, Kidd and himself.
SCARY SIGNS
</P>
<P>
   But, like the calm before a storm, Tarpley's productive games
were only an appetizer for nights of binging on booze.
</P>
<P>
   Tarpley became moody, alternating days of cheerfully taking
teammates to lunch with whopping cover-ups that made Richard
Nixon's tale look like a little white fib. He blamed fits of wobbly
posture and slurred speech on everything, including Nyquil, Tabasco
sauce, natural mood swings, even residual anger from dropping a
water bottle on his toe.
</P>
<P>
   Less than an hour before a game in '95, Tarpley stood stark
naked in front of his locker swaying back and forth trying to pick
a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to like me,'' he slur-bellowed to no one in
particular. ``I don't care. But if you don't, I'll meet you at
Chuck E. Cheese's and we'll settle it.'' After a spurt of
uncontrollable laughter, he continued. ``But I don't care. I live
in a big house on a big lake with a big boat ... I just don't
care.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it was painfully obvious to teammates that he was too
drunk to recognize Popeye Jones from Popeye the Sailor Man, Tarpley
played and played terribly in that night's game and several more.
</P>
<P>
   When pushed for answers about Tarpley's peculiar behavior, the
NBA and its drug counselors claimed he was passing regular tests
for alcohol. In reality, he had discovered a way to beat the
system. According to a league source, he figured out he was only
tested on Mondays. Therefore, he wouldn't drink on weekends so his
system would show up clean, then began a binge on Tuesdays.
</P>
<P>
   ``A random test probably would have caught him a lot sooner,''
said former Mavericks team physician Dr. T.O. Souryal, who oversaw
Tarpley's rehab from a torn anterior cruciate ligament in '90.
``But it was just a matter of time. The Mavericks tried everything
in their power to help Roy, and he turned his back on them every
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarpley tip-toed through the system in '94-95 but never played
in a Mavericks uniform again. He spent 32 days in the hospital the
following summer with pancreatitis, an ailment the Mavericks knew
was caused by excessive alcohol use but one he blamed on ``too much
spicy food, too much Tabasco.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, at the request of the Mavericks, the NBA pulled a
surprise Wednesday test. Hours before tip-off of their game in
Philadelphia, news hit the Mavericks locker room that Tarpley,
still on the injured list and back home in Dallas, had finally
drank himself dormant.
</P>
<P>
   He was paid $665,000 for the season, but his suspension voided
the remaining five years and $22 million of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more relief than sadness at that point,'' said Motta,
who suspended Tarpley seven times in six seasons. ``I gave Roy the
25-cent speech, the one dollar speech, the lecture from the heart,
and it was like talking to a brick wall.'' THE AFTERMATH
</P>
<P>
   Assessing the damage rendered by Hurricane Roy is difficult
because some former team officials believe it's still ongoing.
Tarpley's two swirling visits through Dallas obliterated
potentially numerous Mavericks playoff appearances, which in turn
cost them national television appearances, advertising dollars,
season-ticket holders and, eventually, employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real shame the Mavericks ever laid eyes on him,'' Motta
said. ``He was a bad guy that ruined it for a lot of good people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks' demise into the NBA cellar was nothing, however,
compared to Tarpley's impending implosion.
</P>
<P>
   After a failed stint overseas in which his drinking led to
sub-par play and an eventual release from Cyprus, Tarpley returned
to Dallas in the summer of '97 and climaxed his abusive
relationship with the 23-year-old Spacek. Aguirre quietly bailed
him out of jail on three separate arrests for hitting, choking and
threatening to kill Spacek from July to November.
</P>
<P>
   On each arrest report, Tarpley listed his occupation as ``Pro
basketball player'' and his employer as ``unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to sell the house; I had to take over his debts and set
him up in an apartment,'' Aguirre said. ``There were nights where I
have no idea where he slept and, believe me, I don't want to know.
It was almost out of control at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   That December, Spacek flipped her BMW on Dallas' LBJ Freeway. As
she stumbled onto the shoulder attempting to flag down help, a Ford
Explorer hit and killed her as she talked to Tarpley on her cell
phone. He thought it was only the phone that went dead.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week later, Aguirre said Tarpley experienced his
face-plant into rock-bottom. With Aguirre's help, Tarpley landed a
lawyer, a patched-up relationship with his mother and yet another
chance to save his life. Out of jail and back from rehab, Tarpley
phoned Dallas police last August asking if he could get his clothes
out of Spacek's totaled car.
</P>
<P>
   And with that, Roy Tarpley left Dallas for good. RE-BIRTH OR
REPEAT?
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly twisted in the Terrible Tale of Tarpley,
Carter-the-good-Christian wound up carrying blame for letting
Tarpley fall while Aguirre-the-one-time-malcontent is credited with
helping him back to his feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I did was done because I cared about Roy so much, out of
love,'' Carter said. ``But seeing how it all turned out, it's easy
to say I wish we'd done things differently. I still care about him,
but Roy's one of my most painful failures.''
</P>
<P>
   Aguirre last saw Tarpley a year ago, when the two worked out
together and ``you could just see in his eyes he was clean.''
</P>
<P>
   Through Aguirre and his agent, George Andrews, Tarpley declined
to be interviewed. Though eligible to apply for reinstatement, he
has no immediate plans for a comeback in the NBA. Even if he did,
Stern would have to make the unprecedented, and unlikely, move of
granting re-admission to the league's only two-time substance abuse
loser.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Tarpley is apparently content with staying out of
trouble and the limelight while trying to clear his reputation, and
his memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scars and the heartache here ... they'll never heal,''
Aguirre said. ``I don't think he'll ever be back in Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, just being alive is the perfect place for Roy
Tarpley. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
