The Glen could halt D.J.'s roll (For use by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATKINS GLEN, N.Y. _ Two-time NASCAR Winston Cup champion Terry
Labonte says current points-leader Dale Jarrett is on a
NASCAR-certified ``roll.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look back at the history in this sport, you'll see
people who will get on `rolls,''' said Labonte, the native Texan
who won championships in 1984 and 1996. ``You've seen Rusty
Wallace, Bill Elliott, Dale Earnhardt, Jeff Gordon, Darrell Waltrip
and Cale Yarborough do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``D.J.'s on that deal right now. They can't make no mistakes.
Everything they do is right. Everything is clicking.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he never has won a Winston Cup road race, Jarrett will
carry a 274-point lead over Mark Martin into today's Frontier at
The Glen.
</P>
<P>
   But the 2.45-mile, 11-turn Watkins Glen International road
course never has been particularly forgiving to Jarrett, who will
start ninth. That is an improvement of 20 spots for Jarrett from
the season's first road race, at Sears Point Raceway in Sonoma,
Calif., on June 27.
</P>
<P>
   In 12 races at WGI, Jarrett's best finishes have been
fifth-place results in 1991 and 1998. He finished sixth at Sears
Point in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some guys who are faster than we are, and that
certainly makes a difference here,'' said Jarrett, driver of the
No. 88 Quality Care Service/Ford Credit Taurus. ``We've made our
car better. It seems like we're still two or three tenths \Rof a
second\S off, which is a lot closer on a road course than it is on
ovals. But we're running good enough that if we make the right
choices, and the breaks go our way, then yeah, it \Rvictory\S could
happen.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
