<SLUG> BC-CAR-EARNHARDT-TEX </SLUG>
 
EARNHARDT ADDS TO MYSTIQUE WITH 600TH CONSECUTIVE START (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATKINS GLEN, N.Y. _ With little hoopla outside of a
commemorative T-shirt, Dale Earnhardt will make his 600th
consecutive career NASCAR Winston Cup start today at Watkins Glen
International.
</P>
<P>
   His appearance in the Frontier at The Glen will put Earnhardt in
further exclusive company. Only Richard Petty, NASCAR's all-time
leader in victories with 200, and Earnhardt have won seven Cup
titles. And only native Texan Terry Labonte and Earnhardt have
strung together 600 consecutive Cup starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does make a statement that you've been around for a
while,'' said Earnhardt, who qualified 14th in the 43-car field for
the 90-lap event today. ``I don't feel any older \Rthan 48\S, for
sure. I'm excited about racing and feel good about racing. It's a
pretty monumental thing to see 600 starts.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly speaks well for NASCAR Class of 1979 teammates
Labonte and Earnhardt. Between them, they have won nine
championships, 47 poles, 93 races and nearly $56 million.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte is NASCAR's undisputed ``Ironman,'' having started 623
consecutive races since becoming a full-time Cup driver in '79.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big accomplishment, especially when so many of these
other guys out here come up and say something to you about it,''
said Labonte, a 42-year-old native of Corpus Christi. ``Because the
guys that have been doing it for only two or three or five years,
they know how tough it is. That's what makes you feel good, the
fact that everybody in this garage area knows how tough it is to
accomplish that. And to reach that number is something that not a
lot of guys will have an opportunity to do.''
</P>
<P>
   An injury suffered in a wreck at Pocono (Pa.) Raceway forced
Earnhardt to sit out four of 31 races in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise, we'd probably be tied neck-and-neck for this
deal,'' Earnhardt said, referring to Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, a two-time Cup champion, said he is pleased to have
Earnhardt join him in the 600 Club _ albeit as a solid No. 2
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of respect for Dale,'' said Labonte, who will
start 10th on the 2.45-mile, 11-turn road course. ``He's one of the
guys that when you retire[ that] you'll be proud you raced
against.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of that, Labonte said, is because racking up numbers like
these has been incidental[ for himself and Earnhardt].
</P>
<P>
   ``You go out every week and do your job and do it the best you
can,'' said Labonte, driver of the No. 5 Kellogg's Chevrolet Monte
Carlo. ``I know he's the same way I am. If he didn't think he could
go out and win, he wouldn't do it. That chance for another
championship ... I mean, I know I want to win another championship
awful bad. He does too because he's stuck right there with Richard.
That's what drives you.
</P>
<P>
   ``This other record is something that just happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Earnhardt and Labonte have seen their yearly victory totals
dip this decade but insist that is not tied to either diminishing
skills or commitment. Earnhardt arguably was near the top of his
game in 1990, when he won nine races and his fourth championship.
But he went winless in 1997 before logging his[ overdue] first
Daytona 500 victory, in 1998. Earnhardt's[ most recent, and] only
victory of 1999 at the Talladega (Ala.) Superspeedway in April was
the 72nd of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so competitive in Winston Cup racing today,'' said
Earnhardt, driver of the No. 3 GM Goodwrench Service Plus Chevy.
``It's tougher to win than it's ever been. Look at me. We were on
top so long. We got sidelined with some things, and it's taken time
to get back on the game. You can't put your finger on it. Why do
you go out and race and not win, and why all of a sudden do you
win? How do you judge if it's the car or the driver or the crew
chief or the engine guy or components in between? One day you're on
top of the world, and the next day you're not winning, and somebody
is ready to retire you.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt said he and team owner Richard Childress, with whom
Earnhardt has won six of his seven titles, are working on a
contract extension that will carry them into the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard and I have a great relationship, and there's not been
any talk of retirement between us at all,'' Earnhardt said.
Goodwrench and he and I are working all the details out for our
agreement for three more years after the year 2000. We're going to
keep racing and go forward. We still feel like we can win
championships and win races. So, that's where we're at.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
