<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7685 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-SPRINT-MERGER-SECONDT     08-14 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-MERGER-SECONDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTWOOD, Kan. _ with their own.
</P>
<P>
   What's unclear is how comfortable Sprint would be joining forces
with either partner, both of whom are lumbering bureaucracies just
awakening from long tenures as monopolies. Neither company is as
nimble as Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   With his focus on the company's share price, Esrey appears
disinclined to let either company increase its stake in Sprint
without a full buyout, if only because it might make Sprint less
appealing to other suitors.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Sprint needs an international presence, and
could use a partner with deep pockets to fund its initiatives in
the United States. In the next few years, the company will need to
invest billions to upgrade its nationwide, $10 billion Sprint PCS
network to expand coverage and provide third-generation wireless
services, which incorporate high-speed data.
</P>
<P>
   The company also is investing heavily in its Integrated
On-Demand Network, a bundled package of voice and data services
that it eventually hopes to offer to customers throughout the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts applaud the strategy of Sprint. But they question
how Sprint will keep pace with competitors without borrowing
heavily or issuing new shares, both of which would lean heavily on
the company's earnings and stock price. The answer they reach is
inevitably a merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Deutsche Telekom got hold of Sprint, it would be all about
injecting capital and expanding the business, not a contraction,''
said Andrew Moffatt, an analyst with ABN Amro in London.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts are betting on the Germans as Sprint's ongoing
partner in Global One, if not its owner. The company has more cash.
And it is openly shopping for international deals to reduce its
reliance on the German market, where competition has reduced
long-distance prices by 35 percent in the last year and slashed its
profit.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint would clearly be a large deal, a logical but expensive
move that Deutsche Telekom might have difficulty swallowing so soon
after its deal to acquire One2One. Also, there would be few
opportunities for cost-cutting synergies. Sprint already operates a
leaner business than the German company, and they have few
overlapping operations.
</P>
<P>
   That would be positive for Kansas City, Sprint employees and
vendors in the event of an acquisition. To date, most analysts have
been pairing Sprint off with domestic companies such as BellSouth,
which probably would eliminate redundant operations, consolidate
purchasing and take control of the operation to another city.
</P>
<P>
   A foreign buyer probably would leave Sprint's operations intact,
if not untouched. And, as with the merger of Chrysler and
Daimler-Benz, the company would need a U.S. headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, in the Kansas City area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
