<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7686 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-SPRINT-MERGER-TWOTAKE     08-14 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-MERGER-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT'S ROLE IN MERGER WOULDN'T NECESSARILY BE ALL BAD FOR KANSAS
CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTWOOD, Kan. _ Psychologically, it ranks right up there with
the possibility of the Kansas City Royals someday leaving town.
Economically, it could be worse.
</P>
<P>
   What if Sprint Corp. of Westwood _ the area's largest private
employer, one of its few Fortune 500 companies and a real estate
linchpin _ gets swept up in the next round of telecommunications
mergers?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a headline that any economic development specialist in
the region would dread waking up to,'' said Doug Luciani, senior
vice president of economic development and growth at the Greater
Kansas City Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, most telecommunications analysts think it's
inevitable. But even if Sprint ends up in a merger, that doesn't
necessarily mean the end of the company's presence in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint simply lacks the size, analysts say, to compete in an
industry increasingly dominated by giants, where every new
opportunity comes with a multibillion-dollar price tag.
</P>
<P>
   With each new megamerger, Sprint Chief Executive William T.
Esrey meets the inevitable speculation about his company with a
stock response: Sprint ``has everything it needs to compete'' _
alone.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he says the company's board is bound to
listen to offers.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of an impending merger resurfaced recently with the
latest round of unconfirmed reports that Europe's largest phone
company, Deutsche Telekom, is in takeover talks with Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   According to the German media, senior managers at Deutsche
Telekom say the company, which already owns 10 percent of Sprint,
``has the home straight in sight'' in talks to increase that stake
_ widely seen as a steppingstone to a full buyout.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom and Sprint refuse to comment on what they
characterize as speculation. But part of the media accounts were
borne out when Deutsche Telekom announced plans to buy the British
wireless company One2One.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom Chief Executive Ron Sommer described the
One2One deal as a first step in the company's global expansion
plans, which will include a foothold in the world's largest
communications market: the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason for us to not go after large mergers,''
Sommer said in a news conference Monday in London. ``We won't
become a global player if we are not equally footed in the U.S. and
Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Many observers think a Sprint buyout is a plausible scenario,
especially once Sprint, France Telecom and Deutsche Telekom have
extricated themselves from their troubled international joint
venture, Global One.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Global One alliance likely to fall apart, the odds
are rather high that Deutsche Telekom buys out France Telecom's
stake in Sprint ... to own 20 percent of Sprint,'' Jack Grubman, an
analyst at Salomon Smith Barney, wrote in a recent research report.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't completely shock us if Deutsche Telekom ... over
time decides to buy all of Sprint.''
</P>
<P>
   In parochial terms, a European offer for Sprint may be one of
the best alternatives for Kansas City, which is loath to see
control of its largest private employer slip local moorings. If
there is a merger, a foreign buyer is seen as much more likely than
a domestic one to maintain a large Kansas City presence.
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret that Global One is coming undone.
</P>
<P>
   Originally billed as a model of global telecommunications
alliances, Global One is now described by industry analysts as a
three-headed monster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mess,'' said Jeffrey Kagan, an industry analyst based
in Atlanta. ``It clearly illustrates how sticky these alliances can
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Global One is working to a degree. With a presence in
65 countries and more than $1.1 billion in revenue, the 3-year-old
venture has made big strides to become a one-stop shop for
multinational companies seeking voice, data and networking services
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The venture, however, has been dogged from the start by
larger-than-expected losses, management turnover and the
difficulties of sewing together complex phone networks built by
three different companies.
</P>
<P>
   The venture also has been marred as the partners struggle to
share their most lucrative customers, bill one another for calls on
their respective networks and try to pursue new international
opportunities on their own.
</P>
<P>
   From Sprint's vantage, France Telecom and Deutsche Telekom are
establishing new ventures _ together and alone _ that could compete
directly with Global One, most notably an Italian phone company
called Wind.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey calls the Global One difficulties a ``misalignment'' and
talks in terms of ``restructuring the ownership interests.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the partners in Global One is eager to lose its stake in
the alliance, which is a valuable asset in spite of its troubles.
But the companies are currently negotiating who will sell what.
</P>
<P>
   If the alliance isn't dissolved, it's clear that Sprint won't be
the one left sitting alone on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any European phone company that wants to be global has to have
access to the United States,'' said Peter Roe, an analyst with
Paribas in London. ``There's going to be a reckoning at Global One,
and the gem in that reckoning is the relationship with Sprint.''
</P>
<P>
   For a European company looking for a beachhead in the United
States, there are few better targets than Sprint, which overnight
would offer a huge position in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Europeans already know what Sprint looks like from
the inside. They know Sprint's networks, back-office operations and
management team, and how they would meld with their own. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
