<DOCNO> NYT19990814.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7687 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-MEDAL-RECIPIENTS-KAN &LR;      08-14 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDAL-RECIPIENTS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDAL OF HONOR RECIPIENTS REMEMBER THEIR COMRADES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN BURNES and MATTHEW SCHOFIELD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ First, some etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   The 155 living American veterans who hold the Medal of Honor,
this country's highest decoration for valor in action against an
enemy force, never describe themselves as ``winners'' of the medal.
</P>
<P>
   They are, instead, recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Second, anyone meeting the 20 Medal of Honor recipients who are
in Kansas City this week for the Veterans of Foreign Wars national
convention shouldn't expect to hear war stories.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing heard when these veterans gather is any talk of
that particular hill, bunker or pillbox.
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis, instead, is on love of country and humility. The
humility, however, will be in inverse proportion to the remarkable
acts of valor described in their citations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there is one Medal of Honor recipient who
feels he is a hero,'' said Donald Ballard of North Kansas City,
Mo., a former U.S. Navy corpsman who received his decoration after
throwing himself on a grenade to protect comrades in Vietnam in
1968. The grenade failed to detonate, and he continued fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will all echo the same sentiment, that `I am not a hero.'
We just saw the need to do what we did at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Medal of Honor recipients were to attend a VFW convention
gala Sunday at Bartle Hall in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Though the VFW has brought the 20 recipients to Kansas City,
it's not the only time Medal of Honor recipients gather. The
national Congressional Medal of Honor Society, which promotes
camaraderie among the recipients, holds an annual convention.
</P>
<P>
   Through these and similar events, many of the recipients have
grown close over the years by virtue of their one defining moment.
</P>
<P>
   They've had the chance to reflect on where they found the
courage on that one day, how their lives have changed since, what
they now have in common, how important it is to live their lives in
a manner befitting the medal, and _ finally _ the mystery of why
they survived when so many of their friends did not.
</P>
<P>
   The last question is especially vexing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get to heaven, one of my first questions to God will
be, `Why me?' '' said Hershel Williams of Ona, W.Va., who serves as
chaplain of the medal's national society. Williams received his
medal for his actions in the early days of the Iwo Jima landing in
February 1945 when he, then a Marine corporal, cleared a critical
path through Japanese forces with a flamethrower.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a couple of Marines who died in the process of
giving me protection, so why did I survive when so many around me
did not?'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There must have been a purpose. Perhaps God is using me for
speaking about how great this country is and how fortunate we are
to have been born in America.''
</P>
<P>
   A request that recipients often hear is to describe the
reservoir of inner fortitude they have in common.
</P>
<P>
   But David Dolby of Oaks, Pa., an Army veteran who received his
medal from actions in Vietnam in 1966, insisted that recipients
were normal in every way, except perhaps for that one instant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, we're all equal,'' he said. ``We all did things that, if
we had chosen not to do, nobody would have said we should have
done. We all had that one moment in our lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than that, we're just normal people.''
</P>
<P>
   Many recipients also think they must conduct their lives in a
manner befitting the medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since receiving the medal, we have received along with it a
tremendous responsibility to maintain the dignity of the medal,''
said Joseph Rodriguez of El Paso, Texas, an Army veteran who
received his medal for actions in Korea in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   The Medal of Honor dates back to 1861, when Abraham Lincoln
approved it as a way to reward gallantry in action.
</P>
<P>
   In the 138 years since, the United States has been militarily
involved in the Civil War, two world wars, Vietnam, Korea and
dozens of smaller conflicts. Still, out of the millions of
Americans who have served their country, only 3,410 have received
the award. Nineteen veterans have received the honor twice.
</P>
<P>
   Harry S. Truman once remarked, ``I would rather have that medal
than be president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The standards for receiving the medal are high enough that in
1916, the Army stripped 911 past recipients of their medals, ruling
that their deeds had not been sufficiently ``heroic.'' Among those
who lost their medals was Mary Walker, a physician who served as a
surgeon during the Civil War and is listed as the only woman to
ever receive it. Her medal was reinstated in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Recipients today wear the medal only on occasions they deem
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   For civilian attire, many recipients display a lapel pin that
can be worn in lieu of hanging the medal around their necks.
</P>
<P>
   But some recipients in recent years have found themselves
wearing the actual medal more often.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wear it more frequently now because of the support of the
country,'' Ballard said. ``Since Desert Storm, people have started
to appreciate the military again.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams agreed, adding that recipients wear the medal not to
honor themselves but their comrades, many of whom fell beside them
in battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all have in common the idea that even though we
were awarded the Medal of Honor, it actually belongs more to others
than it does to us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 2227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990814.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7688 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      08-14 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. MILLER EXPOSES THE NAKED TRUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm speaking with one of the many Mrs. George Millers in town
who does NOT pose naked and have sex ``live'' on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Mrs. George Millers from the metropolitan area, this
one has received a number of telephone calls lately from
individuals who believe they've seen pictures of her on their
computer, or who would like to see pictures of her, or who would
like to do things with her that Mrs. Miller finds repulsive.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Television stations and radio stations from all over have been
leaving messages on our machine,'' she says. ``George Miller is a
fairly common name. There are a lot of us in the area. Still, it's
disgusting to me how the media has given these two people so much
attention. And worse, makes them out to be victims.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Miller is referring to George and Tracy Miller, the married
nurses who lost their jobs at Scottsdale Healthcare Osborn because
they operate an X-rated Web site in which Nurse Tracy plays doctor
with Nurse George for any computer owner willing to pay them $15 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   The nurses say they've placed their privates on public display
in order to put their two children through college. &QL; 
NEED A 2ND JOB? &QL; 
``That's just ridiculous,'' the fully clothed Mrs. Miller says.
``First of all, with what they earn (reported to be a combined
$92,000 a year) they don't need a second job to send their kids to
college. Besides, if you're looking for outside work, is this
something the parents of small children should do?''
</P>
<P>
   Only if they want put them through hell before putting them
through school.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, Nurse George told me his 11-year-old son had not
been adversely affected by what his parents do in front of the
camera. As for the couple's 5-year-old daughter, Nurse George says
she's too young to comprehend the naked truth. Or is it the bare
facts?
</P>
<P>
   The raw details? The particulars?
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter. I suspect that among the Miller kids'
classmates, there's a computer wiz who'll eventually uncover the
family enterprise and expose the youngsters to the mom and dad's
hard-core business affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the sad part to me,'' the well-attired Mrs. Miller
says. ``And it's so unnecessary. This isn't about the First
Amendment or about rights on the job. If you're a parent, your
first job is your kids. These people are thinking about only one
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   (No, it's not sex. That's what their customers think about.) &QL; 
ALL ABOUT MONEY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The nurses are thinking about money.
</P>
<P>
   Success in the 1990s is defined by money and nothing else. A
pair of nurses who become millionaires having sex on the Internet
could get a book deal, a movie deal, stories in ``People''
magazine, talk show interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Respectability.
</P>
<P>
   After all, no one in my business is particularly interested in
the many George Millers who don't have an X-rated Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband and I put two daughters through college when we
were earning less than the nurses,'' the neatly dressed Mrs. Miller
says. ``You're not just giving kids an education, you're passing on
a legacy about behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Mr. and Mrs. George Millers live quietly, avoid publicity,
and work with their clothes on.
</P>
<P>
   As long as Nurse Tracy and Nurse George are in the news,
however, other George Miller families can expect to receive unusual
phone calls, along with the usual ribbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband gets kidded about it at work,'' Mrs. Miller says.
`` `Hey, George, saw you on TV,' they say. I get my share of it,
too. You've got to have a sense of humor about it. I tell them it's
a good thing we're not those kind of people. Not only is it the
last thing I'd ever do, but I don't suppose anyone would want to
see a 56-year-old woman undressed on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   She laughs. I laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Then I log onto my computer and type in words like ``mature
woman,'' ``older woman,'' ``old woman'' and ``granny.''
</P>
<P>
   After 1,581 X-rated Web sites pop up, I stop counting. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini &LR; pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
