r a BC-HATE-INTERNET-3rdtake     08-14 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-INTERNET-3rdtake-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY GREG GITTRICH 
</HEADLINE>
 
LOS ANGELES: poaching in the jungle.'' 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  and BETH BARRETT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is the nature of racist groups to disavow isolated acts of
violence while creating a psychological climate capable of
triggering aggressive outbursts by impressionable young people or
unstable adults, Simonelli said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are all kinds of manuals for urban terrorism,'' he said.
``These tend to be indictments of the Jews that would lead an
unstable person to take the next step to violence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They never come out explicitly and say, `Kill Jews, blow up
synagogues,' but what they do instead is draw a picture of the
supposed cataclysm that is coming and how everything we value is
being destroyed by the Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically they end with a question like, `Who will stand up
for the white race?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The ``lone wolf'' strategy of providing incendiary materials to
a susceptible person to push them toward violence was adopted by
The Order.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Order provided the impetus for the lone wolf
actions,'' &UR;  &LR; said Flynn, the Denver-based expert on the violent
white supremacists.
</P>
<P>
   The Order's founder, Robert Mathews, had recruited about 40
people into his ranks and kept a detailed list of the members.
During a shootout in Oregon with federal authorities, he dropped
the incriminating evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson from that was to not write down members' names and
to form smaller cells. But even small cells could be broken up by
law enforcement,'' Flynn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That led to what's known as leaderless resistance with
independent actors. You can't infiltrate one guy like Buford
Furrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Under intense scrutiny from law enforcement agencies and civil
rights organizations, the groups have turned to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Hatred is promoted on a growing number of Web pages, many of
which are designed to mimic educational sites or child-friendly
fare.
</P>
<P>
   A recent review by the Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los Angeles
found about 1,500 objectionable sites around the world. Using
different standards, the Southern Poverty Law Center in Montgomery
Ala., a not-for-profit, public-interest law firm, counted about 300
U.S. sites.
</P>
<P>
   Cyberspace has increasingly become an inexpensive way to promote
racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, if you were someone who lived in a small
community and you didn't know other racists, you probably thought
you were warped and sick,'' the ADL's Galatzan said. ``Now, with
what's on the Internet, you have a virtual racist community. You
can easily get to stuff that validates what you think.''
</P>
<P>
   Graffiti on synagogues in the communities of West Hills and
Northridge vandalized a year ago included Web page addresses for
the National Alliance, a West Virginia-based hate group that the
ADL has identified as the nation's most dangerous. A similar link
was made between the group and anti-Semitic fliers distributed in
the Valley about the same time.
</P>
<P>
   National Alliance leader William Luther Pierce was U.S. Nazi
leader Rockwell's right-hand deputy. After Rockwell's assassination
in 1967, Pierce adopted a more violent philosophy, Simonelli said.
</P>
<P>
   Simonelli said the new racists' tactics and the violent acts of
the past year should stir the country to action using a campaign of
intensive education, public awareness and monitoring of hate
groups' activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a terrible tragedy if we don't learn the lesson
that these things are teaching us: That these people who hold these
views are changing their tactics and becoming more violent while
staking out a new presence among the disaffected, especially the
young,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't sit by while people of fascist mentality demonize and
victimize groups. It doesn't go away or get any better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support free speech entirely, but I want the freedom to
condemn the groups for what they are, as groups that are out to
destroy everything that's good in this society.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
