<HEADER>
A7690 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-HATE-INTERNET-2ndtake     08-14 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-INTERNET-2ndtake-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY GREG GITTRICH 
</HEADLINE>
 
LOS ANGELES: their ranks.'' 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  and BETH BARRETT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Lehrer, ADL regional director in Los Angeles, said racist
acts are increasingly ``bizarre,'' indicating the movement's
``desperation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They had delusions 25 years ago that if the moment came, their
message could have a receptive audience in the vast heartlands of
America, but they've figured out that's not going to happen,''
Lehrer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast bulk of Americans are beyond their reach. So they
focus on younger people, the disgruntled, militia, skinheads.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Richard Butler, the 81-year-old head of the
Idaho-based Aryan Nations, recalled Furrow as a ``nice, affable
person,'' who studied Scripture at his Church of Jesus Christ
Christian several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Butler performed the marriage ceremony for Furrow and Debra
Mathews, the widow of Robert Mathews, the founder of the neo-Nazi
group The Order who died in 1984 following an FBI standoff in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Butler, a former Lockheed engineer from suburban Whittier,
attracted people like Furrow - a former resident of Rosamond near
Edwards Air Force Base - with deep antipathy for the racial
diversity of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   About two-thirds of recent arrivals to the Aryan Nations'
compound and surrounding towns have fled from L.A., Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   The compound's creed: ``We tell the so-called Jews moving in
here to go to Los Angeles because they have there what they want.
Don't destroy this area!''
</P>
<P>
   White supremacists long have been obsessed with Los Angeles,
said Kevin Flynn, who co-authored ``The Silent Brotherhood'' (Free
Press 1989), which chronicled The Order's 1983 assassination of
Alan Berg, the Jewish host of a Denver radio talk program.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Order's) next planned action was sabotage in the L.A.
area,'' Flynn said. ``They were going to take out the high voltage
towers and lines coming into Los Angeles to cause a blackout. Then
they intended to bring in guerrilla-trained units from Idaho to
start shooting randomly - like Furrow did - in minority
neighborhoods to start race riots.''
</P>
<P>
   Neuman Britton, who runs the Aryan Nations in California from
Escondido near San Diego, said that Christian Identity stamped L.A.
as ``a kind of sacred, a holy place.'' He said he dreams of a day
when the city would be all white.
</P>
<P>
   Butler refused to call Los Angeles a ``target'' of the Aryan
Nations, but talked longingly of a day when the city might be
``reclaimed.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he is counting on the likes of Owens, whom he has heard
of but never met, and Britton to carry on the movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like the Apostle Paul, I've served my time,'' he said.
``Someone will pick it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens said he first heard of Furrow after the Granada Hills
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no comment on that action because it was not an AIM
action,'' Owens said. ``Let me say the privileged class do not
realize how far down they have driven the working class, how much
angst is welling up in the white working class.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if they don't wake up and do something they can - there is
going to be a lot more turmoil than they've ever expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens founded the group in September and claims it has about 150
members, mainly in Southern California. The ADL estimated the
membership at 30.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the earlier neo-Nazi groups, AIM has no headquarters
building and doesn't fly the Nazi flag or lead marches.
</P>
<P>
   ``AIM's strategy is to recruit among youth and use more
sophisticated and modern techniques of political and social
activism to move toward a brighter future,'' he said. ``We don't
try to scare people.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the white separatists have launched a grocery
delivery service to help mothers, the disabled, and elderly ``white
folks'' in Los Angeles, San Diego, and Riverside counties. They
also run an ``anti-illegal labor campaign'' to place white workers
in homes that were previously hiring illegal immigrants to do yard
work and cleaning. Their Web site features special pages designed
to appeal to children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not discriminate,'' Owens said. ``All white people are
eligible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been a member of another group because before AIM
there was never a group of racial activism that had potential of
actually winning ... I wish our ultimate goal could be achieved
without violence, but history tells me otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Simonelli, who spent nine years researching neo-Nazism in the
U.S., said the packaging of white supremacism in terms of leaders,
symbolism and speech has changed over the years, but the core of
hatred has remained the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to remember that all these people come back to
the same beliefs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Forbes, who headed the American Nazi Party operation in
Glendale and El Monte, called Furrow a ``nut'' who might have been
pushed to act because he sensed the ``cultural genocide''
threatening the white race.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes a nut do that?'' said Forbes, 59, who lives near
Russellville, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he senses this threat and has no other outlet, like the
last gorilla that's about to become extinct going after the people
poaching in the jungle.''
</P>
<P>
   (THIRD TAKE FOLLOWS.) &QL;
</P>
