<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-INTERNET-3TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEPARATISTS RECRUITING ON THE INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREG GITTRICH  
 and BETH BARRETT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sunk into the cushions of a tattered couch in the
dark back room of a Hollywood cafe, Eric Owens appears to be no one
special, just another slight, white, tattooed, downtown denizen
without a full-time job.
</P>
<P>
   What separates Owens from the crowd, to hear him and hate
experts tell it, is that he is the founder and ruler of the Aryan
International Movement, the most active of the Los Angeles area's
fragmented white supremacist organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Owens stands out as the new face of hate - a 145-pound,
working-class white man from West L.A. who says his experiences in
an integrated high school prompted him to embrace racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't have a complete revolution within 25 years this
country is done for,'' Owens said, measuring every word.
</P>
<P>
   Shifting his body into the purple glow of the cafe's fluorescent
black lights, Owens added: ``It will be such that there won't be
enough consolidated white areas for us to achieve the kind of
victory we want. I believe something drastic has to happen very
soon. I would like to see a complete and total replacement of the
United States government.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar intolerance, seeded and nurtured in cities, small towns
and military outposts across the nation, exploded into view again
Tuesday when a ``lone wolf'' white supremacist, Buford O'Neal
Furrow Jr., rampaged through the San Fernando Valley. Five people
were shot at the Jewish Community Center in suburban Granada Hills,
a Korean woman's car was hijacked at gunpoint and a Filipino
mailman was slain.
</P>
<P>
   With direct ties to the neo-Nazi movements of the post-World War
II era, white power groups in Southern California come in numerous
flavors and with varying degrees of danger. They are small, mobile
and incendiary, and boast tentacles that reach out for new
recruits, often through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   To a large extent, Los Angeles has long been their sacred
ground, viewed as a former holy land of white purity.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Identity, a racist church, was founded by Wesley Swift
in Hollywood after World War II. The American Nazi Party's Western
Division was headquartered in the city of Glendale and later in
suburban El Monte through the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Most old-school racist leaders died or fled L.A. for the Pacific
Northwest or other places where there are fewer blacks, Asians,
Latinos and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a new generation preaches a hate-filled ideology through
telephone hotlines, impromptu meetings and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The growing presence of the Aryan International Movement, gangs
like the Nazi Low Riders, and religious sects such as the Christian
Identity Church are especially troubling because hate-related
violence tends to clump around the roots of organizations'
headquarters, said Sue Stengel, western states counsel for the
Anti-Defamation League.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a decline of larger, ``more traditional'' hate
groups, the ADL and law enforcement agencies have had difficulty
getting accurate head counts for the new splinter organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our best estimate is membership is declining, but the level of
violence is escalating,'' said Tamar Galatzan, ADL western states
associate counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those left may be the die-hards. Or it might be that as a
society we've become accustomed to a certain level of violence and
now, in order to get attention, you have to commit a really
violent, horrendous, vicious act to get noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   By the ADL's count, there are some 14 local hate organizations
and more than a half-dozen related ``skinhead'' or white power
groups in the L.A. area.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish individuals and organizations suffered the bulk of
religious hate crimes in Los Angeles County last year, but those
incidents declined 14 percent, from 100 in 1997 to 86 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Police Department statistics from the first six
months of this year show the largest number of 193 reported hate
crimes took place in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The active hate groups espouse similar beliefs and goals, and
increasingly have been able to abandon the kind of public
recruitment that law enforcement successfully infiltrated, for the
relative anonymity of post office boxes and Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be surprised if there are more than 5,000 hard-core
neo-Nazis in California,'' said Frederick J. Simonelli, author of
the just-released ``American Fuehrer: George Lincoln Rockwell and
the American Nazi Party'' (University of Illinois Press 1999).
</P>
<P>
   ``What's worrisome and dangerous is where the battleground is,
where they are trying to entice people into the movement,''
Simonelli said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Acts like burning the synagogues in Sacramento or the assault
on the Jewish center are designed to raise their profile to attract
the disaffected into their ranks.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND AND THIRD TAKES FOLLOW.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
