<SLUG> BC-FISHER-COLUMN-SECONDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LATHROP, Mo. _ horses or mules.
</P>
<P>
   Schmitt and Foster said they were going to the seminar. Even
Larson _ who looks the part of the Marlboro Man _ could remember
two men hanging on to an unbroke mule with ropes while a third
gingerly climbed into the saddle. He said he saw advantages to such
methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd let go, and then it'd be Katy bar the door for a while
with that mule bucking every which way,'' Larson said. ``The
problem with mules is that once they get a bad habit, they're
harder to break of it. Lots of people are starting them slower _
ground training, longue lines and other stuff. Makes for better
animal in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   Plowman said despite Lathrop's rich legacy as a mule center,
there are no plans to boom the annual show up into something bigger
than can't be handled locally.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a just a get-together for people who like mules,'' he
said. ``There's plenty of them around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
