<HEADER>
A7696 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-FISHER-COLUMN-TWOTAKE     08-14 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHER-COLUMN-TWO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI TOWN CELEBRATES ITS HISTORY AS A MULE CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LATHROP, Mo. _ The eighth annual Lathrop Mule Show took place
here last Saturday _ 84 animals, 46 events from halter to flag
racing, and a good turnout of several hundred people from all over
Missouri, eastern Kansas and southern Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Uncounted, of course, were all the long-eared ghosts.
</P>
<P>
   Phantasms of soft-eyed, stubborn-willed equines, for those who
remember history, still faintly reside in this little town 50 miles
northeast of Kansas City. The town proclaims itself the Mule
Capital of the World, a sobriquet Maury County, Tenn., might
dispute, being big on mules itself and billing itself with the same
name.
</P>
<P>
   Still, signs leading into this town declare its link to mules
and its ``capital'' status.
</P>
<P>
   Lathrop deserved the title when it was bestowed 80-plus years
ago. What are now the surrounding soybean and corn fields then were
pastures. On any given day from 1914 to 1918 _ the years of what
was known as ``the Great War'' _ 30,000 mules and horses blanketed
those pastures.
</P>
<P>
   Most were mules _ so many, in fact, that dried manure in the
fields, ignited from a discarded cigarette or pipe's ember,
smoldered continually. There was constant pall of smoke over
Lathrop and its adjacent 20 ``mule stations'' with their massive
mule barns. One such structure measured 312 by 210 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the mules and horses had to eat. Feed came in by the
train load _ bran, oats, corn and hay. In those years, more rail
cars moved through here than on all the spider web of tracks the
Kansas City Terminal Railway had surrounding Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The trains brought mules, too, ones flushed from the back
country of Missouri, Nebraska, Kansas and Iowa by buyers with
fistfuls of cash to offer eager farmers who invariably had an extra
2-year-old or a brace of 4-year-olds out behind the barn. Tractors
then were ``newfangled.'' Mules and horses were the motive power on
dirt farms.
</P>
<P>
   Even what's now Missouri 116 was a busy thoroughfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``One old man told me he'd take a white pony out to round up the
mules,'' said George McCorkle, 83. ``Mules will always follow a
white horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd tie a knot in the pony's tail, halter just one mule, and
tie a lead line to the tail just above the knot. And then he'd
start to town riding that pony.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the mules would follow down what's now 116. There'd be a
parade of mules a quarter to half mile long, all following that
white pony.''
</P>
<P>
   The demand for such mules was from the British government. Mules
then, at least to military men, were jeeps and Humvees. Mules were
indispensable in hauling the mortars, machine guns, rations,
ammunition, telegraph wire and all the other gear needed on the
evolving battlefield where no longer did two lines of closely
packed men line up and shoot at each other in volleys.
</P>
<P>
   War had become industrialized. And the mule was needed to pack
in its implements.
</P>
<P>
   The English had discovered Lathrop and its mules during the Boer
War at the turn of the century. In World War I they came back in
force and joined with what then was the biggest mule and horse
trading firm in the world, Guyton &AMP; Harrington, to ship Midwestern
mules to the Western Front.
</P>
<P>
   Clipped British accents mingled with the slower Missouri speech;
checks in $100,000-plus amounts (equal to $1.5 million today) were
common. For a time Lathrop, with its nearby rolling fields, black
with Roman-nosed, brown-eyed and braying hybrids, was indeed the
Mule Capital of the World.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, just south of Lathrop's pleasant homes and neat
streets, one fittingly named Mule Barn Road, the mules were back _
albeit in vastly diminished numbers _ at what's called the Antique
Car Grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yes, those days are part of us, except almost nobody knows
about them now,'' said Jim Plowman, who along with McCorkle got the
show organized several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd had some shows, and then it just sort of faded away,''
added Plowman. ``But the interest came back, and we got it going
again. This is our eighth one. And we get bigger every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Nora Foster, who has a mule, said there are now nine mule shows
a year on the Pony Express Horse show circuit in northwest
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just can't get enough of them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Amen, said Sandy Schmitt, who has a quarter horse but longs for
a mule named Bones whose owner won't sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bones is just a so nice to ride, so easy gaited,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A goodly part of the market for mules these days, said Gary
Larson, a breeder and exhibitor, is women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ladies like them,'' said Larson. ``They're nice to ride. Take
about as much training as a horse, but once that's done, they're
real dependable. Especially for trail riding. Comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Larson, of Laredo, Mo., was here with his jack, J.R., who ears
span 38 inches and is named for the character of the television
show ``Dallas.'' J.R. has done of lot of breeding this year, said
Larson, explaining that a jack to a mare produces a mule; a horse
stallion to a jenny (a female jackass) begets what's called a
henny. They are rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sell some mules before they're even foaled,'' said Larson.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, there was talk at the show here about Monty Roberts,
author of the best-selling The Man Who Listens to Horses, who will
conduct a seminar Tuesday at Hale Arena in Kemper Arena in Kansas
City. Roberts, over the last few years, has revolutionized equine
training in some circles through his methods of body language and
trust between trainer and animal.
</P>
<P>
   In short, according to Roberts, a length of 2-by-4 and brute
force are no longer required teaching aids for horses or mules.
MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
