<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA BALANCES PUBLICITY AND PUGILISM 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIG BEAR LAKE, Calif. _ The phenomenon that Oscar De La Hoya has
become is difficult to understand until you sit on his sofa for a
few hours and watch it in action.
</P>
<P>
   There's a dinner with a dozen Mexican media members to plan for.
There's a T-shirt design for his Sept. 18 welterweight unification
fight with International Boxing Federation champion Felix Trinidad
to approve. There's a 15-minute radio interview to do with the
British version of Sports Illustrated that inevitably stretches to
25 minutes. There are five takes of a radio promo taped over the
phone that will be used to hype the fight's pay-per-view sales.
</P>
<P>
   There's a brief conversation with his marketing agent, Leonard
Armato, the same Leonard Armato who handles Shaquille O'Neal and
once took Brian Shaw to Europe. There's a brief conversation with a
representative of the food supplement company MET-RX. There's an
interlude with a dozen bigwigs from Mandalay Bay, who arrive at Big
Bear Lake Airport in a private plane and at Golden Boy Avenue in a
limousine to have a private audience with a man they're paying
millions of dollars because he can fight so well that rich people
in private planes are willing to come to their Las Vegas casino to
watch him.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the thrice-weekly voice lessons he's taking to
further a fledgling singing career, and another magazine interview
by phone. Prior to that, there are sit-down tapings with ESPN's Al
Bernstein and a television reporter from England's Sky-TV.
Sandwiched in between is the reading of a promo for Aruba cable
television, which leads De La Hoya to ask his longtime publicist,
Dena DuBoef, ``What's that?''
</P>
<P>
   After a brief geography lesson in which he learns that Aruba is
a country, De La Hoya does the promo in English and then a language
he recognizes as something akin to Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say Spanish over there?'' he asks before reading the
message in an Aruban dialect. He does it several times before
satisfying himself that it's acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Then he stretches his arms and sits for a few minutes with an
old acquaintance to talk about La Vida Loco, his own unusual brand
of this crazy life, before heading outside for a half-day session
under cool mountain skies with about 100 media members from Mexico
and the West Coast. De La Hoya moves contentedly from chair to
chair to chair doing TV one-on-ones with an assortment of
interviewers he's never met before from an assortment of places
he's not sure he's heard of before. Only after this exercise, which
takes several hours, does he sit down with about eight rows of
writers and radio reporters to hold an informal press conference
that begins with handshakes for each person and ends with a
surprising number of autographs being signed and pictures being
taken that will never appear in a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   After more than a half-hour of controlled conversation, De La
Hoya finally stands in front of the gym he built for himself more
than 7,000 feet above the Los Angeles Basin and goes off to do what
the world thinks he's paid to do. He goes off to train for the
biggest professional fight of his life.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, however, even the training was done for a media
audience. They stood around or sat on folding chairs outside what
appeared to have once been a garage door to watch De La Hoya work
under the close eye of trainer Robert Alcazar. Such promotion is
key to the creation and feeding of a media superstar, and De La
Hoya understands that as well as any athlete since Muhammad Ali. It
is why he is the only boxer with major endorsement deals, with an
assortment of companies ranging from McDonald's to MET-RX, the
latter of which has designed a nutrition plan for him. MET-RX
people will closely monitor everything he eats, adjusting his diet
to help him build lean muscle and stamina while keeping his weight
on target to hit the 147-pound limit at the weigh-in the night
before the fight.
</P>
<P>
   When that weigh-in is over, the tumult of publicity will finally
stop, but MET-RX's food engineers will continue to work on De La
Hoya, putting him on a different meal plan to rehydrate him while
adding only 5 or 6 pounds to his body weight overnight, rather than
the 12-15 many fighters gain.
</P>
<P>
   It is all part of an engineered life, a life in which De La Hoya
is seldom alone until the dark hours of the night or on the bright
night of the fight when he has only one other face to contend with.
</P>
<P>
   All the commotion that swirls around during a big promotion
convinced Alcazar that some changes had to be made in his fighter's
approach. It is a concession to both De La Hoya's popularity and
Trinidad's abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm putting him in lockdown for the first time,'' Alcazar
explained. ``After this week, no phone, no family, no friends. One
month with nothing but Trinidad and training. Just boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a return to a spartan existence (if you can call it that
when you're living with a private cook in a beautifully appointed
log cabin jammed with video and audio equipment). It is something
De La Hoya has not been asked to do until this moment, a moment he
knows could define his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good idea, really,'' De La Hoya said.
``Everything in my life is compartmentalized. It can get pretty
hectic and confusing at times but it's what I choose to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only one with any decision-making is me. The only one who
has any power is me. Everything has to go through me. It was
getting to the point (before the firing of adviser Mike Hernandez)
where I didn't have control of things. Now I've taken full control.
It's a lot of pressure, but it's what I choose to do.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes the choice to lock himself away at Big Bear Lake
for the next month to take care of his real business. The fight
business.
</P>
<P>
   There will be time enough later for all the rest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although De La Hoya-Trinidad is still close to a pick 'em fight
among bookmakers, promoter Bob Arum is planning for the future as
if a De La Hoya victory is assured. He not only has De La Hoya
booked for a Dec. 11 fight at the new Staples Center in Los Angeles
against World Boxing Council 154-pound champion Javier Castellejo,
but also is talking about a title fight in Las Vegas at either 154
or 147 pounds next April, followed by a June fight against Laurent
Boudouani in Paris. Arum was in Europe last month and claims there
are plans already in the works to build a temporary 10,000-seat
arena under the Eiffel Towel to house that match . . . If Arum can
satisfy the financial demands of Johnny Tapia, there will be a
rematch with the man who took Tapia's bantamweight title, Paulie
Ayala, Dec. 4 at Mandalay Bay. Arum said he has already reserved
the date, ``So now it's up to Johnny.'' Tapia left Arum and signed
with Frank Warren, his third promoter in the last few years, after
losing to Ayala . . . World Boxing Association middleweight
champion William Joppy (27-1-1) is set to defend his title against
WBA ``interim'' champion Julio Cesar Green (25-3) Sept. 25 in
Washington, D.C., the rubber match between Joppy and Green. Green
survived two knockdowns to win a decision from Joppy two years ago
but Joppy avenged the loss by winning a unanimous decision last
year . . . Prince Naseem Hamed's Oct. 22 fight with Cesar Soto, the
WBC featherweight champion, appears headed for the Joe Louis Arena
in Detroit . . . Arum has nearly finalized a January unification
fight between WBC super bantamweight champion Erik Morales and
World Boxing Organization titleholder Marco Antonio Barrera, a
fellow Mexican. Morales's manager wants to put the fight in a
bullring near the beach in Tijuana, while Arum believes it's more
likely to end up at the Staples Center. Either way, it would be an
early contender for Fight of the Year . . . Former 140-pound
champion Vince Phillips has moved up to 147 and may go higher. When
he returned to begin training again in Las Vegas, he weighed 170 .
. . Add this to your list of bad ideas. Well shot ex-champion
Livingston Bramble will fight Theo Holland Aug. 26 in Atlanta . . .
Top heavyweight prospect Michael Grant continues to function
without a promoter now that his contract with the Duvas has ended,
but Cedric Kushner is said to have the inside track at taking over
on a fight-by-fight basis. In the meantime, No. 1-rated David Tua
turned down $1.5 million to fight Grant, so Grant settled for
Andrew Golota. The Foul Pole managed to stop substitute journeyman
Quinn Navarre in July in Poland without resorting to felonious
actions and is now 34-3. Now he's landed a big comeback shot with
Grant Nov. 20 . . . In case you missed it, WBA welterweight
champion James Page KO'd Freddie Pendleton in the 11th round last
weekend to improve to 25-3. The loss dropped the well-traveled
Pendleton to 44-24-4. ``He's nothing but pure power,'' Pendleton
said. ``He's the strongest boxer I've faced.'' That's why promoter
Don King would love to get him in with the winner of De La
Hoya-Trinidad, but that will never happen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's a busy guy. Hector Camacho Jr. recently scored two KOs in
a week, improving to 22-0 by stopping first Miguel Angel Ruiz and
six days later cooling Mike Cooley in two rounds. The undefeated
super lightweight is rated No. 6 in the world by the WBC and No. 8
by the WBA, but who knows whether he can really fight or not since
he keeps facing the kind of guys that let you fight twice in a
week? . . . You have to hand it to New Jersey's judges. They've got
petty larceny down to a science. Had two of them not scored the
final round of the Francois Botha-Shannon Briggs fight for Botha by
2 points _ despite the absence of the traditional knockdown usually
required for such a score _ Botha would have lost a fight he
clearly won, and that might have brought new federal heat down on a
state where the boxing industry has a perpetual black eye. Former
light heavyweight champion Bobby Czyz, now a Showtime analyst, has
grown so accustomed to New Jersey's shenanigans that he predicted
the draw before it was announced. When it came through, he said,
``I hate myself for being right.'' At least Czyz had sense enough
to be embarrassed. Briggs did not. ``This is definitely what
Shannon Briggs needed to become a better fighter,'' Briggs said
when asked about the bloody beating he had just taken . . .
Speaking of Botha, he was asked about being knocked out by Mike
Tyson in their January match and about his apparent taunting of the
former champion during the bout. ``Tiger Woods couldn't have hit a
golf ball better than Mike Tyson hit me,'' Botha said of the
knockout punch that saved Tyson from a certain loss to Botha, who
won every round until then. As for taunting Tyson, Botha said
dryly, ``At least we're not only fighting. We're having a
conversation.'' . . . After several weeks of being pilloried quite
rightly in the press for trying to lure Buster Douglas into a
ritual suicide against Tyson, his promoters backed down last week
under the guise of Douglas refusing the fight. Fact is, the MGM
Grand refused the fight and they're paying for it. So a
still-reluctant Tyson is back to square one, with Orlin Norris or
Jorge Luis Gonzalez now likely to serve as his opponent, although
there were rumors in Las Vegas that the date may be shifted to Oct.
16. ``Tyson's not getting in the ring Oct. 2,'' Arum insisted.
``Even with Butterbean, he's not getting in the ring.'' . . . The
long-anticipated Kostya Tszyu-Miguel Angel Gonzalez fight for the
vacant WBC super lightweight title has finally found a home and a
date. The bout, which has been a political and promotional football
between King and Dan Goossen, finally landed at the Miccousukee
Indian Reservation outside Miami next Saturday after being promised
to Las Vegas. But don't put away your skepticism until the bell
rings . . . Frank Bruno may not have been the best heavyweight ever
to put on gloves, but he always understood the business and how to
make the most money in it. That's why it's no surprise to hear his
take on new WBO champion Vitali Klitschko, conquerer of Herbie
Hide: ``He has fast hands and a good defense and he wasn't as slow
as Herbie thought. He's big, he's white, and he can fight.'' In
other words, he's going to make some cash pretty soon, whether he
can fight or is just another European heavyweight mirage like
Golota.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
