<HEADLINE>
CLASS OF 2000: GRIM PREDICTIONS COME TRUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY PEARCE, JENNIFER BARRETT  
 AND ELIZABETH GREENSPAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Class of 2000 was just learning the alphabet when educators
began talking about how many of the kindergartners would never make
it to graduation.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of a dozen pessimistic predictions the ad hoc group
Arizona Alliance for Education released in 1987 about today's
senior class. More than one-third would drop out before graduation,
it said. More than half who stayed in school would use alcohol or
drugs before graduating. A thousand would end up in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The educators and administrators who made up the alliance said
they hoped the dire forecast would serve as a wake-up call for
Arizonans, illustrating the need for the state to spend more money
and time on education. They called the effort ``Vision for
Arizona's Schools.''
</P>
<P>
   But the reality today is even darker than they'd envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not made a dent on those issues brought up in 1987,''
said Dennis Van Roekel, who was co-chairman of the now-defunct
alliance and is now secretary-treasurer of the National Education
Association. ``We need to recommit as to why the country chose
public education for its students (in the first place).''
</P>
<P>
   If educators were to shine the spotlight on the Class of 2000
now, they would see that many of their predictions and few of their
hopes have come true.
</P>
<P>
   Kathi Foster, D-west Phoenix, a legislator since 1995 and former
Cartwright School District board member, says little has changed
since Van Roekel released the group's predictions, including
funding for education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in good economic times, but you wouldn't know it by
looking at our schools,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past dozen years, state spending per pupil has actually
dropped in comparison with the nation's. When the alliance released
its predictions, Arizona ranked 45th among states on expenditures
per student for public schools. The state has stayed at or near the
bottom ever since.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Arizona is at the top of more dubious lists.
According to the most recent data, the state has the highest rate
of teenage dropouts in the country and is among the highest for
teen pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the face of such challenges, the students themselves
have managed to exceed expectations in academic areas. Test scores
have improved over the past decade and have remained consistently
above the national average.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teenagers are not all going down in the dumps,'' said Joy
Richard, a senior at Seton Catholic School in Chandler. ``We need
to show people we can and do wonderful things.''
</P>
<P>
   More Arizona high school graduates than ever, for example, are
going on to college. During the past 13 years, enrollment at
Maricopa Community Colleges, one of the largest community college
systems in the country, has grown 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Educators caution, however, that some of that growth may be
attributed to the overall increase in the state's student
population.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers and educators give the same reason for the disparity
in education funding. Arizona is one of the fastest-growing states
in the country. In 1996, the state's student-population growth was
the second-highest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enrollment is growing so fast that keeping up with the need
seems to be a problem,'' said Vance Grant, statistics specialist
with the U.S. Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Although Arizona's spending per student has increased 20 percent
in the past decade, the nation's average per-pupil expenditure has
jumped nearly 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some state lawmakers say the numbers can be deceiving.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Schottel, R-Tucson, chairman of the House Education
Committee, said Arizona has pumped $1.2 billion new dollars into
education since he was elected to office seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a balancing act,'' he said. ``We have to look at
what's good for students and what's good for taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Roekel said lawmakers nationwide have tried to cut taxes
since the 1980s. Although taxpayers have saved money, students have
paid a price.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we have a whole generation of students who've gone
through the system with this burden,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Next year's graduates faced funding problems throughout their
school years, but educators say there is hope for future classes.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Essigs, an assistant superintendent for Mesa Public
Schools, points out that the Legislature this year fully funded
inflation, for the first time since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least it's an encouraging note,'' he said. ``The '90s was a
very dismal decade for funding for Arizona schools by anyone's
standards. Hopefully, we've turned a corner.''
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Arizona has a new way of paying for school
construction called Students FIRST. Spurred by a lawsuit, the
school funding program, passed last year by the Legislature,
attempts to bring all school districts up to minimum standards.
</P>
<P>
   The state also has a new way of measuring student achievement.
Today's students are guided in the classroom by academic standards
in a variety of subject areas. Beginning with the Class of 2002,
pupils will have to pass AIMS, Arizona's Instrument to Measure
Standards, in order to graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Hull not only made improving education part of the
platform that got her elected in 1998, but she has remained a vocal
and active proponent since taking office. Most recently, she set
aside extra money to help the very young, kindergartners through
third-graders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the governor is pretty clear, funding still needs to
be a priority for education,'' said Jaime Molera, eduction adviser
to Hull. ``But we need to make sure education is accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   That can be difficult when the school is asked to fill so many
roles. Counselors help kids deal with pregnancy and unstable home
environments. Teachers are on the watch for physical, drug and
alcohol abuse. Principals devise plans in case campus violence
breaks out.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the primary mission should be on making sure schools are
focused on academics,'' Molera said. ``Everything at schools should
be centered around that.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the Legislature brought to life charter schools, which
are publicly funded and privately run and often cater to specialty
groups. One-third of the nation's charter schools are in Arizona,
which has more than 300 of them scattered across the state.
</P>
<P>
   Often, there is a different approach to academics in these
classrooms. On the first day of school at Arizona School for the
Arts in central Phoenix this month, students will sit in the
Orpheum Theater watching their teachers perform for them on stage.
</P>
<P>
   The home-school movement has blossomed as well.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, there were an estimated 10,000 Arizona children who
were being taught at home. Three years later, there are more than
20,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started 10 years ago, people didn't know what we were
doing,'' said Kim McInturff, a Mesa mother who home-schools her
children.
</P>
<P>
   Her family, with two boys and two girls, made the decision when
private school got too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of did it as an experiment,'' McInturff said. ``As
time has gone on, the resources have become incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   All of these choices have affected traditional public schools.
Today, some advertise for students. Others have opened up their own
magnet schools, catering to back-to-basics instruction as well as
other niche markets.
</P>
<P>
   Given these changes, Van Roekel said the next step is to ask how
the kindergartners of 2000 will fare as they make their way to
graduation in 2013.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we have not done the interventions necessary, we need
to ask the same questions,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 2236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
