<SLUG> BC-CAR-AUTO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCARD TAKES `PRANKSTERS' SERIOUSLY 
</HEADLINE>
 RACING NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Deplorable. Reprehensible. Intolerable.
</P>
<P>
   Those were some of the words used to describe the actions of two
NASCAR Winston Cup crew members, Mike Culberson and Ray Labbe, who
were indefinitely suspended by the sanctioning body and
subsequently fired from their jobs for playing a racially
insensitive prank on David Scott, a black crew member on Jeremy
Mayfield's team, during the Jiffy Lube 300 weekend at New Hampshire
International Speedway last month.
</P>
<P>
   Here are three more words:
</P>
<P>
   Stupid. Stupid. Stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Culberson and Labbe, who were motorcoach drivers for Derrike
Cope and Terry Labonte, respectively, went beyond the realm of
boorish behavior July 8 when they knocked on the door of Mayfield's
motorcoach and one greeted Scott wearing a pillowcase over his head
in an attempt to impersonate a Ku Klux Klansman.
</P>
<P>
   Acutely aware of the perception that stock car racing is a
``redneck sport'' _ attractive only to an all-white, all-male,
Confederate flag-waving audience from the South, as was portrayed
in a recent report on HBO's ``Real Sports with Bryant Gumbel'' _
NASCAR has fought long and hard to overcome that image and make its
sport accessible to people of all races and creeds, and both
genders.
</P>
<P>
   But to suggest that the actions of an ignorant few represent the
beliefs of the rest of the hard-working people in the sport is
absurd.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR should be applauded for taking the action that it did,
handing down indefinite suspensions and calling the men's actions
socially intolerable. And while it took almost a month for the
sanctions to be announced, Kevin Triplett, NASCAR's director of
operations, said the governing body was deliberate in ``giving the
matter its due diligence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue wasn't the timing, the issue was doing what was
right,'' Triplett said. ``The decision what to do was not that
hard. There's not a whole lot of gray area in determining that this
isn't proper behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR took the only option available; the drivers' employers
took things a step further by terminating both.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find the episode deplorable and we're happy that NASCAR has
taken the measures that they've taken,'' said NHIS spokesman Fred
Neergaard. ``We applaud their actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte, during a recent stop in Atlanta, told the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution that his brother, Terry, was ``torn up about
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It embarrassed him and put him in a bad situation,'' Bobby
Labonte said. ``It put me in a bad situation, too, because I'm his
brother and people are asking me about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Triplett said NASCAR officials talked with Scott ``and we have
given him our support.'' He added that NASCAR president Bill France
also wrote a letter of apology to Scott and pledged his continuing
support to keep the sport intolerant of racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line,'' said Triplett, ``is that people have to
feel like if they want to make a living in NASCAR, then the only
hurdles they have to overcome are because of the difficulty of the
job and nothing else.''
</P>
<P>
   As it should be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The silly season has already started. In CART, Roger Penske made
a stunning announcement before last week's race in Detroit that he
and Al Unser Jr. were parting ways at the end of the season and
that he had signed Greg Moore and Gil de Ferran to three-year
contracts. And in NASCAR, Winston Cup owner Robert Yates announced
that Kenny Irwin would not be back behind the wheel of the No. 28
Texaco Havoline Ford Taurus next season. In both cases, the drivers
failed to live up to the lofty expectations of owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to emphasize that this change is being made in the
interest of all concerned,'' Yates said. ``As for the remainder of
this season, we are committed, as a team, to make the No. 28 car
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Yates said no decision had been made on a replacement.One
possibility could be Unser.
</P>
<P>
   Unser, it has been speculated, also could wind up with the new
Winston Cup team being put together for next season by CART owner
Cal Welles, who has Tide lined up as his primary sponsor. The
theory is that Welles would give Unser a full-time Winston Cup ride
and, as a bonus to his driver and sponsor, field an entry for the
2000 Indianapolis 500. Unser, 37, has not raced at the fabled
Brickyard since 1994, when he captured his second career Indy 500
triumph. He failed to qualify the following year and then was
forced to stay away because of the feud between CART and the Indy
Racing League.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Indy 500 is the Indy 500,'' said Unser, who attended this
year's race as a spectator, rooting for cousins Robby and Johnny.
``I'm not going to wait for the other drivers just to race at
Indy.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a trying year for Unser, who is winless in 11 races
this season and his last 64 overall with Marlboro Team Penske, for
whom he won the CART PPG Championship in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   He broke his right ankle in a crash on the first turn of the
first lap in the first race of the season at Homestead, Fla., then
struggled to get up to speed in the Penske-built PC27B chassis,
which will be scrapped at the end of the season. Then came news of
Unser's impending divorce from his wife, Shelley, with whom he had
four children.
</P>
<P>
   And now comes his separation after six years with Team Penske.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier this year, Al and I discussed the team's contractual
commitments with our manufacturers,'' Penske said. ``And we
mutually agreed it would be best if he evaluated other
opportunities for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Unser, ever the trooper, said he intended to strive for one last
goal before parting with Team Penske.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we keep trying our best, everything will turn out
for the best,'' Unser said. ``We're not lame ducks, by any means.
I'm going to try like the devil to get Roger his 100th victory.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon will be gunning for his fifth consecutive road
course victory in Sunday's NASCAR Winston Cup race at the 11-turn,
2.45-mile, winding circuit at Watkins Glen, N.Y. ``The track is a
little different since they put concrete down in the corners,''
said Gordon, who won the last road-course event June 27 at Sears
Point Raceway in Sonoma, Calif. ``I really like the concrete _ it's
got grip and I know it's going to be consistent.'' Gordon is sixth
in the points, 507 behind leader Dale Jarrett, who won last week's
Brickyard 400 to extend his lead to 274 over Mark Martin (3,199 to
2,925). ``If Jarrett keeps going this season the way that he has,
nobody's going to catch him,'' said Gordon, who has four victories,
seven poles, and 12 top-5 finishes. ``One race, or even one
position for us, isn't going to determine anything as far as points
are concerned. We just need to keep going out there every week and
work hard, try to win races and see what happens.'' . . . Martin
may have won the battle in last week's IROC XXIII series finale at
Indianapolis, but Dale Earnhardt won the war in outpointing Martin,
75-74, to capture the overall series title (the third of his
career) and earn $225,000 . . . IRL driver Greg Ray, who moved into
second place, 1 point behind Scott Goodyear, after last week's
victory at Dover, Del., left Las Vegas unscathed after wrecking his
two Team Menard cars during a test session Tuesday at Las Vegas
Motor Speedway. ``I'm really disappointed for myself and I feel
really bad for my team,'' Ray said. ``These guys have worked very
hard and they're true professionals. They don't deserve being put
through this.'' . . . FedEx CART driver Christian Fittipaldi
continues to recuperate at his home in Miami from the subdural
hematoma he suffered Aug. 2 in a wall crash during a test session
at Gateway International Raceway in Madison, Ill. Fittipaldi, the
27-year-old nephew of retired driver Emerson Fittipaldi, was
replaced by Roberto Moreno in last week's race in Detroit and will
miss Sunday's race at Mid-Ohio. He is expected to be out at least
eight weeks and hopes to return in time for the race at Houston
Sept. 26. ``I think everything happens for a reason in life,'' said
Fittipaldi. ``If God wanted it to be this way, maybe He is trying
to show me some other things in life and He is preparing me for my
future. I honestly believe it has to be this way, and I am sure
that the day I was testing I was doing everything correct. The team
had prepared for me a good, competitive car, and no one was working
in a bad way, so I believe that there are good things that come
from bad things in life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
