<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUY OR BYE-BYE IN PITTSBURGH 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Team Lemieux could be in the stew.
</P>
<P>
   The future of the Penguins very well could hinge on whether
Beverly Hills billionaire Ron Burkle remains committed to ante up
$20 million this week, enabling Hall of Famer Mario Lemieux to move
ahead and close his purchase of the bankrupt franchise.
</P>
<P>
   If Burkle pulls out, as he appeared to do last week, then
there's big trouble in Steeltown. Harry Manion, representing
current owner Roger Marino, has another billionaire, Mark Cuban, at
the ready. In fact, Cuban may come aboard even if the Burkle-backed
deal closes, allowing Burkle to exit graciously from the picture.
Getting dizzy?
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind, if the deal doesn't get done Wednesday, there is
no money for Penguin payroll. One source familiar with the
negotiations said there really isn't anything left in the till as
of Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Manion said Friday that he figured a deal, even without Burkle
in the mix, could get done in time with Cuban's money alone _ but
that would depend on what kind of time was left after a Burkle
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   It's abundantly clear, however, that Lemieux has been tap
dancing around the fact that he just hasn't had the $50 million.
Working out myriad financial entanglements takes time, and some are
still ongoing. But the money is there or it's not. Even as of now,
no one truly knows.
</P>
<P>
   What a mess for the NHL. A doomsday scenario could find the
league taking over the Penguins for the '99-00 season and then
finding a surgar daddy (hello, Paul Allen?) to buy the franchise
out of bankruptcy and likely move it.
</P>
<P>
   With the '99-00 schedule already set and hotels and air travel
arranged, it's too late to move now. Just imagine the head count
inside the Igloo if the Penguins have to play there as lame ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, there is the financial black hole on Long Island. For
a league that talks courageously _ and justifiably _ about
expanding its footprint, the Penguins and Islanders are two reasons
to not even think about expansion for at least another 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Maple Leafs aren't saying they'll walk away from Yanic
Perreault's arbitration award ($1.05 million), but they are saying
the price is too high and he soon will be an ex-Leaf (is his pay
too low for the Rangers?). Perreault made $750,000 last year. He's
small and soft, but he has some touch and he's only 28 years old.
The bet here: Given his last name and his fairly low compensation,
Colorado takes a stab . . . Mark Witkin, agent for Hal Gill,
reports that there have been no substantive talks with the Bruins
about a new deal for the hulking third-year defenseman. Gill made
$410,000 last season and got the standard 10-percent-added
qualifying offer from Causeway Street. The Bruins made it clear
last summer in their dealings with Kyle McLaren and Anson Carter
that they'll stick to the payroll guidelines of Group 2 free
agency, unless it's a scorer of Jason Allison's stature . . . The
soon-to-be-retired Dominik Hasek will make $7 million this year and
then walk away from up to $16.5 million that he likely would have
pocketed by April 2002 (the Sabres, if they chose, could have
walked away from the $9 million in '01-02). Meanwhile, in Detroit,
29-year-old Nicklas Lidstrom could be politely thumbing his nose at
$21 million. The Wings are prepared to pay the big-shooting blue
liner $7 million or more per season, but he has made it clear the
last couple of years that he misses Sweden and wants to raise his
kids there _ similar to Hasek's longing for the Czech Republic . .
. Not a good week for Penguins superstar Jaromir Jagr (due
$10,359,852 this season). Jags was quoted _ he now says misquoted _
in a Czech tabloid as saying the difference between his native
Czech Republic and Pittsburgh is like ``heaven and hell.'' It was a
call to arms for get-a-lifers, who called area talk shows and
voiced their displeasure. Jagr: ``I would be angry, too, if I read
something like that. I would like to apologize to everybody in
Pittsburgh, except that I don't have anything to apologize for,
since I never said anything.'' . . . Mike Smith, home on the
Vineyard after not being rehired to run the Leafs' front office,
could end up as Minnesota's first GM. The ex-Jets GM is the most
likely candidate, unless, say, Craig Patrick exits Pittsburgh or
former Minnesotan Bobby Smith were to leave Phoenix (highly
unlikely). Smith knows who can play, which gives him an edge over
50-60 percent of the GMs currently working in NHL front offices . .
. The Bruins should find out Sunday night what an arbitrator says
they'll have to pay Dmitri Khristich for next season . . . Far be
it from your faithful correspondent to figure out how TV's dim
bulbs in charge go about picking their talent for hockey coverage,
but there has to be room for Andy Brickley in someone's broadcast
booth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Canucks will visit the Vault only once next season, a noon
matinee Nov. 26, and they won't have the Sedin twins, Henrik and
Daniel, when they arrive. Mike Barnett, agent for the talented
twins, told Canucks GM Brian Burke last week that they'll both play
one more year in Sweden. They could be in Vancouver's preseason
camp, but that's yet to be determined. Shocker? No. And, chances
are, another year in Europe will only make them better pros.
However, the lowly Canucks, still throbbing from the forced
departure of Pavel Bure, truly could have used the boost the Sedins
would have brought to waning fan enthusiasm . . . Don't bet on
Alexei Yashin caving in and showing up for the opening of Senators
camp. He is supposed to make $3.3 million in '99-00, the last year
of his deal, but wants to double that dough. The better bet is a
protracted holdout _ very much like Bure's last year in Vancouver _
that will lead to a whopping midseason deal. Question is: Will the
Rangers give up star-in-the-making Manny Malhotra this time? The
Blueshirts balked at sending Malhotra to the Canucks for Bure. It's
unfathomable that they would pass up that kind of swap again. Isn't
it? . . . Rumblings in Anaheim have the Mighty Ducks being shopped
around, a symptom of Disney stock languishing in the
twentysomethings. (Friday's close on the New York Stock Exchange:
27 3/16, down by about one-third over the last 15 months.) Henry T.
Nicholas 3d, cofounder of Broadcom Corp. in Irvine, Calif., and
reportedly worth some $2.3 billion in Broadcom stock, is believed
to be among those interested in the team . . . Good to hear that
Ben Smith will stick around to coach the US women in the 2002
Olympics in Salt Lake City. Meanwhile, the NHL is expected to make
up its mind next month whether it wants to send its soldiers in for
an Olympus Redux in '02 . . . Score of the week was made by New
Jersey's Brian Rolston, who landed a two-year deal in arbitration
worth a total of $2.7 million, an award that about doubles his pay
of $750,000 last season. The Devils were hoping for about $700,000
less . . . Wrentham's Garth Snow remains standing as the No. 1
netminder in Vancouver, where he'll earn slightly less than $1.5
million in '99-00. Snow to the Vancouver Sun: ``You always hear
about professional athletes who are unhappy and want to play
somewhere else. They must be living in a different world than me.''
. . . The Lightning deal that sent Niklas Sundstrom to San Jose
could affect Belmont Hill defenseman Paul Mara, the Bolts' top pick
(No. 7 overall) in the '97 draft. Mara might have been penciled in
for regular time on the Tampa blue line if the package hadn't
included Andrey Zyuzin and Bill Houlder going to Florida. Now Mara,
unless he really lights it up in training camp, might be looking at
some minor league seasoning . . . The Blues/Kiel Center remain up
for sale. Clearly, it's a buyer's market. Meanwhile, in Ottawa,
Senators owner Rod Bryden wants the Canadian government to come up
with substantial tax breaks for all Canadian club owners by Dec. 1
or, he says, he'll put the Senators up for sale. There would be at
least a couple of American-based bidders, but it's a tricky club to
move out of Ontario because of the Ogden Corp.'s ownership position
in both the team and the building (Corel Centre).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Good move for Ron Low, who resigned as the Oilers coach, taking
over as the Houston Aeros (IHL) coach and GM. He did an admirable
job with the low-budget Oilers and there's a better-than-even
chance that the NHL will come to Houston soon (Calgary and Ottawa
are the Canadian refugees in waiting). Low then could be well
positioned to step back into the NHL . . . You know time's flying
when Jumbo Joe Thornton is about to enter the final year of his
original three-year pact. Ditto for Sergei Samsonov . . . Typical
Las Vegas odds right now have the Bruins 22-1 to win the Cup,
ranking them 10th in the Original 28. The favorites: Red Wings
(3-1), Avalanche (7-2), and defending champion Stars (4-1). Tampa
Bay and Atlanta will go off at about 300-1. The Rangers, with a
payroll of some $60 million, are touted at around 50-1 . . . Proof
positive that America is one heck of a money grab: The Islanders
will pay ex-Bruin Marius Czerkawski $1 million this season as their
No. 1 right wing (check LA listings for one Palffy, Zigmund) . . .
Just back in the St. Louis area after a motorcyle tour/charity fund
raiser, Blues tough guy Tony Twist (1,121 career PIMs) cracked up
his motorcycle in Creve Coeur, Mo., Monday and required surgery
later in the week to fix a cracked pelvis. The St. Louis
Post-Dispatch reported Tuesday that Twist, prior to his accident,
had been told by the Blues that he wouldn't be asked back for the
'99-00 season . . . Ex-Flyer defenseman Behn Wilson, he of 1,480
career penalty minutes, is headed for some real jail time after
pleading guilty Wednesday in Philadelpia federal court to a couple
of financial felonies. Now 40 years old, Wilson admitted filing
false financial statements to a dozen lending institutions in the
early '90s, part of a real estate scam that came crashing down in
bankruptcy. The banks lost some $2.4 million. Wilson could get up
to 27 months in the slammer, but likely will skate for less. He
blew the whistle on others, gaining him some leniency . . .
Something that would really impress me: to see someone like Hasek
or Lidstrom agree to play one last season and then use that year's
pay to establish a health-and-welfare fund to aid some of the
game's greats who played before the big-pay era. Some of the golden
oldies see only meager pensions from their NHL days, and more than
a few could use a lift. If not for them . . .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 2238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990814.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7706 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-NBANOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      08-14 1846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUICK HAND PERFORMS MAGIC TRANSFORMATION 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ John Gabriel has never been a typical general manager.
A few years ago, the Orlando Magic executive cashed in his
collection of quarters and purchased a beautiful set of Pearl
drums. He certainly can't play as well as his idol, jazzman Gene
Krupa, but Gabriel has been known to participate in a few
late-night jam sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play '70s and '80s rock, mostly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He was talking about soft rock, we presume. Because this summer,
Gabriel's message seems to have a shrill, hard-core edge to it. He
ripped up his team quicker than you can say, ``Drumroll, please.''
</P>
<P>
   Horace Grant is in Seattle. Penny Hardaway is in Phoenix. Nick
Anderson is in Sacramento. Isaac Austin is in Washington. Even the
coach, Chuck Daly, decided to leave. The Magic were the No. 3 seed
in the Eastern Conference playoffs last season. They won't be
making the playoffs next season. Everyone knows that. The new Magic
include Harvey Grant, Danny Manning, Tariq Abdul-Wahad, Ben
Wallace, and Corey Maggette, the 6-foot-6-inch forward who will
turn 20 in November.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, John. Is something wrong?
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided that if we didn't think we were going in the
direction of a championship, we were going to change things up,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   They changed so much that no one will be surprised if they have
to struggle to eclipse the win total (18) of their 1989-90
expansion team. But it might be a good idea to get all your Orlando
jokes in now. Next summer, also known as the Summer of Tim
(Duncan), the Magic will have plenty of salary cap room. They also
own 2000 first-round picks from Golden State _ the Warriors' last
payment for acquiring Chris Webber in '93 _ Denver and, if they
want, Phoenix. Their deals also created a $4.5 million trade
exception that they can use for a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be very athletic,'' Gabriel said of the
Millennial Magic. ``In Wahad, (Darrell) Armstrong, and (Bo) Outlaw,
we think we have three of the best defenders in the game. And you
should see Maggette. He has tremendous, tremendous athleticism. For
a young guy, he also has a good feel for the game. Every team has
to have a player that they point to as their future centerpiece,
and he is ours.''
</P>
<P>
   New coach Doc Rivers will have to be creative immediately. Not
including free agents, there are 18 names on the Magic roster. That
list will have to be pared to 12 by November. Of course, things
would be a lot easier if 7-footer Duncan arrived in 2000. Rivers
and the center are close from the time they spent in San Antonio,
where Rivers was a Spurs losing streak away from replacing Gregg
Popovich as head coach last season.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Duncan in Florida is speculation. Reality is this
strange mix of youth, veterans, and, essentially, free agency
bargaining chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Younger kids are more exuberant in their playing. They make a
better appearance and you can teach them the way you want 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Krupa said that when talking about young jazz musicians. But
this year, Gabriel will understand his idol's words in a different
context.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There had been some private talk among the Celtics that Greg
Minor's career could be over. His agent, Dan Fegan, said that is
not the case. ``He's got a long way to go in coming back,'' Fegan
said, ``but there's absolutely no way his career is over.'' If
Minor were out indefinitely, the Celtics would be eligible for some
salary cap relief. Minor suffered a severe hip injury last April in
a game at Miami . . . Another Celtic issue involves the stinging
words agent Tevester Scott directed at Rick Pitino. Scott, the
agent for Ron Mercer, has said repeatedly that the coach was
dishonest in his dealings with Mercer. According to Mercer's camp,
the Celtics caused the entire Mercer-not-reporting-to-Denver
episode. After learning of the trade to the Nuggets, Mercer says he
was told by the Celtics that Denver was going to give him a
six-year contract extension and sign him to the maximum allowed,
$73 million. Mercer relayed that news to some friends. But when he
spoke with the Nuggets, they didn't know what he was talking about;
they said there would be no offer until the end of the year. Scott
also blasted Pitino for agreeing to trade Mercer somewhere other
than Denver. Pitino said Scott is ``an inexperienced agent'' who
might not know the difference between Pitino's voice and that of
general manager Chris Wallace. ``Maybe he doesn't know a West
Virginia accent from a Northeast accent,'' said Pitino, emphasizing
that he has talked with the agent only once and that Wallace
negotiated with him. ``Maybe this is a case of mistaken identity.
Maybe he doesn't know who he's talking to. And if that's the case,
we have a deeper problem than we thought.'' . . . One of the themes
of the post-Aug. 1 signing/trading period has been
``misunderstanding.'' Gabriel said, ``The thing that has
disappointed me is the amount of guys who agree to contracts and
then go somewhere else. I'm not singling anybody out, but if you
can't take someone's word for something, what are you going to do?
How can you do business?'' Gabriel said he heard that the Celtics'
Calbert Cheaney originally agreed to sign with Miami before signing
a three-year, $6.6 million deal with Boston. There was also Dell
Curry agreeing _ twice _ to re-sign with the Bucks before going to
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every year, there are signings that people don't understand. The
Raptors gave Michael Stewart a deal that averages about $4 million
a season, even if he didn't average a hoop and two rebounds last
season. The Hawks gave up two first-rounders for Lorenzen Wright
and agreed to pay him an average of $6 million per season. He
averaged 7 rebounds and 6 points last season. Similar cases? Not
really. The 6-foot-11-inch, 260-pound Wright had discussions with
25 teams, according to his agent, Robert Fayne. The Pacers and
Lakers wanted him badly. Teams liked his youth (23), size, and
two-position versatility. In Atlanta, he can back up center Dikembe
Mutombo and power forward Alan Henderson. Wright is a typical
Clippers story: Everyone except the sad Clips could see his
potential. When he arrived in Atlanta, Wright was approached by a
couple of players who told him, ``Welcome back to the NBA.''
Stewart is different. He had major problems in Toronto. But there
had been speculation in January that Stewart and the Raptors had an
agreement for a sizable deal since he played for a comparatively
modest salary last season . . . If you want to talk sports with
someone who doesn't have much to complain about, find Jerry
Colangelo. His baseball team, the Arizona Diamondbacks, is leading
the National League West. His basketball team, the Phoenix Suns,
could have one of the best backcourts in league history with
Hardaway and Jason Kidd. Hardaway is going to see some of the
easiest shots of his career with the dynamic Kidd feeding him. The
Suns also added Rodney Rogers and rookie Shawn Marion, whom
Colangelo called ``a Scottie Pippen-type of player.'' ``If you look
at Hardaway at his best and Kidd, who is at the peak of his game,
it appears to be a perfect combination,'' Colangelo said. ``It will
be interesting to see how it turns out.'' Colangelo still is not
pleased with the way Antonio McDyess left for Denver (``I have some
strong feelings about what took place; I refer to it as `The Heist'
'') but he likes his team: ``I wish Antonio had stayed in Phoenix.
From what I understand, he has shared with people that he made a
mistake.'' McDyess supposedly was hidden from the Suns by the
Nuggets when it was time to pick his team. He anguished over the
decision before taking less money and going back to Denver. He
might be missing out on a championship season in the desert. But
don't give the title to the Suns yet. The Blazers improved, the
Spurs still have Duncan, the Timberwolves still have Kevin Garnett,
there's a center with a Superman tattoo in Los Angeles, and the
Sonics are desperately retooling. ``You'd have to say the power is
in the West,'' Colangelo said. ``There are a number of outstanding
teams who have helped themselves. Sacramento has done some things,
Utah is Utah, and Houston, if they stay intact with their people,
is dangerous.'' Colangelo paused and said, ``With all the power out
here, you almost have to make moves to keep up with the Joneses.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eric Williams was asked about being traded back to Boston.
``It's like all the old wounds are healed now that I'm back,'' he
said. When Williams was traded two years ago, Pitino said the
forward couldn't play for him . . . The NBA's rule-changes
committee took part in a conference call last Thursday. There were
several complaints about officials' interpretations of impeding
progress and forearm checking during summer play. ``The game needs
changes and you will see them,'' said Colangelo, a member of the
committee. ``What we are talking about right now is fine-tuning
some things.'' One thing everyone should remember, Colangelo said,
is ``coaches, officials and players will adjust to whatever the
rules are.'' . . . The Cavaliers think first-round pick Andre
Miller can take the starting point guard job from Brevin Knight . .
. When Dale Davis said he was not willing to play in Boston, it was
nothing personal. The 6-11 forward is 30 and doesn't want to play
in a Pitino system. He expressed his feelings after hearing rumors
that he was going to the Celtics in a deal involving Antoine Walker
. . . Pitino said he wants the Celtics to be tougher. If that's the
case, he'll be pleased with Eric Washington. The 6-4 guard actually
spent some time at power forward during his last season at Alabama.
Washington also is known as a very good shot-blocker for a guard .
. . One of the best stories of the summer is Washington forward
Randell Jackson. When he was a freshman at Madison Park, he was
about 6-1 and not a very skilled player. Now, at 6-11, Jackson is
being counted on as a valuable member of the Wizards' rotation.
Last month, new coach Gar Heard said he was interested in seeing
four players during the summer league: Jackson, Richard Hamilton,
Jahidi White, and Calvin Booth . . . Yet another unknown player to
watch: Greg Buckner of the Mavericks. The guard's game has been
compared to Mario Elie's . . . Fegan also represents free agent
forward Shandon Anderson, who has drawn interest from several
teams, including the Jazz, Rockets, and Lakers. Utah coach Jerry
Sloan believes the departure of executive Scott Layden to the
Knicks could hurt the Jazz in their attempts to sign Anderson.
Layden did the bulk of the club's negotiating . . . Bizarre story
of the week: Pippen said he wants to be traded to the Lakers so he
can be reunited with Phil Jackson. But that's not the strange part.
This is: Pippen told Rockets vice president Robert Barr to work on
the trade; Barr, in an unrelated move, resigned a couple days
later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
