<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7707 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      08-14 2744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICE HAS SOLID GRASP OF NEW ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. _ Jerry Rice is conceding nothing but he is
accepting a few more things than he used to, including the passage
of time and the passing of footballs in the direction of 49ers
other than himself at times when they used to come to him.
</P>
<P>
   But accepting is not conceding, something Rice has never done to
a defense, to a competitor, or even to his own body. It is
something he has no intention of doing now, at the dawn of his 15th
NFL season, despite his insistence last week that he has a new
attitude toward his role in the 49ers' legendary offense after
being accused last year of putting his desires above his team's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had very high expectations last year and I felt, under the
situation (returning from a serious knee injury), I had a pretty
good year but I learned I've got to be very, very patient now,''
Rice explained. ``Other guys have to factor into the offense now.
That was a tough adjustment for me last year. I thought I could
jump right in and be fine with it, but it took time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've matured a lot. Now I know exactly what to do and how to
handle this. I'm not taking a lesser role but I know other guys are
going to factor in (more). Other guys are going to get more
opportunities and it's up to them to make plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``The approach I used to take was that I've got to prove myself
every year by making plays. This year I've got to realize other
guys have got to make plays, too. Now I have to wait for my
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Waiting is something Rice has never been terribly proficient at.
He is a workout freak, a neatness nut, and a receiver without peer
who believes he is always open and usually has a point. He already
holds 12 regular-season NFL records and six postseason ones, yet
had shown little sign of slowing down until his knee injury two
years ago. Although he made two remarkable recoveries from that
injury, late last season his production slowed somewhat from his
own absurdly high standards, and the inevitable whispering about
his athletic mortality began.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rice again led the 49ers in receptions with 82, he
seemed to do less with them and ended up making five or fewer
catches in each of the team's final eight games (including
playoffs), topping 100 yards only once during that span. This
coincided with the rise to prominence of both Terrell Owens (14
touchdowns, 67 catches, and a 1,097-yard Pro Bowl season) and J.J.
Stokes, two in Rice's long line of apprentices. Initially, Rice did
not appear to take to the change in his situation, and he voiced
his complaints publicly.
</P>
<P>
   That led to predictably heavy criticism in some corners of the
Bay Area media and an attitude adjustment this summer that is still
being fine-tuned.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be games now where I'm not the focus,''
Rice conceded. ``That's an adjustment for me. A major adjustment.
But I'm going to enjoy this year. I'm not going to let anything
bother me anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, many things did. His balky knee preyed on his mind,
as did the 49ers' apparent decision to begin subtly changing the
focus of their offense. This in no way meant Rice would be
unproductive, but with age, infirmity, and the emergence of
talented new faces, some things had to change.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, that has been Rice. Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   He grudgingly agreed to take occasional days off from practice
to keep his legs rested and his knee free of fluid. He has also
listened to coach Steve Mariucci's explanation for why he wants to
limit Rice's appearances in the meaningless preseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different but I know it's for the best,'' Rice said.
``It's just being smart as I get older. I have to be more careful
now, even though I feel that I'm in great shape.''
</P>
<P>
   As he stood chatting, clad neck to toes in a black Spandex
bodysuit that looked better on him than it would on a mannequin, no
one would dispute his fitness for football. The greatest receiver
ever to play the game is looking fine, feeling fine, and doing just
fine as his 37th birthday approaches.
</P>
<P>
   But for all his newfound sense of contentment, not too far under
that Spandex burn the same fires that have fueled his
competitiveness for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a competitor,'' Rice said. ``I still want the ball, But
it's up to the coaches now to say, `Let's get the ball to Jerry.'
I'm not going to demand it. I've never demanded it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have accused me of being selfish when I've said I felt
I could make things happen if I got the ball more but they don't
understand. That's being a competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Content or not with his new station in life, Rice has not
changed that part of his game. He remains a competitor, which means
the 49ers will very likely remain competitive for another year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The mystery continues as to why Patriots linebacker Ted Johnson
has twice torn biceps muscles while making tackles, a most unusual
injury. One belief among some in the NFL is that players who use
too much of the supplement Creatine to help build strength and
muscle mass are at greater risk for such an injury because their
muscles can lose water and become more brittle. Retired Jaguars
linebacker Jeff Lageman believes that's why he sustained a torn
biceps last season, an injury that convinced him to retire.
Lageman, in fact, warned Johnson about Creatine a year ago when
they were discussing the unusual injury each had suffered. Johnson
told Lageman he did not use Creatine. Johnson, who has had four
operations on his shoulders and arms in 18 months, realizes he may
be at a career crossroads. Perhaps because of that, he called the
MET-RX people in Southern California recently to ask about coming
out to rehabilitate himself on a program of diet and exercise
similar to the one MET-RX and fitness guru Marv Marinovich created
for New York Giants All-Pro cornerback Jason Sehorn after his
season-ending knee injury a year ago. The results with Sehorn are
taking on legendary status around the league . . . Creatine, by the
way, is not a banned substance like steroids. It is a legal
supplement popular with a lot of young athletes searching for more
strength and power as quickly as possible . . . After a season of
struggling to find an offense, the San Diego Chargers have decided
to look at their No. 1-rated defense for an answer. New coach Mike
Riley has decided to use All-Pro linebacker Junior Seau as an
H-back for 6-10 plays a game this season. The position is a more
glorified form of tight end, and the 6-foot-3-inch, 255-pound Seau
is happy to play it. The same is not true of his defensive coaches.
``They don't like it,'' Riley said. ``But even they can see what he
brings to any group he's playing with. If we put him in there
permanently, he could be an All-Pro at that position.'' Seau brings
unusual speed for a man his size and Riley hopes to use that to
create mismatches against opposing linebackers. This experiment is
far different from the more common switch of a defensive back like
Deion Sanders to wide receiver. ``This is not like putting in some
defensive back to catch a few passes,'' Riley said. ``He's going to
be in the trenches.'' That's what the defensive coaches are worried
about . . . With Reggie White retired, veteran Packer safety LeRoy
Butler has tried to take over the role of team leader. The way he
describes the job is a sign of the times. ``It's my job to make
sure none of these guys wakes up with seven hookers and a pound of
marijuana,'' Butler said. Whatever happened to making sure they
were lined up in the right spot on defense?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the reviews, the NFL won't be replacing the
Australian version of football in Sydney any time soon. The
Broncos' 20-17 victory over the San Diego Chargers there last
weekend inspired the Daily Telegraph to describe the game this way:
``They stop for regular television commercial breaks. They stop to
run on and off the field. They stop for up to a half dozen
timeouts. They stop where there is a kick to be taken. They stop
after a pass is caught. They stop to hear umpires explain
penalties. And they stop to measure distances. It's amazing that a
country like America, whose economy and social structure are based
upon being quicker and slicker, can enthuse about taking three
hours to play one hour of football.'' Considering that the NFL
players hated the long flight and the Australian fans hated the
game, one guesses the NFL won't be rushing back Down Under . . .
Glad There Are No Hard Feelings Dept.: Although Cleveland Browns
owner Al Lerner and club president Carmen Policy were in Canton,
Ohio, last weekend, no one from the Browns organization attended
the Hall of Fame induction of former Cleveland tight end Ozzie
Newsome. That's because Newsome now runs the personnel department
for Art Modell's Baltimore Ravens, the team that used to be the
Browns . . . Newly inducted Hall of Fame running back Eric
Dickerson needs a geography lesson. Dickerson, who might have set
the all-time rushing record if he'd stayed with the Rams instead of
forcing a defection to Indianapolis, of all places, said, ``I never
wanted to leave Los Angeles.'' Maybe that's because he never played
in Los Angeles. Dickerson played all his Rams days in Anaheim, down
in Orange County, which is definitely not Los Angeles . . .
Tennessee Titans owner Bud Adams recently demonstrated that blood
may be thicker than water but it's not thicker than winning. When
he hired NFL Executive of the Year Jeff Diamond and named him team
president and chief operating officer, it not only reduced the
power of general manager Floyd Reese but put the wood to Adams's
son-in-law, executive vice president Tommy Smith. Both now report
to Diamond, and Diamond reports only to the owner. Diamond is the
second person to hold the title of club president, a position Adams
had maintained. Smith didn't attend the news conference that
announced Diamond's arrival in Nashville. Reese, meanwhile, saw his
power eroded in a subtle way. His contract, which has three years
to run, says he has sole control of all personnel decisions over
everyone but the club president. That used to be Adams. Now it's
Diamond, who built the powerful Vikings team that went 15-1 a year
ago. On the upside for Reese, he is a longtime friend of Diamond;
the two worked together for seven years in Minnesota during Reese's
coaching days . . . 49ers defensive tackle Bryant Young returned to
the field for the first time since breaking two bones in his lower
leg last season and is saying that he'll be ready for the season
opener, even though Mariucci has told him he will not be allowed to
play in an exhibition game. Young did no hitting last week but said
after his first workout, ``I guess it was good for me just to be
out there with them. Wearing a jersey means a lot.'' When Mariucci
saw Young lying on his back Tuesday during an onside kick drill, he
went over and told him, ``Wow, I just had a flashback. This is a
little different than the last time I saw you lying on your back.''
That was the night last November when Young suffered a terrible
injury that some said would take him a year to recover from . . .
Young and Oakland Raiders defensive tackle Darrell Russell were
both weighed in an odd fashion last week. As part of a charitable
promotion, the Campbell Soup Co. put them on a special scale that
looked like a spoon. Each, coincidentally, weighed the equivalent
of 262 soup cans, which translates into 290 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With each passing week, it becomes clearer that the city of Los
Angeles doesn't have a clue what it's doing, which is why it won't
get the league's 32d franchise in 31 days unless there's a radical
change in approach, which is unlikely. A majority of the City
Council said Tuesday that it would not support the use of any
public funds to bring pro football back to the Coliseum, although
an official vote isn't to be taken until this week. Councilwoman
Laura Chick showed the level of delusion on the Left Coast when she
said, ``We have everything it takes to bring a team back. We have
the fans, the marketplace, the facilities, and the private sector
leadership willing to put together a financial package. What we
don't have and should not have is use of our precious and short
taxpayer dollars for this project.'' The fact is they don't have
the fans, the facilities, or the financing to get the Coliseum
retooled and a team paid for. Other than that, she was right on the
money. Now that I think about it, no she wasn't. She was wrong
about the money, too . . . As mentioned here a week ago, the 49ers
have only one cornerback taller than 5-7. This amused the brother
of defensive coordinator Jim Mora Jr. so much that he called asking
for one of Mark McMillian's uniforms for his 8-year-old ``before he
outgrows it.'' The situation may not be so funny a month from now .
. . Is it just my imagination or does new Redskins owner Daniel
Snyder think he's George Steinbrenner? In a letter sent before he
bought the team for $800 million, Snyder promised employees that
everyone's job was safe. Then he came in and wiped out 25 people,
including the entire PR staff and general manager Charley Casserly,
who did a fantastic job in difficult circumstances last spring,
making trades to protect the team's long-term future. Snyder also
told other owners and the media that he would not fire Casserly or
head coach Norv Turner because ``football will be a new experience
for me and I'm going to need experienced football personnel to run
the team.'' Apparently he didn't need many of the ones he said he'd
keep . . . Snyder, by the way, is rumored to be the next owner
ready to sell stadium naming rights for millions. Although the
Redskins publicly say they have no deal to rename Jack Kent Cooke
Stadium, insiders expect Federal Express or another bidder to have
its name on the stadium wall by the Sept. 12 season opener. Federal
Express tried to make a similar deal with the Ravens but pulled out
when the rights were sold to PSINet for $100 million. This brings
back to mind the perfect company for the Patriots to contact about
naming rights for the new stadium that will be built in Foxborough.
Owner Robert Kraft could sell the rights to Kraft Foods at a
discount, thereby giving two people the rights with one name . . .
Eddie DeBartolo decided to abandon not only the 49ers but also San
Francisco. DeBartolo has moved himself and his corporation to
Tampa, where he is building a house and relocating many of his
business ventures from the family compound in Youngstown, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The team may not be any better, but at least one thing has
improved in Philadelphia. Hall of Fame center/linebacker Chuck
Bednarik visited training camp for the first time in 14 years,
ending a longtime feud with the team. Bednarik had felt unwelcome
around the Eagles since Dick Vermeil retired in 1982, but new coach
Andy Reid made a point of calling him and asking him to stop by.
Reid claims Bednarik was one of his favorite players. Bednarik, who
played 14 years for the Eagles, lives only 10 minutes from the
Lehigh campus where the Eagles train . . . One reason the Jets
chose to sign free agent safety Steve Atwater after Denver let him
go was the impression he made on assistant coach Eric Mangini
during workouts at the Pro Bowl in February. Instead of hitting the
golf course when he arrived in Honolulu, Atwater sought out Mangini
and sat down with him to study the playbook for the meaningless
game. This impressed Mangini and convinced Bill Parcells that the
eight-time Pro Bowler still wanted to play with enthusiasm . . .
NFL Properties, the league's off-field marketing company, recently
signed a contract with Ed Anzalone, known to Jets fans as Fireman
Eddie. T-shirts, dolls, and fireman hats will be marketed, with
Anzalone getting a piece of the action. It's the first
merchandising deal between NFL Properties and a nonplayer, and one
more reason to hate the Jets . . . The Hammer is back in the NFL.
Well, not the real Hammer _ ex-Kansas City cornerback Fred
Williamson _ but the onetime rap star and failed player agent,
Hammer. He has joined KGO radio in San Francisco as part of its
pregame shows before 49er games. Hammer worked as a batboy for the
Oakland A's under the name Stanley Burrell before he became a rap
superstar.
</P>
</TEXT>
