<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICA'S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYYC FEELS WIND AT ITS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ With kids racing little sailboats in the
distance and the ocean liner Queen Elizabeth II sliding
majestically into the harbor for the start of the Jazz Festival,
the meaning of Friday's sendoff of the New York Yacht Club's
America's Cup team was excruciatingly clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the greatest harbor in the world,'' declared Newport's
mayor, David Gordon, at a press conference on the lawn of Harbour
Court, summer clubhouse of the New York Yacht Club. ``We offer our
arms and hearts to put on America's Cup 2003.''
</P>
<P>
   The Young America sailing team stood in front of the unveiled
graphics on a 26-foot test model of the new IACC yachts, then
departed for New Zealand on what may be the most important of the
26 America's Cup campaigns waged by the NYYC since 1851.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, the last time the New Yorkers tried to win the Cup in
Fremantle, they had a flawed campaign led by a club still angry and
bewildered by its loss to Australia and her tricks in the summer of
'83.
</P>
<P>
   But this time around, the first chance in 13 years to win the
Cup back outright, the New Yorkers seem to have it all: an expert
development team led by veteran John Marshall (engineer of Dennis
Conner's 1996 Stars &AMP; Stripes Cup win), strong funding, two new
boats built by a proven Cup winner (Eric Goetz Custom Sailboats in
Bristol, R.I.), and a deep team of the best sailors and technicians
in the world. So the question arises, ``If not now, when?''
</P>
<P>
   And though questions linger about whether the NYYC has been
soured by its Cup experiences in the '80s, commodore George Isdale
gave a very different picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our members are tremendously behind this campaign,'' he said.
``To date, 30 percent of the membership have contributed millions
and millions of dollars to the effort, and we hope to get as high
as 50 percent. We have put aside the past and are committed to an
all-out effort to make this happen. We want the Cup, and we intend
to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   All morning, winds billowed the red, white, and blue spinnakers
used to veil the tank team model. Then team members drew them aside
to reveal a sleek black International America's Cup Class yacht,
with red and gray shark graphics on the side.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boats this time will be slender compared to '95,''
explained Marshall, president of Young America. ``They will carry a
very high ballast-to-boat weight ratio, and will be lively in light
wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Though customized for different wind and sea ranges, the two
Bruce Farr-designed boats are more similar than different, and both
will be used in the early round-robins of the Louis Vuitton Cup, a
preliminary to the America's Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our two boats are as different as two brothers in a family are
different,'' said Marshall. ``They belong together, but they have
different personalities in their designs. Which one will prove more
versatile in race conditions in Auckland, the sailors will have to
tell us.''
</P>
<P>
   One stunning achievement of the technology team is that Young
America's hulls have been honed to such a gleaming perfection that
they require neither fairing with putty nor painting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are black,'' said Marshall, ``because carbon fiber is
black. They're not painted at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, reminded marine historian Michael O'Connor, New
Zealand's 1995 winning Cup juggernaut used boats nicknamed Black
Magic, so perhaps New York's black color constitutes a
not-so-subtle ``shot across the bow.''
</P>
<P>
   Like all modern Cup racers, the Young America is 75 feet long
with a 12-foot appendage of steel leading to a 20-ton bulb of lead
ballast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best steel in the world,'' said Marshall of the fin.
</P>
<P>
   The formula for so many structures on the boat seeks to combine
``strength, lightness, smallness.''
</P>
<P>
   The first Young America, already on the New Zealand docks, will
be assembled for shakedown sails as the team arrives over the next
couple of weeks, along with families and support personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the first round-robin, Young America will compete
with three other US syndicates, plus five from other countries, for
the right to sail against New Zealand in the Cup Match beginning
Feb. 18, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Other US syndicates are Conner, San Diego; Aloha, Hawaii, John
Kolius; America True, San Francisco, Dawn Riley; and AmericaOne,
Paul Cayard, also San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long way to go,'' said Young America skipper Ed Baird,
who was part of the research and development process that created
the boats over the last two years. ``But we have done 200 days of
two-boat testing and we haven't lost a single day of sailing. It's
kind of amazing how far we've come to this point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
