<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN RETREATS TO VACATION CABIN AS OPPONENTS BATTLE IN IOWA
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John McCain traded the hullaba loo of the Iowa straw poll for
the peace and quiet of Arizona's Lake Powell and a cabin in
Cottonwood, his aides said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the decision of an uncon ventional candidate with an
uncon ventional campaign strategy, which, at least so far, places
far less emphasis on Iowa than do his GOP rivals.
</P>
<P>
   But skipping the straw poll was a calculated gamble.
</P>
<P>
   McCain believes his reformist message may be better received by
voters in other early-primary states such as New Hampshire, South
Carolina and California. He would be at a disadvantage in Iowa
because he opposes subsidies for ethanol, a fuel blend made with
corn that Iowans consider important to their economy.
</P>
<P>
   But shunning the limelight could backfire, especially if the
straw poll only adds more momentum to George W. Bush's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa requires candidates to build strong organizations capable
of turn ing out supporters to caucus meet ings on a winter's night
early in 2000. McCain, whose campaign doesn't want to offend Iowa
voters, says he hasn't ruled out participat ing in the caucuses.
But he doesn't have much of a team in Iowa because he has been
focusing on other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the bounce that a Republican gets out of both New
Hampshire and South Carolina will be even more important than it
has been in years past because of the brevity of the primary
campaign season,'' McCain said at a recent luncheon of Western
reporters. ``I believe the fastest-growing registra tion of voters
in California is independents.''
</P>
<P>
   Independents are a key voting group for McCain, who has bucked
the GOP on major issues and doesn't mind being called a ``mav
erick.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has criticized the Iowa straw poll as a ``spending
frenzy'' for candidates to buy votes. His boycotting the poll is
designed to dovetail with his broad campaign theme of reforming the
campaign system to reduce the influence of big money.
</P>
<P>
   While other candidates cam paigned in Iowa last week, McCain
geared up for a 12-day swing through California, beginning Mon day
with a Santa Monica speech. McCain's emphasis on California is
partly due to a change in the primary rules since the last presi
dential election.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in 1996, California Demo crats and independents will be
able to participate in the popular vote in the state's 2000 GOP
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Their inclusion, McCain strate gists believe, opens a door for
the Arizonan.
</P>
<P>
   ``California voters have a long tradition of fighting back
against the establishment,'' said Dan Schnur, who served as a top
aide to former Gov. Pete Wilson in Sacramento, and is now working
for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the progressives at the turn of the century through the
tax cuts in Proposition 13 to the present day, you see an awful lot
of voter activism in the state. That's a market in which an
outsider candidate with a reform message can do very well.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain and California may seem an odd fit to some observers. The
neighboring states have quarreled about everything from allocations
of Colorado River water to whether too many Arizona tourists
descend on San Diego in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   McCain recently began lunch with many California reporters by
joking, ``Any compliments that I pay the state of California, I'd
like to retract.''
</P>
<P>
   But he went on to credit Califor nia for initiatives on
campaign-fi nance reform and other issues. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
