<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS MUST LEARN FROM MISTAKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Tweaking. That's what Bobby Grier and Pete
Carroll must do before the Patriots' exhibition season gets too
close to the real thing Sept. 12 against the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Vice president of player personnel Grier must tinker with the
roster; Carroll must fine-tune his coaching style, which has gone
from excitable to intense in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's 20-14 loss to the Washington Redskins wasn't
reason for anyone to call 911. It was just the first exhibition
game.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, though, some of the subplots were all too
familiar. The Patriots played shorthanded, with Willie McGinest
held out for precautionary reasons, which was a good thing. But Ted
Johnson was in street clothes and a cast on the sidelines, at one
point talking to Drew Bledsoe, who had an ice pack on his twisted
right ankle, which was a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   Grier said all last week that he was seeking a defensive lineman
and a linebacker, believing the team was thin in both areas. His
instincts proved correct Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins ran up the middle with some authority and neither
rookie linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer, newly appointed starter Tedy
Bruschi, nor defensive lineman Brandon Mitchell, who was playing
with a cast on his broken right hand, did much to stop them. Safety
Chris Carter might have made a whopper of a hit in the second
quarter but otherwise did nothing to alleviate fears that the
Patriots might have let Willie Clay go too soon.
</P>
<P>
   At this stage, it's a little too late for a major reworking of
the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive line is the hardest spot to fill. The Patriots may be
able to bring in a veteran, but the likelihood of finding another
Henry Thomas appears slim.
</P>
<P>
   The team spoke internally about bringing in Pepper Johnson last
week, but it was decided that Johnson was too old and couldn't
provide any more than the young linebackers on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that decision needs to be reevaluated. Also out there is
veteran Seth Joyner, who is not a middle linebacker but could add
experience and direction.
</P>
<P>
   A player who auditioned last week, Steve Morrison, is a veteran
who played with Indianapolis, and he could add some expertise
regarding divisional opponents. Perhaps the Patriots need to
consider more how they think and what they know instead of how fast
they run and what the stopwatch says.
</P>
<P>
   If too much is being expected too soon of young players, the
Patriots created that situation, cutting veterans to get younger
out of either necessity or choice.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer didn't look like the answer to replacing Johnson, at
least not yet. He has too much to learn before we see the
professional version of one of the most ferocious players in
college football history. And it still appears the Patriots miss
Todd Collins.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots may have waited too long to shore up their depth.
One thing former Patriots coach Bill Parcells is known for, for
better or worse, is that when he recognizes a need, it doesn't stay
a need for very long. If it means giving up draft picks or signing
a player for more than he's worth, the Jets coach gets it done in a
hurry. That's why he signed Scott Zolak. He knew he had to have a
backup and he probably could have waited to see if a better one
became available, but he didn't want to let the situation fester.
</P>
<P>
   As for Carroll, he's already being bashed again as a coach and a
leader. He will get such treatment as long as he produces a team
inferior to the ones of the previous regime.
</P>
<P>
   It may sound curious, but Carroll's first two weeks of training
camp may have been too hard. The players weren't used to two-a-days
for so many consecutive days. By Thursday there was a dropoff in
intensity. Many veterans, who normally were able to take it easier
so early in camp, were showing signs of fatigue, and Carroll even
lashed out at them a bit because of the dropoff.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe now he needs to back off a bit, especially with his
veterans.
</P>
<P>
   But there certainly were some positive things Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Faulk may have proven that the Patriots don't need to
bring in an older back with bad knees after all (the Terry Allen
talks have been the longest in history for what would be an
insignificant move). Bledsoe was sharp before his interception.
Chris Floyd showed he can play.
</P>
<P>
   Tebucky Jones was very physical, although he really does look
more like a safety than a cornerback. Michael Bishop proved he
should be used somewhere on the field this season. The receivers
were on their game.
</P>
<P>
   First-round pick Damien Woody just needs more reps and
experience at center. Despite Carroll's disappointment with the
kicking game (Lee Johnson punted for a 45.6-yard average, Adam
Vinatieri missed a 29-yard field goal), Vinatieri and Johnson
executed an onside kick successfully. And the third team did a nice
job in bringing up the spirits of the crowd and the rest of the
team in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``You shouldn't be happy with this,'' said cornerback Ty Law.
``We didn't perform well as a team. It's more like an intense
practice right now. We made some mistakes and we can correct
them.''
</P>
<P>
   True, the first game wasn't so good, but it was nothing that a
good tweak or two can't fix. That will be happening all this week
in Smithfield, R.I., as camp continues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
