<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON SUSPENDED BY UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA has suspended starting cornerback Marques
Anderson from school for the fall quarter for his participation in
the disabled-parking scandal and prior incidents with the dean of
students office, according to a statement issued by his family.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant dean of students Kenneth Kelly informed Anderson of
the decision Friday. Anderson, a junior from Long Beach, will
redshirt this season and return to school (and the team) for the
winter quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Anderson family is devastated and saddened by the behavior
leading to this suspension,'' the statement said. ``We regret what
has happened but must accept it as one of life's harsh lessons.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing state and federal privacy laws, UCLA declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 current players involved in the parking scandal are
required to meet with the dean's office. A source said no one else
is expected to be suspended; Anderson's prior, undisclosed
incidents were his undoing.
</P>
<P>
   However, sources said the dean's office is adding 50 hours of
community service to the 200 court-ordered hours given to the
players at their July 28 arraignment. The players also were fined
$1,500, suspended for two games and required to participate in
educational programs to raise awareness of the rights of the
disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was one of UCLA's most experienced cornerbacks and
usually saved his best performances for USC. He contained Trojans
receiver R. Jay Soward in 1997 and forced two USC fumbles last
year.
</P>
<P>
   __ Corner concerns: Anderson's absence leaves the Bruins a man
short in the secondary once senior Ryan Roques returns from his
two-game parking scandal suspension. They have two options: put
Roques at safety and find a cornerback, or put Roques at cornerback
and find a safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty talented and we'd like to play him at safety,''
Toledo said. ``That way, he can roam the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Safety seems the best bet for Roques. Although inexperienced,
cornerbacks Lovell Houston, Joe Hunter, Julius Williams and Ricky
Manning Jr. are talented _ probably more talented than the players
competing for the safety vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to get by for the first couple games and see how
we do,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Recruiting update: The Bruins landed their seventh recruit
Saturday when Chris Kluwe, a punter from Los Alamitos High School,
gave Toledo an oral commitment.
</P>
<P>
   __ Movin' up: Sophomore DeShaun Foster is no longer the Pac-10's
most talented third-string tailback. Because of Keith Brown's
parking-scandal suspension, Foster has ascended to second string
behind starter Jermaine Lewis. And he might not be there for long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep teasing (Foster) how I want to keep him third string so
he won't (enter the NFL) as a junior,'' Toledo quipped. ``But he'll
probably be the starting tailback. He's really talented.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Movin' up II: Another underclassmen set to challenge the
veterans is rookie tight end Mike Seidman from Westlake Village.
After four workouts, Toledo pronounced Seidman ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the one (true freshman) on offense who will definitely
play,'' Toledo said. ``He's everything we thought he'd be.
(Tight-ends coach) Gary Bernardi is very impressed. He's strong. He
runs well. He catches well. We're very excited.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 2304EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
