<P>
   HATE-INTERNET (Los Angeles) _ Eric Owens appears to be no one
special, just another slight, white, tattooed, downtown denizen
without a full-time job. What separates Owens from the crowd, to
hear him and hate experts tell it, is that he is the founder and
ruler of the Aryan International Movement, the most active of the
Los Angeles area's fragmented white supremacist organizations. By
Greg Gittrich and Beth Barrett. (Has already MOVED in the ``a''
national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   HEALING-SHOOTINGS (Los Angeles) _ In the aftermath of last
week's racist shootings, Jewish religious leaders in the San
Fernando Valley are urging congregations to fight back - by praying
for peace, reaching out to others and tempering emotions. By
Dominic Berbeo and David. R. Baker. (Has already MOVED in the ``a''
national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-SUMMER (Los Angeles) _ Hollywood studios, wielding a
finely tuned hype-and-buzz machine, have confounded the skeptics
this summer with an astounding string of successes at the nation's
box office. Hollywood will easily smash last summer's Memorial
Day-Labor Day record of $2.58 billion by at least 20 percent, or
better than $500 million. By Dave McNary. (Will move in the ``a''
national and ``n'' California news files.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IRON-GIANT (Los Angeles) _ What in the world happened to the
``Iron Giant''? Despite universally positive reviews of the Warner
Bros. animated movie, the ``Iron Giant'' opened with a massive thud
last weekend. It finished with $5.7 million at 2,171 theaters _
barely one-fifth of the business generated by Bruce Willis' ``Sixth
Sense.'' That's a flat-out disaster for a project that racked up a
tab estimated at $50 million and an embarrassment for the studio
considering ``Iron Giant'' debut during a supercharged summer in
which grosses have risen an astounding 20 percent over last year's
record-setting pace. By Dave McNary. (Has already MOVED in the
``e'' entertainment and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
