<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7720 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-IOWA-STRAW17-COX     08-14 1416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-STRAW17-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Bush takes one-third of Iowa vote
</P>
<P>
   By Ken Herman and Scott S. Greenberger
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AMES, Iowa _ In a battle waged more with money and buses than
message and policy, Gov. George W. Bush on Saturday won the biggest
preseason event of the 2000 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's victory in the Iowa GOP straw poll fell short of the
margins he has shown in most major nationwide polls, a result that
left Saturday's win open to spin and speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Bush finished first with 31 percent of the nearly 24,000 straw
votes cast. Forbes, solidifying his role as the leading alternative
to frontrunner Bush, ran a solid second with 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more than accomplished what we set out to do,'' Bush
said after the results were announced. ``The victory today in Iowa
put me on the road to earning the nomination of the Republican
party.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Forbes camp also left pleased with the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``A funny thing happened on the way to the coronation,'' said
Forbes, ``the people voted.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole was third with 14 percent. The worst news for the
night came for former Vice President Dan Quayle, who ran eighth
with less than 4 percent, and former Tennessee Gov. Lamar
Alexander, who was sixth with 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John McCain, who called the event a ``sham,'' did
not participate, but still received about half a percent of the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   The straw poll, which plays no official role in the nomination
process, attracted a full-house crowd at Iowa State University's
campus coliseum. It cost $25 to vote, but the candidates bought the
tickets and handed them out to supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was on the rhetorical dart board for opponents struggling
to compete with his money-raising machine and high poll numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes was generous in his criticism of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends, the power of these Washington elites won't be
tamed, bent or broken by a candidate who relies on pollsters and
tutors to tell him what he thinks,'' Forbes said of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   He also tried to forward the image of Bush as a candidate
without positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a candidate won't tell you where he stands that means he
either doesn't know where he stands or he doesn't want you to know
where he stands, and either one is not good for the American
people,'' said Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who offered up a truncated version of his standard stump
speech, had only kind words for his opponents, referring to them as
``good and decent people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned you cannot lead by dividing people. I reject the
ugly politics of division,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle, who served with Bush's dad,
joined Forbes and others who took direct aim at the front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can ill-afford to have another president who needs
on-the-job training when it comes to foreign policy and
international experience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Quayle took aim at Bush's big money advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Washington establishment, they want to control this
election. They want to tell you who to vote for. They say that
money will determine who our nominee is going to be,'' said Quayle.
``I say let's send them a message.''
</P>
<P>
   And then Quayle got personal, targeting Bush's self-professed
young and irresponsible years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say it doesn't really matter what you did before you were
40 years old. I'm proud of what I did before I was 40,'' said
Quayle, who had served two terms in the U.S. House and two in the
U.S. Senate before age 40.
</P>
<P>
   Social conservative Gary Bauer urged voters to ignore money.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a lot of talk about how much money one guy has
raised and another has inherited,'' he said of Bush and Forbes.
``But campaigns are supposed to be about the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander summed it up simply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the nomination can't be bought and shouldn't be
inherited. It should be earned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several candidates made bold promises about ending legal
abortion and appointing judges who share that goal _ a vow Bush has
declined to take.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have been told by politicians, including some in our
party, that this issue will take 50 years to deal with, 40 years to
deal with. No it won't,'' Bauer said, noting that the next
president could have two Supreme Court vacancies to fill.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who usually does not mention abortion in his stump speech,
made two brief abortion references, saying ``a generous society
protects the vulnerable, the aged, the handicapped, the unborn''
and then touted the Texas Legislature's approval of a law mandating
notification of parents prior to abortions performed on minors.
</P>
<P>
   The only politician who took more flak than Bush was President
Bill Clinton. Pat Buchanan got the day's most boisterous response
when he announced the first thing he would do as president would be
turn to Clinton and say, ``Sir, you have the right to remain
silent.''
</P>
<P>
   Though more than half the straw pollees did not vote for Bush
(and Sen. John McCain did not participate), the results met his
definition for victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a first-place finish is a win,'' he said late Friday
at a rally in Indianola, Iowa. ``That may not be the conventional
definition of a victory, I readily concede.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush knew that anything short of an overwhelming win could
be played as something of a loss for a candidate who is way ahead
of the pack in early polls and fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth of the matter is it's up to you all to determine who
wins or loses,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   An Iowa Project poll completed last week and carrying a margin
of error of 5.7 percentage points, showed Bush with a 37-15 lead
over Forbes among Iowans who said they are likely to attend next
February's caucuses. No other candidate was in double figures.
</P>
<P>
   Though some questioned the validity of the event _ essentially a
fund-raiser in which votes cost $25 apiece, all paid for by the
candidates _ all of the candidates said it was, at least, a
credible test of ability to move and motivate supporters. In early
February, contenders who survive that long will be back here trying
to convince supporters to brave wintry weather to attend the
caucuses that kick off the for-real part of the presidential
selection process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way of seeing where you are strong and where you need
to make improvements,'' Forbes said while campaigning here last
week. ``I see it as a critical milestone, a benchmark on the way to
the caucuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Forbes waged high-dollar efforts here, with Forbes
spending about $2 million and Bush spending about $750,000. Forbes
ran television and radio ads, in addition to mobilizing a 90-bus
platoon to bring supporters to Ames. His campaign said it bought
more than 7,000 tickets to allow Iowans to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was in Iowa only one day last week. But his events drew the
biggest crowds and his campaign said it had purchased 11,000 entry
tickets. He ran no media ads, but depended on a sold organization
and more than 100 buses to move supporters to Ames.
</P>
<P>
   But a quick check on the straw poll grounds found that some
attendees were thinking convenience, not candidate, when they
picked a bus to ride to Ames.
</P>
<P>
   Retired state employee Richard Brackett from Rock Creek rode an
Elizabeth Dole bus and was standing in a Forbes barbecue line when
he declared himself uncommitted prior to the vote. ``I haven't
really decided, but I like Gary Bauer, Forbes, Buchanan and Alan
Keyes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Ames, straw poll participants found a county fair atmosphere
leading up to the 13-minute speeches from each candidate. The
Forbes and Bush tents were at adjacent locations near the coliseum.
Bush won a bidding war for what his team considered the best site
by paying $43,500. Forbes paid $8,000 for a site that seemed just
as good.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes pumped up attendance at his site by offering kiddie rides
along with food and music.
</P>
<P>
   The carnival-like atmosphere drew the curious as well as the
committed. Rod MacBride, a graduate student at Iowa State who
described himself as an independent, said he came ``to see the
media watching the people and the people watching the media.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can go down to the state fair if you want, but I think
this is more fun for the day.''
</P>
<P>
   As a throng of diners chewed happily in the Bush tent, a Bush
aide with a microphone felt compelled to give them a reminder.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't vote with your fork,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
