<HEADLINE>
CLARIDGE MAKES MOVE UP FRONT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ It's been a sore point for the previous three
years of USC offensive lineman Travis Claridge's career: At some
point during each of those seasons, his unit drew criticism as one
of the Trojans' weakest positions.
</P>
<P>
   Although Saturday was USC's first day of training camp, Claridge
already sees more talent in this year's line than any of the others
he played on. That's significant, because the outspoken Claridge
rarely tosses out compliments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see improvement in everybody,'' Claridge said. ``The one
who's really good is Lenny Vandermade. Lenny is a good, tough
football player.''
</P>
<P>
   Vandermade, a true freshman from Mater Dei, is one reason the
line is better. He is a backup at guard and might not redshirt this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Claridge is moving from right guard to right tackle as USC
attempts to get more athletic along the line. Redshirt freshman
Zach Wilson and senior Jason Grain (who lost 30 pounds this summer)
are battling at right guard.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Donta Kendrick and sophomore Faasea Mailo are the
candidates at left guard. Mailo started three games in 1996 before
going on a Mormon mission.
</P>
<P>
   As camp opened, the only weak point appeared to be left tackle.
Starter Brent McCaffrey (punctured foot) is out for the first few
days, leaving junior Trevor Roberts as a practice mainstay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll be a very good line,'' Claridge said. ``It has
the most potential of any line I've played on.''
</P>
<P>
   __ First-day report: Hackett was pleased with the Trojans' first
day at UC Irvine. Many of the true freshmen stood out, including
wide receivers Kareem Kelly and Marcell Allmond and defensive back
Darrell Rideaux.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early to tell, but it looks like those guys can make
contributions and help us,'' Hackett said. ``Only time will tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Freshman linebacker Chris Prosser also stood out in the
afternoon practice.
</P>
<P>
   Redshirt freshman tailback Sultan McCullough, limited by a
strained hamstring he suffered at the NCAA Track Championships in
June, was supposed to practice lightly this week but went full
speed in the afternoon practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, he was ready to go,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Tip-top condition: One player who arrived in great shape was
Allmond, who is one of the top junior decathletes in the country.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Allmond set the national record for 17-and-18-year
olds with 7,377 points in the decathlon. He also scored 7,111
points at the Junior Nationals, which used adult implements for the
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in the best shape of my life,'' Allmond said. ``It's
helped a lot (here).
</P>
<P>
   It gives me a chance to run more routes in practice because I'm
in better shape and I don't get tired.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Injury report: Freshman Armand Holland is out with a strained
back, and Hackett said he will miss the first week of practice
while undergoing therapy.
</P>
<P>
   __ Crooked field: Training camp got off to an inauspicious
debut, when Hackett learned the practice-field chalk lines were
slanted and not square.
</P>
<P>
   USC called the crew that paints the Coliseum field and an
emergency repair job was done Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm much more involved in horticulture and agriculture now,''
Hackett said.
</P>
</TEXT>
