<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NGUYEN-TEX </SLUG>
 
COWBOYS' NGUYEN POSSESSES EXTRA SENSE FOR FOOTBALL, LIFE (For use
by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The first clue that Dat Nguyen was going
to be rich, famous and always in the right place at the right time
came when he was a second grader at Rockport-Fulton Elementary. He
received $50 a day to appear in a handful of scenes of an Ed
Harris/Amy Madigan movie titled ``Alamo Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen doesn't recall all the particulars, except that the
filming lasted about three months, and he missed a few weeks of
school because the filming ran into September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows I'm a movie star,'' Nguyen said during a break
recently at Cowboys camp. ``Nobody knows that I co-starred in a
movie with Ed Harris.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen is running second team behind Randall Godfrey at middle
linebacker for the Cowboys. For all his achievements _ 1998
Lombardi Trophy winner, Dick Butkus Award finalist, Big 12 and
national defensive player of the year _ he never takes himself too
seriously. But the rest of the NFL might want to. Based on what he
has shown in training camp, Nguyen seems to have some star power.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen is the NFL's first Vietnamese-American player. He was
conceived in Vietnam and born to Tammy and Ho Nguyen on Sept. 25,
1975, in a Vietnamese refugee camp in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until several years after filming ``Alamo Bay'' that
Nguyen realized the movie was an unflattering portrayal of
Vietnamese shrimpers working off the Texas gulf coast near Seadrift
and Port O'Conner. It was filmed in 1982. The Vietnam War had been
over for seven years, but the emotional scars in this country were
still fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was too young to understand the storyline,'' said Nguyen,
who eventually watched the movie when he could understand it. ``The
Vietnamese shrimper came in and took away business from the people
in that community. I didn't know that I was part of a movie that
portrayed Vietnamese shrimpers in a bad light.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly? The movie wasn't very good,'' he critiqued with a
grin. ``In the end, though, I think it does prove a point. We're
all in this world together, and we have to learn to make
adjustments.'' According to Nguyen, the movie is hard to find in
video rental, but there is one copy at his cousin's video store in
Rockport.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, Long ``Lee'' Cao at Kim Video said, ``''Alamo Bay''
rents out once, sometimes twice, a week. Maybe I miss something ...
\Rbecause\S I see the movie and I don't see Dat.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen doesn't have a speaking part in the movie but does appear
in several scenes. In one, he plays shortstop on a softball team
and makes a catch and tags out a runner.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey saw enough of the ``movies'' on Nguyen
at Texas A&AMP;M to make him the 85th selection overall in the April
draft. ``Don't take into account the way he looks, as far his size
\R5-foot-11, 231 pounds\S and speed. ... Just watch him play the
game,'' Gailey said. ``Wherever the football goes, Dat's right
there. He has a real knack for putting himself around the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how a great running back has great vision? You know
how a great running back has that `feel' for where the defender is
and knows that the crease will be there if he can just stretch a
linebacker and hit it back up in there. Well, Dat has that same
`feel' on the other side of the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen seems cut from the same mold as former Texas Tech
lineback Zach Thomas. The 5-11, 235-pound four-year veteran was a
fifth-round draft choice from Texas Tech who recently signed a
multi-million-dollar contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to depict that this guy is totally a finesse
player. He's not,'' Gailey said. ``He's a pretty physical guy who
can take on people when he has to do that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M has been Linebacker U. for years, but Aggies coach
R.C. Slocum said this past week, ``Dat Nguyen is as instinctive a
player as we've ever had here.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is so alert; he sees things before they happen,'' Slocum
added. ``For example, if a guard is leaning back in his stance or a
running back is cheating up on the line, Dat sees it. He has great
anticipation. We had an onside kick once _ you know, you just hope
somebody falls on the ball _ but Dat picked it up and ran for a
touchdown.'' The Cowboys decided before the April draft to move
Godfrey to middle linebacker. Godfrey started all 16 games in '98
at strong-side linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   But if Nguyen continues to make big plays (he had a flying sack
against Cleveland), and if he continues to be around the ball as he
always is in practice, Gailey will be forced to get him onto the
field for more than just special teams.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen has come a long way since being recruited by Slocum on a
tip that this Vietnamese-American could dunk a basketball from a
flat-footed start. But when Nguyen was redshirted as a freshman in
1994, he weighed a fat 240 pounds and was extremely lonely away
from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared to death that he was going to leave,'' Slocum
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I nearly did,'' Nguyen admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Nguyen worked all her American life in the restaurant
business until she underwent eye surgery last year. For nearly two
decades, she ran Hong Kong, a Vietnamese-Chinese restaurant in
Rockport. Six years ago, she opened Hu Dat in Fulton. Ho Nguyen, a
longtime shrimper, now operates a marine supply store next to the
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   In junior high school in Rockport, Nguyen found the security of
friends by hanging out with an older crowd. He sometimes wouldn't
get home until 2 a.m. His mother considered sending him to a
Missouri all-boys school because she felt that he needed structure
and discipline.
</P>
<P>
   The mere threat of being uprooted prompted Dat to latch onto
something. He tried out for football. Rockport-Fulton gained a
great player, and Dat found the structure and discipline that he
needed to make his mom happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I started playing football, that took up all my
time and kept me out of trouble,'' he said. ``I look back on it
now, I wasn't really bad. I just stayed out late and worried my
mom. That was the good part. I was fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Slocum: ``I've heard those same stories about Dat. It's
hard for me to even imagine him getting into trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen signs autographs and poses for pictures with fans for
20-30 minutes after every practice. He is so patient and thorough
that each time an equipment boy has to ask him for his blue No. 45
jersey and shoulder pads to take into the locker room ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   After one practice this past week, a teen-ager called Nguyen
aside just to ask if he could get Emmitt Smith's autograph for him.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen politely surveyed the practice field and said, ``Gee, I
don't see Emmitt Smith right now. Sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a sixth-grade boy named Quang Pham in College Station
who knows how helpful Nguyen can be. Nguyen is credited with saving
Pham academically a couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Pham came to this country from Vietnam in 1996 at the age of 9.
When he was 10, he still had a prekindergarten English reading
level and was falling behind so quickly in school that the problem
had compounded into a total withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just shy,'' said Nguyen, who spent time with Pham and
helped him to read and comprehend. ``Now he's taking honors
courses.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Dat Nguyen, always in the right place at the right time.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 2332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990814.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7724 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GOP-BUSH-STRAWPOLL-HN     08-14 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-BUSH-STRAWPOLL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG WIN FOR BUSH IN IOWA STRAW POLL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMES, Iowa _ In an early affirmation of his political prowess,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush bested his GOP competitors Saturday in an
Iowa straw poll that could winnow the crowded field of Republican
presidential contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more than accomplished what we set out to do,'' Bush
told a crowd of about 250 cheering supporters after the nonbinding
vote was counted. ``We jump-started our grass-roots organization
for the main event, the Iowa caucuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush garnered about 31 percent of the vote in a 12-candidate
field to triumph in this first test of Republican candidates'
organizational strength.
</P>
<P>
   Magazine mogul Steve Forbes, who reportedly pumped more than $1
million into the straw poll effort, came in second with 20 percent
of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``A funny thing happened on the way to the coronation,'' Forbes
said in a written statement, after his strong second-place finish.
``The people voted.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Cabinet official Elizabeth Dole, whose campaign sorely
needed a boost, came in third with 14.4 percent after spending only
$250,000 on the straw poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't accept the premise that money is the only thing that
matters in politics. Tonight shows that,'' said Dole spokesman Ari
Fleischer.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, a fund-raiser for state Republicans, took on greater
significance this year after Bush declared that he not only
intended to participate but to win.
</P>
<P>
   While the exercise is meaningless in terms of a candidate's
ultimate success, the media and the candidates have placed
increasing weight on the results as a barometer of the campaign's
early health. No straw poll winner has ever won the presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush and Forbes relied on sophisticated operations to turn
out the vote, efforts that are likely to put them in good stead for
the Iowa caucuses in January.
</P>
<P>
   While Forbes spent far more time in the state than Bush,
spokeswoman Karen Hughes said the results showed that the Texas
governor would be prepared to ``organize a grass-roots effort when
it counts _ the caucuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Bush's supporters made it clear that the principle
reason they were backing the Texas governor was that he appeared to
have the greatest chance of winning back the White House for the
GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I think he will be a winner,'' said Margaret Whitlach,
74, of Pelfa, who was sitting in the Bush tent area. When asked if
any of the governor's positions particularly appealed to her, she
paused and then turned to her husband for an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like that he is a conservative with a compassionate heart,''
said Forrest Whitlach, 76, repeating the Bush mantra that he is a
``compassionate conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   The straw poll may mean more for the candidates who performed
poorly because it will be far more difficult to raise money to
continue the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Most at risk was former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, who
spent more time in the state than any other candidate, yet finished
sixth with 6 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Bush suggested it was time to narrow the field. ``Everybody's
going to have to reassess their position to find out whether or not
they can stay competitive,'' he said. ``I feel great.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle is likely to find his quest for
the Oval Office finally out of reach, as he finished eighth, even
behind broadcaster Alan Keyes, with less than 4 percent of the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   But a respectable finish of fourth place is likely to boost the
campaign of conservative activist Gary Bauer, who rallied his base
of social conservatives with his focus on abortion and family
values.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are looking for a new face that has strong
conservative values,'' Bauer said after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Other more conservative candidates did not fare as well.
Commentator Pat Buchanan, who finished third in 1995, placed fifth
this time with 7.3 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   This year, party officials estimated they sold more than 20,000
tickets, with most of them snapped up by the Bush and Forbes
campaigns to distribute to supporters. Party officials boasted that
they took in $520,000 on the event.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the straw poll were announced several hours after
the eight participating candidates addressed a sports arena on the
Iowa State University campus that was so packed that many
participants were barred from entering.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the candidates lobbed barbs not only at the Clinton-Gore
administration but also at Bush, who has led the pack in both in
terms of early polls and fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   Bush avoided criticizing his opponents, and instead repeated his
major campaign themes that he would run an inclusive campaign that
focused on his message of ``compassionate conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned you cannot lead by dividing people or pitting
them against one another. I'm a uniter, not a divider,'' Bush told
the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But Forbes made it clear that he was running against the
political establishment in Washington, which he and others
suggested had tried to anoint Bush as the next GOP nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power of these Washington elites won't be tamed, bent or
broken by a candidate who relies on pollsters and tutors to tell
him what he thinks,'' said the New Jersey millionaire whose entry
was greeted by bleating horns and a shower of confetti and
fireworks. The first half of his speech was drowned out by a group
of Buchanan supporters who popped dozens of balloons while he
spoke.
</P>
<P>
   Others also took aim at Clinton, saying he had eroded the moral
values of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan received some of the loudest applause of the day when
he said one of his first actions as president would be to direct
the Justice Department to tell Clinton, ``You have the right to
remain silent.''
</P>
<P>
   The straw poll, which drew a record crowd on this sun-splashed
day, was a cross between a carnival and national political
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the coliseum, vendors hawked campaign paraphernalia as
participants strolled through tent parties sponsored by each
candidate. The tents included barbecue spreads, sports figures and
entertainers. Caravans of buses from across the state rolled onto
campus with supporters who were sporting candidates' T-shirts, hats
and buttons.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes clearly threw the most elaborate party, as children
frolicked in a playground complete with a huge inflatable slide and
moonwalk. Adults stood around an air-conditioned tent and listened
to singer Debby Boone croon, ``You Light Up My Life.``
</P>
<P>
   ``This is sort of like Disneyland for politics,'' said Tom Rath,
a New Hampshire lawyer and political adviser to Alexander who was
checking out the Forbes party.
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Zeliff, Alexander's national chairman and former New
Hampshire congressman, was less amused by the circuslike
surroundings, including a man on stilts standing next to him
welcoming Forbes supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this the real way to pick a president? If it is, we are in
bad shape,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
