TCU RUNNING BACK TOMLINSON ANTICIPATES BREAKING FREE _ AND GETTING
HIT (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ Tiny charges, it seems to LaDainian Tomlinson, are
pulsing through his body as he takes his first step after receiving
the handoff.
</P>
<P>
   His senses, except for hearing, are jarred into heightened
awareness with each subsequent step. The sounds are around him but
don't penetrate. The silence is so thick that he swears he can hear
the tightening of his muscles as he prepares for the impact of the
tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Only there is no tackle. There are only the coaches' whistles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been tackled since the Sun Bowl,'' Tomlinson said
ruefully. ``Coaches won't let them.''
</P>
<P>
   He is ``the'' tailback in TCU's backfield this season, and if
you think coach Dennis Franchione is going to let him get hit,
you're probably one of those people who hits on 19 when playing
blackjack. The Horned Frogs aren't going to do anything during
two-a-day practices to risk injuring their proven junior tailback.
</P>
<P>
   Tomlinson has 717 yards and eight touchdowns worth of proof from
1998 when he backed up Basil Mitchell. With Mitchell in Green Bay
Packers' camp, Tomlinson is the only tailback returning with any
real experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has run for 165 yards against a Division I team \RWeek 10
against Tulsa in 1998\S, so he doesn't have a lot to prove,'' TCU
running backs coach Mike Schultz said. ``What I need to be doing
now is making sure on Sept. 5th against Arizona that LT's the guy
I'm lining up.''
</P>
<P>
   The quick whistle during two-a-days and the scrimmageless spring
were all to ensure that Tomlinson entered the 1999 season, arguably
TCU's most anticipated in recent memory, healthy and ready to go.
The precautions almost were for naught.
</P>
<P>
   Four hours spent in the wrong place at the wrong time had the
potential to do more damage than any would-be tackler.
</P>
<P>
   On July 24, Tomlinson was arrested with two others on suspicion
of possessing marijuana and evading police. He said he didn't do
either. But he was in the same place at the same time with people
suspected of doing it, and that was enough to get him arrested. The
charges weren't pursued because of lack of evidence, but Tomlinson
said he hasn't forgotten the 24 hours he spent in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really sunk in how fast trouble can get to you,'' Tomlinson
said. ``Everybody had spent all summer telling me the sky is the
limit for me, and I saw that it could've all been gone. I learned a
lot that night, and it changed me in some ways.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change was in the way Tomlinson perceived himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had always seen himself as part of the team, no more no
less, and that's one of the great things about him,'' said Greg
Walls, Tomlinson's best friend on the team. ``But, in my opinion,
he is going to be the man for us this season. We all look toward
him to be a leader. I think now he knows we need him out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Need is the understatement of the week. There is no more
Mitchell in the Mitchell-Tomlinson tandem that helped the Frogs
average 239.1 yards a game in 1998. When Mitchell went, so did the
days of the backup getting starter-like carries. ``We will probably
lean to playing LT a little bit more until one of the guys behind
him proves himself,'' Schultz said.
</P>
<P>
   Tomlinson is indeed ``the'' man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's ready,'' Franchione said. ``He has all of the
qualities to be a resilient back.''
</P>
<P>
   He weighs 221 pounds, can bench 430 pounds, can squat 610
pounds, can power clean 333 pounds, can incline bench 400 pounds
and can handle the go-to role the coaches need for him to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting very anxious,'' Tomlinson said. ``TCU fans have
never really gotten a full taste of what I can do. I can't wait for
the season to start to show them.''
</P>
<P>
   Just make sure to look real close when the first would-be
tackler heads his way, and there is no coach's whistle to prevent
the impact. The muscles will tighten, and then Tomlinson hopes to
really show everybody what all of the precautions were about. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-99 2348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
