<HEADER>
A7737 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-IOWA-STRAW-POLL-1STLD     08-14 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-STRAW-POLL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TRIUMPHS IN IOWA STRAW POLL; FORBES FINISHES SECOND IN
NONBINDING VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to update with results)   (Eds., this story is now on NYT Page 1, top center; the Kosovo
story moves inside)  
 (HLW)  
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMES, Iowa _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas triumphed Saturday
night in a straw poll here of nearly 25,000 Iowans, a nonbinding
but high-profile test of the Republican Party's presidential field.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, the multimillionaire publisher, placed second,
establishing himself as a force that Bush will have to reckon with
as the primary season unfolds. Elizabeth Dole ranked third,
quieting, at least for now, critics who said her campaign was
flagging after a fast start.
</P>
<P>
   In the competition for support from religious conservatives,
Gary Bauer, a former head of the Family Research Council, placed
fourth, ahead of Pat Buchanan, the conservative television
commentator.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Lamar Alexander of Tennessee, who has made Iowa
practically a second home, came in sixth. And there was even more
dismal news for former Vice President Dan Quayle, who ranked eighth
behind Alan Keyes, a radio talk show host. Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah
finished ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes poured the most money into the straw poll, followed by
Bush, and had been expected to place second. But the results
underscored that the Forbes operation is deft at turning its deep
resources into organizational prowess.
</P>
<P>
   The event at Iowa State University was devised as a money-making
operation by Iowa Republicans, and the straw poll victor has never
ended up in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   In a practice that critics say is meaningless because it verges
on outright vote-buying, the campaigns bused Iowans here, fed them,
entertained them and then paid their $25 entry fee. The hope was
that, in return, the sated participants would cast a vote for the
candidate who treated them best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this the way to pick a president?'' asked former Rep. Bill
Zeliff of New Hampshire as he stood between a clown on stilts and
an inflatable playground, courtesy of Steve Forbes' campaign. ``If
it is, we're in bad shape.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Zeliff's candidate _ he is a national chairman for
Alexander _ eagerly took part. Alexander's enticement for voters:
the singer Crystal Gayle.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that in the 2000 campaign, this, indeed, may be a
way to pick a nominee. Because the campaign has started so soon,
with many states moving up the dates of their primaries, the straw
poll here could winnow the field. And because Bush has so dominated
the polls and amassed so much cash, some campaigns said that Ames
might be their last stand.
</P>
<P>
   As indoor fireworks illuminated the stage of a darkened arena
here, the announcer proclaimed: ``On this stage is the next
president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Neglecting those who questioned the fairness of the event, Bush
told the crowd, ``I am proud to be here for this grass-roots
exercise in democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the first event in which nine candidates (except Sen.
John McCain of Arizona, who called it ``a scam'') took part. As
people waited in long lines to vote, each contender was allowed 10
minutes to make his or her pitch and three minutes for a
demonstration of support from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the revelry on this bright and festive afternoon,
campaigns were partaking in high-stakes politics. Campaign workers
scurried about in golf carts with walkie-talkies and cell phones,
sizing up the lines at their rivals' tents.
</P>
<P>
   The event was an organizational test to see which campaigns
could convince the most people to travel far and wide to this event
_ and then take the next step to support their candidate. Any Iowa
resident of voting age could participate, a change in the rules
that gave this event more credibility than the event four years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, candidates turned this grass-roots exercise into the
campaign equivalent of a Berlin airlift, flying in supporters from
around the country. To prevent the rampant cheating that marked
that event, voters Saturday had their thumbs stamped with indelible
red ink.
</P>
<P>
   This spectacle was by far the most extravagant ever, and it drew
thousands more people than four years ago, when then-Sen. Bob Dole
of Kansas and Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas tied for first place.
Republicans sometimes call themselves the party of the Big Tent
and, certainly, the scene was a sea of big and small tents. The
campaigns engaged in a bidding war to rent parcels of grass and
pavement in the parking lot around the Hilton Coliseum, with the
Bush campaign paying the most _ $43,500.
</P>
<P>
   If sheer resources were any guide to who would triumph, Forbes
would have won hands down. No one could stop talking about his
colossal, air-conditioned tent (with French doors).
</P>
<P>
   Marveling, perhaps, at the competition, Benjamin Ginsberg, the
Bush campaign's legal counsel, called it ``Chateau Malcolm,'' a
reference to Forbes' given name.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of people coming here to get cooled off _ in the
Bush tent they come off a little stodgy,'' said Greg Mueller, a
spokesman for Forbes. ``And we have the only kids' stuff _ Forbes
family values.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the pivotal Iowa caucuses nearly six months from
now, when people will actually vote in a binding contest, William
Dal Col, the Forbes' campaign manager, said, ``This is all a down
payment for a cold night in February.''
</P>
<P>
   One Forbes supporter who was cooling off was Joanne Pohlman, 62,
a retired schoolteacher from Webster City, Iowa. ``It's like a
carnival,'' she said, clutching a Forbes gift bag. ``But it's fun.
Great sport. Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   Max Eckstein, 22, a college student from Boone, Iowa, who was
surveying the band in a Bush tent, said the governor and other
candidates ``must be kicking themselves'' for not air-conditioning
their tents. But, he said, that would not in itself sway him to
back Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do food and entertainment make a difference?'' Eckstein asked.
``Maybe for the common person.''
</P>
<P>
   Some party-goers, while not shy about sampling the food and
accepting the free rides on hot air balloons, denounced the
extravagance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forbes is trying to appeal to the side of us that says, `OK,
we can play so he must be good,''' said Tanya Bignell, a data-entry
worker from Bettendorf, Iowa, who was backing Hatch. ``I don't
think so,'' Ms. Bignell said as she picked over a modest spread of
chicken and baked beans in the Hatch tent.
</P>
<P>
   The campaigns that spent the most were worried that some people
they transported here would use their tickets to vote for another
candidate. So before people could get their tickets from the Forbes
organization, they had to sign a pledge that said, ``I, the
undersigned, pledge to support Steve Forbes.''
</P>
<P>
   D. Jim Moore and his wife, Greta, farmers from Thornburg, Iowa,
peered into the Hatch tent, where Vic Damone was crooning, but said
they were backing Bush anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forbes' is probably the best,'' Moore, 69, said of the
entertainment. ``He had Debby Boone in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Moore, 68, added, ``It was packed, I'll tell you.'' She was
not put off by the heavy spending, saying, ``That's their business.
You spend your money where you have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Endicott, 34, an English teacher who lives near here,
said he was a Democrat but voted for Elizabeth Dole, hoping that
she would deprive Bush of votes, and soften him up for the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get her more points against Bush to keep her in the
race,'' Endicott said. He said he was ``turned off'' by some of the
fancy tents, even by the decor of the low-budget operation of
former Vice President Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quayle's corn cobs and hay stacks,'' he said. ``It's just too
hick.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
